=== Aziwu of Haichuang ===
E1: A monk asked at the end of the summer retreat: "You told us all to go where for ten thousand miles there is not a blade of grass. What is this place where for ten thousand miles there is not a blade of grass?" The Master said: "Grass covers every inch of ground." The monk pressed: "The ancients say, 'Step outside and there is nothing but grass.' What is stepping outside?" the Master answered: "Take care not to fall into the thorns." The monk pressed again: "Another ancient said, 'Even without stepping outside, the vines tangle everywhere.' What is not stepping outside?" said the Master: "You must know how to turn your body." The monk said: "Suppose someone says, 'Reverend sir, speaking this way is itself vines tangling.' Then what?" The Master said: "In ancient times, Huo Guang sold the Surrender City to the Xiongnu. Tell me, who wrote the deed of sale?" The monk gave a shout and bowed. The Master laughed: "I'll concede you one move."
E2: New Year's Day. The Master said: "The golden crow breaks through the eastern sea gate. Three hundred and sixty days begin from today. Reckon it up: I have been here ten years already. May auspicious things begin again from the start." He struck the staff: "From the start -- one bright pearl, big as a platter. Ten monks together cannot lift it."

=== Baichi ===
E1: A monk asked: "The World-Honored One was already honored the moment he left his mother's womb -- why then did he go to Snow Mountain and gaze at the morning star before being called enlightened?" The Master said: "Disasters never come alone."
E2: A monk asked: "What is taking away the person but not the environment?" the Master responded: "A promise was made, yet past midnight no one has come." "What is taking away the environment but not the person?" "Idly tapping chess stones, the lamp-flower falls." "What is both person and environment taken away?" "A thousand mountains, birds all gone; ten thousand paths, footprints vanished." "What is neither person nor environment taken away?" "Rush cape, bamboo hat, an old man -- fishing alone on a cold river in snow." The monk pressed further: "Beyond these distinctions, is there anything more?" The Master struck him: "First digest what's already been said."

=== BAISHAN KAI ===
E1: After years of practice, Dekai still could not penetrate the phrase "a sentence with words and a sentence without words, like a vine clinging to a tree -- when the tree falls and the vine withers, where does the sentence return to?" His teacher Chenxian pressed him relentlessly on this point. One day during mealtime, the rice ladle fell to the ground and bounced twice. Suddenly he had a great awakening to the meaning of the "profound essentials." He spontaneously laughed and chanted: "When the thieving mind has completely died and the eyes go numb, the stone woman in her dream -- her hair stands on end. Indeed! So that is what Old Man Hongjue meant by those words." He rushed to the abbot's room, and Chenxian said: "In recent times, even the ablest masters in their halls could not penetrate this far -- how much less ordinary folk? Now that you know this essential, you must guard it carefully. Later, as a master of the school, you may pull out nails and extract pegs for others."
E2: When Dekai delivered a letter to Master Baiyu, who asked: "The letter has been delivered. But what is your own matter?" Dekai said: "Yesterday I crossed the river; today I see the Master." Baiyu said: "How deep is the river?" Dekai said: "I only saw the boat reach the shore; I did not know the depth of the water." Baiyu turned to those beside him and said: "Tell me, does this monk have insight or not?" Dekai said: "If the Master doubts this, he had better buy more straw sandals and go traveling." Baiyu said: "Considering your hardship on the road, I will hold thirty blows in reserve for you." Dekai said: "In that case, I will pay my respects and be going."

=== Baiyu Jingsi ===
E1: A monk came forward and bowed. The master said, "Ask your question properly." The monk gave a shout. The master hit him. The monk shouted again. The master hit him again. The monk raised his fist and declared, "The great road to the capital -- it goes right through here!" The master said, "You've been told to stop, and you won't stop." The monk tried once more, offering a verse: "Silently the yellow leaves fall -- not just autumn for one alone." The master hit him yet again and said, "Wait till the rain pours on your head."
E2: The master ascended the hall and raised the old case: "A monk asked Master Guizong, 'What is Buddha?' Guizong said, 'I'd like to tell you, but I'm afraid you won't believe me.' The monk said, 'The master's words carry weight -- how could I dare not believe?' Guizong said, 'You yourself are it.' The monk asked, 'How should I preserve it?' Guizong said, 'One film across the eye, and phantom flowers fill the sky.'" The master commented: "Old red-eyed Guizong -- though his verbal skill was nimble and his responses supple, if you examine it closely, it still gets caught in the lips. If someone had asked me, 'What is Buddha?' I'd say, 'You're a thief howling that you've been wronged.' And if they pressed, 'How should I preserve it?' -- I'd answer with a blow. Not only would this give the monk a fresh turning point, it would also keep him from loitering in the women's quarters." Then he asked the assembly: "After all, is Guizong right? Or am I right? If you hesitate -- well, you go to Xiao-Xiang, and I go to Qin."

=== Baiyun Shouduan ===
E1: Baiyun Shouduan was a native of Hengyang, surnamed Ge. In his youth he devoted himself to letters. Upon reaching manhood he took ordination under Chaling Yu and then went to study with Yangqi. One day Yangqi suddenly asked, "Who was your ordination teacher?" Baiyun said, "Master Chaling Yu." Yangqi said, "I've heard that he had a great awakening when he stumbled crossing a bridge and composed a verse. Can you recite it?" Baiyun recited: "I have a bright pearl, long imprisoned by dust and toil. This morning the dust is cleared and the light shines forth, illuminating the mountains and rivers by the thousands." Yangqi laughed and walked away. Baiyun was dumbfounded and could not sleep all night. At dawn he went to ask about it. It happened to be New Year's Eve. Yangqi said, "Did you see the demon-chasers yesterday?" Baiyun said, "Yes." Yangqi said, "You are not as good as they are." Baiyun was shocked and asked, "What do you mean?" Yangqi said, "They love it when people laugh at them. You are afraid of people laughing at you." At these words Baiyun was greatly awakened.
E2: A monk asked, "What is the great meaning of the Buddha-dharma?" Baiyun said, "Pressing a gourd under water." Another monk asked, "Not seeking from the sages, not valuing one's own spirit -- that is not yet the monk's business. What is the monk's real business?" Baiyun said, "Dead water cannot hide a dragon." The monk said, "Then what if I proceed accordingly?" Baiyun said, "You've been tricked."

=== Baizhang Huaihai ===
E1: Baizhang was walking with Mazu when a flock of wild ducks flew overhead. Mazu asked, "What is that?" Baizhang said, "Wild ducks." Mazu said, "Where have they gone?" Baizhang said, "They've flown away." Mazu suddenly reached over and gave Baizhang's nose a sharp twist. Baizhang cried out in pain. Mazu said, "You say they've flown away?" At these words, Baizhang had an insight. He went back to the attendants' quarters and wept bitterly. A fellow monk asked, "Are you homesick for your parents?" "No." "Did someone insult you?" "No." "Then why are you crying?" "The Master twisted my nose so hard I can't bear the pain." The monk said, "What did you fail to accord with?" Baizhang said, "Go ask the Master yourself." The monk went and asked Mazu, "What happened with attendant Hai that he's weeping in the quarters? Please tell me." Mazu said, "He understands. Go ask him yourself." The monk returned and said, "The Master says you understand, and told me to ask you." Baizhang burst into great laughter. The monk said, "A moment ago you were weeping -- now why are you laughing?" Baizhang said, "A moment ago I was weeping; now I'm laughing." The next day Mazu ascended the hall. The assembly had just gathered when Baizhang came forward and rolled up the sitting mat. Mazu immediately stepped down from the seat. Baizhang followed him to the abbot's quarters. Mazu said, "I hadn't even begun to speak -- why did you roll up the mat?" Baizhang said, "Yesterday you twisted my nose and it hurt terribly." Mazu said, "Where was your attention yesterday?" Baizhang said, "Today my nose doesn't hurt anymore." Mazu said, "You deeply understand yesterday's matter." Baizhang bowed and withdrew.
E2: Every day when Baizhang ascended the hall to lecture, an old man would come to listen, then leave with the assembly. One day the old man did not leave. Baizhang asked, "Who is standing there?" The old man said, "I am not a human being. In the time of Kashyapa Buddha, I was the abbot of this mountain. A student asked me, 'Does a person of great cultivation still fall into cause and effect?' I answered, 'Such a person does not fall into cause and effect.' For this, I have been reborn as a wild fox for five hundred lifetimes. I beg you, Master, please give a turning word on my behalf." Baizhang said, "Just ask." The old man asked, "Does a person of great cultivation still fall into cause and effect?" Baizhang said, "Such a person is not blind to cause and effect." At these words the old man was greatly awakened. He bowed and said, "I am now freed from the wild fox body. I live behind the mountain. Please bury me according to the rites for a deceased monk." Baizhang had the assembly informed: "After the meal, we will send off a deceased monk." The assembly was puzzled -- no one was ill. After the meal, Baizhang led them to a cave behind the mountain and poked out the body of a dead fox with his staff. They cremated it according to the rites. That evening, Baizhang recounted the whole affair. Huangbo immediately asked, "The ancient one gave a wrong turning word and fell into the wild fox body for five hundred lives. But if every answer had been correct, what then?" Baizhang said, "Come closer, and I'll tell you." Huangbo stepped forward and slapped the Master. Baizhang clapped his hands and laughed, saying, "I thought only the barbarian had a red beard -- here is another red-bearded barbarian!"

=== Bajiao Huiqing ===
E1: Bajiao showed the assembly and said: "If you have a staff, I give you a staff. If you do not have a staff, I take away your staff." Wumen comments: "Supporting you across the broken bridge's water, accompanying you back to the moonless village. If you call it a staff, you enter hell like an arrow."
E2: Bajiao addressed the assembly and said: "The nostrils of patch-robed monks are all on the tip of the staff." Then he said: "It is like the qin, the se, and the konghou -- though they possess marvelous sounds, without a marvelous touch they can never be brought forth."

=== Baling Haojian ===
E1: A monk asks Baling: "What is the tradition of Deva?" Baling says: "Snow contained in a silver bowl." The commentary: "Only Baling spoke like this -- utterly solitary and sheer, not revealing the slightest edge or point."
E2: A monk asks Baling: "What is the hair-blowing sword?" Baling says: "Coral branches, each one holding up the moon." The commentary: "Baling never stirred spear or halberd -- yet how many tongues fell to the ground across the four seas and five lakes."

=== Banshuiyuan of Sanfeng ===
E1: A monk came to interview him. The Master held up his staff: "Sanfeng has a flat-nosed viper here. Do you see it?" The monk recoiled in fear. The Master struck him. The monk made a gesture of lying down. the Master replied: "Drag this corpse out of here!"
E2: The Master asked a layman: "Everyone has a shadow. Why can't you step on it?" The layman said: "Beneath my feet there is nothing private." the Master replied: "There is still a shadow there." The layman said: "No." The Master said: "Where are your eyes then?" The layman bowed. The Master promptly stomped on him. The layman said: "Marvelous!" The Master said: "How about another stomp?"

=== Baochizong ===
E1: The Master raised an old case: "Moshan, the nun Liaoran, was sitting in her room when a monk passed by. She said, 'Who are you?' The monk said, 'A lion cub.' Liaoran said, 'Since you are a lion cub, why does Manjushri ride on your back?' The monk had no answer, so she struck him." The Master said: "I am not Moshan, flailing hands and feet. If a lion cub came to me, I would simply say: 'Try roaring.' If he can truly overturn and leap, he naturally has his own livelihood." A monk stepped forward. The Master said: "If it is a jackal chasing the Dharma King, a hundred-year-old specter opens its mouth in vain." He descended the seat.
E2: Ascending the hall, the Master said: "Even bodhisattvas find that seeing and awareness become obstructions. Mountains, rivers, and the great earth are obstructions. Grass, bushes, people, and animals are obstructions. Houses, fields, and estates are obstructions. Father, mother, and family are obstructions. Bodhi and nirvana are obstructions. Dhyana and liberation are obstructions." He took up the staff and said: "The staff leaps up to the thirty-third heaven, punches through the nostrils of the Thus-Come-One of Supreme Fragrance, so that all the voice-hearers and pratyekabuddhas fall over east and west, crying in distress. But the staff casually saunters back and, leaning on its corner of the bench, laughs loudly: 'I have no awareness, and no obstruction either -- I am accustomed to following others without claiming credit. Therefore my name is Avalokiteshvara, the Self-Existing One.'"

=== Baoen Xuanze ===
E1: Fayan asked Xuanze, "Whom did you study with before coming here?" Xuanze said, "I saw Master Qingfeng." Fayan said, "What words were spoken?" Xuanze said, "I once asked, What is the student's self? Qingfeng said, A Bingding boy comes seeking fire." Fayan said, "How do you understand it?" Xuanze said, "Bing and ding belong to fire. To seek fire with fire is like seeking oneself with oneself." Fayan said, "If you understand it that way, how will that do?" Xuanze said, "I am only like this. I do not know your venerable meaning, Master." Fayan said, "You ask me and I will tell you." Xuanze said, "What is the student's self?" Fayan said, "A Bingding boy comes seeking fire." Xuanze was suddenly enlightened at these words.
E2: Xuanze ascended the hall at Bao'en Monastery, surveyed the great assembly, and said, "What a fine topic for discussion, only no one knows how to ask about it. That is why the ancients had to call out three times. You all do not need to be called. Setting aside the ancients' intent for the moment, how would you express it? A thousand Buddhas appearing in the world does not add a single hair. The six realms of rebirth does not diminish a single hair. Bright and clear it appears without a single thread of obstruction. The ancients said, 'If there is so much as a fine hair, it is dust.' Yet right now, things and appearances stand towering -- how do you deal with them? If you cannot deal with them here, that is the realm of ordinary beings."

=== Baofeng Mingxuan ===
E1: Mingxuan was a carpenter from Wujiang. While building a stupa for Master Haizhou, he injured his foot with an axe and had a preliminary awakening. He then took the post of fire-tender, throwing himself into intense investigation. One day, without noticing, the fire singed off his eyebrows; his face felt as if slashed by a knife. He looked in a mirror and was suddenly, vastly awakened. He went to Haizhou to seek confirmation. Haizhou immediately struck him. The master grabbed the stick: "This seven-foot staff has gone unused for years -- today you want to pick it up again?" Haizhou laughed and let it go.
E2: The master presented a verse: "Where the blow lands, blood-stains appear; look closely at the knife hidden inside the smile. If you are not a true hero of spirit, you are just a dead man eating blows and mumbling nonsense." Haizhou confirmed him: "This very verse can carry on my lineage."

=== Baofu Congzhan ===
E1: At the end of the summer retreat, Cuiyan addresses the assembly: "All summer long, I have spoken to you brothers. Tell me, are Cuiyan's eyebrows still there?" Baofu says, "A thief has a guilty heart." Changqing says, "They grow." Yunmen says, "Barrier."
E2: Baofu saw a monk and struck the exposed pillar with his staff, then struck the monk on the head. The monk cried out in pain. Baofu said, "Why doesn't that one hurt?" The monk had no reply.

=== BAOJUE ZUXIN ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master said: "I have true gold refined a hundred times. Its skillful or clumsy shaping depends entirely on the craftsman. The names in this world are merely conventional labels -- following the shape, we call them vases, plates, hairpins, and bracelets." Then he addressed the assembly: "The forest of ten thousand phenomena does not obstruct the eye's light. Why then do we speak of seeing and not-seeing? Only because it is so utterly clear and obvious -- that is precisely what makes realization come late."
E2: A monk asked: "What was Bodhidharma's intention in sitting facing the wall for nine years?" The Master said: "Too poor to have a blanket." The monk asked: "Surely we must not betray the ancient sage?" the Master asked: "What is your own view then?" The monk drew a circle in the air. The Master said: "The swallows and sparrows never leave the nest." The monk bowed. the Master responded: "After midnight it is still bearable -- after noon is when the real trouble begins."

=== BAONING RENYONG ===
E1: From the preface: The old master of Fengtai Mountain was traveling south when he met a good teacher seated like a lion, white snow covering his head, using the gold ring and chestnut burr as his Buddha-work. He proclaimed to all students: "The Iron Encircling Mountains can be penetrated, but my diamond ring cannot be penetrated. The waters of the great ocean can be swallowed, but my chestnut burr cannot be swallowed. If you can pass through one ring, then a hundred thousand million rings will be passed through without doubt, and all afflictions will be liberated. If you can swallow one burr, then a hundred thousand million burrs can be swallowed without doubt, and all merit will be accomplished." At that time, the assembled monks were bewildered and retreated from their seats, not knowing what to do.
E2: Ascending the hall, Renyong said: "The mind follows myriad conditions and turns; the turning place is truly profound. Following the flow, recognizing your nature -- no joy, no sorrow." He struck the platform and said, "Baoning has become a water buffalo! Is there anyone who will follow along? If you follow, where is the nose-ring? If you cannot follow, Baoning will just get up and fall down by himself." Then he added: "Where there is spirit, add more spirit. Where there is no elegance, even that becomes elegant."

=== Baoshou Yanzhao ===
E1: Baoshou asked Hu Dingjiao, "I have long heard of Hu Dingjiao; are you the one?" Hu said, "I am." Baoshou said, "Can you nail empty space too?" Hu said, "Please, master, break it open and bring it." Baoshou struck. Hu would not accept it.
E2: Referenced in the saying: "Xuansha did not leave the ridge, and Baoshou did not cross the river." Baoshou is praised as one who, like Xuansha, completed his practice without wandering far -- his mastery was total within his own ground.

=== BEIJIAN JUJIAN ===
E1: Ascending the hall: The Buddha struck a skull and asked Jivaka, "Where was this person reborn?" Jivaka said, "In heaven." He struck another skull: "Where was this person reborn?" "Among humans." He struck a third skull: "Where was this person reborn?" Jivaka was baffled. Beijian commented: "Jivaka was skilled at distinguishing sounds -- how could he not know where the third one went? If so, the first two answers were surely also in error. I ask the assembly: today, this father and two sons are not reborn in heaven or among humans. Where exactly did they go?" Then a verse: "Seven-jeweled lotus flowers open in the shape of the character 'pin.' Each flower, each leaf, a pavilion. A water-bird calls from deep within the blossoms; the flower opens where the water-bird sings."
E2: Ascending the hall on the night of the Lantern Festival: "Before the King of Awesome Sound, every one set themselves up as lords. In the stream of later generations, there is nothing they will not stoop to. There is a dharma-gate called the Inexhaustible Lamp -- those who see its brightness all become bright, yet the brightness never runs out." He struck the staff once and said: "The road is long and the night is deep -- put down your torches. Everyone walk in the dark together."

=== Benzhen of Baiyun ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is Buddha?" The Master said: "Teeth -- a set of bones." "What is Dharma?" "In the empty woods, birdsong slides." "What is the Sangha?" "Your question just now -- that is the most intimate."
E2: A monk came for instruction. The master asked: "Where are you from?" The monk said: "The South Sea." The master asked: "Is Guanyin Bodhisattva there?" The monk said: "Yes." The master said: "Call her over to wash my feet." The monk was speechless. The master said: "You liar!" And drove him out with continuous blows.

=== BIE MUCHUN ===
E1: On his last day as abbot, the Master ascended the hall: "Since coming to this river land, I have done nothing but plant rice paddies for meals. I would not dare use Chan or Buddha-dharma to corrupt people's sons and daughters. And now I am glad it has come to this -- today I sing a song of returning to the mountains." He tapped his staff and sang: "A thousand-year field has eight hundred owners; how many times has it been plowed through wind and rain? Now the plow and harrow are all thrown away. What remains is Weishan's water buffalo. Blowing a short flute, I return -- singing one song, forgetting past and present." A monk started to come forward. The Master pushed him back with his staff: "In the smoky rain of the next village, another day we will discuss it." He threw down the staff, descended the seat, and walked away.
E2: On the anniversary of the Buddha's enlightenment, the Master held up his staff, making a casting-with-a-fishing-line gesture, and said: "A line dropped a thousand feet -- the intention is in the deep pool. Three inches from the hook -- why don't you speak?" A monk said: "Fortunately I am not like Jiashan." He withdrew and returned to the assembly. the Master answered: "Already pierced by the willow switch." Then he held up the staff: "This one thing props up heaven and supports earth, illumines the ancient and pervades the present. Shakyamuni for six years on Snow Mountain could not grope his way to it. Bodhidharma for nine years at Shaolin could not see through it. Today I take it up to dam the myriad currents of the Cao stream and drive the waters of the Dong cave in reverse. How many people here cannot find where it arises? Listen well, stiffen your backbone, carry it forward, do not let it be cut off."

=== Binya ===
E1: A monk asked: "All sentient beings possess the wisdom of the Tathagata. Why then can they not become Buddhas?" the Master responded: "A cat has the merit of lapping blood, but lacks the virtue of raising the dead." The monk said: "Then nirvana-mind is easy to understand, but the wisdom of differentiation is hard to fathom." The Master struck him and said: "It's all right here."
E2: A monk asked: "When the kalpa-fire blazes and the great cosmos is destroyed, is this [true self] destroyed or not?" said the Master: "Not destroyed." The monk continued: "Why not destroyed?" The Master said: "Destroyed." The monk pressed: "Why is it then destroyed?" The Master struck him once with the staff and said: "This one -- destroyed or not destroyed?"

=== Bodhidharma ===
E1: Bodhidharma faced the wall. The Second Patriarch Huike stood in the snow and cut off his arm, saying, "This disciple's mind is not at peace. I beg you, Master, pacify my mind." Bodhidharma said, "Bring me your mind, and I will pacify it for you." The Patriarch said, "I have searched for the mind, but it cannot be found." Bodhidharma said, "I have pacified your mind for you." Wumen's comment: "The tooth-gapped old barbarian sailed ten thousand miles across the sea, coming on purpose. It may be said he raised waves where there was no wind. In the end he took in a single disciple, yet even that one disciple was defective in all six senses."
E2: Emperor Wu of Liang asked Bodhidharma, "What is the highest meaning of the holy truth?" Bodhidharma said, "Vast emptiness, no holiness." The emperor said, "Who stands before me?" Bodhidharma said, "I do not know." The emperor did not accord, so Bodhidharma crossed the river to Shaolin and faced the wall for nine years.

=== BOSHAN WUYI ===
E1: Yuanxian writes: "When I was in seclusion at He Mountain, the Master [Boshan] was returning from Shigu and passed through Jianzhou. We met at Guangxiao Temple. The Master asked: 'Have you swept Shouchang's pagoda yet?' I said: 'The sweeping is never neglected. I just don't let anyone know about it.' The Master said: 'So you've been sweeping on the sly.' I said: 'That's how it is for me. What about you, Master?' The Master said: 'The sweeping is never neglected. I just have never disturbed anything.' I said: 'Then it seems the Master has never swept at all.' We burst out laughing and parted."
E2: ---

=== Bu'yanle ===
E1: A monk asked: "Wuxi donated funds and labored hard to build this hall, and today invited the Reverend to ascend this seat and speak the Dharma. What benefit does he gain?" The Master said: "Only someone with a bitter heart would know." The monk said: "I don't understand." The Master said: "If you don't understand, go ask Wuxi."
E2: A monk asked: "All day long you burn incense and tend the fire, not knowing that your body is itself the temple. What does that mean?" The Master said: "The body is the temple." The monk pressed: "What are its limits?" The Master said: "East to west, a hundred thousand; north to south, eight thousand."

=== Buhui ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the first mystery?" The master said: "Sleeping with legs outstretched on a great tiger's tongue." The monk pressed: "What is the second mystery?" The master said: "Sailing an iron ship on the tip of a needle." The monk pressed: "What is the third mystery?" The master said: "In an instant, already past the great three-thousand worlds." A layman then asked: "What is the first essential?" The master said: "Just now I heard the amnesty decree arrive." "What is the second essential?" "A hundred-thousand troops listening for the command." "What is the third essential?" "The great thousand sand-worlds illumined by a single wheel." The layman pressed: "Please, Master, overturn everything to the bottom and point directly to the supreme matter!" The master struck him.
E2: The master retold how Patriarch Linji entered the monks' hall with Minister Wang. The minister asked: "Do the monks here read sutras?" Linji said: "They do not." "Do they practice Chan?" "They do not." The minister said: "If they neither read sutras nor practice Chan, what on earth are they doing?" Linji said: "I'm just teaching every one of them to become buddhas and patriarchs." The minister said: "Gold dust, though precious, in the eyes becomes a disease." Linji said: "I had taken you for a layman of some understanding." The master commented: "If someone asked me 'Do the monks here read sutras?', I would say: 'Passing through ten-thousand blossoms, not a single petal sticks.' And if asked 'Do they practice Chan?', I would say: 'It fills the eyes and ears.' And if told 'Gold dust in the eyes becomes a disease,' I would say: 'Do not speak of sorrows to one already sorrowful.' Now tell me: is this the same as the ancients, or different?"

=== Bulinjian of Doushuai ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is Buddha?" The master said: "A mud pig." The monk said: "Then it is truly inconceivable!" The master said: "Sun, moon, and stars; mountains, rivers, and grasses."
E2: A monk asked: "What is the killing sword?" The master said: "It makes you stand right here just like this." The monk pressed: "What is the life-giving blade?" The master said: "It releases your life and opens your breath." The master then said: "The life-giving blade is beyond form and name. The killing sword leaves no dust, no trace. Pick them up and heaven and earth suddenly shift; set them down and the great earth shines anew. Here you must know the simultaneous use of illumination and function, the total seizure of person and environment, the single opening above, the transcendent wielding. If you speak of the single opening above and transcendent wielding, then both buddha and demon are dismissed, both sacred and ordinary forgotten -- only then is there a way in." He struck the platform and said: "The staff has eyes bright as the sun. To know true gold, test it in fire."

=== Caoshan Benji ===
E1: Caoshan asks Senior Monk De, "The Buddha's true dharma body is like empty space, responding to things and manifesting form like the moon in water. How would you speak of this responding principle?" De says, "Like a donkey looking into a well." Caoshan says, "You speak well enough, but you have spoken only eighty percent." De says, "Master, then how about you?" Caoshan says, "Like the well looking at the donkey."
E2: A monk asks Caoshan, "When the mourning garments are not worn, what then?" Caoshan says, "Caoshan today has fulfilled mourning." The monk says, "After mourning is fulfilled, what then?" Caoshan says, "Caoshan loves drunken wine."

=== Caoshan Yuanzheng ===
E1: A wandering ascetic known as the Paper-Robe Practitioner came to see Caoshan. The Master asked, "Are you the one they call the Paper-Robe Practitioner?" He replied, "I would not presume." The Master asked, "What is the matter beneath the paper robe?" The wanderer said, "The moment this single garment is draped on the body, all dharmas are just as they are." The Master asked, "What is the function beneath the paper robe?" The wanderer stepped forward, said "Yes," and died on the spot, standing upright. The Master said, "You only know how to go like that -- why don't you know how to come back?" At this, the wanderer suddenly opened his eyes and asked, "When the one true spirit-nature does not depend on a womb, what then?" The Master said, "That is not yet the marvelous." The wanderer asked, "What is the marvelous?" The Master said, "Not borrowing -- and yet borrowing." The wanderer said, "Farewell," and passed away for good. The Master composed a verse: "The awakened nature, perfectly luminous, is the formless body. Do not use knowledge and views to falsely estrange or befriend it. When a single thought deviates, the mysterious essence grows dim. When the mind errs, it no longer neighbors the Way."
E2: A monk asked, "Do the eyebrows and the eyes know each other?" Caoshan said, "They do not know each other." The monk asked, "Why don't they know each other?" Caoshan said, "Because they are in the same place." The monk said, "Then there is no distinction between them." Caoshan said, "The eyebrows are certainly not the eyes, and the eyes are certainly not the eyebrows." The monk asked, "What are the eyes?" Caoshan said, "They go straight to the point." The monk asked, "What are the eyebrows?" Caoshan said, "Caoshan has his doubts about that." The monk asked, "Why do you have doubts?" Caoshan said, "If I didn't have doubts, it would mean going straight to the point."

=== Caoyuan Daosheng ===
E1: Caoyuan ascended the hall at the Mid-Autumn Festival and raised a case: "Changsha and Yangshan were gazing at the moon together. Yangshan pointed at the moon and said, 'Everyone has this -- they just can't use it.' Changsha said, 'Precisely! I invite you to use it.' Yangshan said, 'How would you use it?' Changsha stepped forward and kicked Yangshan to the ground. Getting up, Yangshan said, 'You're just like a great tiger!'" Caoyuan then offered his own verse: "Floating clouds all scattered, the moon hangs in empty sky. The rabbit conceives and gives birth to a great tiger. It leaps before the wind, baring fangs and claws -- to this day it shakes the Cold Palace of the moon."
E2: A monk asked Caoyuan: "What is the Dharma-realm of noumenon?" He said: "One mote of dust enters true concentration." The monk asked: "What is the Dharma-realm of phenomena?" He said: "All motes of dust arise from samadhi." The monk asked: "What is the Dharma-realm of noumenon and phenomena without obstruction?" He said: "Spitting in the pure vase, defecating in the alms bowl." The monk asked: "What is the Dharma-realm of phenomena and phenomena without obstruction?" He said: "In a barren field, grab whatever grass comes to hand -- life and death, letting go and holding tight, all freely done." The monk asked: "You have shown me the Dharma-realms. What about the matter of the Supreme Vehicle?" Caoyuan said: "The more you talk, the further you get from the Way." Then he held up his palm: "The entire Buddhist canon is right here in the cracks of my fingernails. Spread open, it encompasses the three realms and wraps the ten directions -- jade turns, pearls revolve, illuminating heaven and reflecting earth. Pinch it together, and it becomes so fine and dense that not a thread leaks through."

=== CHANGLING SHOUZHUO ===
E1: Shouzhuo cited Master Chonghui: A monk asked, "Before Bodhidharma came to this land, was there Buddha-dharma or not?" Chonghui said, "Let that be for now -- what about the matter right before you?" The monk said, "I don't understand." Chonghui said, "Ten thousand ages of empty sky, a single dawn of wind and moon." After a long pause he added, "Do you understand? The matter of your own share -- what does his coming or not coming have to do with it? He came like a fortune-teller: seeing you don't understand, he cracks open the divination for you. Once the hexagram appears, fortune and misfortune are on your side -- look at it all yourself." The monk then asked, "What is one who understands divination?" Chonghui said, "The moment you step out the door, it's already wrong." Shouzhuo commented: "Chonghui was like a bell on a stand -- strike it and it rings. Good as that was, when it came to reading the hexagram, he still couldn't be truly precise. Just as before stepping out the door -- is it fortune? Is it misfortune? The bare-footed man catches the rabbit, while the man in boots eats the meat."
E2: A monk asked: "What is the host within the host?" Shouzhuo said, "When it is time to cut, cut -- and you will not invite disorder." The monk asked about the guest within the host, and so on through all four positions. When the monk bowed, Shouzhuo held up the whisk and said, "Host and guest are perfectly clear." Then he descended from the seat.

=== Changming Jiong of Pufeng ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is 'seizing the person but not the environment'?" The Master said: "Two eyes looking at the green mountains." "What is 'seizing the environment but not the person'?" "The whole body without a single thing." "What is 'both person and environment seized'?" "Clear sky without a patch of cloud." "What is 'neither person nor environment seized'?" "Sitting at ease beneath the pines." The monk pressed: "When black and white are not yet distinguished, and there is no person and no environment, where do you discern intimacy?" The Master held up his staff: "Look higher!"
E2: The Master cited the old case: "Yaoshan had not ascended the hall for a long time. The head monk asked him to speak for the assembly. Yaoshan ordered the drum struck, ascended the seat, sat for a long while, and descended. The head monk said: 'Everyone has long hoped for your instruction -- why did you not say a single word?' Yaoshan said: 'Sutras have sutra teachers, treatises have treatise teachers. How can you blame this old monk?'" The Master commented: "Old Yaoshan can truly be called unprecedented -- he held the critical pass. Too bad those who appreciate his kindness are few, while those who ignore it are many. If it were me and someone asked: 'Why not a single word?' I would just say: 'You cannot dig a hole in empty space.' And when they hesitated, I would give them a wild rain of blows across the back and drive them out."

=== Changmu Dian ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall and said: "The light of silent illumination pervades the sands of the Ganges; all beings, sacred and profane, share my home. When not a single thought arises, the whole body is manifest; the moment the six senses stir, clouds obscure it. Cut off afflictions and you only add more illness; pursue True Suchness and that too is error. Follow worldly conditions without hindrance -- nirvana and samsara are equally empty flowers." Then he said: "Scholar Zhang Zhuo put it that way -- beautiful, yes, but there is still a whiff of the vulgar. I say it differently: The light of silent illumination commands the sands of the Ganges; all beings, sacred and profane, have lost their way. When not a single thought arises, ride the jade elephant; the moment the six senses stir, slay the dragon-serpent. Cut off afflictions? -- that is just endless calculation. Pursue True Suchness? -- a rich man's extravagance. Don't say worldly conditions hold no hindrance -- the city playboy still pines for rouged blossoms."
E2: The Master ascended the hall and said: "The Fifth Patriarch Yan cast a heaven-wide net with military strategy -- even soaring phoenixes cannot escape his snare. But I say otherwise: the entire ten-direction world is the window frame; the entire ten-direction world is the iron ox's body; the entire ten-direction world is the iron ox's tail. Five organs, six viscera, liver, gall, intestines, and stomach -- node by node they connect. Eighty-four thousand pore-openings -- each one breathes. And yet this muddleheaded fellow clings to the tail like a starving dog gnawing a dry bone, refusing to let go even at the point of death."

=== Changqing Da'an ===
E1: Da'an instructed the assembly: "With phrase, without phrase, it is like a vine leaning on a tree." Shushan traveled four thousand li to ask him: "Suppose the tree falls and the vine withers -- what then?" Da'an set down his mud pan, laughed loudly, and returned to the abbot's room. Shushan chased after him: "I sold my cloth robe and came four thousand li especially for this. Master, how can you toy with me?" Da'an called the attendant: "Fetch money and repay him for his cloth robe, and send him off." Then he charged him: "Later a one-eyed dragon will come and break it open for you."
E2: Xuefeng once entered the mountains and found a branch of wood shaped like a snake. On its back he inscribed: "Originally natural, not needing carving." He sent it to Guishan Da'an. Da'an said, "A true mountain dweller, and without marks of knife or axe."

=== Changqing Huileng ===
E1: At summer's end, when Cuiyan asks if his eyebrows are still there, Changqing immediately says, "They grow."
E2: After Xuefeng says "Gather up the whole earth and it is like a millet grain," Changqing asks Yunmen, "When Xuefeng speaks like that, is there still a place where one cannot stick one's head out?" Yunmen says, "There is." Changqing says, "How?" Yunmen says, "You must not always make it into wild-fox-sprite views."

=== Changsha Jingcen ===
E1: One day Changsha went roaming in the mountains. When he returned, the head monk asked, "Master, where have you been?" Changsha said, "Roaming the mountains." The head monk said, "What places did you go to?" Changsha said, "At first I followed the fragrant grasses away; then I chased the falling blossoms back." The head monk said, "It greatly resembles springtime." Changsha said, "It even surpasses autumn dew dripping on lotus."
E2: One day Changsha and Yangshan were enjoying the moon. Yangshan pointed to the moon and said, "Everyone has this, but they cannot use it." Changsha said, "Exactly so. Then I'll ask you to use it." Yangshan said, "You try using it and see." Changsha took one step and knocked Yangshan down. Yangshan got up and said, "Uncle Master, you're like a great beast!" Later people called him Cen the Great Beast.

=== Chaozong ===
E1: A monk asked: "Pressed in from all four sides, where does one go?" The master said: "Go right here." The monk pressed: "But ultimately, where does one go?" The master said: "What kind of place do you think this is?" The monk bowed. The master said: "Now you've been pressed to death on all four sides."
E2: A monk asked: "If one understands at the first sentence, one is fit to be teacher of buddhas and patriarchs. What is the first sentence?" The master said: "Understand it before you even ask." The monk said: "If one understands at the second sentence, one is fit to be teacher of humans and gods. What is the second sentence?" The master said: "Just now I already said it and it passed." The monk said: "Then Sanskrit and Chinese can each sort it out on their own." The master said: "You're still dripping wet with complications." The monk began: "If one understands at the third sentence--" Before the words ended, the master struck him, saying: "That sentence is useless here." The monk protested: "Then the tangle of vines is cut and the wild fox's doubt laid to rest!" The master said: "I hear no lion's roar -- only the yelp of a jackal." The monk shouted. The master said: "Just as I expected." The monk shouted twice more and walked out.

=== CHAOZONG HUIFANG ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master cited: "Bodhidharma told the Second Patriarch: 'Simply let all conditions outside cease, and let the mind within have no panting. When the mind is like a wall, then you can enter the Way.' The Second Patriarch offered various explanations of mind and nature, but none hit the mark. Then one day he suddenly had a great awakening and said to Bodhidharma: 'Now I can let all conditions cease.' Bodhidharma said: 'Be careful not to fall into annihilation.' The Patriarch said: 'No.' Bodhidharma said: 'How so?' The Patriarch said: 'It is clearly and constantly known -- words cannot reach it.' Bodhidharma said: 'This is what all the buddhas have transmitted. Doubt no more.'" The Master commented: "If the mind is like a wall, why is there clear and constant knowing? If you can see into this, then you are one who eats rice all day long without ever biting a single grain, and the ten directions of empty space all vanish completely. If you cannot see into it, then karmic consciousness rushes on and on, cycling through the three paths of suffering -- with no end in sight."
E2: The Master cited: "On the road to Mount Wutai there was an old woman. Whenever a monk asked her, 'Which way to Mount Wutai?' she would say, 'Go straight ahead.' As soon as the monk took three or five steps, she would say, 'What a fine monk -- and yet he goes that way too.' Later a monk told Zhaozhou about this. Zhaozhou said, 'Wait -- I'll go test this old woman.' The next day he went and asked the same question. The old woman gave the same answer. Zhaozhou returned and told the assembly: 'I have seen through the old woman of Wutai.'" The Master commented: "One person reads the seedling to know the soil; one person stands at the cliff's edge without flinching. Do you want to know Zhaozhou? -- A tiger in the marketplace."

=== CHEWU ===
E1: Chewu recounts: When Shishuang passed away, the assembly proposed that Head Monk Tai succeed him as abbot. Attendant Jiufeng Qian objected: "If you would succeed as abbot, you must understand our late master's meaning." Tai said: "What meaning did our late master have? I cannot grasp it." Qian said: "Our late master always taught people: 'Rest! Cease! Be cold and still! Be like an ancient shrine with a cold incense burner! Be like a single strip of white silk! Be like ten thousand years in a single thought!' Setting the rest aside -- what is 'a single strip of white silk'?" Tai said: "This merely illuminates one-color-side of things." Qian said: "So you never understood our late master's meaning after all." Tai said: "Bring incense. If I fail to depart before the incense burns out, then I did not understand." They lit the incense; before it burned down, Tai died sitting upright. Qian patted his back and said: "Dying while sitting or standing -- that much is not lacking. But you haven't even dreamed of our late master's meaning." Meanwhile, at Caoshan's monastery, a wanderer wearing paper robes passed through the hall. Caoshan asked: "Are you the Paper-Robe Wanderer?" The wanderer said: "I would not presume." Caoshan asked: "What is the matter beneath the paper robe?" The wanderer said: "The moment one puts on this single garment, all dharmas are just thus." Caoshan asked: "What is the function beneath the paper robe?" The wanderer said: "Yes." And died on the spot. Caoshan said: "You only know how to go like that -- you don't know how to come." The wanderer opened his eyes again and asked: "When the one true nature does not depend on a womb for birth -- what then?" Caoshan said: "That is still not the marvelous." Chewu's comment: Dying while sitting or standing, even without understanding the great matter, is already no easy feat. If one could redirect that same spiritual energy single-mindedly toward buddha-recitation and seeking rebirth in the Pure Land, one would certainly attain the highest grade of birth -- and no one could find fault.
E2: Chewu tells: The monk Yingke was a man who made no distinction between wine and meat. Later he read the Records of Those Reborn in the Pure Land, and with each biography he read, he nodded in affirmation. He then stopped eating and recited the buddha-name. On the seventh day, the Buddha appeared and comforted him: "You still have ten years of life remaining. Practice buddha-recitation well, and I will come to receive you after ten years." Yingke said: "The saha world is turbid and evil -- it is easy to lose right mindfulness here. I wish to be born in the Pure Land soon, to serve the holy ones." The Buddha said: "Since your resolve is thus, I will come to receive you in three days." Three days later, he was indeed reborn.

=== Chijue Daochong ===
E1: Chijue raised: At Baofu's opening ceremony, Sansheng pushed a monk forward. Baofu immediately struck him. Sansheng said, "If you treat people like this, you'll blind not only this monk's eyes but the eyes of the whole city of Zhenzhou." Baofu returned to his quarters. Chijue commented: "Cast the hook in the four seas -- only to catch fierce dragons. When Luoshan said 'Farewell' and made to leave, that was somewhat better. But when he turned back and said 'Those who don't yet know, come forward' -- his heart, liver, and five organs were all seen through by that monk. Even so: the sky is high and all creatures find their proper course; the sea is vast and a hundred rivers pay homage."
E2: Chijue said: "The abbot's quarters are damaged -- I can't sleep there. The monastery has no provisions -- I can't keep monks. The old debts are piled like the sea -- I have no money to repay them. The Great Way is right before our eyes -- but I can't open my mouth to speak of it. If someone penetrates these four barriers, they are fit to serve as a model for all. Zhaozhou personally met old Nanquan -- in the Guanyin Temple there is indeed a Maitreya."

=== Chisongling ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master raised the case: "Seven wise women were walking through a charnel ground. One pointed at a corpse and said: 'The corpse is here -- where has the person gone?' Another said: 'What do you mean? What do you mean?' The sisters contemplated deeply and each attained realization. Indra scattered flowers in celebration." The Master raised his staff and said: "Look at this wooden fellow -- if you want to awaken, awaken now! What are you waiting for?" He struck the ground once and said: "If you awaken, a single hair-tip swallows the great ocean, and you know the whole earth is just one mote of dust."
E2: The Master cited the dialogue between Manjushri and the god Shanzhu about finding the Tathagata. When Shanzhu said "there is empty space before me," Manjushri replied: "The Tathagata is identical with empty space. Within this, there is not a single thing to discriminate." The Master said: "Manjushri cast his pearl into darkness, and the god unfortunately could not recognize the jewel. Were it up to me, when he said 'empty space is the Tathagata,' I would simply give one great shout. Why? One shout and all of empty space is shattered to dust -- where then could he find a place to stand?"

=== Chuanzi Decheng ===
E1: Jiashan Shanhui came to the Boatman's ferry. The Boatman asked, "What temple do you live in?" Jiashan said, "I don't live in a temple; where I live is not like anything." The Boatman said, "Not like anything -- what is it like?" Jiashan said, "It is not the Dharma before your eyes." The Boatman said, "Where did you learn this?" Jiashan said, "Neither ear nor eye can reach it." The Boatman said, "A single phrase following the ten thousand-foot fishing line; on the hook-tip, talk of the ultimate principle is different" -- and he pushed Jiashan into the water with his oar. When Jiashan clambered back into the boat, the Boatman said, "Speak! Speak!" As Jiashan opened his mouth, the Boatman hit him. Jiashan suddenly had great awakening. After transmitting the Dharma to Jiashan, the Boatman capsized his boat and disappeared into the water.
E2: Referenced throughout as "the boatman and Jiashan cutting it off." The commentary notes: "It is not that people today have no share in it; mostly they just greedily take the bait." The Boatman's style is praised as the ultimate in decisive transmission -- once the heir was confirmed, he destroyed his own teaching platform (the boat) entirely.

=== Chuiwan ===
E1: The senior monk came out and said: "The wind from the clouds comes to the dawn moon, the nine peaks chant with dragons." said the Master: "Sparse trees cross the old road, heaped stones flank the hill." The senior monk continued: "Then the whole earth has not an inch of ground, and I alone am honored." The Master said: "Where did you get that news?" The senior monk shouted. The Master said: "Try shouting again." The senior monk bowed. The Master said: "Just as I suspected -- all show and no substance."
E2: Ascending the hall: "Before your father and mother were born, what news was there? Stones in the sky clasp their hands; turtles in the trees bow in greeting. A mayfly's tail is three yards long; Mount Sumeru's peak is eight feet wide. Grind it all up fine into paste, and have Mr. Nothing bring it over -- it still won't make one mouthful for my staff."

=== Chuiwan Zhen of Juyun ===
E1: A monk came to visit. The Master asked: "Where from?" The monk said: "From Jinsu." The Master said: "What is the power-phrase you got at Jinsu?" The monk said: "White clouds cover the green mountains; the green mountains do not show their peaks." The Master said: "That is intellectual consciousness speaking. What is the power-phrase?" The monk said: "Empty space shatters, the great earth sinks flat." The Master said: "That is textbook-scholasticism speaking. What is the power-phrase?" The monk had no reply. The Master said: "You never came from Jinsu at all."
E2: Question: "When sound asleep, when dead and cremated -- mind and nature cannot reach each other. You must find the great function right here. What is this great function?" Answer: "Better to dress a demon-mask in the blazing sun than to play Avalokiteshvara in the dark."

=== Chulin ===
E1: Citing the case: Linji saw a monk coming and held up his whisk. The monk bowed; Linji struck him. Another monk came; Linji held up his whisk. The monk paid no attention; Linji also struck. A third monk came; Linji held up his whisk. The monk said: "Thank you for the instruction." Linji also struck. The master said: "One blow transcends Buddhas and Patriarchs. One blow mixes mud and water. One blow has no handle at all. If anyone can discern the three, they may stride freely under heaven."
E2: In a small talk, the master raised: "Panshan said: 'The upward path -- the thousand sages do not transmit it.' Ciming said: 'The upward path -- the thousand sages are not so.' Dahui said: 'The upward path -- the sound of a hot bowl.' " The master said: "These three great elders only managed to illuminate the downward path. As for the upward path -- even across three lives and sixty kalpas, what I see here at Xinghua, I still want all of you to know: the upward path is slippery."

=== Chunbeide ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall: "True emptiness, tranquil and still, without odor or sound. One nature, perfectly luminous, neither surplus nor lack. Why can't all of you directly take hold of it right now? Stop burying the Patriarch's mind beneath idle learning."
E2: The Master ascended the hall on account of an incident: "An ancient worthy said: 'A single grain of the donor's rice weighs as much as Mount Sumeru. If you fail to realize the Way, you will repay it by wearing fur and horns.' Tell me, how many pounds does this single grain weigh, that they say it weighs as much as Sumeru?" He then raised the case of Xuefeng serving as rice-steward under Guishan. Guishan entered the mill room and said: "Don't scatter what comes from the faithful of the ten directions." Xuefeng said: "I haven't scattered any." Guishan picked a single grain of rice from the ground and said: "Don't take this one grain lightly -- a hundred thousand grains are born from this one." Xuefeng said: "But tell me, where does this one grain come from?" Guishan lowered his head and returned to the abbot's room, then ascended the hall and addressed the assembly: "Eat carefully -- there are worms in the rice." the Master answered: "These two great elders looked after each other with nothing but love, entirely for the sake of the donors' faith and the practitioners' lifeblood, lest any of you indulge recklessly and fail to clarify your own affair."

=== Chushi Fanqi ===
E1: A monk asked: "They say, 'Do not worry about thoughts arising -- only fear being slow to notice them.' What is this noticing?" The master said: "Ox horns, horse horns." The monk pressed: "What then is a thought?" The master said: "You cannot even figure out that four times five is twenty."
E2: New Year's Eve, evening talk. Chushi said: "Panshan said, 'The upward path -- a thousand sages have not transmitted it.' Ciming said, 'The upward path -- a thousand sages would not consider it so.' Miaoxi (Dahui) said, 'The upward path -- the sound of a hot bowl.' " The Master commented: "These three venerable elders spoke with all their might, but they only illuminated the downward path. As for the upward path -- will you see it even in the Year of the Donkey?"

=== Cuiwei Wuxue ===
E1: Longya asked Cuiwei, "What is the meaning of the Patriarch's coming from the West?" Cuiwei said, "Hand me the Chan board." Longya handed the Chan board to Cuiwei. Cuiwei took it and struck him.
E2: Touzi visited Cuiwei Wuxue. He met him pacing in the hall and asked, "The hidden meaning of the Patriarch coming from the West -- Master, how is it shown to people?" Cuiwei stopped pacing and looked at him. Touzi said, "I beg the Master to point it out." Cuiwei said, "Do you want a second ladle of foul water too?" Touzi suddenly awakened. He bowed in thanks and withdrew. Cuiwei said, "Do not fall away." Touzi said, "When the time comes, root and sprout of themselves grow."

=== CUIYABI (Bi of Yongshou) ===
E1: A monk asked about the Three Mysteries and Three Essentials. "What is the first mystery?" said the Master: "The iron cow doing somersaults on a swing." "What is the second mystery?" "The wooden horse climbing a high pole." "What is the third mystery?" "The stone woman laughing before the eaves." "What is the first essential?" "Release the heaven-piercing hawk." "What is the second essential?" "The blazing sun illuminating the open sky." "What is the third essential?" "Who can thread the single-line path?"
E2: While wandering in the mountains, the Master saw the characters "Huiji Chan Monastery" carved on a cliff. He asked a monk: "Where is Huiji?" The monk said: "Half a mile ahead." The Master pointed at the cliff: "Then what is this place?" The monk had no reply. The Master said: "Only because it is too close." A boy standing nearby said: "Only because it is too far." The Master said: "Where is the fault?" The boy said: "Too many paths." the Master replied: "Where is your path?" The boy drew a line on the ground with his stick and said: "Right here." said the Master: "Whoever enters by this way must not forget it." The boy said: "I won't forget." the Master responded: "I feared it was not jade -- but if it is jade, that is truly remarkable."

=== Cuiyan Lingcan ===
E1: At summer's end, Cuiyan addresses the assembly: "All summer long, for you brothers I have spoken to you. Tell me, are Cuiyan's eyebrows still there?" Baofu says, "A thief has a guilty heart." Changqing says, "They grow." Yunmen says, "Barrier."
E2: A Huayan lecture master invites Cuiyan for a meal. Cuiyan says, "This mountain monk has a question; if you answer it, then I will attend." He picks up a sesame cake and says, "Does this possess the dharma-body?" The lecturer says, "It does." Cuiyan says, "If so, then you are eating the dharma-body." The lecturer has no reply.

=== Dabian Quan ===
E1: The Master asked a monk: "Where from?" The monk said: "From Guoqing." said the Master: "If the country is pure, why are signal-fires burning everywhere and swords and spears covering the ground?" The monk hesitated. The Master said: "You yourself, Reverend, are right in the middle of the turmoil."
E2: A monk asked: "When sound asleep -- no dreaming, no thinking, no seeing, no hearing -- where does the master of the house reside?" The Master said: "Let me ask you first: during the broad daylight bustle, where does the master of the house reside?" The monk slapped the table once. The Master said: "That is the force of wind; in the end it leads to ruin." The monk said: "The turtle in the jar does not escape." the Master replied: "The turtle in the jar does not escape, yet fire in the midst of it still produces smoke."

=== Daboqian ===
E1: The Master raised the old case: "An ancient said: 'This matter is like a water buffalo passing through a window lattice -- the head, horns, and four hooves all pass through, but only the tail cannot get through.'" Then he laughed loudly and said: "Separating milk from water in a single stream -- only the king of geese can do that."
E2: He raised the case: "An old woman donated money and asked Zhaozhou to chant the entire Great Treasury of scriptures. Zhaozhou descended from his seat, walked once around it, and said: 'The chanting of the Treasury is complete.' When told, the old woman said: 'I asked you to chant the whole Treasury -- why did you only chant half?'" The Master called to the assembly: "So what is that other half?" He descended from the seat.

=== Dachuan Puji ===
E1: A monk asked Caoshan: "What was it like before the Buddha appeared in the world?" Caoshan said, "Caoshan is not his equal." The monk asked, "What about after he appeared?" Caoshan said, "Not Caoshan's equal." Dachuan commented: "Do you want to know Caoshan? Ever since he gave himself over to that handsome lord, he has lost all shame before others."
E2: Dachuan raised: National Teacher Drum Mountain addressed the assembly: "Within Drum Mountain's gates, no one is permitted even to cough." A monk coughed once. The master said, "What was that?" The monk said, "A cold." Dachuan commented: "The National Teacher's command silenced the whole earth, yet he could not cover that monk's mouth. Still, do you want to know that monk? He would not rest until he reached the banks of the Wu River."

=== Dafang ===
E1: A layman asked: "Greedy for life and afraid of death -- how can one find peace?" The master said: "Life is born from the unborn -- just as in the depths of winter, water becomes ice. Death dies from the undying -- just as when the sun comes out, ice becomes water. The one who comes is the same as the one who goes. Cut off the marks of coming and going -- tell me, who is it?" He shouted once and said: "Just empty out all that exists -- where then is there no elegance?" The laypeople bowed in thanks and withdrew.
E2: Before planting trees at the hermitage, the master addressed the assembly: "Come, all of you! Arouse the mind of awakening, plant the bodhi tree, enter the bodhi field, realize the bodhi fruit." He struck the ground with his staff and said: "On this patch of earth, worldly and world-transcending, adorn the Buddha-land, benefit self and other, illuminate past and present. The ape cradles its young and returns to the fragrant grass; birds sing and flowers smile by the emerald stream. Clearly these are the grounds of our mountain gate." Then, holding his staff horizontally, he said: "Having cut off the road for saints and ordinary beings alike, how shall we communicate?" He gave a shout and said: "When the mind is empty, one graduates and goes home."

=== Daguang Juhui ===
E1: ---
E2: ---

=== Dahui Zonggao ===
E1: At an evening gathering, the Master said: "The Great Way is right before your mouth -- yet it is hard to perceive what is right before your eyes. If you want to know the Great Way's true substance, it does not depart from sound, form, and language." He held up the whisk and said, "This is form." He struck the seat and said, "This is sound. Right now my mouth keeps moving -- these are words. Which one is the true substance of the Great Way?" He gave a shout and said: "This seeing and hearing is not seeing and hearing; beyond it there is no further sound or form to present to you. If you understand this completely, there is nothing more to do. Substance and function may be divided or undivided as you please." "If you do divide them: when rain falls the ground is wet; when the sky clears the sun comes out; in a short month there are twenty-nine days; in a long month, thirty." "If you do not divide them: the Diamond Guardian scrubs the Earth God's back, and one rub strips away the bones." He continued: "An ancient said, 'The last word -- only then do you arrive at the barrier gate. Seize the essential crossing and let neither ordinary nor sacred pass.' What is this last word?" After a long pause he said, "Don't talk about dreams." He slapped the seat and descended.
E2: At his opening sermon at Jingshan, after several monks competed in questions, the Master halted them and said: "Suppose every blade of grass and every tree on the great earth were ground to dust, and every single dust-mote had a mouth, and every mouth possessed an infinite, broad, long tongue, and every tongue produced immeasurable varieties of sound, and every sound expressed immeasurable varieties of words, and every word contained immeasurable varieties of subtle meaning. Suppose monks as numerous as those dust-motes, each endowed with such mouths, such tongues, such sounds, such words, such meanings, were simultaneously to hurl a hundred thousand challenges at me, each question different from the rest -- the Abbot of Jingshan would not need more than a single cough to answer them all at once. And in the space between, he would perform limitless, boundless, vast buddha-work -- each act of buddha-work pervading the entire dharma realm. But even going on like this, though it makes for a bustling, lively assembly hall -- if examined with the true eye, it is nothing but the surging ocean of karmic consciousness, with no real ground to stand on. Under the patriarch's gate, not a single bit of it is of any use."

=== DAI'AN PUZHUANG ===
E1: The Master was hoeing weeds when a monk asked: "When will this patch of ground be completely cleared?" The Master held up the hoe and said, "You are not allowed to call this a hoe. What do you call it, Reverend?" The monk had no reply. The Master tossed down the hoe and said, "When will this patch of ground be completely cleared?"
E2: The Master ascended the hall: "Last night in a dream I raised a single case, and three people in the assembly attained awakening. I was going to wait until dawn and present it to all of you, but I've completely forgotten it. Let me think about it some more." After a long silence, he said: "All of you have come here to listen to me talk about a dream -- what's the point?" He seized his staff and chased everyone out.

=== Damei Fachang ===
E1: Mazu was asked by Damei: "What is Buddha?" Mazu said: "Mind itself is Buddha." Years later, when Mazu had changed his teaching to "Not mind, not Buddha," a monk went to tell Damei. Damei said: "That old fellow confuses people endlessly. Let him have his 'not mind, not Buddha' -- I just stay with 'mind itself is Buddha.'" When Mazu heard this, he said: "The plum is ripe."
E2: A monk asked Damei: "What is the meaning of the Patriarch coming from the West?" Damei said: "Coming from the West has no meaning." Yanguan heard and said: "One coffin, two dead fellows."

=== Dangui of Danxia ===
E1: Ascending the hall: "A person who has truly broken through -- among a thousand thoughts and ten thousand thoughts, not a single one flows into a second thought. It is not that there are no thoughts; it is only that they do not continue. Within continuation, there is no continuation. This non-continuation is not something you cobble together in a moment or accumulate through years of practice. You must awaken to achieve it, and awakening must go all the way to the bottom in a single step."
E2: One day it was raining. The Master glanced at a monk and said: "What is that sound at the eaves?" The monk said: "I don't know." The Master cocked his ear: "You don't even recognize the sound of rain."

=== Danxia Tianran ===
E1: After studying with Shitou for three years, Danxia went to visit Mazu. Before paying respects, he went into the monks' hall and sat astride the neck of the holy monk statue. The assembly was horrified and rushed to report. Mazu personally entered the hall, looked at him, and said: "My son Tianran." Danxia came down and bowed: "I thank the master for granting me a Dharma name."
E2: Danxia asks a monk: "Where have you come from?" The monk: "From below the mountain." Danxia: "Have you eaten yet?" The monk: "I have eaten." Danxia: "The one who brought the food for you to eat -- does he still have eyes?" The monk had no words.

=== Danxia Zichun ===
E1: New Year's Eve, evening talk. The Master said: "Tonight the year is exhausted and the age is done. Tomorrow morning we change the calendar and welcome spring. Time flies and does not spare anyone -- teeth and hair are worn, yet another year is added. Great assembly, time shifts and passes, thought after thought is impermanent. Time does not wait for people -- how long can life last? Everyone knows that today is the thirtieth of the twelfth month. But have you prepared for today's business? Have you all gathered wealth as your preparation? Have you read and studied the sutras as your preparation? Have you memorized practice instructions as your preparation? Have you cultivated cleverness of mind as your preparation? At the very moment when the light drains from your eyes and your hands and feet are in confusion, everything you ever memorized is forgotten in an instant. At this point you absolutely must have your feet on solid ground -- you cannot get by on bluffing. All of you, in your daily life, hurry up and put things to rest. Prepare for it. Let go of everything in the present. Go sit cold in the hall of dead wood. You absolutely must die once. Then from within death, establish yourself anew. No place can deceive you then, no place can turn you. Every place, you are free. As it is said: 'Let go with both hands on the cliff edge -- accept and affirm on your own. After the absolute death, come back to life -- then no one can fool you.' If you can do this, then a hurricane can topple mountains and yet all is still; rivers rush to the sea and yet nothing flows; wild horses gallop in the wind and yet nothing moves; sun and moon cross the sky and yet nothing revolves. If not, then: 'You only know that things pass before your eyes -- you don't notice that old age comes down upon your head.' "
E2: The Master ascended the hall, held up his whisk, and said: "Dahong's whisk -- raise it, and spring light is lovely, ten thousand trees hold their fragrance. Put it down, and not a blade of grass grows, the whole sky is one color. Even so, examined carefully, this is still the den of ordinary people. How does one actually walk through these two paths?" After a long silence he said: "Do you understand? Just get the spring wind warm and gentle, and naturally the flowers on the shady side will bloom."

=== Danyayuan of Tongtian ===
E1: The Master raised this case: An old woman had supported a hermit monk for twenty years, regularly sending a young woman to bring his meals. One day she told the girl to embrace the monk and ask: "What is it like just at this moment?" The monk replied: "A withered tree leaning against a cold cliff -- no warmth in the three winters." The girl reported this. The old woman said: "For twenty years I've been feeding nothing but a common fellow!" She drove him out and burned down the hermitage. The Master commented: "This monk sat alone on his cold cliff, not knowing that spring was already unfolding outside his walls. The old woman tested him in secret, but who could say the jade was flawless from the start? Why? Have you not seen -- deep in the snow on the mountain ridge, the plum tree's cloudy hair has not yet been combed."
E2: The Master addressed the assembly: "Avalokiteshvara Bodhisattva took money to buy flatbread, but when he set it down, it turned out to be a steamed bun. Tell me, where is the crux of this matter?" After a pause: "It was only after cutting the grass short that they discovered the ground was uneven."

=== DAODENG OF KONGGU ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master raised a case: "When the World-Honored One descended from the Trayastrimsha Heaven where he had taught the Dharma for his mother, King Udayana's sandalwood image also came outside to greet him. The World-Honored One called three times and it responded three times. Then he said: 'The true, unconditioned Buddha is actually within my own body.' Tell me, which body is the real Buddha?" He exclaimed: "Look carefully from the beginning to the end -- there are not two! Three calls and three responses -- the real Buddha is still just me. Ha! The sandalwood and Gautama -- do not foolishly split them into two!"
E2: A monk asked: "When good and evil are both unborn, what then?" The Master said: "Earth, wood, tiles, and stones." The monk continued: "When all kinds of mind arise, what then?" the Master answered: "Toads and mice." The monk said: "Both arising and non-arising miss the mark. What then is correct?" the Master responded: "Green mountains, clear water -- within the home there is a true Buddha." The monk bowed.

=== Daoxin (Fourth Patriarch) ===
E1: The young Daoxin came to the Third Patriarch Sengcan and said: "I beg the Master's compassion. Please teach me the dharma gate of liberation." Sengcan said: "Who binds you?" Daoxin said: "No one binds me." Sengcan said: "Then why seek liberation?" At these words, Daoxin had a great awakening.
E2: ---

=== Dasui Fazhen ===
E1: A monk asked Dasui, "When the kalpa fire rages and the great thousand worlds are all destroyed, I wonder -- does this get destroyed or not?" Dasui said, "Destroyed." The monk said, "In that case, it goes along with it?" Dasui said, "It goes along with it." Later, the monk carried this question all the way to Touzi in Shuzhou. When Touzi heard it, he burned incense and bowed, saying, "In Western Shu an ancient Buddha has appeared in the world. You should quickly return." The monk returned, but Dasui had already passed away.
E2: When Dasui was cook under Guishan, Guishan said, "You've been here for several years, yet you still don't know how to bring a question and show it -- how about that?" Dasui said, "What should you have me ask to make it?" Guishan said, "You just don't know to ask, 'What is Buddha?'" Dasui used his hand to cover Guishan's mouth. Guishan said, "After this, you won't even find someone to sweep the ground."

=== Daxiaochong ===
E1: The Master took up his staff, struck it once, gave a shout, and said: "Linji and Deshan have arrived! They are debating doctrine right on the head of my staff, and the staff cannot suppress them. Right now, if anyone does not fear for his life, let him come out and meet them." A monk stepped forward. The Master struck him and said: "Deshan's blows, Linji's shouts -- today I crack them open for you anew. Those on the left must accept this squarely. Those on the right need not deliberate further. Old Man Pang sold bamboo strainers. Puhua shook his bell." He struck the staff again and gave another shout.
E2: On the third anniversary of Master Gaofeng's death, the Master pointed at the portrait and said: "This old fellow with his demon face and spirit head has no shame that cannot be washed away. His whole body has fallen into the hands of his unworthy son, to be killed or spared, captured or released, picked up or set down at will. Before the eighteenth day, there was a tail but no head -- at midnight the sun shone red. After the eighteenth day, there was a head but no tail -- at noon the stars appeared. Right now on the eighteenth day, what then? Going on like this: leaving the door, one does not walk on green grass. Staying like this: returning home, one does not sit on a white-cloud bed. If among the assembly there is a sharp monk who says: 'Elder! Whose family's words are you -- a Linji descendant -- speaking?' I would simply say: 'Today is the Old Man's death anniversary. Even this one offering cannot be spared.'"

=== Daxiu Zhu ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the complete functioning, the great activity? Please, Master, say one phrase." The Master said: "I won't strike a snake that's not threatening anyone."
E2: A monk asked: "Clean and pure in original nature -- whence comes karma?" The Master spread both hands and said: "Clean and pure in original nature -- whence comes karma?" Then he said: "If you can directly understand such a question and answer, you will not fall into conceptual thought."

=== Dayang Jingxuan ===
E1: Dongshan asks: "Where for ten thousand miles there is not an inch of grass -- how do you go there?" Shishuang answers: "As soon as you go out the gate, it is grass." Dayang counters: "Straight talk -- if you do not go out the gate, it is also grass stretching everywhere." Then adds: "Do not keep to a cold cliff where strange grass grows green; sitting fixed in white clouds is not the school's marvel."
E2: Dayang Ming'an ascended the hall and said: "Do not travel the road of mind-made places. Do not sit in the achievement of nowhere. Being and nonbeing both left behind, vast and open, heaven and earth are empty."

=== Dayutao of Guoqing ===
E1: The Master addressed the assembly, raising the old case of Nanquan cutting the cat when the two halls of monks quarreled. Zhaozhou later returned, put his sandals on his head and walked out. Nanquan said, "If you had been there, you would have saved the cat." The Master said: "Old Wang [Nanquan] spent thirty years and only managed to kill one cat. He thought he had the market cornered. But Zhaozhou, with nothing but a broken straw sandal, casually opened an enormous shop and seized the high ground -- leaving everyone under heaven with money to buy but nothing left to wear. Today at Guoqing I will give the assembly a expedient means." He spat once and descended the seat.
E2: A monk asked Zhaozhou, "Does the cypress tree in the garden also have buddha-nature?" Zhaozhou said, "It does." "When will it become a buddha?" "When empty space falls to the ground." "When will empty space fall to the ground?" "When the cypress tree becomes a buddha." The Master gave a shout and said: "Empty space has already fallen! The cypress tree has already become a buddha!"

=== Dazhu Huihai ===
E1: When the Master first arrived in Jiangxi to study with Mazu, Mazu asked, "Where have you come from?" He said, "From the Great Cloud Monastery in Yuezhou." Mazu said, "What do you intend by coming here?" He said, "I have come seeking the buddha-dharma." Mazu said, "You ignore your own treasure house and run away from home scattering yourself everywhere -- what for? Here I have not a single thing. What 'buddha-dharma' are you seeking?" The Master then bowed and asked, "Which is Huihai's own treasure house?" Mazu said, "That which is asking me right now -- that is your treasure house. It is completely furnished, lacking nothing whatsoever. It is free for you to use. Why are you seeking outside?" At these words, the Master had a great awakening and recognized his own original mind, not through conceptual knowledge. He leaped up and bowed in gratitude. He served the Master for six years.
E2: A group of sutra lecturers came to visit. One said, "We wish to put a question to you. Will the Master respond?" The Master said, "The moon reflected in the deep pool -- pluck at it as you please." They asked, "What is Buddha?" the Master asked, "A clear conversation face to face -- if it is not Buddha, what is it?" The whole group was bewildered. After a long pause, a monk asked again, "What dharma does the Master teach to save people?" The Master said, "This poor monk has never had a single dharma to save people." The monk said, "All you Chan masters are just like this." The Master asked him, "What dharma does the venerable sir teach to save people?" The monk said, "I lecture on the Diamond Sutra." The Master said, "How many times have you lectured on it?" The monk said, "More than twenty times." The Master said, "Who spoke this sutra?" The monk raised his voice: "Master, are you mocking me? Don't you know the Buddha spoke it?" The Master said, "The sutra itself says: 'If anyone claims the Tathagata has spoken any dharma, that person slanders the Buddha and does not understand my meaning.' But if you say this sutra was not spoken by the Buddha, then you slander the sutra. Please, venerable sir, explain." The monk had no reply. After a moment, the Master asked, "The sutra says, 'If you see me through forms, if you seek me through sounds, that person walks a deviant path and cannot see the Tathagata.' Tell me, venerable sir -- which one is the Tathagata?" The monk said, "At this point I find myself confused." The Master said, "You were never enlightened in the first place -- what do you mean 'confused'?" The monk said, "Please, Chan Master, explain for me." The Master said, "You have lectured on this sutra more than twenty times, and you still do not recognize the Tathagata?" The monk bowed again and begged for instruction. The Master said, "'Tathagata' means the suchness of all dharmas. How could you forget?" The monk said, "Yes, yes -- the suchness of all dharmas." said the Master, "Is your 'yes' truly a 'yes,' or not yet?" The monk said, "The sutra text is perfectly clear -- how could it not be so?" the Master asked, "Are you 'thus'?" The monk said, "I am." The Master said, "Are wood and stones 'thus'?" The monk said, "They are." the Master asked, "Is your 'thus' the same as the 'thus' of wood and stones?" The monk said, "No different." The Master said, "Then how are you different from wood and stones?" The monk had no reply. He sighed and said, "This is a person whom it is truly difficult to answer." After a long pause, he asked, "How does one attain great nirvana?" The Master said, "Do not create the karma of birth and death." The monk said, "What is the karma of birth and death?" the Master responded, "Seeking great nirvana -- that is the karma of birth and death. Discarding defilement and grasping purity -- that is the karma of birth and death. Having attainment and having realization -- that is the karma of birth and death. Not transcending the gate of antidotes -- that is the karma of birth and death." The monk said, "Then how can one be liberated?" The Master said, "You have never been bound in the first place. Why seek to be freed? Act directly, go directly -- that is the unequaled equality." The monk said, "A Chan master like yourself is truly rare." He bowed in thanks and departed.

=== Deshan Xuanjian ===
E1: Deshan consulted Longtan into the night. Longtan said, "The night is deep -- why do you not go down?" Deshan lifted the blind and went out. Seeing it was dark outside, he returned and said, "It is dark outside." Longtan lit a paper candle and handed it over. As Deshan was about to take it, Longtan blew it out. At that moment, Deshan was suddenly awakened. The next day, before the Dharma hall, Deshan set a torch to his commentarial notes, saying, "To exhaust all subtle discriminations is like a single hair sent into the great void."
E2: One day Deshan carried his bowl down from the hall. Xuefeng asked, "Old fellow, the bell has not yet been rung and the drum has not yet sounded -- where are you carrying your bowl to?" Deshan returned to his quarters. Xuefeng told Yantou. Yantou said, "Great Deshan has not yet understood the last phrase." Deshan heard of it and called Yantou in. Yantou secretly revealed his meaning. The next day Deshan ascended the seat, and indeed it was different from usual. Yantou clapped his hands and laughed: "How glad I am the old fellow has understood the last phrase. Hereafter, people under heaven will have nothing they can do about him."

=== Donglin Changzong ===
E1: Donglin Changzong versified: "The hundred negations and four propositions cut off no words."
E2: Donglin Changzong held up his whisk when the monk Shaoci came. Ci was about to speak. Changzong struck him with the whisk twice. Ci immediately seized the whisk. Changzong said, "How dare you do that?" Ci replied, "The whisk now belongs to Ci."

=== Dongshan Liangjie ===
E1: Yunmen asked Dongshan, "Where have you just come from?" Dongshan said, "Chadu ford." Yunmen said, "Where did you spend the summer?" Dongshan said, "Baozi in Hunan." Yunmen said, "When did you leave there?" Dongshan said, "The twenty-fifth day of the eighth month." Yunmen said, "I spare you three blows." The next day Dongshan went to Yunmen and asked, "Yesterday you spared me three blows. I do not know where my fault lies." Yunmen said, "You rice-bag! Going about Jiangxi and Hunan this way!" At this Dongshan had great awakening.
E2: Dongshan was unwell. A monk asked, "When master is sick, is there one who is not sick?" Dongshan said, "There is." The monk asked, "Does the one not sick still look after master?" Dongshan said, "This old monk has a share in looking at him." The monk asked, "When master looks at him, how is it?" Dongshan said, "Then no sickness is seen." Later, after his verse, he had his head shaved, bade farewell, and sat to pass away. The assembly wailed. Dongshan opened his eyes and reproved their foolishness. He then extended his stay by seven days before finally departing.

=== Dongyan of Huanglian ===
E1: The Master was sitting with the assembly around the stove. A monk asked: "What is the meaning of the Patriarch's coming from the West?" The Master said: "One stove of flames, a few pieces of dead firewood." The monk said: "I don't understand." the Master replied: "Your whole body is warm."
E2: The Master asked a monk: "Who is that behind you?" The monk said: "I'm a newcomer." The Master said: "You've been in the hall for three days already -- how can you still be a newcomer?" The monk had no reply. the Master answered: "Go do walking practice."

=== DOUNAN WEI ===
E1: The Master returned to his tonsure temple. The Dharma Master asked: "What did the various teachers say to you?" The Master said: "Please, Dharma Master, guard your mouth carefully." The Dharma Master said: "Have you been to Guishan?" "Yes." "How about the water-buffalo affair?" The Master said: "Treading through mud and water, dragging the plow and pulling the harrow." The Dharma Master said: "I asked about the water buffalo, and you talk about plowing. If I ask you, 'What is Buddha?' -- how would you answer?" The Master turned to a pillar and made a woman's bow, saying: "Take care!" The Dharma Master was dumbfounded. The Master clapped his hands and walked out.
E2: Master Fayu asked: "My heart is in pain -- can you cure it?" the Master asked: "You are a person of no-mind. From where does this pain come?" Fayu walked briskly back to his quarters. The Master said: "That old fellow -- one question from me and his mouth went completely mute." A monk nearby said: "Don't slander the Master." The Master slapped the monk. The monk said: "Why did you hit me?" The Master said: "Deliver that to the abbot." The monk said: "Why?" The Master said: "Stop putting on airs."

=== Doushuai Congyue ===
E1: Master Tusita Yue set up three barriers to question students: "Brushing aside grass to investigate the mysterious only seeks to see one's nature -- right now, where is the venerable one's nature?" "Recognize your own nature, and only then escape birth and death -- when the light of the eyes falls, how do you escape?" "Escape birth and death, and then you know where you go -- when the four elements separate, where do you go?" Wumen: "If you can bring forth these three turning phrases, then you can, wherever you are..."
E2: ---

=== Duanqiao Miaolun ===
E1: Duanqiao entered the Buddha Hall. "Two thousand years ago, I was not as good as you. Two thousand years from now, you will not be as good as me." He lifted the incense and said: "Look! In a cold place, I'll light a fire for you."
E2: Duanqiao ascended the hall and raised a case: "Ananda asked Kashyapa, 'Besides the golden robe that the World-Honored One bequeathed to you, what else did he transmit?' Kashyapa called out, 'Ananda!' Ananda responded. Kashyapa said, 'Knock down the flagpole in front of the gate.'" Duanqiao offered his verse: "The house style of a down-and-out family -- both brothers know it well. Coarse tea and plain rice, leaning on each other for a while. When the brothers have finally settled accounts, the autumn wind at the front gate blows the evening cool."

=== Dulang ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the master gave a thunderous shout, held up his whisk, and looked left and right. He said: "Last night at midnight I beat the featherless iron hawk to death. This morning upon rising, it suddenly leapt up from the ground and flew high, smashing through the palace of blue lapis lazuli, drying up the waters of the four oceans. Mountains, rivers, and the great earth -- whether half-revealed or fully-revealed -- none of this has anything to do with it. Indeed -- unless the person is beyond measure, the words cannot be beyond measure." He gave another shout and descended.
E2: The master asked a monk: "Before ascending the jeweled seat, where was I?" He struck him. The monk pressed: "After descending, where will you go?" He struck again. The monk pressed: "Right now on the jeweled seat, what exactly are you teaching?" He struck a third time.

=== Ehu Dayi ===
E1: Baofu asked Ehu about a place of meeting: "Set aside 'in front of the monks' hall' for the moment -- what is the place of meeting at Wangzhou Pavilion and Wushi Ridge?" Ehu simply strode back to the abbot's quarters.
E2: Li Ao asked Ehu, "What does Great Compassion use a thousand hands and eyes for?" Ehu said, "What does the emperor use you for?"

=== Er'an Song ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is motion?" The Master stepped forward. "What is stillness?" The Master stood stock-still. "What about neither motion nor stillness?" the Master replied: "Where is your mouth?"
E2: A monk asked: "What is the Guiyang school?" The Master said: "Shut your dog-mouth." "The Caodong school?" "Open the door, close your eyes, and look." "The Yunmen school?" "Water dripping from a high cliff." "The Fayan school?" "Just this." The monk pressed: "And the other school?" The Master struck him and said: "A biting wind howls, as if in the Snow Range mountains; jade sleet whirls, as if by Bear's Ear Peak. Last night this mountain monk seized the Dragon King of the sea and gave him a blow -- blood flowed everywhere, scales flew in all directions, scattering into the five gates. This morning they are sorted into lineage-teachings. But tell me -- beneath whose jaw has the bright pearl fallen?"

=== Eryin Mi ===
E1: Eryin ascended the hall: "Third day of the fourth month, the rice seedlings are just green. The old farmer leads the crew to open the paddies. A tuneless ditty -- a field song of joy -- how many are really listening? If you can hear the field-song, you can settle the universe with a single blade of grass. Plant one paddy and a thousand, ten thousand paddies are not fallow. Cross-hauling, lengthwise-dragging, seven zigzags and eight tangles -- it all comes naturally. But enough of the farming song. How do you sing the field-tune?" He sang out: "Pomegranate flowers! Green leaves! When the season comes, don't dawdle! Beat the drum -- general assembly -- now look: how many are actually in the field?"
E2: The master ascended the hall: "Dragon lanterns butt heads, smoke-trees scatter blossoms, fire spits in people's faces, the pain goes straight through to Shakyamuni. Right at this moment, where is the Ancient Lamp Buddha? Arms round each other's shoulders, the whole drunk crowd -- at midnight, flutes and songs carry them home."

=== Erzhan Zun of Shishuang ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the first mystery?" The Master said: "A broken dung-scraper." "What is the second mystery?" -- "A bald broom." "What is the third mystery?" -- "A bottomless bowl." "What is the first essential?" -- "Two-faced and three-headed." "What is the second essential?" -- "Throwing east, tossing west." "What is the third essential?" -- "The arrow has passed beyond India." The monk bowed. the Master answered: "I deeply appreciate your exertion."
E2: The Master addressed the assembly: "Vulture Peak, the flower held up, Kashyapa's smile -- that is pressing the ox's head to make it eat grass. Bodhidharma facing the wall, the Second Patriarch pacifying mind -- pressing the ox's head to eat grass. All the great masters since, with their devices for snatching food and driving plows -- every last one, pressing the ox's head to eat grass. If some monk came forward and said: 'Master, what you're saying is also pressing the ox's head to eat grass' -- I would burst out laughing and happily give him half the monastery. Why? These days, in all of Wu and Zhejiang, that kind of mettle is rare."

=== FACHANG YIYU ===
E1: Ascending the hall, a monk asked: "What about the ancient mirror before it is polished?" The Master said: "You still need to polish it." The monk pressed: "I don't know how to set my hand to it." The Master said: "Where is the mirror?" The monk drew a circle in the air. The Master struck him and said: "You lacquer bucket! You can't even recognize a brick!" The Master then addressed the assembly: "The Patriarch came from the West specifically to proclaim this matter -- just wanting people of the present to know they have it. Like the jewel sewn in the poor man's robe, it is not obtained from another. The Buddhas of the three worlds are merely people who play with the jewel. The bodhisattvas of the ten stages are people who seek the jewel. All of you are precisely the destitute beggars who carry the treasure while lost and confused. A sharp fellow need only blink the moment he hears this, and he knows where it lands. But take one step further, and you'd do better to grab your staff and head back to the mountain -- a long whistle, and the mist deepens."
E2: When Chan Master Huanglong Nan arrived, the Master ascended the hall. A monk asked: "When two dragons contend for the pearl, what then?" the Master answered: "Fachang is small in stature but great in encounters." The monk pressed: "What if they suddenly overturn the pools and topple the peaks?" The Master struck him. The monk said: "There was a question and an answer -- why didn't you distinguish host from guest?" The Master said: "That blow just now -- was it host or guest?" The monk said: "Student and teacher share it together." The Master said: "You lacquer bucket!" And struck again. The monk said: "If not for the fisherman's guidance, how would one ever see the waves?" The Master said: "Don't insult Huanglong with your dullness." The monk bowed. The Master said: "Told you to stop and you wouldn't stop." Afterward, the Master and Huanglong exchanged verses: Huanglong wrote: "Wearing a flowered turban, he left Shaoshi; carrying a straw hat, he departed Chang'an. At Vulture Peak they meet again -- the nostrils turn out to be just the same." Fachang replied: "A gourd hanging on the trellis, a shrimp fished from the wheat-waves. Who is at the painted pavilion buying wine? Come, let us drink Zhaozhou's tea together."

=== Falan Cheng ===
E1: The Master asked a monk: "Everyone has a shadow -- why can you not step on it?" The monk said: "I step on it with every step." the Master answered: "If you step on it, you lose your body and your life." The monk shouted. The Master struck him.
E2: Vice-Commissioner Wang and Hanlin Scholar Qin visited the Master. Wang asked: "Does the Master still dream?" The Master said: "I do." Wang asked: "What is the Master's dream like?" The Master gave a shout and said: "Did you dream that?" Wang said: "Water-moon, sky-flowers -- already gone." The Master turned to Qin and said: "And you?" Qin said: "There are no water-moons, no sky-flowers." said the Master: "What then, ultimately?" Qin gave a shout. The Master said: "A fine piece of news." Qin was startled. The Master said: "Before the time of Patriarch Mazu, what on earth did people bring forth?" Qin said: "Before the time of Patriarch Mazu, what on earth did people bring forth?" The Master laughed heartily.

=== Fangrongxi ===
E1: At the mountain gate: "The entire great earth is the Dharma gate. Where do you enter?" He suddenly struck the ground with his staff and said: "Watch your step." At the Maitreya Hall: "Everyone says he will come down and be reborn in the future. Just look at this new arrival today. You think it's funny -- I think it's funny too."
E2: The Master pointed at the Dharma seat and said: "This seat is a lofty platform built on emptiness -- a jeweled pavilion, but also a forest of swords and a mountain of knives. Unless you have forgotten both merit and sin, who would dare touch it? Touch it, and gain and loss follow your body. Today I want to ascend, so I ascend; I want to sit, so I sit. How is it that I am completely without prohibition?" He gave a shout and ascended. Then he said: "The ways of one who walks the Way are hidden and manifest beyond reckoning. Sometimes on a solitary peak he ties his grass hut and lets spring, summer, autumn, and winter come as they please. Sometimes at the crossroads he opens his cloth bag and walks alone through east, west, south, and north."

=== Fangshan Wenbao ===
E1: Fangshan studied under Duanqiao at Guoqing monastery. After a sudden experience of clarity -- when a fellow monk carried a paper lantern through the door and everything became transparent like crystal inside and out -- he reported his realization. Duanqiao tested him with case after case; Fangshan answered them all. Then the old master raised his hand in a chopping gesture and said: "Attendant! You still lack this one cut." Fangshan stormed out, shouting that he had been wronged. Duanqiao still would not approve him. After the meal, during vegetable-sorting duty, Duanqiao arrived and saw Fangshan sitting idle. He asked: "Have you sorted them clean?" Fangshan replied: "Perfectly clean." Duanqiao reached into the basket, picked up a single amaranth root, and tossed it in front of him, saying: "What is this?" At that moment Fangshan broke through completely. Duanqiao beat the drum and ascended the hall, announcing to the assembly: "Attendant Bao has penetrated. From now on he doubts neither Buddha nor patriarch."
E2: Ascending the hall, Fangshan said: "It is not mind, not Buddha, not a thing -- bursting forth, impossible to identify. It cannot be named, cannot be described, cannot be categorized -- the bystanders laugh themselves to death." Then he addressed the assembly: "This old fellow of Ruiyan will go off freely with all of you." He threw down the whisk and said: "Green mountains only know how to grind away past and present. Flowing water has never washed away right and wrong."

=== Faxiyin ===
E1: The old man of Hanshan [Deqing], wearing a bamboo hat, came to pay respects. The Master asked: "Where have you come from?" He answered: "From the south." The Master asked: "Do you remember the road you took coming here?" He answered: "Once past, I let it go." The Master said: "You are clear about your path. Guard it well."
E2: A monk asked: "What is a shout like the Diamond King's precious sword?" The Master struck and said: "Before it leaves the scabbard, its light is already showing." "What is a shout like a crouching lion?" The Master struck and said: "Even a stone man's heart would freeze." "What is a shout like a probing pole with its shadow-grass?" The Master struck and said: "Don't say nobody gets beaten unjustly." "What is a shout that is not used as a shout?" The Master struck and said: "The moment it touches past or present, it misses the mark."

=== Fayan Wenyi ===
E1: Fayan asks Head Monk Xiu: "A hair's breadth of difference and heaven and earth are far apart. How do you understand it?" Xiu replies: "A hair's breadth of difference and heaven and earth are far apart." Fayan says: "How can that do?" Xiu asks back: "How about you, master?" Fayan says: "A hair's breadth of difference and heaven and earth are far apart." Xiu bows. The commentary asks: the head monk said it and was rejected; Fayan says the same words and it works. Where does the difference lie?
E2: Fayan asks Xuanze: "What words did you hear from Master Qingfeng?" Xuanze says he once asked "What is the student's self?" and Qingfeng said: "A Bingding boy comes seeking fire." Fayan asks how he understands it. Xuanze explains: "Bing and ding belong to fire. To seek fire with fire is like seeking oneself with oneself." Fayan says: "To understand it that way, how can that do?" Xuanze is stuck. Fayan says: "You ask me and I will tell you." Xuanze asks: "What is the student's self?" Fayan says: "A Bingding boy comes seeking fire." Xuanze is suddenly enlightened.

=== Fazhuangyuan ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the true Dharma eye?" The Master was silent for a long while, then said: "Do you understand?" The monk said: "No." the Master replied: "Selling jewels, you've run into a blind Persian."
E2: The Master addressed the assembly: "This matter of the Way is like an army of a hundred thousand clashing in battle. Right at that moment -- can you turn and look around? Can you retreat? You must push forward with all your might. Harbor even a hair's breadth of fear, and you are unfit for the task -- how then could you earn anyone's trust? Is there anyone here who can hear this, kick it up, and go? If so, I am overjoyed. If not, I have lost the battle." He threw down the whisk and returned to the abbot's quarters.

=== Fazhudong of Pufeng ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the face before your parents were born?" the Master responded: "Wind blows the willow catkins and the fluff-balls run; rain strikes the pear blossoms and the butterflies fly." The monk said: "Kick over Mount Sumeru, crush empty space!" The Master said: "A truly rare event." The monk bowed. The Master held up the whisk: "Do you understand?" The monk gave a shout. The Master hit him.
E2: A monk asked: "What is heaven?" The Master said: "Wearing a cangue and dragging chains." "What is hell?" "Playing the lute and blowing the reed-organ." The monk protested: "Master, aren't you turning things upside down?" The Master struck him: "You lacquer bucket!"

=== Feiyin ===
E1: A monk came for an interview. The Master stuck out his foot and said: "It so happens my foot is numb. Rub it for me, would you?" The monk shouted. The Master hit him: "You can't even rub a foot." The monk then bowed. The Master said: "Only now do you truly 'receive and uphold.'" The monk stood up and said: "This old fellow is just making waves where there's no wind." the Master responded: "You've seen through me." The monk fell silent. The Master said: "And yet -- still falling into pits and ditches."
E2: The Master asked a monk: "Where are you from?" The monk said: "Haiyan (Sea-Salt)." the Master replied: "Did you bring any salt?" The monk said: "I did." The Master said: "Then show me some." The monk presented his sitting-cloth. The Master said: "That's the bland kind." The monk said: "It's the salty kind." The Master gave him a whack: "You can't tell salty from bland." The monk had nothing to say.

=== Feiyin Tongrong ===
E1: ---
E2: The master, lying on his sleeping platform one evening, called attendant Lingji over and suddenly said: "Donkey!" Lingji said: "One of them is lying right here." The master said: "And where is the other one?" Lingji said: "Donkey!" The master said: "Delighted that you accept the role." Lingji struck the master once. The master said: "Do you even know pain?" Lingji was speechless. The master said: "You don't even know where it itches."

=== Fengxue Yanzhao ===
E1: A monk asks: "Speech and silence involve subtle separation; how can one pass through without violating it?" Fengxue replies: "I always recall, in Jiangnan in the third month, where the partridge cries, a hundred flowers are fragrant." Wumen comments: "Fengxue's function is like lightning; once he has the road, he goes."
E2: Fengxue, in the government office at Yingzhou, ascends the hall and says: "The Patriarch's mind-seal is shaped like the mechanism of an iron ox: if you go, it seals you fast; if you stay, it shatters the seal." Elder Lupi comes forth: "I have the iron ox mechanism. I ask the master not to apply the seal." Fengxue says: "Used to fishing for whales in the clear great deep, yet I lament a frog's gait in mud and sand." Lupi stands thinking. Fengxue shouts: "Elder, why do you not speak?" Lupi hesitates; Fengxue strikes him with a whisk. He's about to speak; Fengxue strikes again. The governor observes: "The Buddha-Dharma and the king's law are the same." Fengxue says: "What have you seen?" The governor: "If what should be cut off is not cut off, one invites disorder instead." Fengxue descends from the seat.

=== Fenyang Shanzhao ===
E1: In the bitter cold of the north, Fenyang had stopped the evening assembly. A foreign monk rode in on clouds and urged him: "Do not miss the time. Though this assembly is not many, six are great vessels; their Way will shade humans and gods." The next day Fenyang ascended the hall and said: "The foreign monk's golden staff shone; for the Dharma he came to Fenyang. Six will become great vessels -- he urged me to expound." At that time Ciming Yuan, Langya Jue, and others were all seated below.
E2: Fenyang's "eighteen questions" are referenced. Also cited: Fenyang called a teaching method "He says: 'Wait until you come out of the net, and then I will tell you.'"

=== Fenyang Wude ===
E1: A monk asked, "What is the phrase for receiving beginners?" Fenyang said, "You are a traveling monk." "What is the phrase for testing seasoned practitioners?" Fenyang said, "The sun in the west rises at the hour of the Hare." "What is the phrase for exercising absolute authority?" Fenyang said, "From a thousand miles away he brings and presents his original face." "What is the phrase for establishing heaven and earth?" Fenyang said, "In Uttarakuru, the land of the north, they eat long-grain rice." Fenyang then said, "With these four phrases alone, I test every patchrobed monk in the world. The moment I see you step forward, I have already tested you."
E2: Fenyang addressed the assembly: "One who preaches the dharma must possess the Ten Kinds of Wisdom in harmony with the True. Without them, he is like a bird trying to fly with only one wing, like a cart running on a single wheel. If you ask and I answer, there will be no end to it, even to the end of future time, without a single pause. It is not that there are no ancient phrases -- but among them, can you find even one that has a drop of moisture?"

=== Fenzhou Wuye ===
E1: All his life, whenever Wuye was asked anything, he only said: "Do not think falsely." This was his singular teaching device -- used for every occasion without exception.
E2: All his life, whenever Wuye was asked anything, he only said, "Do not indulge in deluded thinking." He also instructed the assembly: "The patriarchs observed that this land has roots for the Great Vehicle, so they transmitted only the mind-seal, singly. They point out the deluded path. Those who obtain it are not chosen by foolishness or wisdom, by ordinary or sage. Moreover, better a little truth than much emptiness. You great man, right now, directly, rest and let go. At once stop the myriad entanglements; transcend the stream of birth and death; stand far outside the usual pattern. Even if you have family and adornments, without seeking you attain it of yourself."

=== Foguo ===
E1: A monk brought up the old case of the Salt Official calling for the rhinoceros-horn fan. "The fan is broken," said the attendant. "Then return me the rhinoceros," replied the Official. The monk asked Foguo for the meaning. Foguo said: "A clear wind arises from all eight directions." The monk pressed: "Tiger Hill later wrote a verse: 'In scorching heat, the Salt Official's usage is no ordinary thing -- lightly wave it and don't ask where the rhino went; just produce the clear breeze that cools the whole cosmos.' Is this right?" Foguo said: "Fine jade without flaw -- to carve patterns on it is to ruin its virtue." The monk pressed further on the two old masters' shortcomings, asking Foguo to clear their names. Foguo said: "Bury them both in the same pit."
E2: A monk brought up Zhaozhou's famous "Have some tea" koan. Foguo was asked how to distinguish between the monk who had been there before and the one who had not, since Zhaozhou told them both the same thing. Foguo said: "A jewel moon in an ancient emerald pool -- only after hauling the net three times does one finally know." The monk asked about the head monk who was also told "Have some tea." Foguo replied: "Dragon Gate, three cascades -- the wind and waves grow more treacherous."

=== Foguwen ===
E1: The master passed through the Fugu Hall, where the court officials Feng and Yang were playing the qin. They set aside the strings and invited him to ascend the seat. He said: "When presenting the matter directly, only a true listener is prized. When lifting it beyond convention, only genuine apprehension serves. If you seek the marvelous within the strings or chase the extraordinary beneath the tuning pegs, you not only miss the point of the finger, you also betray the music itself." He then raised the case of Huanglong Xin discussing the Zhao Lun with the scholar Xia Gongli -- debating that "all the myriad things are the self" and that sentient and insentient share one body. A dog lay beneath the incense table. Huanglong struck the dog with a paperweight, then struck the incense table, saying: "The dog has feelings, so it moves away. The incense table has no feelings, so it stays put. How can sentient and insentient be one body?" The scholar had no reply. Huanglong said: "The moment you engage in thinking, it becomes superfluous. When have you ever made the myriad things your own self?" The master commented: "Huanglong Xin was like a crane dancing in a grotto -- but alas, he rarely met his Ziqi. Scholar Xia could play 'Flowing Water' and 'High Mountains' -- but his fingering lacked refinement. This mountain monk also has a tune, but it belongs to none of the five modes." He made a plucking gesture with his fingers and said: "Do you understand? If not, hear this verse: Burning incense, tuning the bridge, then playing -- unexpectedly the moonlit stream and mountains return. When the taut and slack break off, only a dripping silence remains -- look for bloodstains on the fingertips."
E2: Citing the case of a monk asking Yuanwu: "Does the True Person of No Rank experience heat and cold?" Yuanwu said: "Sweating like rain." The monk pressed and Yuanwu parried, but the master commented: "Yuanwu was too compassionate -- his 'falling into the weeds' talk let this monk mistake the servant for the master. I would not do likewise. If asked 'Does the True Person experience heat and cold?' I would say: 'When cold, freezing cold kills you. When hot, burning heat kills you.' If he hesitated, I'd strike him across the spine and drive him out. Why? To spare him groping around in heat and cold."

=== Foyan Qingyuan ===
E1: Foyan said: "Riding a donkey while searching for a donkey is one illness. After finding you are riding a donkey, not being willing to dismount is also an illness."
E2: Foyan said: "If one supports and nurtures it right here, what a lively, orderly unfolding." Wansong responds: "For other schools and different lineages, this must indeed be said."

=== Foyin Liaoyuan ===
E1: Su Dongpo wrote in a poem to Foyin: "I have no leisure yet to study long life; for now I study long not-dying."
E2: Foyin's verse on Changsha's encounter: "A traveler meets Changsha and they share the same road; it makes one dimly probe the family style. Sumeru, ten thousand fathoms, grinds past and present; breaking grass to measure the sky is vain effort."

=== Foyu Yu ===
E1: A monk was reading a sutra. The Master asked, "What sutra?" The monk said, "The Shurangama Sutra." "What part have you reached?" "The forty-four minds." the Master replied, "Of those, which mind do you inhabit?" The monk spread both hands. The Master seized them and said, "Where did you get this?" The monk said, "When the sky is clear, there is a great sun overhead; when it rains, the water flows freely." The Master slapped him and said, "And now what?" The monk said: "People cross the bridge; the water flows, but the bridge does not move."
E2: Before passing away, the Master wrote a verse: "Leaving the womb thirty years ago, birth after birth, death after death, all thoroughly investigated. After wearing out the force of several kalpas, heart weary, spirit spent, too lazy to go forward." One day he showed slight illness, suddenly called his disciples, and pointed to the seat: "Turn it over -- still me. Turn it back -- still me. Cough and spit -- still me. Turn my back -- still me. You only need to arrive where there is no 'I' and no 'mine.'" Then he said: "Ha! Ha!" With that, he sat upright and departed for good.

=== Foyuan ===
E1: One day the Master visited Zizhou. Zizhou said, "We haven't met in many years." The Master said, "How could I ever have forgotten?" Zizhou asked, "Where have you been living in seclusion?" The Master said, "Mountains wreathed in perpetual green, waters flowing in countless ripples." Zizhou said, "I thought the entire great earth had sunk flat -- yet there are still mountains and waters!" The Master said, "Today I have blundered before you, elder brother."
E2: The Master asked a monk, "What bridge is this?" The monk said, "A single-log bridge." The Master rushed ahead and crossed. The monk asked, "What was the meaning of that?" The Master said, "You'll only know when you step on it."

=== FU DASHI ===
E1: The Great Adept Fu Xi, styled Xuanfeng, was a farmer from Yiwu. At age 24, while fishing, he met an Indian monk called Song Toutuo, who told him: "You and I vowed together before Vipashyin Buddha to liberate all beings. Your enjoyments in Tushita Heaven are all still there -- when will you return?" Fu stared blankly. The monk said: "Try looking at your reflection in the water." Fu looked and saw a circular halo and jeweled canopy, and suddenly recalled his past causes. Later he traveled to the capital to see Emperor Wu of Liang. The emperor had all the palace gates locked to test him. Fu had already foreseen this: he brought a great wooden mallet, struck the first gate, and all gates opened at once. He walked straight into the Hall of Good Words, refused to bow, and climbed directly onto a precious couch sent as tribute from a western kingdom -- a seat that only Crown Prince Zhaoming, the monk Zhizhe, and Fu himself had ever sat. The emperor asked: "From whom did you receive your teaching?" Fu answered: "From no one do I come, no teacher do I follow, no affair do I serve."
E2: At a great assembly in the Chongyun Hall of the Hualin Gardens, Emperor Wu ascended the throne to lecture on the Prajna Sutra. A special seat was prepared for Fu with four attendants. Grand Secretary Liu arrived and asked Fu: "Why do you neither submit to the emperor nor befriend the nobles?" Fu replied: "In respect there is no nature of respect; in non-respect there is no mind of non-respect." When the full assembly had gathered and the emperor ascended, Fu alone did not rise. The Grand Secretary again asked why. Fu said: "If the dharma-ground were to move, not a single dharma would be secure." When princes and officials presented offerings and requested the assembly to chant sutras, Fu alone sat in silence. Asked why, he said: "Speech and silence are both buddha-activity."

=== Furong Daokai ===
E1: Yang Wuwei asked Master Furong Kai, "How many years since we parted?" Furong said, "Seven years." Yang said, "Have you come studying the Way, or to practice Chan?" Furong said, "I do not beat that drum and flute." Yang said, "Then you've only wandered mountains and rivers in vain, good for nothing at all." Furong said: "We have not been apart long, yet your lofty discernment is excellent." Yang laughed aloud.
E2: A nun named Zongchi, rising from illness, composed a verse: "Breath cut off, all feelings spent; raise an intention and there is no road for it. Even blinking lacks strength; all year I do not leave the door." Furong Kai said: "With just this one verse, she naturally succeeds this old monk."

=== Fushan Fayuan ===
E1: "Fushan Yuanlu said: Ox-head south, Horse-head north. If one gets the meaning, one forgets the trap."
E2: "Fushan Yuanlu said: For one who has not yet penetrated, investigating the phrase is not as good as investigating the intent. For one who has penetrated, investigating the intent is not as good as investigating the phrase."

=== Fushi ===
E1: According to his biography, Fushi had an initial breakthrough contemplating the "seven female corpse" contemplation ground (a contemplation of bodily decay). Later, the definitive awakening came from the koan about "a warm breeze at the corner of the temple hall." His teacher Miyun still refused to approve him and forced him to write formal essays on "spiritual sprouts" versus "root-source" -- driving him until "inside and outside were transparent, hands and mouth unobstructed." Only then came the seal: "Go open halls anywhere and teach on my behalf." 
E2: ---

=== Fushi Qiyuan (Nun Master) ===
E1: A student asked: "What is guest within guest?" The master said: "Bustling through the red dust." "What is host within guest?" "The question itself draws naturally near." "What is guest within host?" "The answer goes beyond the ordinary." "What is host within host?" The master said: "I smash your skull open."
E2: Qiyuan told the assembly: "The ancients said 'when the days of ease come, think of danger; when there is joy, think of suffering.' Seize this idle time and put your koan right in front of your face, press into it day and night!" She raised the old story: "The Tang Emperor sent an emissary to summon the monk Laizan from his mountain. Three imperial edicts came. Laizan finally stirred himself to poke at a roasted yam in the ashes, snot running freely down his face, not even glancing at the messenger. The envoy laughed: 'Please, Reverend, wipe your snot.' Laizan said: 'Who has time to wipe snot for worldly people?'" The master then said: "Look at how the ancients practiced! Fame and fortune didn't enter their hearts. Naturally their daily activity accorded with the Way. Do you understand? If you've cried till the blood flows and it's still no use, better to shut your mouth and get through the remaining year."

=== Gaoan Dayu ===
E1: After being beaten three times by Huangbo for asking about the Buddha Dharma, Linji went to Dayu. Linji said, "I asked three times and three times I received blows. I do not know whether I was at fault or not." Dayu said, "Huangbo is so grandmotherly, wearing himself out completely for your sake, and still you come asking whether there was fault or no fault." At these words Linji had a great awakening and said, "Huangbo's Buddha-Dharma is not much." Dayu grabbed him and said, "Just now you said there was fault, and now you say the Buddha-Dharma is not much -- how is that?" Linji struck three punches under Dayu's ribs. Dayu pushed him away and said, "Your teacher is Huangbo; this is none of my business."
E2: In the original record, after awakening Linji immediately said, "Originally Buddha Dharma is not much." Dayu said, "You bed-wetting ghost! Just now you asked whether there was fault or not, and now you say Buddha Dharma is not much. How much is it then?" He grabbed him and said, "Speak, speak!" Linji punched him three times under the ribs.

=== Gaofeng Yuanmiao ===
E1: Gaofeng addressed the assembly at Lion Cliff on West Tianmu Mountain: "When I was young, I entered the hall at Shuangjing. Before even a month had passed, one night in my sleep I was seized by doubt over the phrase 'The ten thousand dharmas return to one -- where does the one return to?' From that moment, the feeling of doubt erupted all at once. I forgot sleep and food. I could not tell east from west, could not distinguish day from night. Whether unrolling my mat, opening my bowl, going to the latrine, or relieving myself -- in every single motion and stillness, every word and silence -- there was only this: 'Where does the one return to?' Not the slightest other thought arose, nor could I have produced one if I tried. It was like a nail driven into glue -- immovable. Though I stood in the midst of crowds, it was as if no one else existed. From dawn to dusk, from dusk to dawn -- clear, clear, settled, settled, towering, towering. Utterly pure without a single speck. One thought spanning ten thousand years. Scene forgotten, self forgotten. Like an idiot, like a stump. Without realizing it, on the sixth day, while chanting sutras with the assembly at Santa, I raised my head and suddenly caught sight of the portrait-verse of Wuzu Fayan. In a flash it triggered the phrase my old master at Yangshan had asked me -- 'Who is it that drags this corpse around?' Suddenly the empty sky shattered and the great earth sank away. Self and world both vanished. It was like one mirror reflecting another. The hundred-zhang fox, the dog and Buddha-nature, the Qingzhou hemp shirt, the girl coming out of samadhi -- I took them all up one by one and examined them closely. Every single one was perfectly clear. The marvelous function of prajna is trustworthy indeed."
E2: Gaofeng raised a case: "Danxia once visited a temple during bitter cold. Seeing a wooden Buddha in the hall, he took it and burned it for warmth. The abbot happened to see this and scolded him: 'How dare you burn my wooden Buddha!' Danxia poked through the ashes with his staff and said, 'I'm burning it to get the sacred relics.' The abbot said, 'How can a wooden Buddha have relics?' Danxia said, 'Since there are no relics, let me have the other two to burn as well.' Afterward the abbot's eyebrows and beard fell out." Gaofeng commented: "Danxia burned the wooden Buddha because he was pressed by the cold -- what else was there? The abbot's eyebrows and beard fell out -- a coincidence that happened to match the pattern. Nothing to puzzle over. But if you try to discuss this as a matter of Buddha-dharma, you'll enter hell swift as an arrow." He flung down his whisk and descended from the seat.

=== Guantaoqi ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall. He raised this: "A monk asked Caoshan: 'What was it like before the Buddha appeared in the world?' Caoshan said: 'Caoshan is not as good.' 'What about after he appeared?' Caoshan said: 'Not as good as Caoshan.'" The Master said: "Old Caoshan took everything before the King of Awesome Sound and after the Louzhi Buddha, lifted it in one hand and shouldered it on one arm -- just as if measuring others by his own standard. Today if someone asks the new abbot: 'What was it like before the Buddha appeared in the world?' I just say: 'Filling ditches and blocking gullies.' 'And after he appeared?' 'Brocade on brocade.' If you can appreciate this, you can repay the unrequitable debt of gratitude. If not -- " He struck his staff and said: "The warhorses of the past went unrecognized; what matters is to discuss the achievement that crowns the age."
E2: The Master ascended the hall. "Gaoting opens its furnace for the retreat. Firewood and rice are hard to procure. We can barely endure the hunger, so what Patriarch's-coming-from-the-west meaning could there be? We chop green wood to burn; the wet smoke stings our eyes and brings tears. The monks from the ten directions come for the retreat -- we are just scraping by, following precedent. The two ranks of officers keep order; the monastic standards must not fall. At the start of this endeavor, I announce a three-article code: First, no hiding and slacking. Second, no sleeping. Third, the crucial matter: who takes up the spoon and grasps the chopsticks? The tongue has no bone in it; the nose can only breathe. From the crown of the head to the soles of the feet, examine thoroughly -- where do holy names and ordinary designations belong? On this basis I issue my command: the stratagem of smashing the pots and sinking the boats. Fight back the army of birth-and-death, and only then will you see 'mind emptied, examination passed.' Wait until you are so disgusted with Buddhahood you refuse it -- then from behind the head, one hammer-blow of certification." He called to the assembly: "If you truly loathe being a Buddha, why would you still want certification? Without the carving hand of a skilled craftsman, even good material ends as a useless vessel."

=== Guishan Lingyou ===
E1: Baizhang needed to appoint an abbot for Mount Weishan. He set a purifying vase on the ground and posed a challenge: "You must not call it a purifying vase. What do you call it?" The head seat said, "It cannot be called a wooden post." Then Baizhang asked Guishan. Guishan kicked over the purifying vase and walked out. Baizhang laughed and said, "The head seat has lost to Weishan." He appointed Guishan as founding abbot.
E2: Guishan, Wufeng, and Yunyan were attending Baizhang. Baizhang asked Guishan: "Seal up your throat and your lips -- how will you speak?" Guishan said, "I ask the master to speak." Baizhang said, "I do not refuse to tell you, but I fear that later I will lose my sons and grandsons."

=== Guizong Zhichang ===
E1: Nanquan, Guizong, and Mogu went together to pay respects to National Teacher Zhong. On the road, Nanquan drew a circle on the ground and said: "Speak, and we go." Guizong sat within the circle. Mogu gave a feminine bow. Nanquan said: "If so, then we won't go." Guizong said: "What kind of mind-conduct is that?"
E2: An official visited Guizong. Guizong picked up the two ends of his cap and showed them, saying: "Do you understand?" The official said: "I do not." Guizong said: "This old cap of mine cannot help you."

=== Gulin ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall and said: "I originally had no mind seeking anything, yet now this great treasure has come of itself. I dare ask the assembly: above is heaven, below is earth, left is the road, right is the stream, in front is the donor, behind is the Ci'en Temple -- where is the treasure? Does anyone in the assembly have a word to say? If not, I will speak it myself." He gave a thundering shout and descended.
E2: A monk asked: "What was it like before the Patriarch came from the West?" The Master said: "In China, every house has its moonlight, night after night." The monk said: "And after he came?" The Master said: "In some places there is singing; in some places there is grief."

=== Gulin Qingmao ===
E1: Raising Chuanzi's verse: "A thousand-foot silk line hangs straight down. One ripple stirs and ten thousand waves follow. In the still night, cold water -- the fish won't bite. A full boat carries nothing home but the bright moon." Gulin commented: "People nowadays say the old man labored without result. They don't realize that across ten thousand acres of misty waves his intent was on the leviathan -- mere minnows waste their time taking the bait. Can you tell where this falls? To cite old or present -- who does not understand? But to strum a different tune on a moving string: rare is the one who truly hears." He struck the whisk and descended.
E2: Ascending the hall: "Hearing the bell, you put on the seven-strip robe. Seeing the sun rise, you dry your leather mat. Everyday affairs, perfectly ordinary -- why seek anything else? The samadhi of the World-Honored One, Kashyapa does not know. The samadhi of Kashyapa, Ananda does not know. The samadhi of Ananda, Shanakavasin does not know." He raised his staff: "The samadhi of this staff, none of you know." He struck it down: "When the dragon finds water, its spirit rises. When the tiger meets the mountain, its ferocity grows."

=== Gulin Ru ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall and raised this: "A monk came to Xuefeng for an interview. Feng asked: 'Where are you from?' The monk said: 'From Zhejiang.' Feng said: 'Did you come by boat or by land?' The monk said: 'I traveled neither path.' Feng said: 'Then how did you get here?' The monk said: 'What obstruction could there be?' Feng immediately struck him and drove him out. Ten years later, this monk came again. Feng said: 'Where are you from?' The monk said: 'From Hunan.' Feng said: 'How far is Hunan from here?' The monk said: 'Not separate at all.' Feng held up his whisk and said: 'Is there still this separating you?' The monk said: 'If it separated us, how could I have gotten here?' Feng drove him out again. The monk went to live in a hermitage and whenever he met people he cursed Xuefeng. A fellow traveler heard this and went to visit him, asking: 'Why do you curse Xuefeng?' The monk recounted both encounters. The fellow traveler berated him thoroughly and broke it open for him. The monk then wept bitterly, and every midnight he burned incense and bowed toward Xuefeng." The Master said: "Xuefeng's way of teaching people -- he only has the sword that kills, not the blade that gives life. That fellow traveler who broke it open for him was piling a point on the arrow tip, leaking badly. This monk who first cursed and then wept -- two faces and three sides, rising and falling on his own. Today at Lotus Flower I judge this case on its merits: each one gets thirty blows of the staff. Why? 'The sword leaves its jeweled scabbard because of injustice; the medicine leaves its golden vase because of illness.'"
E2: The Master ascended the hall and raised this: "Nanquan said: 'Old Teacher Wang has raised a water buffalo since he was small. If I try to graze it east of the stream, I cannot help but trespass on the king's water and grass. If I try to graze it west of the stream, I cannot help but trespass on the king's water and grass. Better to just accept things as they come.'" the Master replied: "Old Teacher Wang's way of presenting things is admirable, but he could not help trespassing on the king's water and grass. How much better is Lotus Flower's daily practice -- dragging the plow and pulling the harrow, turning over the field below Pine Ridge and by the Octagonal Well, planting in summer, harvesting in autumn, hulled rice and fragrant gruel, happy and at ease. Does this not surpass Old Teacher Wang's position by a whole head? If someone in the assembly came forward and said: 'What kind of mental activity is this?' -- " He struck his staff and said: "You too cannot escape this circle." He laughed heartily and descended the seat.

=== Gumeilie of Weishan ===
E1: The Master raised the old case: "Xuefeng said to the assembly: 'When the world is one foot wide, the ancient mirror is one foot wide. When the world is ten feet wide, the ancient mirror is ten feet wide.' Xuansha pointed to the fire and said: 'How wide is the fire?' Xuefeng said: 'As wide as the ancient mirror.' Xuansha said: 'This old fellow's feet have not yet touched the ground.'" The Master said: "Indeed, indeed. But Xuansha's own statement -- he did not realize his own life-root had already fallen into another's hands." Then he took up his staff: "When the world is one foot wide, the ancient mirror is one foot wide. When the world is ten feet wide, the ancient mirror is ten feet wide. Smash the entire universe -- how wide is the ancient mirror then? Shatter the mirror -- how wide is the world then? Right now, is there anyone whose feet have touched the ground?" He threw down the staff: "Before the rain, one first sees buds among the leaves; after the rain, there are no more leaves beneath the flowers."
E2: The Master raised the old case: "When Guishan Lingyou was once sitting, Yangshan and Xiangyan attended at his sides. Lingyou raised his hand and asked: 'Nowadays, those who are entirely thus are few; those who are not thus are many.' Xiangyan moved from the east side to stand on the west; Yangshan moved from the west to stand on the east. Lingyou said: 'This incident, thirty years from now, will be like gold cast upon the ground.' Yangshan said: 'It still requires the Master's advocacy.' Xiangyan said: 'Even now it is not lacking.' Lingyou said: 'Shut your mouth.'" The Master composed a verse: "One episode -- a puppet show of living flesh; divine skill like child's play. 'Thus' and 'not thus' -- one scene, completely spontaneous. From east to west: Mount Sumeru soaked through. From west to east: the great ocean turned crimson. 'Shut your mouth' -- that single phrase! Boundless splendor in the mist. Father and son -- gold tested against gold. Elder and younger brother -- water poured into water. Before the Hall of Good Teaching, laughter and joy. To this very day, through a thousand ages, all envy Weishan."

=== Gusuzun ===
E1: A monk asked, "When a monk dies, where does he go?" The Master said, "Yesterday it rained; today it is clear." The monk said, "Then he merges with heaven and earth as one root?" said the Master, "You cannot stick ears onto empty space."
E2: The Master asked a monk, "What is your dharma name?" The monk said, "Loves-to-Eat." The Master held up his fist and said, "Try taking a bite." The monk was about to speak. The Master struck him, saying, "You'll choke to death, ghost!" The monk bowed. the Master replied, "That's even worse."

=== Guxue Zhe ===
E1: At the opening ceremony, the Master followed the Precenter's gavel-strike with a great shout and said: "Did you observe it? If you observed it that way, that counts as right observation. Any other observation is wrong observation. Veterans of long practice already know before I raise the topic. Come forward with your single sword!" A monk asked about continuing the ancient tradition. The master said: "The stone bell and stone drum ring out together." Another monk asked about "smashing the earthen pot." The master said: "Seven cracks, eight splits!" The monk ventured: "Lamp after lamp continues the flame through the ages..." The master cut in: "You haven't arrived yet." Then he gave his formal teaching: "Since the ancestral hall is restored, all within the four seas rejoice. The ancestral command shall be carried out, and a thousand differences are cut through at a single sitting... bare and naked, exposed and bright, clear and empty, white and vivid -- monks are thus, laypeople are thus, ordinary beings are thus, sages are thus."
E2: ---

=== Haiyin Zhaoru ===
E1: Raising the old case of the Sixth Patriarch at Faxing Temple where two monks argued whether the wind or the banner was moving, Haiyin commented: "The Sixth Patriarch could silence the two monks' dispute, but he could not make them truly alive." Then he held up the staff and said: "It is not the wind moving. It is not the banner moving. It is not the mind moving." He threw down the staff: "What is this?"
E2: "Do not walk the road of the mind. Do not wear the original garment." Haiyin explained: "'Do not walk the road of the mind' -- the moment you stir thought, there is already a gap. But if you neither stir thought nor move a single notion, is there still a road of the mind? Where language is cut off and mental activity ceases -- that is not walking the road of the mind. Yet the moment you stop, you have donned the original garment and fallen into the fearsome pit of liberation." He called this the "sweat-stained undershirt" that even ten out of ten practitioners on the path cannot peel off. "Even if you strip it away briefly, the moment conditions arise you drift with them -- like pushing a boat downstream without knowing the currents, floating unknowingly into a sea of poison." Then: "What is the turning point? -- Though the ocean may transform, I will never open this passage for you."

=== Hanshan Deqing ===
E1: When Hanshan Deqing was still a young novice (shami), he served Master Yungu Fahui most diligently. One day he said: "People say my lifespan will be short. What can I do?" Yungu said: "Lifespan and early death belong to the dharma of birth and death. Investigating Chan is the dharma of transcending birth and death. If you thoroughly penetrate this matter of the single great affair, what concern is life or death?"
E2: ---

=== Hansong Cao ===
E1: The old master ordered the bamboo stick sent to the head monk's quarters to test the assembly. The Master took the bamboo splint into the hall and addressed the monks: "Call it a bamboo splint and you offend; don't call it a bamboo splint and you turn your back. What do you call it after all? If you can say, I'll still snap it; if you cannot say, I'll also snap it." No one in the assembly replied. The Master snapped the bamboo splint in two and returned to his quarters.
E2: One day, after examining the assembly in the hall, the Master went to the abbot's room to pay respects. The old master said, "How many people attained awakening in the hall today?" the Master replied, "If it weren't Zhicao standing here, I'd have nearly given you the wrong answer." The old master said, "The head monk seems never to have set foot in the hall at all." The Master said, "I'm glad someone was there to witness it." The old master said, "Since you did enter the hall, why did you let the Holy Monk fall asleep?" said the Master, "How fortunate -- today the formal session is dismissed."

=== Hanxiu ===
E1: A Confucian scholar presented his visiting card, styling himself a "student of the Way." said the Master, "Never mind 'study' -- what is the Way?" The scholar said, "Why ask?" said the Master, "Don't pretend to understand." The scholar was dumbstruck. The Master said, "Your own tradition teaches: 'Be cautious about what you do not see, be fearful about what you do not hear.' Try saying a single word from the place where there is nothing to see and nothing to hear." The scholar opened his mouth to speak, and the Master cut in: "Not it. Not it." The scholar was bewildered and said, "Can the Master himself say it?" The Master said, "Ask me, then." The scholar repeated his original question. The Master said, "Mountain flowers bloom like brocade; hidden birds sing like flutes." The scholar said, "But then there IS seeing and hearing!" the Master responded, "Not seeing and not hearing -- that is still the realm of negation. When sight and hearing are vivid and clear yet no perception of seeing or hearing arises -- THAT will do." The scholar sighed in admiration, bowed, and withdrew.
E2: When a rooster crowed at midday, the Master said, "What a fine call -- only no one understands it." A monk then asked, "Does the Master understand it?" The Master said, "Distant water shines on white sand; in deep autumn the leaves turn yellow." The monk said, "If one understands it just like that, what then?" the Master replied, "It nearly resembled a melody worth hearing -- then the wind blew it into another key."

=== Hanyu Xian ===
E1: Entering his chamber at the Lion Hermitage in Fenyang, the Master said: "A lion in the lion's den; sandalwood within the sandalwood grove." He looked left and right: "Tell me, what kind of place is this?" He gave a shout: "Elephants and dragons may tread here -- it is no place for donkeys."
E2: New Year's Eve. A monk asked: "Evergreen pines and cypresses -- that I'll set aside. What is the year-end phrase?" The Master said: "In Fenzhou the cold reaches its extreme -- thank goodness there is coal to burn." Then the Master said: "Look, look -- another year has come to its end. Have you all gotten hold of the matter under your heels yet? If you haven't, you must press your awl fiercely right here. If the lamp-flower suddenly pops and falls, won't that be a fine laugh?" He struck the ground with his staff: "Next year there will be new branches again, vexing the spring wind without cease."

=== Hefeng ===
E1: The Master was cutting grass in the garden. A layman on the other side of the fence drew a circle in the air. The Master said: "That's right, but you're still on the other side of the fence." The layman then walked off into the rain. The Master said: "That's right, but you're still on the road."
E2: A monk asked: "Not thinking good, not thinking evil -- what is the original face?" The Master said: "Thought after thought follows in succession -- what kind of face is that?" The monk said: "I don't understand." the Master replied: "What use is understanding?"

=== Hengchuan Xinggong ===
E1: Hengchuan pointed at the three gates upon entering the temple: "The entire great earth is this very monastery. So from which gate do you enter?" He lifted his foot and said: "Eight characters flung open -- bright day, clear sky."
E2: Hengchuan addressed the assembly upon entering the Buddha Hall: "A pearl turns on a jade plate. The moon wanders through a lapis lazuli palace. Whose realm is this? If you cannot yet discern the origin, then watch as the new abbot unfolds his sitting cloth and makes three full prostrations."

=== Hengshan ===
E1: The Master raised this case: "The World-Honored One sent Ananda to the hells to ask Devadatta: 'Are you happy here?' Devadatta said: 'As happy as in the Third Dhyana Heaven.' The messenger asked: 'Do you wish to get out?' Devadatta said: 'I will leave when the World-Honored One enters hell.' The messenger said: 'How could the World-Honored One ever enter hell?' Devadatta said: 'If the World-Honored One has no reason to enter hell, then I have no reason to leave.'" The Master said: "If you can understand it right here, then within rising and falling, within the cycle of transmigration itself, you will recognize the scenery of your original ground. Tell me: what is the scenery of the original ground?" He drew a circle with his whisk and said: "Every place is the Flower Treasury World. In every hall, Vairocana is everywhere."
E2: The Master gave an address: "Before Shakyamuni appeared in the world, before Bodhidharma came from the West, before this old monk planted his staff on this mountain -- every person already had a great jewel-light shining from the crown of their head, and at the sole of every foot, the crossroads extended in all ten directions. Nothing was lacking, nothing ever rested. And yet, though you use it daily, you do not know it. In the human realm, if this light were absent -- who answers when called? Who knows what is seen? Who raises eyebrows and blinks? Who bows and greets guests? Who dresses and eats? In the hell realm, if this light were absent -- who drinks the molten copper poured into the mouth? Who endures the scorching iron? Who walks up the mountain of swords? Who runs across the forest of blades? Who suffers the pain?" He continued through every realm -- heavens, hungry ghosts, animals, asuras, shravakas, pratyekabuddhas, bodhisattvas, and buddhas -- asking of each: "If this light were absent, who is it that does these things?" Then he concluded: "Thus this light of the Way manifests on every thing, shines through every dharma. It is originally complete, originally perfect. Know it or call it 'buddha-nature.' Fail to recognize it, and you call it 'soul.' The king heard these words and his mind immediately opened."

=== Hengxiulin of Luluo ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall and raised this: "Shigong was once a hunter chasing a deer. He passed by Mazu's hermitage and asked: 'Have you seen a deer come by?' Mazu said: 'Who are you?' 'A hunter.' 'Do you know how to shoot?' 'I do.' 'How many can you bring down with one arrow?' 'One.' Mazu said: 'You are not a good shot.' The hunter said: 'Can you shoot?' 'I can.' 'How many can you bring down with one arrow?' 'A whole herd.' The hunter said: 'They are each a living being -- why shoot a whole herd?' Mazu said: 'Since you know this, why don't you shoot yourself?' The hunter then broke his bow and arrows and became Mazu's disciple." the Master responded: "Shigong saw what was right and acted with courage -- a true great man. Mazu turned the error to advantage -- truly hitting the mark every time. But his eye was too narrow. Here at Jixiang it is different: with one casual arrow, every person on the great earth loses body and life. Why? Have you not heard: 'To protect life you must kill; only when all is killed can you dwell in peace.'"
E2: A monk asked: "What is it like before the lotus emerges from the water?" The Master said: "Lotus!" "What about after it has emerged from the water?" "Lotus!" "What about when it is neither emerged nor not-emerged?" "Lotus! Lotus!" "What about directly accepting it on the spot?" The Master said: "A sharp sword cleaving empty space."

=== Heyizi ===
E1: The Master raised the story of Juzhi: Whenever anyone asked about the Dharma, he simply raised one finger. A boy attendant imitated this when questioned outside. Juzhi heard of it, took a knife, and cut off the boy's finger. As the boy ran away screaming, Juzhi called out to him. The boy turned his head. At that moment Juzhi raised one finger. The boy was instantly enlightened. The Master called to the assembly: "Tell me -- at what point did Juzhi and the boy awaken?" He raised his own finger, looked left and right, and descended from the seat.
E2: The Master raised the case: "The World-Honored One, walking with the assembly, pointed to a place and said: 'This is a suitable spot for a monastery.' The god Indra took a single blade of grass, stuck it in the ground, and said: 'The monastery is built.' The World-Honored One smiled." The Master called to the assembly: "Do you understand?" Everyone was silent. The Master could not help but burst into great laughter: "The ten thousand sounds of nature -- none with ears can hear them. The lone cliff without ears nevertheless knows the music."

=== Hongjue Chaomin ===
E1: A monk asked, "What is the present Buddha?" The master said, "The nun was originally a woman." "What is the past Buddha?" "Step back to the side." "What is the future Buddha?" "The donkey dreams of next year's hay." The monk was about to press further. The master gave a thunderous shout.
E2: During an evening talk, the master said, "In this matter, what counts is having clear eyes. Clear eyes means quick hands. Quick hands means every move has a way out." Then he told the assembly: "I remember when my late teacher was at Tiantong. One evening he hung the signboard for a private interview. A certain Zen monk came in, fully armored, martial skills superb. The moment he crossed the threshold, he declared, 'No need for polite preliminaries -- please, Master, just bring out the stick!' He planned to sell a feint and topple the man before him." "But what he didn't know was that my teacher was a veteran of countless campaigns, an old warrior of the battlefield. Sitting calmly beneath his banner, neither flustered nor afraid, he simply tossed out a trip-wire with one question: 'Why?'" "And the monk was tripped flat. He stood there with nothing to say, and the master seized him alive. A fine monk, to be sure -- but as they say, he'd built his mountain nine layers high and still lacked the final basket of earth. All offense and no defense." The master continued: "If it had been me, and my teacher had said 'Why?' -- I'd simply have replied, 'Striding sideways through the golden palace, one always carries the scent of the imperial incense.' That alone would have been enough to make the old man hand over his staff with both hands." Then he called out: "Is there anyone here like that monk? Come out and let us sharpen each other! One, to display your strengths. Two, to raise the fighting spirit of this assembly. Three, to show that Tiantong's family style has not declined." A monk stepped forward. The master held up his hand and said, "You're not a worthy opponent." Then to the whole hall: "The monks sitting below actually have some ability. Why won't any of them come out?" No one spoke. The master said, "Every last one of you is a frog hiding beneath his robe." He poked them back with his staff. Another monk came forward and said, "Both halls are in retreat -- how many of them truly grasp the master's meaning?" The master said, "Ha!" The monk tried to ask again. The master struck him. Then he called out: "Anyone? Anyone?" The assembly was silent. He gave a shout: "Standing tall between heaven and earth -- who here will raise their head?"

=== Hongren ===
E1: The Fifth Patriarch asked a monk, "When Qiannu's soul left her body, which was the real Qiannu?" Wumen comments: "If here you awaken to what is real, then you will know leaving the shell and entering the shell is like lodging at an inn. If it is not so, do not run about in confusion. Suddenly when earth, water, fire, and wind disperse, you will be like a crab dropped into boiling water, seven hands and eight feet."
E2: The Fifth Patriarch said, "It is like a water-buffalo passing through a window lattice. Head, horns, and four hooves have all passed through. Why is it that the tail cannot pass through?" Wumen's verse: "Going past, you fall into a pit and trench; coming back, you are again ruined. This little tail -- truly is most strange."

=== Hongzhi ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the person who goes forth?" said the Master: "White clouds pour into the valley and are gone; green cliffs lean against empty sky, high." The monk asked: "What is the person who returns?" the Master responded: "Head full of white hair, he leaves the rock valley; at midnight he passes through clouds into the marketplace." The monk asked: "What is the person who neither comes nor goes?" said the Master: "The stone woman calls back the dream of the three realms; the wooden man sits and severs the mechanism of the six sense gates." Then the Master said: "It is easy to clarify the school within a phrase; it is difficult to discern the essential within the school." After a long silence: "Do you understand? The frozen rooster has not yet announced the dawn in the home forest -- dimly, dimly, a traveler crosses the snow mountain."
E2: Citing: "A monk asked Yunmen: 'If not a single thought arises, is there still any fault?' Yunmen said: 'Mount Sumeru.'" said the Master: "Not a single thought arising -- he answers 'Mount Sumeru.' A tongue is just a lump of meat; lips are just two flaps of skin. Yunmen's skill is marvelous indeed. It does not fall into right or wrong, knowing or not knowing."

=== Hongzhi Zhengjue ===
E1: Tiantong (Hongzhi) versifies the World-Honored One ascending the seat: "A single stretch of true wind -- can you see it?" Wansong asks: "Is the World-Honored One's ascending the seat a single stretch of true wind, or is Tiantong's raising it in verse a single stretch of true wind?" The entire Book of Serenity is structured around Hongzhi's verses -- he is the poet to Wansong's commentator.
E2: Tiantong ascended the hall and said: "One point within the circle shines on the utmost subtlety. Where wisdom has no handle, it hangs down in the night."

=== Huaihai Yuanzhao ===
E1: Huaihai raised the case: Huangbo, while serving as head monk under Nanquan, one day sat down in Nanquan's seat holding his bowl. Nanquan entered the hall, saw him, and asked, "Elder, in what era did you begin practicing the Way?" Huangbo said, "Before the time of the King of Awesome Sound." Nanquan said, "So you're still old Teacher Wang's descendant. Move down." Huangbo then moved to the second seat. Huaihai's verse: "Peach and plum blossoms say nothing, yet the courtyard fills with spring. Songs and drums pass through the Clear Brightness Festival. Whose garden pond reflects a pair of mandarin ducks that no painting can capture?"
E2: Huaihai raised: Linji asked Huangbo about the essential meaning of the Buddha-dharma, and was struck three times. Huaihai's verse: "Before Huangbo Mountain, clutching his uncut jade -- at the rapids of Gao'an, shame finally came. Though he won a price equal to a walled city, the pain has never ceased, right down to today."

=== Huanchu ===
E1: The master took up his whisk, brushed it once, and said: "The chicken goes cold and roosts in the tree; the duck goes cold and descends to the water. Their spiritual natures are clearly not two. Why then are their responses to cold so different? Is it because the familiar is hard to forget? As they say: make the familiar strange, and make the strange familiar. Here in our assembly at Huayan, everyone wears the same clothes and eats the same food. Is this the familiar, or the strange?" After a long pause, the master called to his attendant. Two attendants answered simultaneously. The master said: "One gains, one loses." Then he added: "Shortly, sweep the grass in front of the Dharma Hall." He struck the armrest and descended.
E2: The master raised the case: Fushan asked Gushan: "Before your parents were born, where was your nose?" Gushan said: "Now that you are born today, where is your nose?" Fushan was not satisfied, and said: "You ask me, and I will answer you." Gushan asked: "Before your parents were born, where was your nose?" Fushan just fanned himself -- and that was all. The master said: "If someone today asks me 'Before your parents were born, where was your nose?' I would just say to them: 'Fist-sized rice dumplings are not so very large -- take care not to swallow them whole.'"

=== Huangbo Xiyun ===
E1: Huangbo addressed the assembly: "You are all nothing but dregs-drinking fellows. Traveling on pilgrimage like this, where could you have today? Do you know that in the Great Tang there are no Chan masters?" A monk stepped forward: "If so, what about those in the various regions who guide disciples and lead communities?" Huangbo: "I do not say there is no Chan; I only say there are no teachers."
E2: After Baizhang tells the wild fox story, Huangbo asks: "The man of old gave a wrong reply and fell into a fox body for five hundred lives. If every reply is correct, what then?" Baizhang says: "Come nearer and I will tell you." Huangbo steps forward and slaps Baizhang. Baizhang claps his hands and laughs: "I thought the barbarian's beard was red, but there is also a red-bearded barbarian."


=== Huanglong Huinan ===
E1: Huanglong raised the following story: On the anniversary of the Buddha's birth, all the monasteries in the world perform the bathing ceremony. The monk Zun, who served as temple steward under Yaoshan, was bathing the buddha-image. Yaoshan asked, "You can bathe this one -- but can you bathe that one?" Zun said, "Bring that one here." Yaoshan said no more. Huanglong commented: "Such a casual remark by the ancients -- no cleverness at all. People today use their full mental resources to arrange things, but they never reach the same ground. Among the assembly, some say: 'This one is the copper statue, that one is the dharma body. The copper statue has form and can be washed; the dharma body is formless -- how can it be washed?' Others say Yaoshan only knew one side and not the other, and Zun backed him into a corner. Still others say both men had already attained realization and were just playing. All such interpretations arise from those who have never met the right teacher. Using deliberate thinking to handle the business of the school is like taking a firefly and trying to burn Mount Sumeru -- though you labor through endless kalpas, you will never succeed."
E2: Huanglong said: "The Buddha himself has declared: 'In preaching the dharma, there is nothing said and nothing shown; in hearing the dharma, there is nothing heard and nothing gained.' Furthermore, I have heard that Confucius and Wenbo Xue had long wished to meet one another. One day their carriages crossed paths on the road. Neither spoke a word. Each simply turned around and went home. Later a disciple asked, 'Master, you had long wanted to meet Wenbo Xue. When you finally met, why did you not exchange a single word?' Confucius said, 'When true gentlemen meet, the Way is grasped at a glance.' Now consider: the ancients met and grasped the Way in a single glance. Yet today I have beaten the drum, ascended the seat, and rattled on at length -- a complete loss."

=== Huanxi Weiyi ===
E1: Thanking the temple officers, Huanxi ascended the hall: "Here at Dongshan I have opened a small theater and arranged scenes that even the buddhas and patriarchs could not choreograph. Yet a single thread cannot make a line, and one hand cannot clap. It needs all of you together to make it work -- the singer sings, the percussionist beats, silks and bamboo play in concert, bells and stones ring in turn. And I, in the midst of it all, hold up the great principle and seize the essential pivot -- rolling up and spreading out, opening and closing, sometimes showing a demon's mask or a god's face, sometimes extending a buddha's hand or a donkey's hoof. A thousand changes, ten thousand transformations, moving freely in all directions. The bystander merely blinks. Tell me: is this supernatural power and wondrous function, or simply the way things naturally are?" He paused: "Have you not heard: 'Just watch the puppet show on stage -- the one pulling the strings is the person behind the curtain.'"
E2: "If you want to trust that the plum blossom's fragrance strikes the nose, you must first endure one thorough bone-piercing cold."

=== Huanyou Zhengchuan ===
E1: One day the attendant Yuandi knelt before the master's couch and earnestly said, "Ever since I left home to study the Way, I still haven't found an entry point. I beg the master to show me a way -- how should I apply my mind in daily life?" The master said, "If you can't manage putting on clothes, eating rice, pissing, and shitting, and need this old monk to teach you -- well, this old monk's own skill is nothing but putting on clothes, eating rice, pissing, and shitting -- going with conditions and passing the time. There are no magical powers, special methods, or clever tricks here. What else do you have to doubt?" Yuandi said, "I have only one doubt, about this verse: 'Right at this very moment -- who comprehends it?'" The master said, "Go away for now. Come back another time and I'll tell you." Later, one day the master saw Yuandi passing by the abbot's quarters and called out, "Hey, you!" Yuandi answered "Yes!" and hurried in through the door. The master said, "Go fetch Yuandi for me." Yuandi hesitated, then said, "I am Yuandi." The master paused, his expression shifting, and said, "You are Yuandi? Then how is it I don't recognize you?" Yuandi stood there, dumbfounded, unable to speak. The master gave a shout: "Get out!"
E2: A monk who had long recited the Avatamsaka Sutra came and said, "I've chanted this sutra for years but still don't understand the meaning of the Four Dharma Realms. Please instruct me." The master said, "Just ask one by one." "What is the Dharma Realm of phenomena?" The master raised his fist. "What is the Dharma Realm of principle?" The master raised his fist. "What is the Dharma Realm where principle and phenomena are unobstructed?" The master raised his fist. "What is the Dharma Realm where all phenomena are unobstructed?" The master raised his fist. The monk, not understanding, went to the head monk and told him: "I asked the master four questions about the four Dharma Realms, and each time he just raised his fist. What did he mean?" The head monk said, "Do you understand?" The monk said no. The head monk said, "Ask me one by one." "What is the Dharma Realm of phenomena?" The head monk said, "The fist that was raised -- isn't that itself a phenomenon?" "What is the Dharma Realm of principle?" He said, "What raises it -- how is that different from the fist?" "What about principle and phenomena unobstructed?" He said, "The fist IS the raising. Can the raising and the fist be separated into two things?" "Then what is phenomena and phenomena unobstructed?" The head monk said, "If we're talking about all phenomena unobstructed, it's not just raising a fist or pointing a finger, blinking or raising the eyebrows -- it goes as far as rolling balls, waving staffs, striking the ground, holding fishing rods, drawing circles, bowing like a woman, and the meaning of the Four Dharma Realms pervades them all completely. It doesn't stop at monks or laypeople, men or women -- burning incense, bowing to Buddha, striking the chime, beating the drum, blowing the conch, playing music, receiving guests, carrying children, combing hair, washing faces, eating meals, wearing clothes, spinning cotton, weaving cloth, chopping wood, digging earth, planting grain, writing characters, reading books, wielding spears -- nothing fails to partake of this power and deeply accord with this meaning." The monk bowed three times in thanks. He then returned to the master to express his gratitude. The master simply acknowledged him.

=== Huanzhuming ===
E1: A monk asked: "The World-Honored One on the eighth of the twelfth month gazed at the morning star and awakened to the Way. What does the Master see today?" The Master said: "The red sun pierces my eyes." Another monk said: "The subtle meaning of the One Vehicle is entirely within silence. Why all this fuss today?" The Master shouted. The monk said: "Then quickly speak the phrase that is not fussy!" The monk continued: "A man of ambition has his own path to heaven and does not walk where others have walked." the Master replied: "The ancients already said that." The monk said: "Whatever you pick up, there is nothing that isn't it; wherever you apply it, doubt does not arise." the Master replied: "Have you truly reached the place of no-doubt?"
E2: A monk asked: "What about when it is bare and stripped clean?" The Master was silent for a long while, then said: "Do you understand?" The monk said: "I don't understand." The Master said: "There's still a single thread hanging."

=== Huigongxiong ===
E1: At his first formal Dharma-talk, the Master raised the whisk and struck a circle in the air, saying: "All the Buddhas of three times and all the ancestral teachers have just now, on top of this whisk, emitted great light and turned the great Dharma-wheel." He raised the whisk: "Do you see?" He struck it: "Do you hear? If you see -- the light is not blue, yellow, red, or white, so how do you see it? If you hear -- the Dharma transcends words, sounds, and letters, so how do you hear it? If you say you do not see, your own eyeballs are blocking you. If you say you do not hear, your own ears have plugged you up. Turn your body around right here, and Buddhas and Ancestors must stand downwind. Fail to do so, and today you are checkmated right before your face."
E2: At a small gathering on the third day of the first month, the Master said: "Today is said to be Maitreya Buddha's birthday. Anyone with spirit ought to find this suspicious. Why? Maitreya as future-buddha has not yet come. Maitreya as present-buddha -- where is he now? If you say he is in Tushita Heaven, that makes 'birthday' an empty tale. Even granting his actual birth, if I saw Maitreya, I would still follow Yunmen's example and beat him to death with one blow. Nevertheless, let me raise a case for him and for all of you."

=== Huijueyi ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is 'depriving the person but not the environment'?" The Master said: "An empty boat drifting on waves." "What is 'depriving the environment but not the person'?" "A destitute son without clothes." "What is 'depriving both person and environment'?" The Master suddenly held up his staff. "What is 'depriving neither person nor environment'?" The Master struck and said: "When one person has cause for celebration, ten thousand citizens rely on it."
E2: The Master raised the case: Zhaozhou said, "The gold buddha does not survive the furnace, the wood buddha does not survive fire, the clay buddha does not survive water. The true buddha sits within." The Master said: "Zhaozhou, that ancient buddha, always reveals one scene -- his eye-light shatters the four quarters. But in this particular turning, half remains unilluminated. If you ask me: the gold buddha must pass through the furnace, the wood buddha must pass through fire, the clay buddha must pass through water, and the true buddha -- has no fixed location."

=== Huike ===
E1: Huike stands in the snow, cuts off his arm, and asks Bodhidharma to pacify his mind. When told to bring out his mind, he says, "I have searched for the mind, but it cannot be found." Bodhidharma replies, "I have pacified your mind for you."
E2: Bodhidharma asked his four disciples what they had attained. Each spoke in turn. To the first he said, "You have my skin." To the second, "You have my flesh." To the third, "You have my bones." Huike simply bowed silently. Bodhidharma said, "You have obtained my marrow."

=== Huineng ===
E1: The Sixth Patriarch was pursued by Senior Monk Ming to Dayu Ridge. Seeing Ming arrive, he threw down the robe and bowl on a rock: "This robe is the emblem of faith; can it be contended for by force?" Ming lifted it but it would not move. Trembling, he said, "I came seeking the Dharma, not for the robe." The Patriarch said, "Do not think good, do not think evil -- at just such a time, which is Senior Monk Ming's original face?" Ming at once had great awakening, his whole body sweating.
E2: When the wind tossed the monastery banner, two monks debated. One said, "The banner moves." One said, "The wind moves." Back and forth, they never accorded with principle. The Patriarch said, "It is not the wind that moves, it is not the banner that moves; benevolent ones, it is your mind that moves." The two monks were startled.

=== HUITAI YUANJING ===
E1: At the opening ceremony, lay practitioner Yu Jiquan asked: "Linji said: If you grasp it at the first phrase, you can be teacher of Buddhas and patriarchs. At the second phrase, teacher of humans and gods. At the third phrase, you cannot even save yourself. Please instruct me -- what is the first phrase?" The Master said: "Bite through the iron Mount Kun-lun." "What is the second phrase?" "The skull of the Empty King splits open." "What is the third phrase?" "On the first night of the new year, gaze at the full moon." The layman was about to bow. the Master responded: "Wait. I also have three questions. If you answer, I'll grant you half an open eye. If not, do not take this matter lightly." "Please ask." "What is the one thought that has never arisen since beginningless time?" "Three times seven is twenty-one." "What is that which you use throughout the twelve hours?" "The wind and moon of Chang'an thread through past and present." "What is the smashing of the barrier of birth and death?" The layman raised his fist and cried: "There! There!" The Master said: "Not intimate enough. Say more." The layman said: "Please -- you say it yourself." The Master said: "Ask me one by one." "What is the one thought that has never arisen since beginningless time?" "Exactly so, exactly so." "What is that which you use throughout the twelve hours?" "Perfectly clear, perfectly clear." "What is the smashing of the barrier of birth and death?" "Don't be dreaming." The layman said: "Still only eighty percent." The Master said: "An old horse at rest still aims for a thousand miles. A hero in twilight years -- his bold heart never rests." The layman bowed.
E2: On the winter solstice, the Master called the assembly: "Today is the winter solstice. A single yang stirs within; the mass of yin issues outward. In the depth of bitter winter, how will you all prepare? Those rich in worldly means warm themselves by braziers in heated chambers, with fox-fur robes and fine wine. But we monks, fortunate to be born in the mild south of Fujian -- in stillness, we pull our patched robes over our heads and sit in closed rooms. In leisure, three or five of us gather round the stove for tea and conversation. But let me ask you further: the nobleman dispatched to a foreign land, the wealthy man trading in a distant province -- what about them, caught halfway? Born in a border country, low-caste and destitute -- what then? The criminal locked in prison right now with no food and no clothes -- what then? And when heavenly merit is exhausted and one falls into the freezing hells -- what then? To pity others' suffering is still one step removed. Setting yourself in their place is not so easy. Do not deceive each other, saying such suffering has nothing to do with us. Right now we are trapped inside the vajra ring. No matter how hard we struggle, we cannot jump out. Can we really escape the wheel of the six realms? Tell me -- how exactly do you escape this prison? Is there anyone here who, within the ring itself, is untouched by the coming and going of heat and cold, pain and pleasure? Is there anyone who, within the ring itself, can perform Buddha's work throughout all lands? If such a marvel exists, where is it? Show me."

=== Huitang Zuxin ===
E1: A monk asked Huitang, "What is the four-line verse?" Huitang said: "Even if words collapse, you still do not know." Yuanwu uses this to show that even the Diamond Sutra's most famous teaching cannot be caught in language -- Huitang's answer demolishes the question itself.
E2: When the official Huang Luzhi was in political difficulty, a man arrived at Huitang's place. Huitang asked, "Who sent you?" The man said, "Scholar Ye of Dalin." Huitang asked, "Is there a letter?" The man said yes, then drew open his robe collar, produced the letter, and presented it. Huitang said: "To study the Way to this degree -- that is acceptable." Huang looked ashamed. Wansong uses this to illustrate the difference between a "steady, solid, level man" and one who displays wit and shows off.

=== Huiyue Xu ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall. He had just sat down when he said: "Already wrong!" and immediately returned to the abbot's quarters. A monk came in and asked: "The Master had not yet spoken a single word and already said 'wrong.' Was the Master wrong, or was the assembly wrong?" the Master replied: "If you can discern these two 'wrongs,' your bones will be ground to powder." The monk said: "Thank you, Master, for the confirmation." The Master said: "Wrong! Wrong! Wrong!"
E2: During a work period of moving roof tiles, the Master picked up a tile and showed it to the assembly: "The entire Buddhist canon speaks only of this." At that moment a monk also picked up a tile and said: "The entire Buddhist canon does not speak of this." the Master responded: "Speaking and not speaking -- they're not even worth a single coin." The monk said: "Not even half a coin." the Master responded: "Today I've taken a loss." The monk smiled faintly. When the Master returned, he addressed the assembly: "Yunmen had a work period moving firewood; Jinming had a work period moving tiles. I won't speak of the entire canon -- I only want all of you to put it down. Is there anyone among you who can put it down?" No one spoke. The Master took up his staff and drove them all out at once, then returned to the abbot's quarters.

=== Huizhou Hao of Wanshan ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master said: "Good people! Do you recognize this old monk? If you want to recognize him, you must listen to the bells and drums being struck." He looked around: "Just now the bell has been rung and the drum beaten -- so how do you recognize the old monk?" No one answered. After a long pause he said: "If you cannot even recognize the bells and drums, how much less the old monk?" He gave a great shout and descended.
E2: A monk asked about the four modes of Linji: "How is it when the person is taken away but not the surroundings?" the Master answered: "A gentleman beneath the flowers, his dream not yet broken." "How is it when the surroundings are taken away but not the person?" "In the waves, alone occupying one fresh reed." "How is it when both person and surroundings are taken away?" "The moon sets at the third watch -- all words are cut off." "How is it when neither person nor surroundings are taken away?" "An old man on the embankment gazes at the green sedge."

=== Huqiu Shaolong ===
E1: Huqiu ascended the hall and held up his staff. "Call this a staff, and heaven and earth are worlds apart. Don't call it a staff, and heaven and earth are still worlds apart. The Buddhas of the three times, the Patriarchs of every generation, and all the old masters under heaven -- at this point they have a grievance with nowhere to cry out. If you just go like this, you exhaust the Dharma and leave no people." He then held the staff crosswise and looked left and right. After a long silence he said: "The three-foot Dragon Spring sword lights up the gall-bladder. In a peaceful realm it cuts through the foolish and obstinate." He gave a shout and struck the floor once.
E2: Huqiu held up his staff again and said: "Fenzhou said, 'Recognize the staff, and your traveling is finished.' But this is the staff -- so how do you finish your traveling?" He struck once and said: "If you don't understand, it's a lump of raw iron. If you understand, even a spoon can't lift it. Even if you find a turning-point before Fenzhou opened his mouth, that is still what Xuefeng already said." He slapped the seat and descended.

=== Ji Zongche (Nun Master) ===
E1: Ji Zongche raised the ancient case: "Governor Lu asked Nanquan: 'I'm raising a goose in a bottle. The goose has grown too big to get out. Without breaking the bottle or harming the goose, how do you get it out?' Nanquan called out: 'Governor!' Lu responded: 'Yes?' Nanquan said: 'It's out.'" The master commented: "Governor Lu was too clever by half. If not for Nanquan, the bottle would have shattered and the goose would have flown away, killing itself in the process. But tell me -- after the goose was called out, then what? A great roc soars ten thousand miles; a crane of a thousand years flies alongside."
E2: A monk asked about the five schools of Chan, one by one. "What is the Linji school?" -- "One blow, one welt." "What is the Caodong school?" -- "Travel by night is forbidden; you must arrive by dawn." "What is the Yunmen school?" -- "The sun behind your skull glows red." "What is the Fayan school?" -- "Arrow points meeting." "What is the Weiyang school?" -- The master drew a circle with her staff: "All of empty space bundled into a single ball."

=== JIANFU CHENGGU ===
E1: When Master Chenggu held his formal opening ceremony, Prefect Fan Zhongyan himself composed the invitation. After the reading, a monk asked: "Apes carry their young back behind the green cliffs; birds hold flowers and drop them before the jade crags. This is the scenery of Jiashan. What is the scenery of Jianfu?" the Master asked: "Don't." The monk pressed: "What is the person within the scenery?" The Master said: "Don't." Another asked: "We know the Master has long kept a treasure in his pouch. Today before the assembly, may we borrow a look?" The Master said: "Don't." "Is there no expedient means?" "Don't." "When the great good and wise teacher appears in the world, what does he use to help people?" "Don't." "Then there is both question and answer after all!" "Don't." A monk was about to ask another question. The Master said: "Enough questions. Even if you ask perfectly and I answer perfectly, it is still far from the Way. Assembly! These several monks asking questions have not yet shown the eye of a true renunciant. If you had the eye of one who has left home, upon hearing that a good and wise teacher has appeared ten thousand miles away, you would wash your ears, furrow your brows, brush your sleeves, and depart far away. How could you come here, throw yourself to the ground with all five limbs, and ask 'What about this? What about that?'"
E2: Ascending the hall, the Master raised the case: "Baizhang Heng sometimes ascended the hall, and as soon as the assembly gathered, he would say 'Drink tea' and step down. Sometimes he ascended the hall, and as the assembly gathered he said 'Take care' and stepped down. Sometimes he ascended the hall, and as the assembly gathered he said 'Rest' and stepped down. People could never fathom his meaning. Later, Heng composed a verse about these three turning-words: 'Baizhang had three precepts: Drink tea, Take care, Rest. If you accept them directly, I dare say you haven't penetrated.' Assembly! When Heng composed this verse, how was his understanding? Do you see the gain and loss? If you want to understand: when he ascended the hall those three times, he was like a fine person. But when he later composed this verse, it was like carving two lines of characters on his own face. If you are a person of penetrating understanding, you know at once when the matter is raised. For beginning students, it is hard to discern. This old monk will annotate it line by line for you: 'Baizhang had three precepts' -- the thief's body is already exposed. 'Drink tea, Take care, Rest' -- the stolen goods are brought out. 'If you accept them directly, I dare say you haven't penetrated' -- this is like a judge who examines the case while clutching the stolen goods himself."

=== Jianguan Ziyi ===
E1: Evening talk after entering the monastery: "A long sword leans against heaven, its edge concealed. Neither the three worthies can discern it, nor the ten sages fathom it." He held up the staff: "Look! Now the edge is revealed -- cold light pierces the stars, fierce energy frosts the air. Meeting a buddha, slay the buddha; meeting a patriarch, slay the patriarch. In all the great earth, who dares look straight at it? Is there anyone here who, heedless of mortal danger, can turn their body beneath the blade?" He struck with his staff: "I'll give you one move's grace."
E2: Mid-autumn, ascending the hall: "In heaven the moon is full; on earth the moon is half. The clear-eyed monk -- sees as if not seeing." He paused: "Do you see?" He flung down the whisk. "The cup falls and smashes on the ground; the saucer breaks into seven pieces."

=== JIANRU YUANMI ===
E1: Teaching the assembly, Yuanmi said: "Arsenic is inherently a weapon that kills. What matters is that the master physician knows how to use it. Killing and saving do not require one to claim a marvelous hand -- to locate the root of the disease is what counts. Take care!"
E2: On the Lantern Festival, Yuanmi said: "This lantern -- its whole body is a mouth. Tell it to walk and it walks. Tell it to run and it runs. Appearing and vanishing without reason, hiding in the Northern Dipper, throwing heaven and earth into chaos, making no distinction between before and after. Above, no teacher; below, no disciple. It continues the Buddha's mind-lamp, pressing through with its whole body. When the World-Honored One held up a flower, he still couldn't escape routine. That sloppy ascetic Kashyapa cracked a grin and broadcast the stink. Touch the slightest bit of it and it fills the universe. Its legacy upon the children and grandchildren -- fathomless depth, impossible to plumb. A thunderclap from a clear sky, one sound of a frog -- the iron ox breaks free from its tether. Truly beyond doubt."

=== Jiashan Shanhui ===
E1: Luopu visited Jiashan. Without bowing, he stood face to face. Jiashan said, "A chicken roosting in a phoenix nest is not of the same kind -- get out." Luopu said, "I have traveled far, drawn by your reputation; I beg the Master for a single audience." Jiashan said, "Before me there is no monk. Here there is no old monk." Luopu then gave a shout. Jiashan said, "Stop, stop, do not be so hasty and rushed. Clouds and moon are the same, but streams and mountains differ. Cutting off the tongues of everyone under heaven is not impossible -- but how will you make a tongueless man speak?" Luopu was speechless. Jiashan struck him. From then on Luopu submitted.
E2: A monk asked Jiashan, "When brushing away dust and seeing Buddha, how is it?" Jiashan said, "If you do not wield the sword, a fisherman will nest there." The same question was then asked of Shishuang, who said, "He has no country; where will you meet him?" When the monk reported Shishuang's answer, Jiashan ascended the hall and said: "In outward presentation he does not match this old monk, but in deep talk of entering principle he surpasses Shishuang by a hundred paces."

=== JIDIAN DAOJI ===
E1: Young Xiuyuan (later Daoji) was twelve, brilliant in literature. Entering a temple, he found monks competing to complete a poem for a patron who wished to sponsor one monk's ordination. The poem was a "Man Jiang Hong" about a hermit's life. None could complete the final couplet. Xiuyuan picked up the brush and wrote: "With pure eyes looking upon the three realms -- they are all just a single thatched hut." The patron and abbot were astonished.
E2: After ordination as Daoji, he found dhyana unbearable -- falling off the platform repeatedly, getting beaten by the monitor. He went to the abbot wanting to return to lay life. The abbot said, "Come closer." When Daoji stepped forward, the abbot grabbed him and gave him a single slap, saying, "This person will surely awaken." Daoji leapt up, stared at the abbot's chest, butted him headfirst off the chair, and ran away. The abbot called out, "Thief!" The monks gathered asking what was stolen. The abbot said, "The great treasure of the Zen school." From then on, Daoji ran wild -- singing street songs, eating meat on the Buddha hall floor, leading children in parades. The monks demanded punishment. The abbot wrote only ten characters: "The Zen school is vast -- can it not contain one mad monk? The mad one is the true one."

=== Jie'an Jin ===
E1: The Master raised Linji's saying: "There is a true person of no rank, constantly going in and out through the gates of your face. Those who have not yet realized it -- look! Look!" The assembly had no response. The Master turned to Chan Master Yuanmen: "What is the true person of no rank?" Yuanmen shouted. the Master replied: "What face does it ultimately have?" Yuanmen covered the Master's mouth with his sleeve. The Master said: "Say something else." Yuanmen said: "The nostrils still hang downward." The Master said: "Why do the Buddhas of the three worlds not know it exists?" Yuanmen said: "Everyone says 'resign your post and retire.'" The Master said: "Why do house-cats and water-buffalo know it exists?" Yuanmen said: "In the forest, I have never seen a single person." The Master turned to a bystander monk: "Why don't you look at how he answers?"
E2: The Master was viewing the moon and said: "You all look -- is the moon inside the trees, or are the trees inside the moon?" A monk said: "It is right before our eyes." the Master replied: "You have studied for many years, yet you still have not shed your worldly habits."

=== Jieshi Zhipeng ===
E1: Jieshi addressed the assembly at Baofu Monastery: "The ancients said: 'If a student's body and mind are not fierce and intense, if their effort has gaps, it is like intermittent malaria -- shivering one day, burning the next. When will such a person ever reach the great death and revival, arriving at the field of great peace?' Looking around, I see not a single person, not one moment of the twelve hours, who pursues this as fiercely as a bout of malaria. If only they would suffer one real attack! Why? When the cold shivers come, you clench both fists, bite down on your teeth -- even Buddha is unrecognizable. When the heat reaches its peak, fire pours from your mouth, your body heavy as a mountain. Then suddenly, one great sweat." He struck his staff and said: "This medicine cannot be omitted."
E2: Jieshi said: "Lingyun spent thirty years and could only say 'no more doubt' -- he never truly saw the face of the peach blossom. Xuansha said 'Quite right, quite right -- but I dare say the old brother hasn't penetrated through.' Even that is only like helping a drunk man across a bridge. But when Fenyang heard it and laughed out loud -- what was that? The path into Peach Blossom Spring goes deeper and deeper."

=== Jieweizhou ===
E1: A laywoman asked: "Setting aside the three mysteries and three essentials, what is Buddha?" The Master said: "Are you male? Or female?" The laywoman hesitated. The Master struck her and said: "You've already forgotten!" She continued: "What is the Dharma?" "It is as you hear it." "What is the Sangha?" "Make your prostration." "What are the three jewels of Buddha, Dharma, and Sangha?" "Putting on clothes. Eating rice." "Setting aside putting on clothes and eating rice, please, Master, speak." The Master struck her: "Have you even bitten through a single grain of rice yet?"
E2: A monk asked: "What is the Linji school?" -- "Killing Buddhas, killing Patriarchs." "What is the Caodong school?" -- "A son inheriting his father's enterprise." "What is the Yunmen school?" -- "The sound of a spring flowing forth as a vast tongue." "What is the Weiyang school?" -- "The blazing sun in open sky." "What is the Fayan school?" -- "No obstruction between any things." "These five houses you have shown me -- but what about here at Nanhu?" The Master struck him: "You try saying it." The monk shouted. The Master struck him again. The monk bowed and withdrew.

=== Jiguan Huo ===
E1: Evening talk. The Master asked: "After the ancients entered the hall, within three days or one week they each had a point of entry. Is there anyone among you like this? If so, come forward and let me see. If not, the sound of the living spring has already leaked it to you." A monk asked: "What about when the spring has not yet come alive?" the Master asked: "Before I entered this hall, where were you?" The monk made a gesture of holding something up and said: "Right here." The Master said: "That is something you learned by imitation. Ultimately, where were you?" The monk said: "I can only hang my mouth on the wall." The Master struck him. Another monk asked: "What about when the in-breath does not dwell in the realm of aggregates?" the Master replied: "I know you are making your living in the cave of ghosts." The monk said: "When the out-breath does not touch the ten thousand conditions -- what then?" The Master said: "Wandering monks running wild, thick as hemp and millet seeds." The monk bowed. The Master gave him a kick.
E2: Tea talk. The monk Zhuoan asked: "An ancient said: 'Where there is Buddha, do not stay. Where there is no Buddha, run past quickly.' What does it mean -- where there is Buddha, do not stay?" The Master said: "The fishing line dangles from the pole-tip -- play with it as you wish." "What does it mean -- where there is no Buddha, run past quickly?" The Master said: "Not floating on the clear waves -- the intent is something else."

=== JINGCI HUIHUI ===
E1: Ascending the hall on the fifteenth of the second month, Huihui said: "The Great Immortal of India today enters nirvana. The rice grains beneath the crane trees fall withered and pale. Tell me -- is this the same or different? The four trees with form are the Tathagata's sixteen-foot body. The four trees without form are the Tathagata's true seeing. People of this age see extinction; this mountain monk sees birth. People of this age see birth; this mountain monk sees death. Between these -- there is the principle of no-birth and no-extinction. And so the Great Awakened One toasted the assembly, and light shone forth from the coffin. What wondrous mind-seal text is written by those two upturned feet?" Shishuang Mingzong commented: "The Great Immortal Shakyamuni never truly entered final extinction. Only amidst rice grains did he take extinction as bliss. For he was playing on the character 'rice' (mi) -- whose strokes form 'eight trees' (ba mu). With these eight trees the Tathagata illuminated becoming, abiding, decay, and emptiness. Tell me: what about the matter in between? The wondrous text of the mind-seal -- not even a single dot of it can be put to use. Those who truly possess it, test and see for yourselves."
E2: The same evening, Huihui continued: "Look! The assembly on Vulture Peak has never dispersed! Look! The cloud-assembly of Jingci stands majestic and unconfused. Tell me: why did the Tathagata enter the empty cave? Why does this mountain monk ascend the empty hall? After all, there is no lack of old decrepit ones. When you reach the infirmary, how will you present the teaching?" He then recalled: "Master Xinfeng, at his final moment, asked a monk: 'Leaving this leaking shell, where will you meet me?' The monk had no answer." After a long silence, Huihui cried: "Chih! Only a Buddha together with a Buddha --" He opened both hands. "-- can fathom this completely."

=== Jingqing Daofu ===
E1: A monk says, "I chirp; please, Master, peck." Jingqing says, "Can you still get to live or not?" The monk says, "If I do not live, people will laugh at me." Jingqing says, "You are also a fellow in the grass."
E2: A monk says, "This student has not yet reached the source; please, Master, use an expedient." Jingqing says, "What source?" The monk says, "The source." Jingqing says, "If it is the source, how could it receive expedients?" The attendant asks, "Just now, did you strip it for him?" Jingqing says, "No." The attendant asks, "Then did you fail to strip it for him?" Jingqing says, "No." The attendant says, "What then is the venerable master's meaning?" Jingqing says, "A single dot of watery ink makes dragons in two places."

=== JINGTINGSONG ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master struck the seat with the whisk and said: "Do you hear it? If you hear it, then your ears are made deaf." He then held up the whisk: "Do you see it? If you see it, then your eyes are made blind. If you neither see nor hear, then what?" He waved the whisk: "Seen and not seen -- Mount Sumeru hangs upside down from a thread of tortoise-hair. Heard and not heard -- a hornless mud ox enters Lake Dongting. Beyond this there is still one device that surpasses all Buddhas and Patriarchs: the City of the Dharma King inside the eye of a gnat."
E2: Ascending the hall, the Master laid the staff horizontally and said: "Spring waters fill the four marshes." He stood the staff upright: "Summer clouds make strange peaks." He tapped it to the left: "The autumn moon spreads its brightness." He tapped it to the right: "Winter ridges display the solitary pine." Then: "Within these four phrases, one is guest-within-host, one is host-within-guest, one is guest-within-guest, one is host-within-host. If anyone can sort them out, a lifetime of study is complete."

=== Jinniu Heshang ===
E1: Master Jinniu, whenever it was mealtime, would carry his own rice bucket and dance in front of the monks' hall, laughing loudly, saying, "Bodhisattva children, come eat!" He did this for twenty years.
E2: A monk asked Changqing, "The ancients said, 'Bodhisattva children, come eat' -- what is the intent?" Changqing said, "It is very much like celebrating and praising because of the meal." The commentary: "If you are a golden-haired lion cub, there is no need for Jinniu to bring the rice bucket and dance and laugh. From three thousand miles away, you would already spot his fatal flaw."

=== Jiqi of Nanyue ===
E1: The master raised Xuefeng's saying: "At Lookout Pavilion I already met you; at Black Rock Ridge I already met you; at the front of the monks' hall I already met you." The master said: "Look -- the entire three-thousand great-thousand worlds are shaken at once by this old fellow. But at Xiangfu Temple we pay it no mind. No matter if they come a thousand or ten-thousand miles from Qi, Chu, Yan, or Zhao -- even if they cross Lake Tai and reach the Old Bamboo Shore, they still don't know where Mount Fuzhao is. Even if they walk west from the Shuiping King Temple to reach the front of the stockade, they don't know where Xiangfu Temple is. The sharpest fellow enters the gate, reads the plaque, and confirms: yes, this is Xiangfu Temple. But after three or four steps, a mud wall swaps out his eyeballs." Then he leaned forward and said: "Tell me -- have I met you all just now, or not?" The assembly hesitated. He swept them away with his staff in a whirlwind.
E2: The master raised Fenyang's saying: "Understand the staff and your study of Chan is complete." Then Letang's saying: "Understand the staff and you'll enter hell swift as an arrow." The master picked up his staff and said: "This plain straight staff -- people keep adding knots to it. Ever since I received it from Sanfeng, for years I've left it in a cold corner of the wall, never once stirring it. You tell me: do you understand it or not? Is the study of Chan finished or not? Will you enter hell or not? If you can sort it out, then Fenyang enters hell like an arrow and Letang's study of Chan is complete. If you cannot sort it out, this staff will be a curse and a calamity right in your eye." Then he snapped the staff in two and said: "Everyone -- don't you dare speak of it as two pieces."

=== Jiufeng Daoqian ===
E1: A monk asks Jiufeng, "What is the head?" Jiufeng says, "Opening the eyes, one does not notice dawn." The monk asks, "What is the tail?" Jiufeng says, "Not sitting on the ten-thousand-year bed." The monk asks, "When there is head without tail, how is it?" Jiufeng says, "In the end it is not precious." The monk asks, "When head and tail match, how is it?" Jiufeng says, "Sons and grandsons grow strong, but within the room no one knows it."
E2: After Shishuang dies, the assembly wants the head monk to succeed as abbot. Jiufeng refuses to approve. The head monk tries to prove his understanding by dying seated after lighting a single stick of incense. Jiufeng pats his back and says: "Dying seated, passing away standing -- these you have. But our late teacher's meaning -- you have not even dreamed of it."

=== Jue'an Kexiang ===
E1: Jue'an raised the case: "Guishan and Yangshan were picking tea. Guishan said: 'All day I only hear your voice but cannot see your form.' Yangshan shook the tea bush. Guishan said: 'You only grasp the function, not the essence.' Yangshan asked: 'How about you, Master?' Guishan was silent for a long time. Yangshan said: 'You only grasp the essence, not the function.' Guishan replied: 'I'll let you have thirty blows of the stick.'" Jue'an commented: "If the wind does not come, the tree does not move. Guishan and Yangshan, father and son, mutually displayed essence and function. The thirty blows of the black-thorn staff had already been administered -- not even ten thousand oxen could turn the weight of it."
E2: Dharma hall: "Manjushri and Samantabhadra expounded at length on principle and phenomena. Deshan and Linji employed only the stick and the shout. Do you all know how Xingsheng puts these to use?" He threw down his staff and said: "Though it is a dead snake, if you know how to handle it, it comes alive."

=== Juelang Daosheng ===
E1: A monk said: "The paper windows of your quarters are full of holes -- everyone has seen right through you!" The master said: "Even if someone shared my pillow and blanket, they would not necessarily see me in their dreams." The monk said: "The Way of the Buddhas and Patriarchs is like the sun in the sky -- how can you be so hidden?" The master said: "And now you're breaking in through the window yourself?" The monk was startled and withdrew.
E2: A monk in the guest hall asked: "I have a question for you." The master said at once: "I'm not available today." The monk said: "It's urgent -- please instruct me." The master said: "I said I'm not available, so why the urgency?" The monk bowed and stood there. The master looked at him and said: "Where are you from?" "Jianxing, the East Pagoda." The master said: "I hear the East Pagoda was struck by lightning -- did you know?" The monk said: "I didn't know." The master said: "Dead skull! Not even a lightning strike wakes you. And you call it 'urgent'?"

=== Juelangsheng (Daosheng) ===
E1: On the Buddha's birthday, a monk asked: "He pointed to heaven and earth right at birth -- so why did he go to Snow Mountain for six years before seeing a star and awakening? Was it real, or expedient?" the Master replied: "Hot broth goes down easy; old debts served cold are hard to settle." The monk pressed: "How is it, after all?" The Master said: "Chew through the tongue-tip and it still isn't meat." He then declared: "My staff was starving last night. It sat down and devoured Mount Sumeru without thanking the earth; drank up the ocean without toasting the source. Then it came up with a radical theory: 'The World-Honored One never pointed to heaven or earth at birth, and afterward never saw a star or awakened. This is all fabrication -- that's why Yunmen wanted to kill him with one blow.' The staff came to tell me, so I could present this outrageous new case at today's assembly." Then: "I gave a great shout -- 'You freak!' -- snapped the staff in two and burned it in a roaring fire. Now I have this brand-new staff, head straight, tail straight, no twisted knots. If anyone asks 'What is the meaning of the World-Honored One's birth?' -- just hit them and say: 'Congratulations! Good omen!'"
E2: In his opening-hall sermon, the Master laughed and said: "What a pity that old Bodhidharma, when he first met Emperor Wu of Liang, was never pushed up onto a high throne like this to see how he'd present the true meaning of coming from the West! If all he had was 'Vast emptiness, nothing holy' and 'I don't know who faces me' -- his face was three feet thick. If some clear-eyed person hadn't overturned his seat, he should have beaten the retreat drum himself and crossed the river on a reed. Why stay and make a spectacle, burdening all future generations?"

=== Juzhi ===
E1: Whenever Master Juzhi was questioned, he only raised one finger. Later a boy attendant, when a visitor asked, "What essential Dharma does the Master teach?" also raised his finger. When Juzhi heard of it, he took a knife and cut off the boy's finger. The boy, bearing the pain, ran away crying. Juzhi again called him. The boy turned his head. Juzhi then raised his finger. The boy suddenly had realization.
E2: When Juzhi was about to pass away, he told the assembly, "I received Tianlong's one-finger Chan. My whole life I have used it and never exhausted it." Wumen's comment: "The place of awakening of Juzhi and the boy was not on the finger."

=== Kaifu Daoning ===
E1: On the night of his first small gathering at Kaifu, Daoning said: "When the whole function is not employed, only those who share the Way know it. When illumination and function operate together, who can penetrate it?" He then raised the old saying of Bajiao: "If you have a staff, I will give you a staff. If you have no staff, I will take your staff away." Daoning commented: "Bajiao set up this standard, but through the ages it has rarely met anyone who truly heard it." Then he said, "Later, Juehai turned it around and said: 'If you have a staff, I take it away. If you have no staff, I give you one.' Juehai was like a man who measures his feet before buying boots -- to reach Bajiao, he still has a long way to go." "But the new Baoci says it differently: 'If you have a staff, I give you a staff' -- a gentleman who loves wealth acquires it by the proper way. 'If you have no staff, I take your staff' -- when kindness deepens, words fail, but the heart holds everything clearly." "Suppose someone comes forward and asks: 'Setting aside both approaches, what is the Baoci staff?'" A long silence. Then: "Right now I plant it on the summit of Mount Sumeru. Even a six-armed, three-headed one may not look upon it."
E2: A monk asked, "What is guest within guest?" Daoning said, "This year's poverty is like last year's poverty." The monk asked, "What is host within guest?" Daoning said, "Troops follow the seal; generals follow the tally." The monk asked, "What is guest within host?" Daoning said, "He removes his precious garments and puts on tattered, filthy robes." The monk asked, "What is host within host?" Daoning said, "He straddles the universe with his whole body -- who dares raise their head?" The monk asked, "You have explained the four ranks. What about the matter above, the hidden barrier?" Daoning said, "One gust, two gusts of clear breeze arise, scattering white clouds by the ten thousand."

=== LANGKONGSHUN ===
E1: The Master raised a case: "Emperor Taizong of the Song asked a monk: 'Where have you recently come from?' The monk said: 'From the Hermitage of Reclining Clouds.' The Emperor said: 'Deep in the reclining clouds you do not come to court -- why then are you here?' The monk had no answer. Xuedou answered for him: 'One cannot escape the supreme transformation.'" The Master then offered his own verse: "The dragon chants and mist arises; the tiger roars and a fresh wind stirs. A single cloud lies across the mountain path, and every sparrow and songbird loses its way."
E2: Evening talk: "The Way of the patchrobed monk is something special. Walking, every step must land firmly. Speaking, every sentence must hit the mark. Eating, every grain must be chewed. Sleeping, the whole body must lie down completely. Tell me, is there anyone here who walks and lands every step? Who sleeps with the whole body settled? Who eats and chews every grain? If not, this mountain monk will not begrudge his lips and offer you all a footnote." He gave a shout: "The great Way originally has no male or female form -- within the body of form, there is a body without form."

=== Langye Huijue ===
E1: A monk asks Langye: "Purity is originally so; how then do there suddenly arise mountains, rivers, and the great earth?" Langye simply repeats the question back: "Purity is originally so; how then do there suddenly arise mountains, rivers, and the great earth?" The commentary calls this "riding the thief's horse to chase the thief, seizing the thief's spear to kill the thief."
E2: Langye, ascending the hall, said: "Seeing, hearing, awareness, and knowing are all causes of birth and death. Seeing, hearing, awareness, and knowing are all the basis of liberation. It is like a lion wheeling and hurling itself -- south, north, east, west -- with no fixed resting place."

=== Lanshi Ling ===
E1: A monk asked about life before birth and after birth. The master said: "The sieve has lips." The monk bowed. The master said: "The rice can't jump out."
E2: ---

=== LAYMAN PANG ===
E1: Layman Pang first visited Shitou and asked: "Who is the one not companioned by the ten thousand dharmas?" Shitou covered his mouth with his hand. Pang had a flash of insight. Later he went to Jiangxi and asked Mazu the same question. Mazu said: "Wait until you can drink up the entire West River in a single gulp -- then I'll tell you." At these words, Pang instantly penetrated the profound meaning. One day Pang asked Mazu: "The one who does not obscure the original person -- please, Master, look with elevated eyes." Mazu looked straight down. Pang said: "You alone play this stringless lute with such mastery." Mazu looked straight up. Pang bowed. Mazu returned to his room. Pang followed and said: "Just now, trying to be clever, you made a mess of it."
E2: One day Layman Pang was sitting in his thatched hut when he suddenly said: "Difficult, difficult, difficult -- like trying to scatter ten bushels of sesame seeds all over a tree." His wife said: "Easy, easy, easy -- like touching your feet to the ground when you get out of bed." Their daughter Lingzhao said: "Neither difficult nor easy -- on every blade of grass, the Patriarch's meaning."

=== Lianfeng ===
E1: A monk asked: "The Buddha appeared in the world for the sake of sentient beings. The Master also goes forth to save beings. What about before sentient beings are liberated?" The Master said: "Eyes horizontal, nose vertical." "What about after they are liberated?" "Nose vertical, eyes horizontal." "What about when they are completely liberated?" "A total embarrassment."
E2: A monk asked about the four modes. "What is 'seizing the person but not the environment'?" The Master said: "A needle-point crushes the titan Asura." "Seizing the environment but not the person?" "An ant's mouth swallows the great ocean dry." "Neither person nor environment seized?" "A crescent moon rises from the sea -- how many families go up to their rooftop?" "Both person and environment seized?" "Do not tell your sorrows to the sorrowful; tell them, and you kill the sorrowful with sorrow." "Is there anything beyond these?" The Master said: "String them on a single thread."

=== Liangting Ting ===
E1: Ascending the hall: "A hundred flowers have all fallen, yet the cuckoo's crying has no end; its cry carries on into the deepest peaks. Ha! It has cried until blood flows -- what use is that? Today Yunxi has lost the advantage."
E2: At a small gathering: "Better to meet a hostile stranger than an old acquaintance -- on a narrow road, enemies collide. The Lay Practitioner Shan suddenly asked me point-blank: 'What is "waves flooding heaven from the top of Mount Sumeru"?' I was asked, and like a mute man tasting bitter melon, I could barely open my mouth. Fortunately the Lay Practitioner is a supremely clever man and took away two sentences of doctrinal reasoning. But even so -- a mustard seed containing Sumeru, Sumeru containing a mustard seed, huge waves surging, white breakers flooding heaven -- don't you dare understand all this as mere doctrinal reasoning." Then he chanted: "Topsy-turvy, topsy-turvy! Sumeru has no peak, the waves flood heaven, lotuses bloom red on dry land. Driving the great elephant, a lotus thread for a leash; at midnight, riding a fish through the marketplace, both ends of the staff piercing through."

=== Lianyue ===
E1: A monk asked: "Looking up, boring in, gazing ahead, then suddenly behind -- what is the meaning?" The Master responded with a verse: "Hard as a cotton ball, soft as iron. A snowflake in the sixth month's blazing heat. The pillars and lamp-stands smile and nod their heads -- a mute man has a dream -- to whom can he tell it?"
E2: The Master cited Hanshan's poem: "The old woman next door, rich for three or five years -- she used to be poorer than me, now she laughs that I have no money. She laughs at me from behind; I laugh at her from ahead. If the mutual laughter never stops, from east to west it goes." the Master answered: "Everyone! If you can't get it right here, you could chew through five thousand volumes of scripture and it would still be someone else's tea and rice -- your eyes are full but your belly is empty. Just put it off until the thirtieth of the twelfth month, and then like a crab thrown into the boiling pot, all your legs will scramble in every direction."

=== Liao'an Qingyu ===
E1: Liao'an held evening discourse: "Deshan held evening talks and answered no questions -- a treacherous minister in a peaceful age. Zhaozhou held evening talks and answered questions -- a hero in a time of chaos. Both old men committed boundless offenses." "The new abbot at Qiyuan, entering office with many affairs, has had no leisure for testing and probing. Tonight, let me just reach out a single hand for the Patriarch and set the cracked clay pot in order, so that all may share in its use." With the whisk he drew a circle in the air and said: "Do you understand? The Southern Dipper turns west, the Northern Dipper shifts east." Then he raised a case: "A monk asked Touzi, 'What is the ten-body sovereign?' Touzi stepped down from his seat and stood there." Liao'an offered his verse: "Dawn flowers just opening, the dew-fragrance fresh. Alone it faces the empty mountain, propping up the clouds in the cold. Suddenly the spring wind lightly touches it -- pale red petals fall in wild confusion."
E2: Duanqiao Miaolun (Liao'an's teacher) once picked up the Dharma robe and said: "This single piece of cowhide -- all the old masters under heaven have been wrapped up in it. Today the new Qiyuan was a moment too slow in dodging, and he too has been caught. He can only accept it joyfully. Wear it on the crown of the head, drape it over the shoulders -- why would one dread being dragged through the mud?"

=== LIAOTANG WEIYI ===
E1: A monk asked: "What can be placed in the diamond eye?" said the Master, "Never mind what can be placed there -- what do you call the diamond eye?" The monk said, "This student doesn't understand." the Master answered, "Ask the lamp post." The monk pressed further: "How should one exert effort through the twelve hours of the day?" The Master said, "There is nowhere for you to exert effort." The monk bowed. The Master then said: "I've been ill in my quarters and haven't ascended the hall for a long time. Yet though spoken words may have gaps, this dharma has no gaps. Day and night I have relied entirely on the myriad forms of the universe -- walls, tiles, and pebbles -- to expound the teaching for the assembly. As it is said: 'Dust preaches, worlds preach, blazingly they preach, all three times completely preach.' If you try to hear it with your ears, you'll never understand. Only when the eyes hear sound does it become truly intimate." He gave a shout.
E2: New Year's Eve, evening talk. A monk asked: "On the last night of the year, a traveler ten thousand miles from home -- who is this person who has not yet returned?" The Master said, "Eyes like drumsticks." The monk said, "Who knows that across the distant misty waves, there are fine thoughts?" The Master said, "You've mistaken the fixed star on the astrolabe." The Master then said: "Just now it was the winter solstice, now it's already New Year's Eve. The two luminaries rush along, the ten thousand things succeed each other. Floating life is like this -- gain and loss, flourishing and decline, all just a tangle of confusion. We who are monks and disciples of Shakyamuni have no hunger or cold pressing us, no corvee labor burdening us. Through the twelve hours of the day, what should we be doing? Seeking the mysterious and marvelous is a waste of spirit. Doing nothing at all is just being slovenly. Great Master Linji said: 'There is a true person of no rank, constantly going in and out through the gates of your face. Those who have not yet verified this -- look! Look!' But even speaking this way is still ten thousand miles from Yazhou." After a long silence: "Next year there will be new branches -- they will trouble the spring wind without cease."

=== LIAOZONG OF PANSHAN ===
E1: A monk asked: "An empty valley transmits an echo -- where does the echo return to?" the Master replied: "A thousand mountain ridges reach their limit at the great peak; ten thousand streams find their end where the sea swallows them." The monk pressed: "Shakyamuni appeared in the world, Bodhidharma came from the West -- what did they talk about?" said the Master: "Not half a word." The monk said: "Then why are there the Three Vehicles and Twelve Divisions of scripture?" The Master said: "Cut the tangled vines." The monk said: "Every day I study the Way, but I do not know where the Way is." The Master struck him.
E2: Ascending the hall: "If we speak of the Buddha-dharma, it has been here all along, without the slightest gap. The whole great earth is a gate of liberation, bright as the sun and moon, illuminating past and present. Only because from beginningless time our deluded thinking has been thick and heavy, we have turned our backs on our own radiance." He raised the whisk and said: "If you are a great hero, turn the light around and take it up directly. Stand firm and be the master. Then you walk hand in hand with all the Buddhas and Patriarchs, coming and going together."

=== Lingji (Guan) of Zifu ===
E1: "For fifty years, Zifu has never bitten into a single grain of rice. What then has he been eating? For fifty years, Zifu has never worn a single thread of silk. What then has he been wearing? If you understand this, not only do you deserve to consume ten thousand taels of gold daily, you deserve the offerings of the four continents. If you don't understand -- for every grain of rice, every thread of silk, you must drag the plow and pull the harrow to pay it all back. Why is it so? If you take a cow from someone, you must return a horse."
E2: The master opened the Dharma for forty years. His talks and encounters were plentiful. But he constantly scolded those who muddied the separate transmission with written words, and forbade all copying. After his death, not a single character remained for posterity -- what survives was secretly jotted by long-serving attendants, perhaps one-tenth of the whole. As one preface noted: "Language from his record is like fire that must be hot, like water that must be wet, like gold that must be hard, like a blade that must be sharp -- how could one deliberate or revise? If you delete or embellish, you produce a painted puppet, not a living person."

=== Lingyin Wen ===
E1: A monk asked: "The ancients awakened upon seeing peach blossoms. Why is it that people today see flowers and do not awaken?" the Master answered: "Because you do not recognize it." The monk said: "I'm awakened! I'm awakened!" The Master said: "Then give me back the news." The monk was speechless. The Master struck him. Then he said: "Spring reaches the doorstep and the hermit grows rich. Glorious peach blossoms are right before the eyes. I dare ask the cloud-and-water guests in both halls: Reverend Ling has seen through it -- what do you call this Chan? Don't say it is the flower-holding and subtle smile. Don't say it is striking bamboo or raising the pitchfork. Don't say it is using the staff or shouting. Don't say it is rolling the ball or drawing the bow. Don't say it is beating the drum or shaking the bell. Today when I examine all of these, none of them will do." He suddenly raised the whisk and called out to the assembly: "Ultimately, how is it?" The verger struck the chime once. The Master said: "No need to add a point to the arrowhead."
E2: The Master raised this case: "Layman Pang first called on Shitou and asked: 'Who is the one who is not a companion to the ten thousand dharmas?' Shitou covered the Layman's mouth with his hand, and the Layman had an insight. He then brought this same question to Mazu. Mazu said: 'Wait until you have swallowed the West River in a single gulp, and then I will tell you.' At these words the Layman was greatly awakened." The Layman composed a verse: "My sons unmarried, my daughters unwed, the whole family gathered in a circle, together we speak the talk of no-birth." The Master said: "The family circle we can set aside. But what is this talk of no-birth? Do you understand? The sound of the stream is nothing but the vast, long tongue. The color of the mountains is nothing but the pure dharma-body."

=== Linji Yixuan ===
E1: Linji asked Huangbo three times, "What is the great meaning of the Buddha-dharma?" Each time Huangbo struck him. Linji left and went to Dayu. Dayu asked why he came. Linji said, "Three times I asked and three times I was struck. I don't know if I was at fault." Dayu said, "Huangbo was so grandmotherly kind to you, and you come here asking about fault?" At these words Linji was greatly awakened and said, "So there isn't much to Huangbo's Buddha-dharma after all!" Dayu grabbed him: "You bed-wetting devil! A moment ago you said you didn't know, and now you say there isn't much to it. Speak!" Linji punched Dayu three times in the ribs. Dayu pushed him away: "Your teacher is Huangbo. It's none of my business."
E2: Puhua goes around the marketplace ringing a bell, saying: "If you come in the light, I hit you in the light. If you come in the dark, I hit you in the dark. If you come from the four directions and eight sides, I hit you like a whirlwind. If you come from empty space, I hit you with a flail." Linji sends his attendant to grab Puhua and ask: "When none of these apply, what then?" Puhua pushes the attendant away and says: "Tomorrow there's a feast at the Great Compassion Temple." The attendant reports back. Linji says: "I've always had my doubts about that fellow." Later, Puhua begs for a robe in the marketplace. Everyone offers one. Puhua refuses them all. Linji has the temple steward buy a coffin. Puhua comes back. Linji says: "I've had a robe made for you." Puhua shoulders the coffin and goes through the marketplace shouting: "Linji has made me a robe! I'm going to the East Gate to die!" People follow him to watch. Puhua says: "Not today. Tomorrow I'll go to the South Gate to die." After three days of this, nobody believes him anymore. On the fourth day, with no one following, he goes outside the city alone, climbs into the coffin, and asks a passerby to nail it shut. Word spreads. People rush to open the coffin: the body is gone. Only the sound of his bell could be heard, fading high into the sky.

=== Linwo ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall and raised the case: "National Teacher Nanyang Zhong one day called to his attendant. The attendant responded. Like this three calls, three responses. The National Teacher said: 'I was going to say I had failed you, but it turns out you have failed me.'" the Master answered: "This case is most extraordinary. Some say the National Teacher was compassionate toward the attendant, so he used 'falling into the weeds' talk. Others say the attendant saw through the National Teacher, so he responded unfailingly. If you judge it this way, you are gazing at Changlu from Zhenzhou. Fahai says otherwise. Don't you know? The National Teacher's three calls were stale rice in a mud stove. The attendant's three responses were red clay smeared on cow's milk. But tell me, what about the line 'you have failed me'?" He waved the whisk and said: "The lion teaches its cub the art of losing its trail -- no sooner does it leap than it turns its body again." He threw down the whisk and descended.
E2: A monk asked: "What is the student's most intimate phrase?" The Master said: "When cold, go near the fire; when hot, seek the shade." The monk asked: "What is the student's phrase of turning the body?" The Master said: "In a dream, the six realms are perfectly clear; upon waking, the great void is utterly empty." The monk asked: "What is the student's phrase of the upward path?" The Master said: "Stamp out the moon that fills a thousand feet of sky; wash clean the frost that covers every tree." The monk asked: "What is the student's final phrase?" The Master struck him and said: "You haven't even dreamed of it."

=== Linyeqi ===
E1: On the Dragon Boat Festival, Linyeqi says: "Today is the festival. There's nothing special anywhere. Luckily our fundraiser came back and made big steamed buns. Tell me: compared to the story of Guanyin who went to buy sesame cakes but reached down and found a steamed bun instead -- how far apart are they?" He looks left and right: "Among us there are also guests from south of the Yangtze. Please don't sing the partridge song into your wine cups."
E2: A monk tests him with the Four Guest-Host positions. "What is 'host within guest'?" -- "Before you even asked, the face was already showing." "What is 'guest within host'?" -- "Rising and sitting, perfectly clear." "What is 'guest within guest'?" -- "Three thousand miles away, sorting out confusions." "What is 'host within host'?" -- "No place for your interpretive chatter." Monk pushes: "What about host and guest in perfect accord?" Linyeqi strikes him: "Grasp it right here."

=== Liu Tiemo ===
E1: One day she went to visit Guishan. When Guishan saw her coming he said, "Old cow, you've come." Tiemo said, "Tomorrow at Mount Tai there is a great assembly feast. Will the master go?" Guishan let his body go and lay down. Tiemo then went right out. The commentary says: "Like two mirrors reflecting one another with no image between them -- move matching move, phrase fitting phrase."
E2: Zihu went to visit her and said, "Are you Liu the Iron Grinder or not?" The Grinder said, "I would not dare." Zihu said, "Turn left, turn right." The Grinder said, "Venerable, do not turn things upside down." Zihu gave a shout and struck her.

=== Longtan Chongxin ===
E1: Deshan consulted Longtan deep into the night. Longtan said: "The night is deep -- why do you not go down?" Deshan bowed, rolled up the blind, and stepped out. He said: "It is dark outside." Longtan then lit a paper candle and handed it to him. Just as Deshan was about to take it, Longtan blew it out. Deshan suddenly had insight and bowed. Longtan said: "What principle have you seen?" Deshan said: "From now on I will not doubt the words of the old masters under heaven." The next day Longtan ascended the hall and said: "Among you there is a fellow whose fangs are like sword trees and whose mouth is like a blood basin. Strike him with a staff and he does not turn his head. One day he will establish my Way on a solitary peak."
E2: Longtan Chongxin was originally the son of a cake-seller on the temple street. He would daily bring ten cakes to offer to Master Tianhuang Daowu. Daowu would accept them and after eating always keep one cake back, saying, "I bestow this on you to shade your descendants." One day Chongxin thought to himself, "The cakes are what I bring -- why does he give one back to me? Could there be some other meaning?" So he went and asked. Daowu said, "It is you who bring them. What fault is there in returning them to you?" Hearing this, Chongxin had some understanding of the profound principle and asked to leave home as a monk. Daowu said, "In the past you pursued blessings through goodness; now you trust my words. You may be named Chongxin." From then on he served diligently at Daowu's side. One day he asked, "Since I arrived, you have never pointed out the essential of mind to me." Daowu said, "Since you came, I have never failed to point out the essential of mind to you." Chongxin said, "Where have you pointed it out?" Daowu said, "When you bring tea, I receive it for you. When you bring food, I accept it for you. When you bow, I nod my head. Where have I not pointed out the essential of mind?" Chongxin lowered his head and stood silent for a long while. Daowu said, "If you see it, see it directly right now. If you try to think about it, you miss it." At these words Chongxin broke through to understanding.

=== Longya Judun ===
E1: Longya asks Cuiwei, "What is the Patriarch's meaning in coming from the West?" Cuiwei says, "Bring me the dhyana board." Longya hands it to him. Cuiwei receives it and immediately strikes him. Longya says, "Strike me if you like -- there is still no Patriarch's meaning in coming from the West." He then asks Linji the same question. Linji says, "Bring me the sitting cushion." Longya hands it over; Linji strikes him. Longya again says, "Strike if you like, but there still is no Patriarch's meaning." Later, as abbot, a monk asks if those two masters understood or not. Longya says, "They understood indeed, but there still is no Patriarch's meaning."
E2: After failing with Cuiwei and Linji, Longya asks Dongshan, "What is the Patriarch's meaning in coming from the West?" Dongshan says, "When the stream in the cave flows backward, then I'll tell you." At this the master awakened.

=== Longyuan Jieqing ===
E1: At Daochang Mountain, Longyuan addressed the assembly: "The Great Penetrating Wisdom Buddha -- utterly beyond name and form. Ten kalpas sitting on the bodhi-seat -- long habits become obstructions. Buddha-dharma does not appear -- yet this is somewhat better. He does not attain Buddhahood -- the whole body revealed as genuine. I have already laid out the ancient Buddha's fine counsel and disclosed it all to you. Yet as they say, 'The clouds and moon are the same, but each valley and mountain differs.' Two mountains and one gate control your path of entry. Now that you stand before the clear pool at the base of these cliffs, have you ever seen fire burning in the midst of water? If you can see it, then hand in hand with the patriarchs you may roam freely through the tiger's den."
E2: Longyuan raised: National Teacher Yanquan called to his attendant, "Bring me my rhinoceros-horn fan." The attendant said, "The fan is broken." The National Teacher said, "Then return the rhinoceros to me." The attendant had no reply. Touzi said, "I wouldn't refuse to bring it out, but I fear the horns wouldn't be complete." Xuedou said, "I want the incomplete horns." Shifang said, "If I return it to you, there'd be nothing left." Xuedou said, "The rhinoceros is still there." Zifu drew a circle with a character for "ox" inside. Baofu said, "Your Reverence is getting old -- better ask someone else." Longyuan commented on each response, then concluded: "This whole group of old fellows -- if they had actually gotten the rhinoceros fan and put it to use, they would never have quarreled so desperately over scraps. Have any of you ever put it to use? Please go back to the hall and check for yourselves."

=== Lumen Zijue ===
E1: "Master Zhichan of Lumen pointed at the monk and said, 'One who truly knows the Dharma is filled with dread.'" A concise judgment on a monk who recognized the pivot of a koan -- knowing it is genuinely dangerous.
E2: "Lumen said: 'The whole great earth is the student's one scroll of scripture; all heaven and earth are the student's one eye.' With this eye, read such a scripture, and through thousands of myriads of millions of kalpas there is never interruption." Wansong drily adds: "Reading in this way is not easy."

=== Luohan Guichen ===
E1: Dizang (Luohan Guichen) says to Xuansha: "I have heard that the master has talk of the three kinds of sick people, is that so?" Xuansha says, "It is." Dizang says, "Guichen now has eyes, ears, nose, and tongue. How do you receive him?" Xuansha then stops.
E2: Dizang (Luohan Guichen) said to Xuansha, "I have heard that the master has talk of the three kinds of sick people -- is that so?" Xuansha said, "It is." Dizang said, "Guichen now has eyes, ears, nose, and tongue. How do you receive him?" Xuansha then stopped. Later a monk brought it up to Yunmen. Yunmen immediately understood and said, "You, bow." The monk bowed and rose. Yunmen struck with his staff. The monk stepped back. Yunmen said, "You are not blind." He called the monk close again. The monk came near. Yunmen said, "You are not deaf." Then he said, "Do you understand?" The monk said, "I do not understand."

=== Luopu Yuanan ===
E1: Luopu visits Jiashan without bowing, standing face to face. Jiashan says, "A chicken roosting in a phoenix nest is not of the same kind -- get out." Luopu softens: "I have traveled far, drawn by your reputation; I beg the Master for a single audience." Jiashan says, "Before me there is no monk. Here there is no old monk." Luopu shouts. Jiashan says: "Stop, stop. Clouds and moon are the same, but streams and mountains differ. Cutting off the tongues of everyone under heaven is not impossible -- but how will you make a tongueless man speak?" Luopu is speechless. Jiashan strikes him. From then on Luopu submits.
E2: Near death, Luopu addresses the assembly: "Now there is one matter. If this is so, it is putting a head on top of a head; if it is not so, just cutting off the head to seek life." His senior monk Yancong steps forward and says, "Leaving aside these two paths, I ask the master not to question them." Luopu says, "Not there yet. Speak further." Back and forth until Luopu calls him in the evening and tries to entrust him with the robe and bowl. Cong says, "I do not understand." Luopu shouts, "Bitter! Bitter indeed, bitter indeed!"

=== Luyan He ===
E1: The Master cited several great teachers on "returning to the source": Shakyamuni said if one person returns to the source, all of space collapses. Wuzu said space bumps and knocks against you. Yuanwu said space adorns itself with brocade flowers. Chushi said a needle cannot pierce through space. the Master answered: "If one person returns to the source, all of empty space is simply all of empty space."
E2: The Master said: "Not mind, not Buddha." Then he spread open both hands: "Open wide both hands for all to see -- ultimately, what is this thing?" After a long silence he said: "Countless people chase after echoes in the void, but to the end no one can transmit the sound of high antiquity." He descended from the seat.

=== Luzu Baoyun ===
E1: Whenever Luzu saw a monk come, he would immediately face the wall. Nanquan heard of this and said, "I ordinarily tell him: Before the empty kalpa, bear it up; before the Buddha appeared in the world, even to understand at that time, one cannot get even one or half a one. Yet going on like this, he will continue till donkey-year."
E2: A monk asked, "What is speechless speech?" Luzu said, "Where is your mouth?" The monk said, "I have no mouth." Luzu said, "Then what do you eat rice with?" The monk had no reply. Dongshan substituted: "He is not hungry -- what rice would he eat?"

=== Mayu Baoche ===
E1: Magu carries his staff to Zhangjing, circles the seat three times, shakes the staff once, and stands upright. Zhangjing says "Yes, yes." Magu then goes to Nanquan and performs exactly the same ritual. Nanquan says: "No, no." Magu: "Zhangjing said yes; why does master say no?" Nanquan: "Zhangjing is indeed yes; it is you who are no. This is merely blown about by the force of wind -- in the end it becomes ruin and decay."
E2: Magu also once went to National Teacher Zhong and performed his staff-shaking ritual. The National Teacher said: "You came first from Mazu's place -- what use is there in seeing this poor monk again?" Magu shook the staff again. The National Teacher said: "This wild fox spirit -- leave, leave!"

=== Mazu Daoyi ===
E1: Mazu was sitting in his hut doing nothing but seated dhyana. Nanyue took a brick and began polishing it in front of the hut. Mazu asked, "What are you doing?" Nanyue said, "Polishing it into a mirror." Mazu said, "How can polishing a brick make a mirror?" Nanyue said, "If polishing a brick cannot make a mirror, how can sitting in dhyana make a buddha?" Mazu rose from his seat. Nanyue said, "If you are sitting as buddha, you kill buddha. If you cling to the sitting posture, you have not reached the principle." At these words, Mazu was completely awakened.
E2: Shuilao asks: "What is the meaning of the Patriarch coming from the West?" Mazu says: "Bow down." As Shuilao bows, Mazu kicks him. Great awakening. Shuilao stands up clapping and laughing: "How marvelous! Hundreds of thousands of samadhis, countless meanings -- recognized at their source on the tip of a single hair!" Later he tells his assembly: "Ever since I took that one kick from Master Ma, I haven't been able to stop laughing."

=== Meixi Du of Dongshan ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the past mind that cannot be grasped?" "Last night the bright moon hung in the doorway." "What is the present mind that cannot be grasped?" "This morning fine rain drifts through the curtain." "What is the future mind that cannot be grasped?" "Tomorrow when I ascend the hall, I will tell you."
E2: A monk asked: "The five watches end, the last moon has set, dawn comes, white clouds fly. This is clearly the matter before our eyes -- why is it not the device before our eyes?" said the Master: "Clearly the fragrance is on the plum blossom; search for it on the plum blossom, and the fragrance is gone."

=== Mi'an Xianjie ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall and raised a case: "In former times, an old woman supported a hermit for twenty years, always sending a young girl to bring him food. One day, she instructed the girl to embrace the hermit and say, 'What about right now?' The hermit replied, 'A dead tree leans against a cold cliff -- in the depths of winter, not a trace of warmth.' The girl returned and told the old woman. The old woman said, 'For twenty years I have only been supporting a common layman!' She then had the hermitage burned down." The Master commented: "This case -- few in the monasteries dare to take it up. I, your teacher, will tear off the skin of my face and risk one disastrous attempt. Let everyone examine it. The old woman -- her inner chambers were deep and impenetrable, watertight. Yet she deliberately scattered flowers on a dead tree and kindled flames amid cold cliffs. The monk -- solitary and aloof, accustomed to entering the great waves -- he easily sat still through the surging tide, and in the end not a drop of water touched his body. Examine this carefully: as for the cangue around their necks and the shackles on their legs -- yes, both of them are guilty. But as for the buddha-dharma? They have not dreamed of it yet."
E2: A monk asked, "What was Deshan's meaning when he carried his bowl down to the monks' hall?" the Master replied, "No meaning." The monk pressed, "Then why did he carry the bowl down to the hall?" The Master said, "He wanted to walk, so he walked. He wanted to sit, so he sat." The Master then raised a case: "Xuefeng once addressed the assembly saying, 'The entire great earth, take it up, and it is the size of a grain of millet. Toss it right before your face -- the lacquer bucket does not understand! Beat the drum and call everyone to look!' This old fellow -- three times he climbed to Touzi, nine times he went to Dongshan, exhausted every calculation. Finally at Turtle Mountain Inn he made one losing deal, crying out, 'Today Turtle Mountain has attained the Way! Today Turtle Mountain has attained the Way!' He then took the entire great earth and all its beings as his own personal domain. The result: for a thousand years afterward, the ancestral tradition has been humiliated. I tell you this not to put down Xuefeng, but to urge all you monks: each of you has your own livelihood. Don't all become wild fox-spirit types." He shouted and descended.

=== Miaoyun of Dabei ===
E1: When Miaoyun first met Master Jie'an at Jinming, the old teacher said: "The lion's den is sealed with clouds, there is no gate front or back. From where did you enter?" The Master replied: "What enters through the gate is not the family treasure." The old teacher said: "You are a wandering monk. Why are you making your living in the womb of a donkey and the belly of a horse?" the Master answered: "Today I have seen the Reverend in person." The old teacher said: "Look at my eyebrows -- how many have fallen out?" The Master said: "They are growing." The old teacher said: "Never mind the money for broth -- who will pay for your straw sandals?" The Master said: "How much does the Reverend owe?" The old teacher struck him. the Master answered: "If you don't enter the raging waves, how will you ever meet the one who rides the tide?"
E2: The Master was sitting by the fire with his dharma-brother Zhufeng. The old teacher said: "By the fire there is a host-and-guest phrase. Speak it." The Master said: "The Reverend sits; I stand." The old teacher pointed at the fire: "Why does flame arise from cold ashes?" the Master replied: "It is not something extraneous." The old teacher rapped the stove with the fire-poker: "Can you leap out of this?" the Master responded: "Not just I alone -- even the Buddhas of the three ages are entirely within it." The old teacher said: "You had better be very careful."

=== Mingdao Zhengjue Sen ===
E1: A monk asked, "This student's eye of the Way is not yet clear. What is the obstruction?" The master said, "When did spring begin?" The monk said, "Yesterday, the twenty-third." The master said, "And you blame me?"
E2: At the end of the retreat, a monk asked, "The treasury of the true dharma eye I'll set aside -- but what is today's phrase for the end of the retreat?" The master said, "The mountain's nostrils are pierced clean through." The monk bowed. The master burst out laughing and said, "Although I've laid everything out in the open, it's still utterly different from what you think. Master Langya said, 'Originally there is not a single thing' -- and that phrase has disgusted people throughout the world. Even if you get it perfectly clear, you're still sitting in a shit-pit. Tell me: what is the path of liberation?" Then he rattled off: "The wonderful sound of Avalokiteshvara! The Brahma sound! The voice of ocean tides!" And to the assembly: "Look east in the morning, look west at night. In these degenerate days, even the double flute comes from foreign lands. Can't even get a meal before the gourd runs dry." And he stepped down from the seat.

=== Mingjue ===
E1: The Master one day raised a case for the assembly: "In former times, there was an old master who spent an entire summer retreat without speaking a word of dharma to the monks. One monk sighed and said, 'I have just wasted this whole summer like this. I did not expect the Master to teach the buddha-dharma, but if I could even hear the two words "true cause," it would be enough.' The old master happened to overhear this and said, 'Venerable sir, do not slander me! If we are speaking of "true cause," there is not a single word to say about it.' Having said this, he clicked his teeth and added, 'Just now I spoke carelessly without reason.' A neighboring old master heard all this and commented, 'A fine pot of soup -- ruined by two mouse droppings.'" The Master's comment: "Whose pot is without a dropping or two?"
E2: Five newcomers arrived. The Master said, "At the very summit of Dongting, there is no path for travelers. Without ladder or ferry, speak quickly!" A monk said, "We have come specially to pay respects to the Master." the Master answered, "A boat stopped in still water -- you boast of your navigation for nothing." The monk had no reply. The Master said, "Come over to this side." All the monks crossed over together. The Master said, "When the general at the front is not bold, the whole army suffers for it. Go to the monks' hall."

=== Mingjue Cong ===
E1: A monk asked, "The Diamond Sutra speaks of five eyes. What is the fleshly eye?" the Master replied, "Through the window, one cannot see outside." "What is the heavenly eye?" "Not the slightest obstruction -- everywhere it fills its sphere." "What is the wisdom eye?" "It cuts off the root of birth and death." "What is the dharma eye?" "It sees through the liver and gall of buddhas and patriarchs." "What is the buddha eye?" "It serves as the torch of wisdom for the four modes of birth." The monk stood there thinking. The Master said, "Blind!" Then he addressed the assembly: "Plum blossoms breaking through snow wear a smiling face; the returning spring stirs their competing fragrance. The dark mystery withdraws its traces even as its first signs show; it leaks out from before the age of the Primordial Sound. If you can grasp this, you will trust that before the world was divided, buddha-nature was already present -- luminous since the farthest antiquity, pure through every kalpa. Among sages it gains nothing; among ordinary beings it loses nothing."
E2: Mingjue Cong raised the following story: Tang Emperor Zhuangzong said to Master Xinghua, "In the Central Plains I obtained a single treasure, but no one can appraise its value." Xinghua said, "Let me see Your Majesty's treasure." The Emperor took his imperial cap in both hands and placed it on his knee. Xinghua said, "A treasure belonging to the sovereign -- who would dare put a price on it?" Mingjue Cong commented: "Zhuangzong was an adept sovereign; Xinghua was a clear-eyed patriarch. The way he appraised the price -- such style echoes through a thousand ages. Yet viewed with the true eye, this exchange can scrape the cataracts from a blind person's vision and serve as a mirror for buddhas and patriarchs." He then gave a shout and descended from the seat.

=== Minnuo ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the master said: "I have one sentence I wish to share with all of you. If anyone can discern it, I will permit them the title of Chan champion." After a long silence he said: "A mute dreams of his own dear father." He descended.
E2: The master raised the case: Chan Master Daolin went to Qinwang Mountain. Seeing a tall pine with branches curling like a canopy, he settled in its crown, earning the name "Bird's Nest." One day, Prefect Bai Juyi entered the mountain to pay respects and said: "Master, your dwelling place is extremely dangerous!" Bird's Nest said: "Your Honor's situation is far more dangerous." Bai said: "I command the rivers and mountains of this region -- what danger is there for me?" Bird's Nest said: "Day and night, the firewood of karma blazes and the consciousness-mind never stops -- is that not dangerous?" Bai then asked: "What is the great meaning of the Buddha-dharma?" Bird's Nest said: "Commit no evil; practice all good." Bai said: "Even a three-year-old child can say that." Bird's Nest said: "A three-year-old child can say it, but an eighty-year-old man cannot practice it." Bai bowed and withdrew. The master commented: "These two old fellows, one questioning, one answering, one seizing, one releasing -- call it Chan, call it Buddha-dharma, call it the upward path or the downward path, call it bodhi or nirvana, call it the Patriarch's very nostrils -- it is exactly like leaving Zhengzhou through the Cao Gate. This old monk today has none of such entanglements. Vice Commissioner Luan also does not come here to bandy words. Shortly, when the meal is set out in the hall, everyone may chew coarsely or swallow finely, bite sideways or gulp down whole. How does this differ from the ancients? A frozen brick strikes frozen ice; inflamed eyes meet a firebrand."

=== Minshu ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall and said: "The one who kills without blinking becomes a buddha on the spot. Consider the butcher Guange, who each day slaughtered a thousand pigs and a thousand sheep. One day he went to the assembly on Vulture Peak, threw down his butcher's knife, and said: 'I am one among the thousand buddhas.' The World-Honored One said: 'Just so. Just so.' Everyone! This is the model for becoming a buddha in former ages. Then consider Lord Guan, who in the midst of a million troops moved as though entering an uninhabited land, taking the heads of great generals as easily as reaching into a bag. One day in the Yuquan Temple he raised his mighty blade and said: 'I am one of the dharma protectors.' The ancient master said: 'Indeed! Indeed!' Is this not the great hero who becomes a buddha on the spot, who kills without blinking? Therefore it is said: the sword that kills and the sword that gives life -- these are the ancient standard and the essential pivot of the present. If you understand through words: to protect life, you must kill. If you do not understand through words: kill everything, and only then can you dwell in peace."
E2: The Master raised this case: "Emperor Wu of Liang met Bodhidharma and asked: 'What is the highest meaning of the sacred truth?' Bodhidharma said: 'Vast emptiness, nothing sacred.' The Emperor asked: 'Who is this facing me?' Bodhidharma said: 'Don't know.' The Emperor did not connect." The Master said: "Emperor Wu, though he had an eye in his crown, did not notice the jaw protruding behind the head. Bodhidharma, though his words carried an echo, was unaware that the sentences concealed a blade. Inevitably a gap was left between them -- but what can you do when Emperor Wu missed the point right before his eyes? From this old monk's true-eye perspective: the empire can be shared equally, rank and salary can be declined, bare blades can be walked upon -- but the Middle Way cannot be attained. Why? If you are not someone who plays in the tidal bore, how can you grasp the meaning within the waves?" He gave a shout and descended.

=== Mixingren ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall and raised this case: "A general returned from battle. The emperor consoled him at a banquet and said: 'When you were wielding your sword on the battlefield, did you happen to meet any old acquaintances in the ranks?' The general said: 'At that very moment, your servant could not even see himself -- how could he see any acquaintance?'" The Master said: "Students of the Way today must fight through at least one such round themselves."
E2: The Master ascended the hall. He held up the whisk and called to the assembly: "Do you understand?" No one spoke. The Master threw down the whisk and descended. The next day he ascended the hall again: "Yesterday I held up the whisk and said 'Do you understand?' -- I had already laid it all out plainly. Seeing you still didn't get it, today I have no choice but to pour a second ladle of foul water. A sharp fellow, hearing this, would grab hold of it and go -- but even that would already be too slow. You come up when you hear the drum, you go down following the crowd. What are you doubting? Is it that the wind blows and the trees move, the flowers bloom and the birds sing? Is it that empty space has no boundary, heaven and earth have an end? If you doubt such things, then truly: the world has no problems -- ordinary people trouble themselves. If you have no doubt, then when hungry eat, when tired sleep -- what else is there? Still, as the saying goes: a person without far-reaching concerns will surely have worries close at hand. Go investigate."

=== Miyin ===
E1: The master cited an old case: Master He'an once called to the novice Yangshan: "Bring me the bed." Yangshan brought it. He'an said: "Put it back where it was." Then he asked: "What is on the other side of the bed?" Yangshan said: "The pillow." He'an said: "And on this side?" Yangshan said: "Nothing." He'an called again: "Yangshan!" Yangshan answered. He'an said: "Go." The master commented: "The physician at Spirit Mountain could not have done better -- yet even with a thousand remedies, how could any match that single word 'Go'? If you want to settle the matter, you must rob the nest while the bird is home -- one call brings the head up, and you advance with blade drawn. Tell me, where is the crux? If you can discern it, the great Yangshan's life is in your hands. Otherwise, hear this verse: If people could understand this encounter, they would see that through countless kalpas they have been sunk right here. Look closely -- where does the madman run? He loses his horse at the gate and boards another boat."
E2: A monk asked: "All Buddhas appeared in the world for the sake of the one great matter. The Patriarch came from the West to settle the matter before our eyes. When it is settled, what is it like?" The master said: "Sun and moon have but one face; mountains and rivers share the same spring." The monk pressed: "Having understood this, is one yet through?" The master said: "Still on the road."

=== Miyun Yuanwu ===
E1: A monk asked, "When the paulownia leaf falls, it carries autumn's message. When adepts meet, what is the real intention?" The master gave a shout. "After the shout, then what?" The master struck him. "Why not just say 'Look!'?" The master said, "I thought you were an adept. Turns out you are not." Then the master addressed the assembly: "To raise one thing is not to raise a second. Let one move pass and you fall to the second level. As for today, the first of the seventh month -- how do you raise it? If you can raise it -- south to Tiantai, north to Wutai. If you cannot --" He gave a shout. "Withdraw! Withdraw!" And he stepped down from his seat.
E2: The master raised the old case: "Deshan, carrying his commentaries, went south to refute the southern school. On the way, he stopped at a roadside stall where an old woman sold rice cakes. Deshan asked for some refreshment. The old woman said, 'What are you carrying in that bundle?' Deshan said, 'My commentaries on the Diamond Sutra.' The old woman said, 'The Diamond Sutra says: past mind cannot be grasped, present mind cannot be grasped, future mind cannot be grasped. Which mind does Your Reverence wish to refresh?' Deshan was speechless." The master commented: "If I had been Deshan, I would simply have said, 'This monk is hungry. Pick the biggest ones and bring them quick!' That old woman would have been so flustered, tripping over herself to serve them up. When the food arrived, I'd eat my fill and head on my way."

=== MU'AN WENKANG ===
E1: Mu'an ascended the hall at Jinshan and raised an old case: Commissioner Wang once visited Linji. Linji took the Commissioner on a stroll through the monks' hall. The Commissioner asked, "Do the monks in this hall read sutras?" Linji said, "They don't read sutras." The Commissioner asked, "Do they practice sitting dhyana?" Linji said, "They don't practice sitting dhyana." The Commissioner said, "If they neither read sutras nor practice sitting dhyana, what on earth are they doing?" Linji said, "I'm teaching every one of them to become buddhas and patriarchs." The Commissioner had a great awakening and said, "Gold dust, though precious, falls into the eye and becomes a disease." Mu'an commented: "Old Linji held up the true seal on high. Commissioner Wang received it directly, face to face. Effortlessly, the light of the patriarchal way shone forth, and the royal web was revealed in full clarity. Great assembly, do you see it yet? Fling open the golden palace lock, and strike the jade tower bell." He descended from the seat.
E2: That evening at the informal talk, Mu'an said: "The ancients called the evening talk 'household instruction.' What are the households? The household of worldly convention, the household of the five aggregates, the household of the three realms. Being able to leave without entering -- that is what 'household instruction' means. Our kind has abandoned father and mother, put on patched robes, does not get involved in worldly entanglements, and dwells at ease in forests and wilds -- this is called leaving the household of worldly convention. Awakening to the dharma of purity and defilement, not getting stuck in the dust of afflictions, not clinging to delusive attachments -- this is called leaving the household of the five aggregates. Riding upon sound and straddling form, transcending both the sacred and the common, smashing open empty space and attaining great freedom -- this is called leaving the household of the three realms. If you can truly accomplish this, your rewards in fields, dwellings, robes, and all manner of precious things -- I will not be stingy with any of it. Even the bright pearl in the topknot I will place in your two hands. Great assembly, will you accept this? The sea god knows the value but not the price -- he leaves it for the human world to illuminate the night."

=== Muchen Daomin ===
E1: The Kangxi Emperor brought his scholars to the master's quarters. He ordered the scholar Wang Xi to ask: "What is the orthodox dharma eye?" The master raised his fist and said: "It juts right out, yet is hard to discern." Another scholar asked: "What is Guanyin (Avalokiteshvara, 'perceiver of self-nature')?" The master clapped his hands and said: "Did you hear that?" The scholar then asked: "In the Great Learning it says 'illumine bright virtue.' Zhu Xi says: 'Illumine means to make bright.' What is the principle of this 'making bright'?" The master said: "Go ask Master Zhu Xi yourself." All the scholars were speechless. The Emperor burst out laughing.
E2: The master said to the Emperor: "I am always making a fool of myself before Your Majesty. Today I shall raise a koan and request Your Majesty to say a turning word." He then told the story of the old woman who burned down the hermit's hut: "Suppose a beautiful woman embraced Your Majesty and said 'Right now, in this very moment' -- how would you respond, so the old woman would not drive you out and burn your hut?" The Emperor said: "I have never given this any thought. How would I dare point east and say west before you?" The master said: "I beg Your Majesty to say just one word." The Emperor declined again. The master said: "Since Your Majesty cannot say it, you must rouse fierce determination and investigate. Investigate until there is nothing left to investigate, and suddenly -- CRACK! -- you will be free in all directions and attain great liberation."

=== Muyun ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the dharma, both worldly and beyond the world?" said the Master: "Hares and horses have horns; cattle and sheep do not." The monk pressed: "But they do have horns!" The Master said: "That is beyond your realm of experience."
E2: A monk asked: "Master, your birthday this year, last year's birthday, next year's birthday -- which birthday is the real one?" The Master said: "When you have finished counting them all, I will tell you."

=== Muzhou Daoming ===
E1: In his usual way Muzhou demanded that visitors identify themselves when they knocked. One time, as soon as Yunmen knocked, Muzhou said, "Who is it?" Yunmen said, "Wenyan." The moment the door opened, Yunmen leapt inside. Muzhou grabbed him and said, "Speak, speak!" Yunmen hesitated and was immediately shoved out -- one foot still inside the threshold. Muzhou slammed the door shut, crushing Yunmen's foot. Yunmen endured the pain and cried out -- suddenly he had a great awakening.
E2: Muzhou asked a monk, "Where have you just come from?" The monk gave a shout. Muzhou said, "This old monk has been shouted at by you once." The monk shouted again. Muzhou said, "After three shouts, four shouts -- how will it be?" The monk had no words. Muzhou then struck him, saying, "You empty-headed fellow!"

=== Nanming Guang ===
E1: It was snowing. A monk pushed open the window and said: "The whole mountain is covered with snow." The Master said: "You're chasing after sound and form." The monk said: "Please, Master, say a phrase apart from sound and form." said the Master: "The whole mountain is covered with snow."
E2: When the Master was in seclusion at Gaoting, a monk said: "Master, now that you have entered seclusion, surely you will not come out until you have attained complete awakening." the Master answered: "If that's the case, I will never be able to leave this gate, even to the end of all future ages." The monk had no reply. The Master shut the door.

=== Nanquan Puyuan ===
E1: The monks of the east and west halls were fighting over a cat. Nanquan lifted it up and said: "If you can speak, you save it; if you cannot speak, I will cut it." The assembly had no reply. Nanquan then cut it. In the evening Zhaozhou returned from outside. Nanquan told him what happened. Zhaozhou took off his sandals, placed them on his head, and walked out. Nanquan said: "If you had been here, you would have saved the cat."
E2: Minister Lu Gen was conversing with Nanquan and quoted Sengzhao: "Heaven and earth and I share the same root; the ten thousand things and I are one body. That is quite strange." Nanquan pointed to the flower in front of the courtyard and called the minister, saying: "People of today see this one flower as if in a dream."

=== NANSHI WENXIU ===
E1: End of the summer retreat, evening talk. The Master said: "The message of the Patriarch's coming from the West is revealed at every turn, manifest in every place. A thousand suns shining together cannot match its brightness. The five great mountains in their majesty cannot match its vastness. Empty space cannot contain it. The great earth cannot support it. If you can grasp it directly, it's already a case of 'marking the boat to find the sword.' If you still stand there deliberating, you're already ten thousand miles of white cloud away. If you then want to discuss Linji's three mysteries and three essentials, Dongshan's five ranks of lord and vassal, Yunmen's sesame flatbread, Zhaozhou's tea-drinking -- all of that is just madly running around outside. You must trust that within this, there are no such matters. Speaking of the wonderful, speaking of the profound -- it cannot be gotten. Discussing the real, discussing the expedient -- it cannot be gotten. Wielding the stick, wielding the shout -- it cannot be gotten. Raising old cases, raising present cases -- it cannot be gotten. And even this 'cannot be gotten' also cannot be gotten. Even so, 'thus' is also up to me, 'not thus' is also up to me. I am the dharma king, sovereign over the dharma. In that case, speaking of the wonderful also works, discussing the real also works, wielding the stick also works, raising old cases also works. All day long speaking, yet nothing is spoken. All day long moving, yet nothing is moved. All day long wearing clothes, yet never hanging a single thread. All day long eating rice, yet never biting a single grain."
E2: The Master ascended the hall: "The dharma body is without form, yet it takes shape in response to things. Prajna is without knowledge, yet it illumines in response to conditions." He suddenly picked up his staff: "This is the staff. Which one is the dharma body?" He pointed the staff at the incense stand: "This is the incense stand. Which one is prajna? If you can see this clearly, every place returns to the source and every step fits the track. If not, the Lingyan staff is not yet ready to be handed to you."

=== Nanyang Huizhong ===
E1: A monk asked National Teacher Zhong, "What is the original-body Vairocana?" The National Teacher said, "Bring me the pure vase." The monk brought it. The National Teacher said, "Put it back in its old place." The monk asked again, "What is the original-body Vairocana?" The National Teacher said, "The ancient Buddha passed away long ago."
E2: The emperor asked the National Teacher for the stupa pattern. The National Teacher was silent a long while, then said, "Do you understand?" The emperor said, "I do not understand." The National Teacher said, "I have a Dharma-heir disciple, Danyuan, who does understand this matter." After the National Teacher passed away, the emperor summoned Danyuan, who recited: "South of Xiang, north of Tan -- in the middle, gold fills a whole country. Beneath the shadowless tree, a shared boat. Atop the lapis hall, no knowing."

=== Nanyuan Huiyong ===
E1: Nanyuan addresses the assembly: "The various quarters only have the eye of chirping and pecking at the same time, but do not have the function of chirping and pecking at the same time." A monk asks, "What is the function of chirping and pecking at the same time?" Nanyuan says, "A true adept does not chirp or peck; chirping and pecking at the same time is missed." The monk says, "This is still where the student doubts." Nanyuan says, "What is it that you doubt?" The monk says, "Missed." Nanyuan strikes him. The monk refuses to accept it, so Nanyuan drives him out. Later the monk went to Yunmen's assembly and brought up the earlier exchange. Another monk said: "Nanyuan's staff broke there." That monk suddenly had an awakening.
E2: Nanyuan addressed the assembly: "The various quarters only have the eye of chirping and pecking at the same time, but do not have the function of chirping and pecking at the same time." A monk came forward and asked, "What is the function of chirping and pecking at the same time?" Nanyuan said, "A true adept does not chirp or peck; chirping and pecking at the same time is missed." The monk said, "This is still where the student doubts." Nanyuan said, "What is it that you doubt?" The monk said, "Missed." Nanyuan then struck him. The monk would not accept it, so Nanyuan drove him out. Later the monk went to Yunmen's assembly and brought up the earlier exchange. Another monk said, "Nanyuan's staff broke there." That monk suddenly had an awakening. He went back to see Nanyuan, but Nanyuan had already passed away. He then went to see Fengxue. As soon as he bowed, Fengxue said, "Are you not the monk who at that time asked the former master about chirping and pecking at the same time?" The monk said, "Yes." Fengxue said, "How did you understand it at the time?" The monk said, "At first it was like walking within lamplight and shadows." Fengxue said, "You understood it."

=== Nanyue Huairang ===
E1: The Book of Serenity records: "The Sixth Patriarch told Master Rang: The prophecy of the twenty-seven patriarchs of India says that beneath your feet a colt will appear and trample everyone under heaven to death. The illness is in your mind; you need not speak too soon." Then: "Later, after polishing tile and beating the ox, the divine colt entered the stable and came to be called Mazu." This refers to the famous story where Huairang polished a tile next to Mazu who was meditating, and when asked why, said, "I'm polishing it to make a mirror" -- to show Mazu that sitting dhyana alone would not make him a Buddha, just as polishing a tile would not make a mirror.
E2: In the Kaiyuan era, the monk Daoyi (later known as Mazu) was at Hengshan constantly practicing seated dhyana. Huairang knew he was a vessel of the Dharma and went to ask him, "Great worthy, what do you aim at by sitting in dhyana?" Daoyi said, "I aim to become a Buddha." Huairang then took a tile and began grinding it on the stone in front of the hermitage. Daoyi said, "What are you grinding it for?" Huairang said, "I am grinding it to make a mirror." Daoyi said, "How can you make a mirror by grinding a tile?" Huairang said, "If grinding a tile cannot make a mirror, how can sitting in dhyana make you a Buddha?" Daoyi said, "Then what is right?" Huairang said, "It is like an ox pulling a cart. If the cart does not move, is it right to hit the cart, or to hit the ox?" Daoyi had no reply. Huairang continued, "Are you learning sitting dhyana, or learning sitting Buddha? If you are learning sitting dhyana, dhyana is not sitting or lying down. If you are learning sitting Buddha, Buddha is not a fixed form. In the dharma of non-abiding, one should neither grasp nor reject. If you sit as Buddha, you are killing Buddha. If you cling to the sitting form, you have not reached its principle." Daoyi, hearing this instruction, felt as if drinking ghee. He bowed and asked, "How should one apply the mind to accord with formless samadhi?" Huairang said, "Your study of the mind-ground dharma is like planting seeds. My teaching of the essential dharma is like the rain from heaven. When your conditions meet, you will see the Way."

=== Xiu of Dajue ===
E1: A monk asked, "In the Fifth Patriarch's assembly, there was a great master named Shenxiu. Why didn't he receive the robe and bowl?" The master said, "Because he was covered from head to toe in Buddha-dharma." "Then why did the illiterate laborer Huineng receive it?" The master said, "Because he didn't understand Zen at all." The monk said, "So it seems -- cleverness always has stupidity close by; true rarity in this world is genuine simplicity." The master struck him.
E2: Before the emperor's court, the master was asked about the four positions of host and guest: "What is guest within guest?" The master said, "One bowl, a thousand households' rice." "What is host within guest?" "Those with clear eyes who see others truly are few." "What is guest within host?" "The ancient cypress before the hall shades all of heaven and humanity." "What is host within host?" The master said, "Sitting in the hall, not sitting properly." "Host and guest are now clearly shown -- but the phrase at the very summit: what is that?" The master struck him and said, "Those with merit shall be rewarded."

=== Neishaozhong ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master said: "Spiritual light is never obscured; for ten thousand ages its excellent influence endures. Enter this gate -- do not hold on to understanding." He gave a shout and continued: "Have you entered yet? If not, you must find a way in. Once you are in, you must still find a way out. The Buddhas of three times entered and refused to come out -- they go about forever bare-chested and barefoot. The ancestral teachers came out and refused to go back in -- everywhere they go, they work bare-handed. Here at Moon-Palm, the temple gate and Buddha hall stand wide open year-round with not a thread of obstruction. Enter as you please, exit as you please -- only do not kick the doorsill." He shouted and said: "What limit is there?"
E2: When the old master sent the Dharma-robe to him, the Master ascended the hall and said: "Between the Pagoda of Many Children and the Hall of Bao'en, branch follows branch, flame continues flame." A monk asked: "What is the meaning of Bodhidharma's coming from the West?" The Master said: "Where are you directing this question?" The monk hesitated, and the Master shouted him away.

=== Niutou Farong ===
E1: "Before Niutou met the Fourth Patriarch, how was it?" -- "A roadside shrine -- everyone who sees it raises clasped hands." "After he met him, how was it?" -- "Inside the room there is no spirit-bed; the whole household wears no mourning." The tradition holds that before meeting Daoxin, birds would bring flowers to Farong; after meeting him, even the birds stopped coming -- he had become too ordinary for supernatural display.
E2: The Prince of Boling asked Farong, "When conditions and colors first arise, one does not speak of conditions giving rise to colors. How does one come to know conditions, in order to put a stop to their arising?" Farong replied in verse: "When conditions and colors first arise, the two natures of color and conditions are empty. Originally there is no knower of conditions; mind-measure and knowing are the same. Illumination at the source -- arising is not arising; at that moment, arising ceases of itself. Embracing darkness gives rise to an awareness-condition; when the mind is at that moment, conditions do not pursue. As for before birth, color and mind are not nurtured. From emptiness originally there is no thought; perception and reception speak of thought arising. Arising and stirring have never arisen -- why then need the Buddha's command?" The Prince further asked, "When one closes one's eyes and does not see color, cogitation and reflection increase all the more. Since color is not related to mind, where do conditions arise from?" Farong replied in verse: "Closing the eyes, not seeing color, within the mind cogitation stirs abundantly. Illusory consciousness provisionally makes use -- arising names ultimately do not transgress. Know that color is not related to mind; mind also is not related to a person. Following activity there is form that turns; the bird departs, the sky is true."

=== Nouyunshi of Caotang ===
E1: One evening the Master was strolling idly by the river when he came upon two monks. He asked, "What are you doing here?" They said, "Admiring the water." The Master said, "How deep is the water?" The monks had no reply. The Master said, "Drown."
E2: While drinking tea with a government official, the official said, "What I love best is Chan." said the Master, "I have not the slightest fondness for Chan." The official asked, "Then what is your occupation?" The Master held up his fist and said, "All I have is precisely this." The official was at a loss.

=== Pang Yun ===
E1: Layman Pang takes leave of Yaoshan. Yaoshan orders ten Zen monks to see him off to the gate. Pang points at the snow in the air and says: "Fine snow, flake after flake, does not fall anywhere else." Zen guest Quan asks: "Where does it fall?" Pang slaps him once. Quan says: "Layman, you too must not be careless." Pang says: "You call yourself a Zen guest like this? King Yama has not yet let you off." Quan: "Layman, how is that so?" Pang slaps him again and says: "Eyes seeing like the blind; mouth speaking like the mute."
E2: When Pang first met Shitou, he asked: "Who is the one not companion to the ten thousand dharmas?" Shitou covered his mouth with his hand. Later Pang went to Mazu and asked the same question. Mazu said: "Wait until you swallow the waters of the West River in one gulp, then I will tell you." Pang suddenly had great awakening.

=== Panshan Baoji ===
E1: Panshan offered a phrase: "In the three realms there is no dharma -- where can one seek the mind?" Xuedou versified: "In the three realms there is no dharma -- where can one seek the mind? White clouds as a canopy, running springs as a zither. One tune, two tunes -- no one understands; after the rain, in the night pond, autumn waters are deep."
E2: As Panshan was nearing death, he said to the assembly, "Is there anyone who can depict my true likeness?" The assembly all drew portraits and presented them; Panshan scolded them all. Puhua came forward and said, "I can depict it." Panshan said, "Why not present it to this old monk?" Puhua immediately did a somersault and left. Panshan said, "From now on, this fellow will greet people like a mad wind."

=== Pingshi Rudi ===
E1: Winter solstice evening talk: "Within the monk's domain there is a field without yin or yang. Level and true, stark and solitary -- close as the space within your heart, remote as the far side of the great thousand worlds. Battered by wind, scorched by sun through many years, overgrown with weeds and moss. You have never once turned your eyes to look at it. If you see it: the myriad phenomena, forests and towers, blaze with light. If you fail to see it: the myriad phenomena, forests and towers, blaze with light. And when you abandon both seeing and not-seeing, what then? A scorched brick strikes the frozen ground, and a single red flame leaps from the ice river."
E2: A monk asked: "The World-Honored One held up a flower; Kashyapa smiled. What is the meaning of this?" The master said: "Do not mistake the crane's cry for the oriole's song." The monk pressed: "The World-Honored One said: 'I possess the treasury of the true Dharma eye and entrust it to Mahakashyapa.' How about that?" The master said: "One dog barks at nothing, and a thousand mastiffs snap at what is real."

=== Pinjixiang ===
E1: A monk asked: "Originally pure by nature -- how did mountains, rivers, and the great earth suddenly arise?" The Master said: "How could there be such a thing?" The monk said: "The scriptures clearly state it." The Master said: "Don't believe it. Don't believe it." The monk said: "I have doubts -- please instruct me." The Master said: "Wait until your doubt shatters, then we will examine things." The monk bowed. After a long silence the Master said: "Originally pure by nature --" and took up his staff: "Mountains, rivers, and the great earth have already arisen! Those who understand know the scriptures speak truly. Those who don't --" He threw down his staff: "We'll examine it again shortly." And descended.
E2: On his birthday, the Master gestured in a circle and said: "In a jia-ji year, bing heads the cycle." Then he called out loudly: "Is there anyone born in the Year of the Ox who wants their fortune told?" A monk came forward, bowed, and the Master struck him. The monk shouted. The Master said: "This mountain monk is thirty-six years old, my fate is passing through the Kan trigram, with Five Ghosts pressing my body." The monk asked whether the teaching was about the Patriarch's meaning from the West or a birthday celebration. The Master said: "A father without a son is not truly alone; a son with a father yet returns to solitude." The monk shouted again. The Master struck and said: "Do not damage the spirit in its function -- the lord of the chart must be kept robust." The monk bowed, and the Master descended.

=== Po'an Zuxian ===
E1: Po'an raised the case: "Master Zihu, in the middle of the night, stood before the monks' hall shouting: 'Catch the thief! Catch the thief!' Everyone was startled awake. Zihu seized one monk and said: 'Caught him! Caught him!' The monk protested: 'It is not me.' Zihu replied: 'It is you, it is -- you just refuse to acknowledge it.'" Po'an commented: "Zihu only knew how to startle the crowd and show off his cleverness, heedless of the onlookers, bringing blame upon himself. Why? To slander someone with a crime is to bring that crime upon yourself."
E2: Po'an raised the case: "Yaoshan had not ascended the hall for a long time. The head monk said: 'The assembly has long yearned for the Dharma.' Yaoshan said: 'Ring the bell.' When the monks gathered, Yaoshan returned directly to his quarters. The head monk followed and said: 'You agreed to speak for the assembly -- why did you not utter a single word?' Yaoshan replied: 'Sutras have sutra masters, treatises have treatise masters. How can you blame this old monk?'" Po'an commented: "Yaoshan going straight back to his quarters seemed like a fine fellow, but when the head monk gave him a gentle squeeze from behind, he lost his bearings entirely."

=== Pofeng Chong of Dongshan ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall. "The Patriarch's mind-seal is like the mechanism of an iron bull -- when it goes, it seals and holds; when it stays, it seals and breaks. But what about neither going nor staying -- should it stamp or not?" After a long silence he said: "This seal without pattern or inscription -- whether you are heavenly or human, ordinary or sagely, it has never shifted by a single hair's breadth. Why then do none of you understand? Only because it is so utterly clear that realization comes late."
E2: The Master ascended the hall and raised this: "An old woman once provided for Zhaozhou and asked him to turn the canon. Zhaozhou descended from his seat, walked around it once, and said: 'The canon has been turned.' The old woman said: 'I asked you to turn the complete canon. Why have you only turned half?' Tell me -- what is the complete canon? In honest truth, even if all three-world Buddhas and all patriarchs walked around it billions of times, from the old woman's standpoint they would still have turned only half. Why? Look at this old woman -- her inner chamber was perfectly secure, her ability to end hostilities was superb. Zhaozhou's turning was incomplete, and the old woman saw through it. But tell me: is there anyone who can turn the complete canon?" He said: "When you are tired, bend your arm for a pillow and sleep. Do not fear that someone will steal your pillow." He gave a shout and descended the seat.

=== Poshan ===
E1: A monk asked: "Before you were born, Master, how was it?" The Master said: "Rock sugar comes from Fujian." The monk pressed: "And after you were born?" The Master said: "You cannot even recognize the local goods."
E2: A layman named Wan (meaning "ten thousand") asked: "My surname is Wan. Before my parents gave birth to me, what was my surname?" said the Master: "Here, I can't say it." The layman bowed. The Master said: "Tell me -- have I answered you or not?" The layman said: "I don't understand." The Master said: "If you do not understand, is your surname still Wan?"

=== Poshan Haiming ===
E1: An elder called Bihai from Fengling asked: "Every Buddha appears in the world for one great matter. What is my great matter?" The master said: "Please sit down." Bihai just stood there and would not sit. The master said: "You cannot even manage a small matter like sitting -- what great matter are you talking about?" Bihai was flustered. The master said: "You deserve thirty blows." Bihai bowed. The master said: "Is that a bow of understanding, or a bow of not understanding?" Bihai bowed again and said: "Thank you for your confirmation." The master laughed and said: "Confirming what?" Bihai was about to open his mouth when the master said: "You don't understand my meaning. If you want to pluck leaves and search branches, I cannot help you. Just go and investigate: 'Only a Buddha together with a Buddha can fathom this' -- what is it that they fathom?"
E2: The practitioner Wulou returned for a second visit and presented a verse: "Once at Yue I was kicked full in the body; for years I endured the pain, mouth unable to open. Now I pay three bows face to face, and laugh at how full of grief I was back then." The master just silently regarded him. Wulou bowed and said: "Since leaving you, I have not been idle in this fundamental matter. Studying the koan of Baizhang's nose-twist, I had some insight." The master probed: "Did you understand from the nose-twist? Or from the wild duck flying away?" Wulou immediately made a duck quacking sound, then a cry of pain. The master approved, and composed a verse: "Cold eyes at Wanfeng pierce the subtle and minute; who can sort out black from white and return? Cherish the duck as it flies past -- the cry of pain still falls on the arrow's point."

=== PU'AN YINSU ===
E1: Pu'an wore a paper quilt and cloth robes, eating only morning gruel and evening rice. Beyond dhyana, he only read the Huayan Treatise. One day, reaching the passage "When you reach the root, feelings are forgotten; know that mind and substance merge," he suddenly had a great awakening. Sweat poured from his entire body. He exclaimed joyfully: "Today I have personally entered the Huayan dharma-realm!" Then he proclaimed: "The Elder Li struck a single blow at the very head of the great Huayan scripture, shattering the three-thousand great-thousand worlds like hot water melting snow, not leaving a single hair to obstruct later students. This old man Pu'an, upon seeing it, inadvertently swallowed all five thousand forty-eight fascicles, transforming them into a single energy filling empty space." Then he spoke a verse: "It cannot be pinched into a ball, cannot be pulled apart -- why bother with Nanyue or Tiantai? At the gates of the six senses, no one is using them -- which is precisely what drew the barbarian monk from so far away."
E2: Suddenly a monk named Daocun arrived, trudging through the snow. Upon seeing him, Pu'an said, "This is my uninvited friend." They sat together in silence, then engaged in mutual questioning, sometimes laughing, sometimes shouting. The monk said, "Master, you are a person who has returned. Before long you will greatly revive our teaching." Then he wrote a verse in the snow and departed.

=== PUFUZHUO OF MUKETING ===
E1: On the Lantern Festival, at the evening talk, the Master said: "The new year is half gone before you notice. At Yongzhen, our first winter -- no rice, no firewood. The whole monastery sits in silent rage, lips sealed tight around their teapots. I can do nothing but look up at the sky and hum a tune -- it is what they call making music under the bitter-bark tree. But I once learned an iron flute melody called 'Celebrating the Lantern Festival' from the immortal Lu Dongbin at Yellow Crane Tower." He held his staff crosswise as if playing a flute and sang aloud: "Five-six-five, ruler-servant-benevolence, five-six-work, six-five-five-five!" Then he said: "That is all one should play. Staff! Tonight is the Lantern Festival. We have no firewood and no rice. The entire monastery glares. And yet you drum up such merriment? Truly, this is playing the lute under the bitter-bark tree -- making joy in the midst of suffering." He struck his staff repeatedly and said: "When the spirit is high, add more spirit! When the occasion calls for style, be stylish!" He clapped his hands, roared with laughter, and descended from the seat.
E2: On the anniversary of the Buddha's enlightenment, the Master said: "Ha! What am I laughing at? I laugh at Shakyamuni on the mountain before Correct Awakening -- sleeping on a rope bed, eating hemp and wheat, starved until his bones jutted out like crags and his eyes swam with sparks. You call that 'seeing the morning star and greatly awakening'? That is just seeing ghosts at midnight! And then he says: 'How marvelous! How strange! All living beings possess the wisdom and virtue of the Tathagata, but because of deluded thinking and attachment they cannot realize it.' More drool from the fox's mouth -- he deserves twenty blows of the staff. No wonder Master Yunmen wanted to beat him dead with one stroke and feed him to the dogs, for the sake of peace in the world. Yunmen also deserves twenty blows, to stop future generations from passing along the rumor, person to person, ten to a hundred, a hundred to a fiction, misleading good men and women." He paused: "Yongzhen, judging it all this way, also deserves twenty blows. Why? 'See a marvel and don't marvel -- the marvel destroys itself.' But I still have to ask you: What is Shakyamuni, after all?" He paused again: "Even cats and dogs don't recognize him."

=== Puji Yulin ===
E1: Emperor Shizu (the Shunzhi Emperor) saw a short ordination-candidate and pointed at him, asking the Master about it. Yulin said: "The tall one has a tall dharma-body; the short one has a short dharma-body." The Emperor was delighted and thanked him.
E2: During a small-assembly talk, Yulin recounts visiting his teacher Qingshan for a final meeting. He burst in, hands on hips, and announced: "The wild son was banished from the realm -- is this peak still the old man's dwelling?" His teacher said: "Stand still and I'll explain." Yulin kicked over the incense table and stormed out. His teacher shouted: "Bring me my staff!" Yulin, hearing this from a distance, laughed and called back: "The sword left long ago!" On another day, the teacher ascended the hall. Before the ceremony-leader could strike the mallet, Yulin shouted: "Stop! Let me ask my question first!" He asked: "Huangbo once said there are no Zen masters in all of Great Tang. Are there any now in Great Ming?" His teacher raised his staff to strike. Yulin shouted. The teacher also shouted. Yulin shouted again, then sang out: "It is not that the wild son has too much swagger -- it is only because he once broke through the final barrier!" He left. His teacher shouted after him. Yulin shouted back. Hearing the ceremony mallet finally strike, he yelled from afar: "What a death-rattle! Who does Yangshan say can hear the tune?"

=== PUJUE ZONGGAO (Dahui) ===
E1: The monk Jue of Kaisheng monastery studied under Wuzu Fayan. One day in the interview room, Fayan asked: "Shakyamuni and Maitreya are still his servants -- tell me, who is he?" Jue answered, "Zhang number three of the barbarians, Li number four of the blacks." Fayan approved. But his senior monk Yuanwu said, "Good, but I fear it is not yet genuine. Don't let him off -- probe further." The next day, Fayan asked the same question. Jue said, "I already told you yesterday." Fayan said, "What did you say?" Jue repeated, "Zhang three, Li four." Fayan said, "No, no!" Jue said, "Yesterday you said yes, today you say no?" Fayan said, "Yesterday it was right; today it is wrong." At these words, Jue had a great awakening.
E2: The monk Hai-yin Xin, over eighty years old, had long been supplied by the Zhu household. One day Zhu asked, "After you die, could you be reborn in my family?" Xin laughed and agreed. He returned to the monastery, grew slightly ill, and died within days. On that very day, the Zhu family's daughter was born. When the monk Yuanzhao Ben came to visit and saw the infant -- just one month old -- she smiled the moment she saw him. Yuanzhao called out, "Hai-yin! You made a mistake!" The baby girl immediately cried and died on the spot.

=== PUMEN XIAN ===
E1: On the Buddha's birthday, at the opening of the Avatamsaka assembly, the Master raised an old case: "The king of Eastern India invited the twenty-seventh patriarch Prajnatara to a meal. After the meal, the king said: 'Venerable one, why do you not recite the sutras?' The patriarch replied: 'When I breathe out, I do not get entangled with external conditions. When I breathe in, I do not dwell in the realm of the aggregates. I am constantly turning just such a sutra -- hundreds of thousands of millions of volumes. Why speak of one or two?'" The Master commented: "The patriarch answered this way, but it was like a spirit-turtle dragging its tail -- sweeping away tracks only creates new marks. Since he spoke of breathing in and out, he had already fallen into the realm of the aggregates and become entangled with conditions. How could he ever be free of vines and weeds? If today someone asked me, 'Can you turn the sutras?' I would simply say: 'Morning gruel in one bowl, afternoon tea in one cup, stretch out both legs and lie down -- there is quite another kind of livelihood.' If they said, 'This old abbot speaks this way -- does he not contradict the meaning of the sutras?' I would say: 'True gold has its own true price -- one never mixes sand in when selling it to people.'"
E2: ---

=== Puzhao Yibian ===
E1: He first lived at Puzhao in Sizhou, later moved to Songshao. When Bian fell, he was captured and herded cattle in the north. After returning, an attendant read Dongshan's Record and said, "The ancients were truly extraordinary." Jue said, "After I transform, you may call me. If I can return, that is the power of the Way." Later he predicted his own death, gave away his belongings, and sat to pass away. The attendant called three times. Jue answered: "What is it?" The attendant asked, "Why, master, go off naked and barefoot?" Jue said: "What was there when I came?" The attendant tried to force clothes on him. Jue said: "Stop -- leave them for those who come after."
E2: At the very end, he wrote a gatha: "Seventy-three years were like a flash of lightning. At departure, for you I open a single line: The iron ox leaps across Silla, smashing empty space into seven or eight pieces." Then he majestically died.

=== Qianyan ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master pointed at the incense burner and said: "Great assembly! The incense burner has already finished preaching the Dharma to you all." He then descended from the seat.
E2: Citing Yunmen's saying about the fan leaping up to the thirty-third heaven and knocking the nose of the Lord of Heaven, the Master struck the platform with his fan and said: "The fan leaps down into the eighteen levels of hell and knocks the nose of King Yama. King Yama flies into a rage and says: 'You eat ready-made rice porridge, flap your two lips of skin day and night, recklessly discussing prajna -- you deserve my iron staff!' But at my single shout, the fan goes right back inside the fan. Can you all see it? If you see it, come take up the fan. If you cannot see it, on a blazing hot summer day, what will you use?"

=== Qiaosongyi of Gaofeng ===
E1: The Master visited Commissioner Cao. Over tea, Cao asked: "Are you a Zen teacher or a Daoist?" The Master said: "Neither." "Which school then?" The Master raised his cup: "Have some tea." Cao lowered his head. the Master replied: "Is it Daoist? Is it Zen?" After a long pause, Cao said: "I have been reading the scriptures and came across the udumbara flower that blooms once every three thousand years. I feel I have gained some entry, but it is hard to see." The Master said: "That flower only appears for a moment." Cao said: "Can one see it?" The Master made the gesture of picking up a flower. Cao said: "If both of us recognize it, then it is not the real thing." The Master said: "And how would you get it without recognizing it?" The next day Cao came to the hermitage. They talked at length. Cao joyfully bowed and said: "Now I know you are no ordinary teacher." The Master laughed heartily. Cao thanked him warmly and departed.
E2: The Master saw a snail on the window lattice that had shed its shell in an unusual way. He said to the assembly: "Even creatures can transform like this -- why cannot people?" A monk said: "There are times of transformation." The Master said: "Then you transform -- let me see." The monk said: "I am only a beginner in monastic life." The Master pulled off the monk's robe and cap. The monk was at a loss.

=== Qiaoyin Wuyi ===
E1: Qiaoyin raised the case: "A monk asked Xuefeng: 'What is the first phrase?' Xuefeng was silent for a long time. Later the monk brought this up to Changsheng, who said: 'That was the second phrase.' The monk asked: 'Then what is the first phrase?' Changsheng cried out: 'Heaven! Heaven!'" Qiaoyin commented: "Xuefeng stood on the high peak; Changsheng walked the deep ocean floor. Though both great masters responded thus, neither yet knew the first phrase. If someone asked me: 'What is the first phrase?' -- Clear weather: everyone out to haul timber."
E2: On the Buddha's birthday, Qiaoyin ascended the hall: "The Tushita palace, the den of ignorance -- kalpa after kalpa, head emerging, head submerging. Every year on this day, a basin of hot water. But in the end, you can wash the dust but never wash the bone. Bah! Buddha! Buddha!"

=== Qibaifu of Yuquan ===
E1: Ascending the hall: "Above high heaven, below thick earth, there is a single treasure. No one knows its price. All the Buddhas cannot let it go. The Patriarchs cannot pick it up. Without cause it has tumbled into the Jade Spring, and even eight-armed Nata recoils in fright." He made a gesture of holding something out: "This mountain monk offers it to you on an open tray. Everyone can use it without limit." He paused. "But speaking this way is only fit for worldly circulation. As for the supreme treasure -- let us take it up another time." A monk stepped forward and was about to open his mouth. The Master struck him: "Wherever there are words, there is no real meaning."
E2: Ascending the hall: "A small shop newly opened -- buying dear, selling cheap. Not trying to profit over cost, just wanting the buyer to be satisfied. Yangqi's chestnut-thorn cakes, Mingzhou's ragged cloth bags -- every one flung out in front of you, utterly transparent, nothing concealed. Does anyone care to look?" He struck his staff: "Profit or no profit, you must stay close to the market."

=== Qinguan Xingsi ===
E1: A monk asked Qingyuan, "What is the great meaning of the Buddha-Dharma?" Qingyuan said, "What is the price of rice in Luling?" The commentary explains: When Qingyuan first visited the Sixth Patriarch, he asked, "What should one practice to avoid falling into stages?" The Patriarch said, "What have you done before?" Qingyuan said, "I do not even engage in holy truths." The Patriarch said, "Into what stages could you fall?" Qingyuan said, "If I do not even engage in holy truths, what stages could there be?" The Patriarch esteemed him deeply.
E2: Qingyuan sent Shitou Xiqian to deliver a letter to Nanyue Huairang, saying, "When you have delivered the letter, come back quickly. I have a blunt axe for you to use in living on the mountain." Shitou went there, and before presenting the letter, he asked Huairang, "Not revering the sages, not valuing one's own spirit -- what then?" Huairang said, "Your question aims too high. Why not ask from below?" Shitou said, "I would rather sink in the depths forever than seek liberation from the sages." Huairang let him be. Xuansha later said, "Old Shitou, big and small, was knocked down by Nanyue and to this day has not been able to get up." Shitou returned. Qingyuan asked, "You came back so quickly. Was the letter delivered?" Shitou said, "The letter was not delivered and the message was not communicated. The day I left, you promised me a blunt axe. I now request it." Qingyuan hung down one foot. Shitou bowed.

=== Qinshan Wensui ===
E1: The Chan traveler Liang asks Qinshan, "When a single arrowhead smashes through the three barriers, how is it?" Qinshan says, "Release the master within the barriers and see." Liang says, "If so, then knowing one's faults one must correct them." Qinshan says, "What are you waiting for?" Liang says, "A fine arrow cannot be loosed at the right place," and starts to leave. Qinshan calls him back, grabs him: "One arrow breaking the three barriers, fine -- now try shooting an arrow at Qinshan." Liang hesitates. Qinshan strikes him seven blows, saying: "Let this fellow doubt for thirty years."
E2: One day Yantou, Xuefeng, and Qinshan were talking together. Xuefeng suddenly pointed to a bowl of water. Qinshan said, "The water is clear and the moon appears." Xuefeng said, "The water is clear, yet the moon does not appear." Yantou kicked over the water bowl and walked away.

=== Qiran Zhi ===
E1: On New Year's Day, the Master ascended the hall. "When the six-petaled snowflakes fly, the year changes and mountains, rivers, and the great earth are fresh and pristine. Within this there is a message to penetrate -- the secret meaning is not apart from you. Do not let time pass idly -- right now is precisely the moment for drilling deep. The twin orbs leap and are hard to halt; the thirtieth of the twelfth month is pitiful. The black serpent in your belly makes mischief all day long, making you sleep. In your effort, beware of stopping halfway -- digging a well depends entirely on piercing through to the spring. An iron broom, forged from iron, sweeps back and forth without ceasing. When the blue sky is just the clouds clearing -- but once clouds clear, how are they still in the sky? Do not take my words as a joke; only then will you know the bitter medicine of good counsel. If you ask about the great meaning of the Patriarch's coming from the west: it does not leave the two sides of the hall."
E2: At the end of the session, the Master ascended the hall. "The silent retreat is complete. Raise the eyebrows and see the bright moon -- everywhere its reflection is perfectly round, the scenery is entirely revealed. Heaven and earth are a single mirror; it is not obtained from outside the body. When purity reaches its extreme, brightness hides darkness; all dusts are without arising or ceasing. If a person recognizes this one, what is heard and seen is neither sound nor form. Speak softly, speak softly -- face to face, how do you present it?"

=== Qizhencheng ===
E1: At the mountain gate, the Master said: "Old Zhaozhou said he received the highest guests at the bed, middle guests below the bed, and the lowest guests outside the triple gate. At Huguo we do not follow this rule. Whether you are a prince, a noble, a governor, or a patron, we meet everyone as the occasion calls for, without distinction. Why? The Dharma is equal, with no high or low."
E2: At the Maitreya hall, the Master said: "This old fellow sits there unmoving, not touched by spring or autumn. He always says: 'I am waiting for that person.' I have been coming in and out of abbacies for years -- perhaps I am the one he awaits. Looking closely, we seem no different at all. Since before the primordial sound, we have shared the same nostril for breathing. Today, as I continue the ancestral lamp and ascend the hall, I require the pillar posts to conceive and bear children, the stone women to give birth, you attending heavenly kings to hold out your begging bowls, and the iron trees before your faces to burst into bloom."

=== Qizongzhen ===
E1: At fifty years old, Zhen dreamed of sitting at the foot of a great mountain. A white bull with broad horns and a huge body descended toward her. She reached out to touch it; the bull lowered its head and stood still. She grasped its horns, climbed onto its back, and the bull leapt into the sky. She awoke drenched in sweat. A teacher arrived the next day and said: "Your master has come! The water-buffalo is a Guishan koan. Master Guishan arrived at my hermitage yesterday." Zhen welcomed the master, recognized him as if from a former life, and immediately took ordination. Later, when her family threatened violence against anyone who would ordain her, she took a knife and cut off her own hair.
E2: In an evening talk, the Master said: "All Buddhas appeared in the world for one great matter. All patriarchs arose together for one great matter. All the old masters throughout the world flap their lips, drum their tongues, rake out their innards, talk about the mysterious and the marvelous, discuss nature and mind -- all for one great matter. You people here have broken through the net of love, aroused the aspiration for what is above, traveled to visit teachers, risked your lives -- all just for one great matter. But tell me: what do you call this great matter?" She then cited Touzi's reply when asked the same question: "Administrator Yin invited this old monk to open a teaching hall." She continued: "This case is perfectly direct. But from ancient times to now, people either take it as worldly chatter or as Buddhist philosophy, thereby betraying the ancient sages and burying their own spiritual light. Few have truly understood. If right now you can penetrate directly, not only is the great matter finished, but you can stride alone through the cinnabar sky. If not, then go to your three-foot platform, your seven-foot mat, and grope your way forward. Do not say the new abbot was not good to you."

=== Ruiyan Shiyan ===
E1: Ruiyan asks Yantou, "What is the original constant principle?" Yantou says, "It moves." Ruiyan says, "When it moves, then what?" Yantou says, "You do not see the original constant principle." Ruiyan stands there thinking. Yantou says, "If you assent, you have not yet escaped sense-roots and their dust."
E2: Ruiyan visited Jiashan. Jiashan asked, "Where do you come from?" Ruiyan said, "From Wolong (Crouching Dragon)." Jiashan said, "When you came, had the dragon risen yet?" Ruiyan looked at him. Jiashan said, "Applying moxa to a burn scar." Ruiyan said, "Why does the Master torment himself so?" Jiashan let it rest. Ruiyan then asked Jiashan, "Being so is easy; not being so is hard. Being so, being so -- one is alert. Not being so, not being so -- one dwells in the realm of emptiness. Being so and not being so -- please, Master, speak quickly." Jiashan said, "This old monk has deceived you." Ruiyan shouted, "This old monk! What time is it now?" and walked out.

=== Rujing (Tiantong Rujing) ===
E1: At the Lantern Festival, the Master ascended the hall and said: "The past Buddha of the Burning Lamp -- dragging along karmic consciousness. The present leaking lamp-bowl -- light and shadow deceiving people's eyes. The future dry paper wick -- the stolen goods have nowhere to be pawned. Hmph! Before the skull, crack it open. Inside the nostrils, look and see. Under the monk's gate -- pitch black everywhere. Through countless kalpas, not a single thread of distinction made."
E2: During an autumn drought, the Master ascended the hall: "A single leaf falls -- empty, rustling. Under heaven, autumn -- dry, cracking. All of you! If you just sit here, you will all be fellows who die of thirst. So how will you find a path to life? Qingliang has an expedient means!" He struck his staff once -- crack of thunder! -- "A downpour like overturned basins!" He laughed. "Watch the black vine-staff climb upside-down into the tree."

=== Sanfeng Zang ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the place where a student should apply effort?" The master said: "Look at the place where you turn around." "What is the place where a student turns around?" "Look at the place that is most intimate." "What is the place that is most intimate?" The master said: "Your place of effort is most intimate." The monk said: "This time it is not a dream -- I've truly arrived at Mount Lu!" The master said: "Then why are the Five Old Peaks dancing?" The monk hesitated. The master shouted him straight out of the hall.
E2: On his birthday a monk asked: "The mouth born of father and mother -- you can spin it however you like, great fibs and small fibs. But before father and mother were born, where was your mouth hanging?" The master said: "I can hardly hang it on the wall." The monk said: "I'll be bold and say: it hangs on the wall!" The master said: "I'm timid -- afraid it might rot." The monk said: "Why didn't you say so earlier?" The master struck him repeatedly, saying: "It's not too late." The monk turned and walked out. The master called: "Acarya!" The monk turned his head. The master said: "If you take that as an ordinary beating, you will enter hell like an arrow."

=== Sanshan Lai ===
E1: Layman Pei asked: "Before I was born, who was I?" The Master said: "Zhang San, Li Si." Pei asked: "After I was born, who am I?" The Master said: "Li Si, Zhang San." The layman pondered. The Master slapped him twice across the face.
E2: Magistrate Shen Chijian visited and the Master probed him harshly. Shen hung his head in long silence. the Master asked: "Have you read the encounter of Jiashan visiting the Boatman?" Shen said: "Yes!" The Master said: "Try reciting it." When Shen reached the part where "Jiashan took leave and kept looking back," the Master suddenly held up his palm: "Did you think there was something else?" Shen was released on the spot. Later they saw a cat catch a chicken; the chicken flew into the grass. The Master picked up a brick, set it on the ground, and said: "What is this?" Shen crowed like a rooster. the Master replied: "That answer is not yet complete." Shen kicked the brick away with one foot. The Master then sealed his realization.

=== Sansheng Huiran ===
E1: As Linji is about to die, he instructs Sansheng: "After I have passed away, you must not extinguish my Treasury of the True Dharma Eye." Sansheng says, "How would I dare extinguish master's Treasury of the True Dharma Eye?" Linji says, "If suddenly someone asks you, what will you say?" Sansheng then gives a shout. Linji says: "Who would have known? My true Dharma Eye Treasury has been extinguished by this blind donkey."
E2: Sansheng asks Xuefeng, "A golden-scaled fish that has passed through the net -- I do not yet know what it takes as food." Xuefeng says, "Wait till you come out of the net, then I will tell you." Sansheng says, "A good teacher of fifteen hundred people, and you do not even recognize the topic." Xuefeng says calmly, "This old monk is busy with the affairs of the abbacy."

=== Sanyi Yu ===
E1: A monk asked: "What cannot be grasped, what cannot be let go -- what is it?" The Master said: "Why did you smash a communal bowl and not pay for it?" The monk had no reply. The Master struck him.
E2: A monk asked: "I have always been working on dead phrases. I cannot get the live phrase. What is the live phrase?" the Master responded: "My right ear is deaf. Come around to my left side." The monk went to the left side and was about to ask. The Master stood up and said: "You are driving a dead man."

=== Sengcan ===
E1: "The Supreme Way is not difficult. Just disdain value-creating discrimination. Just do not be averse or attached. Clearly and thoroughly understood, a hair's breadth of difference, and heaven and earth are set apart." This is the opening of the Third Patriarch's Xinxin Ming, his most famous teaching, quoted repeatedly across koan collections.
E2: In the twelfth year of Sui dynasty's Kaihuang era, a novice named Daoxin, only fourteen years old, came to pay respects to Sengcan and said, "I beg the Master's compassion. Please grant me the dharma gate of liberation." Sengcan said, "Who binds you?" Daoxin said, "No one binds me." Sengcan said, "Then why do you seek liberation?" At these words, Daoxin had a great awakening. He served for nine years. Later he received the precepts at Jizhou and attended the Master with ever greater devotion. Sengcan tested him repeatedly with the most subtle matters and, knowing his conditions were ripe, transmitted the robe and dharma to him.

=== Sengzhao ===
E1: When Sengzhao was about to be executed by the Qin ruler Yao Xing, he asked for seven days to complete his final writing. After finishing his treatise, he took up the blade himself, saying: "The four elements have no master. The five aggregates are originally empty. When this head meets the blade, it is like cutting through the spring wind."
E2: ---

=== Shanci Ji ===
E1: On the slopes of Xuefeng's mountain, a monk built a hermitage and lived there for many years without shaving his head. He carved a wooden ladle and went to the stream each day to scoop water to drink. One day a monk asked him, "What is the meaning of the Patriarch's coming from the West?" The hermit replied, "The stream is deep; the ladle's handle is long." The monk went back and reported this to Xuefeng. Xuefeng said, "How extraordinary! Even so, I must go test him myself." One day Xuefeng took a razor and went with his attendant to visit the hermit. As soon as they met, Xuefeng said, "If you can say a word of Zen, I won't shave your head." The hermit silently washed his head and presented it to Xuefeng, who then shaved it. Shanci commented: "A phrase that surpasses the crowd requires a person of keen spirit to bring it forth. A gesture beyond all patterns requires a true adept to discern. Xuefeng's visit -- 'If you do not enter the tiger's cave, how can you catch the tiger's cub?' The hermit, seeing the moment, acted accordingly -- he was not without a path of escape. But tell me: since Xuefeng said 'If you can speak I won't shave you,' why did the hermit simply wash his head and let Xuefeng shave it? If you can sort this out clearly, you will also see what Dongshan the Elder meant when he said, 'Words cannot unfold the matter; speech does not match the moment. Those who grasp at words perish; those who cling to phrases go astray.'"
E2: An old master once said: "Thirty years ago, when I first saw mountains, they were mountains; when I saw water, it was water. Later, when I gained an entry into understanding, I saw mountains that were not mountains and water that was not water. Now, having come to rest, I again see mountains simply as mountains and water simply as water." Master Longchi, my ancestral teacher, said: "At Yumon we do it differently. Forty years ago I saw mountains as mountains and water as water. Then, by chance, in the middle period, I saw mountains that were not mountains and water that was not water -- only then did I gain an entry. Having gained that entry, now I see mountains that are just mountains again, and water that is just water." Shanci commented: "These two old masters are like men who dug up the earth and found gold -- a magnificent windfall! Yet if we examine it closely, both are merely dazzled by a flower in the eye. For the past six or seven years, Dongming too has gone through such a turn -- but the mountains and waters before us have always been utterly ordinary."

=== Shanhui ===
E1: A monk asked: "The ancestral wind is broadly displayed, the patriarchal seal raised high -- is there anyone who has returned home by the road?" The Master said: "Even a woman can't be blamed for that." The monk continued: "What endless scenery to enjoy!" The Master said: "Unaware of her own ugliness."
E2: It was snowing continuously. The Master ascended the hall. A monk asked: "Ice flowers and jade flakes, riding the wind with rain -- what then?" The Master said: "Everything hangs on silver hooks." The monk said: "Then we should look carefully at this silver-colored world." said the Master: "Filling every eye and ear." Then the Master said: "Mountains and streams wrapped in snow -- strange and marvelous. The woodgate sealed with clouds -- cold and desolate. Don't take it as a Buddhist teaching; don't treat it as a mere scene either." A monk came forward and performed a woman's bow. The Master said: "How grotesque." The monk returned to the assembly. the Master replied: "The grass-bandit is defeated!"

=== SHANQUANWEI ===
E1: The Master raised a classic case: "An old woman supported a hermit for thirty years, always sending a young girl to serve him. One day she had the girl embrace him, asking: 'How is it right now?' The hermit said: 'A withered tree leaning against a cold cliff -- in three winters there is no warmth.' The girl reported this to the old woman. The old woman said: 'For thirty years I have only been supporting a common fellow!' She expelled him and burned down the hut." The Master commented: "If it had been me, when the girl embraced and asked 'How is it right now?', I would have given her a sharp pinch and said: 'Don't go spreading rumors!' I guarantee the old woman would then greatly increase her offerings."
E2: Sitting around the fire, the Master stirred the coals and said: "Right now -- how is it?" One monk made a gesture of warming himself. Another monk made a gesture of fear. The Master said: "Singed heads and scorched foreheads, as tiny as millet grains." He then scattered them all with the fire poker.

=== SHANYI CHUN ===
E1: On the day celebrating the Buddha's birth, the Master ascended the hall: "Shakyamuni was a prince of the imperial palace. For no reason he went to Snow Mountain for six years of bitter practice, then gazed at the morning star and called it 'awakening to the Way and becoming a Buddha.'" He gave a shout and said: "White jade originally has no flaw -- why willingly let it be smeared with filth? Yet without the spring wind, flowers do not bloom; for them to bloom, one must borrow the breeze."
E2: Ascending the hall: "Three thousand seven hundred tangled vines have misled later generations into crooked views. Five thousand forty-eight scrolls of idle old paper have burdened the world's fools, manufacturing calamities of the heart. Among you, is there anyone who knows the genuine point?" He struck the staff once: "Water flowing past stones comes out cold; wind passing through flowers arrives fragrant."

=== Shenfeng Xian ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the sash of the True Dharma Eye Treasury?" The master said: "A stone mortar under the open sky." "What is the sash of the Buddha-Dharma Treasury?" "The Yellow River's water comes from Kunlun." "What is the sash of Principle-Penetration?" "Open your mouth and see the gallbladder." "What is the sash of Fact-Penetration?" "South mountain clouds, north mountain rain." "What is the sash of Principle-and-Fact Crisscrossing?" "The laughing Budai at the crossroads." "What is the sash of Bending and Drooping?" "Test kinship by the blood of the lineage." "What is the sash of Subtle Accord?" "The upended sword-that-splits-a-hair shows no edge." "What is the sash of the Golden Needle and Double Lock?" "Mandarin ducks on brocade cannot be embroidered to completion." "What is the sash of Level Mind, Constant Reality?" The master struck him.
E2: Evening talk. The master retold the story of Nanquan cutting the cat, then said: "Pouring water on the horse's head is easy; catching water at the horse's tail is hard. Zhaozhou may be called a worthy heir, but examined closely, it was still not proper dharma. I too keep a cat -- I hold it up before you all. How will you handle it?" He suddenly looked left and right, gave a shout, and descended from his seat.

=== Shengke ===
E1: The Master raised the old case: Nanquan was living on the mountain when a wandering practitioner visited. Nanquan said, "I am going up the mountain to work. Cook some food and bring me a portion." After Nanquan left, the wanderer cooked and ate, then smashed all the pots and bowls and lay down on the bed. When Nanquan saw no food coming, he returned to find the smashed crockery and the wanderer lying on the bed. Nanquan lay down beside him. The wanderer got up and left. Years later, Nanquan said to the assembly: "Twenty years ago on the mountain I met a practitioner of great sharpness. To this very day I have not seen him again." the Master replied: "What do you mean, 'twenty years not seen'? The moment the wanderer smashed the pots, he had already vanished. When Nanquan lay down beside him, he was merely chasing shadows. And bringing it up twenty years later -- what was his intention? 'Past warhorses no one recognizes -- he simply wants to discuss once more his era-defining merit.'"
E2: On the occasion of lifting the summer retreat, the Master said: "The eye born of father and mother will ultimately perish. The ear born of father and mother will ultimately perish. The nose, the tongue, the body, the mind -- all born of father and mother will ultimately perish. When the six sense-roots are destroyed, the six sense-objects have nothing to lean on. Mind and consciousness fully dissolved -- no hindrance, no obstruction. If you can understand this, then you may stand on the highest peak, walk the deepest ocean floor, charge through the crossroads in any direction -- this side, that side, west or east, nothing is permissible and nothing impermissible. But if you do not understand, you are welcome to go on snoring away on the long bench."

=== Shengren of Qianshan ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master said: "The banner-pole has already spoken to you. The triple gate has already spoken to you. The Four Heavenly Kings have already spoken to you. The Dharma-seat and the lamp-pillar have already spoken to you. Have all of you heard them? If you have not yet heard, this mountain monk can only repeat the meaning for you." He descended from the seat.
E2: Ascending the hall: "Between the worldly and the transcendent, if you see their true reality, all differences vanish. If a monastic fails to see through it, that is called a monastic who is really a layperson. If a layperson sees through it, that is called a layperson who is really a monastic. If a man fails to see through it, he is a woman wearing a beard. If a woman sees through it, she is a man who simply lacks a beard. Just this discriminating mind is your root of birth and death, whirling through the six realms for a hundred kalpas and a thousand lives. If before your parents gave you birth you could catch one clear glimpse -- tell me, is there any distinction of lay and monastic, female and male in that place?" He struck the staff: "Snow-lotuses bloom, petal by petal fragrant; in the mirror, willow leaves curve in graceful arcs." He descended.

=== Shexian Guisheng ===
E1: Shoushan held up a bamboo comb and posed his barrier. Master Sheng of Yexian (Shexian Guisheng) snatched it, broke it into two pieces, threw it down the steps, and said: "What is this?" Shoushan said: "Blind fellow!" Sheng then bowed.
E2: A monk requested instruction on the cypress tree case. Shexian said, "I would not refuse to explain it to you. But do you believe?" The monk said, "The Master's words carry weight. How would I dare not believe?" Shexian said, "Do you hear the sound of the raindrops from the eaves?" The monk suddenly became clear and could not help exclaiming, "Ah!" Shexian said, "What principle do you see?" The monk responded with a verse: "Raindrops from the eaves -- clear and distinct, distinct and clear. Smashing open heaven and earth, in that moment the mind rests." Shexian was delighted.

=== Shiguan ===
E1: A monk asked: "Beating the drum and ascending the hall -- that I won't ask about. But when we meet face to face, what then?" The Master said: "I'll give you a hammer-blow to the back of the skull." The monk continued: "The great forge with its red furnace tempers buddhas and smelts patriarchs. If someone comes along who needs no hammer and tongs, how will you receive him?" The Master said: "First, attend to that hammer-blow." The monk said: "When the golden bell strikes, the moon appears above the peak; when the jade flute blows, the wind returns from the sea." The Master said: "Idle chatter."
E2: On New Year's Day, the Master ascended the hall and said: "Heaven opens at the hour of the Rat, earth opens at the hour of the Ox, man is born at the hour of the Tiger. Sun and moon come and go, from ancient times to the present, yin and yang wax and wane. The old year departs, spring arrives. Three hundred and sixty days -- today everything is new again. Li Four congratulates Zhang Three, a blind turtle meets a lame turtle, calling and bowing to each other in the cold. Every brow leaps with delight. And there is a stone woman playing the sheng, a wooden man rising to dance. How laughable that Old Teacher Wang does not beat the Yanguang drum! In the thirty-third heaven, the Emperor's bell is struck. Best of all is Yunmen's single word: 'Universal!' If someone asks: 'What is the Buddha-dharma on New Year's Day?' then say: 'Rabbit horns and tortoise hair show their old faces, yet the entire cosmos of heaven and earth is freshly radiant.'" He struck his staff and descended.

=== Shipuzhi ===
E1: Citing the old case: A monk asked Changqing: "Many hands sifting for gold -- who gets it?" Changqing said: "The one with skill gets it." The monk said: "Does the student get any?" Changqing said: "Too far away." The master commented: "Changqing misled no small number of people! Here at Xianglin we say otherwise. 'Many hands sifting for gold -- who gets it?' I would just say: 'The one without skill gets it.' And if he asks 'Does the student get any?' -- 'Too close.'"
E2: A monk recited Master Gaofeng's six famous unsolvable questions. On "the greatly awakened person has transcended birth and death -- why can the root of life not be cut?", the master said: "A household without servants cannot produce a gentleman." On "the bright sun fills the sky and illuminates everything -- why is it blocked by a single cloud?", the master said: "A single ray of divine light -- ten thousand realms at ease." On "everyone has a shadow that never leaves them for a single step -- why can it not be stepped on?", the master said: "What would you step on it for?" On "the entire great earth is a single pit of fire -- what samadhi must one attain to not be burned?", the master said: "Gold does not trade for gold."

=== Shiqi of Xuedou ===
E1: During an evening talk, Shiqi says: "A man is riding a panicky horse. Terrified, he passes under a tree and grabs a branch. The horse runs off but he's still dangling, yelling for help." He strikes with his bamboo whip and says: "He doesn't realize that right HERE, if he just let go, he'd land safe and solid on the ground. Why waste so much effort?" Strikes again: "Understand?" Long pause. "Dismissed."
E2: A monk asks: "I possess one thing that a thousand sages cannot recognize" -- and raises his fist: "Do you recognize it?" Shiqi just hits him. A monk asks for the Three Mysteries of Linji. A monk asks for the Three Mysteries of Linji. "What is the First Mystery?" -- "Your head touches heaven." "What is the Second Mystery?" -- "A lone goose descends to the stream before us." "What is the Third Mystery?" -- "Perfectly clear, right over there." "What is the First Essential?" -- "Stop your wild shouting." "What is the Second Essential?" -- He hits him: "There's a staff for you." "What is the Third Essential?" -- Hits him again: "Still not enough."

=== Shishuang Chuyuan ===
E1: Shishuang ascended the hall and held up his staff, saying, "All the Buddhas of past, present, and future, the twenty-eight Indian patriarchs, the six Chinese patriarchs, and all the venerable teachers everywhere -- they have all transformed into this staff of Nanyuan. Where will you all find a place to stand? Look! Look! The staff has pierced through all your skulls. Is there anyone who can feel the pain? If so, come out and leap before the assembly. If not, then Nanyuan has lost the contest today." He gave a shout, struck the staff on the ground, and descended.
E2: A monk asked, "What is the meaning of the Patriarch's coming from the West?" Shishuang said, "He loaded the whole family onto the boat." Another monk asked, "What is the great meaning of the Buddha-dharma?" Shishuang said, "One acre of land -- three snakes and nine rats."

=== Shishuang Qingzhu ===
E1: Shishuang said, "How do you advance from the tip of a hundred-foot pole?" An ancient worthy said, "A person who sits at the top of a hundred-foot pole -- though he has entered, it is not yet true. At the top of a hundred-foot pole you must advance a step, and the ten directions' world manifests the full body."
E2: When Luoshan first asked Shishuang, "When arising and ceasing do not stop, what then?" Shishuang said, "You must become cold ashes and dead wood; let one thought be ten thousand years." Luoshan did not agree, and went to Yantou instead.

=== Shitian Faxun ===
E1: Shitian raised the case: "Sleeping Dragon held up his staff and said: 'For twenty years I have lived on this mountain, sustained entirely by the power of this staff.' A monk asked: 'What power do you get from it?' He answered: 'Crossing streams, crossing ridges -- leaning east, leaning west.'" Shitian commented: "Sleeping Dragon boasted of thirty years on the mountain drawing power from his staff. Yet when that monk gave him the lightest push, he wasted so much energy responding. Where was the staff then? When I arrived at this mountain, I too gained this staff's power. What power, you ask?" He leaned the staff against the wall and descended from the seat.
E2: Shitian raised the case: "A monk asked Yunmen: 'When the trees wither and the leaves fall, what then?' Yunmen replied: 'Body exposed in the autumn wind.'" Shitian commented: "Yunmen created a path where there was no path, made a meaning-road where there was none. But I would not say it that way. 'When the trees wither and the leaves fall, what then?' -- The nesting bird first sees the sun; the ant in its hole knows nothing of the cold."

=== Shitou Xiqian ===
E1: Layman Pang asked Shitou, "Not keeping company with the ten thousand dharmas, what person is that?" Before the words were finished, Shitou covered his mouth. The Layman, having gained an understanding, composed a verse: "In daily use there is nothing different, only I myself am naturally in accord. In everything there is no choosing or rejecting; everywhere there is no obstruction... Spiritual powers and wondrous function are: carrying water and hauling firewood."
E2: Wuxie visited Shitou, having agreed beforehand that if one word matched, he would stay; otherwise he would leave. Shitou sat on his seat. Wuxie flicked his sleeves and went out. Shitou called out, "Venerable!" Wuxie turned his head. Shitou said, "From birth to death, it is only this. Do not turn your head and swivel your brain looking for something else." Wuxie had a great awakening upon these words.

=== Shiwu Qinghong ===
E1: Ascending the hall on the fifteenth of the seventh month, Shiwu said: "Today a cool wind opens my bamboo door. On the ridge above, one piece, two pieces of white cloud are blown seven ways and eight by the wind. Floating lightly, hovering softly, wanting to scatter but not scattering, wanting to gather but not gathering. This old monk beckons to the white clouds: White clouds, white clouds, why don't you stay? In the end you always return to the mountain. Why wander at the edge of the world, lost on the road?" He gave a great shout.
E2: "The moon rises from the eastern sea gate, golden waves vast and boundless. Round and never waning, bright and perfectly fine. I send word to the Old Man of the White Rabbit and to Chang'e: gather your radiance without delay, conceal your light while there is still time. Do not wait for black clouds to come from all four directions -- then all the brilliance in the sky will be gone. In all the world only the mind of the practitioner of the Way has remained luminous through all the ages."

=== Shixi Xinyue ===
E1: Ascending the hall, Shixi said: "All day long busy, busy -- yet that matter is not hindered. What is 'that matter'? If you understand, you enter hell swift as an arrow. If you do not understand -- all day long busy, busy, yet that matter is not hindered."
E2: On the Buddha's birthday, ascending the hall: "A flawless jade of connected cities -- why did he come sprinkling sand the moment he was born? The lame old teacher knows where it falls. A good enemy has an evil enemy."

=== Shoushan Xingnian ===
E1: Shoushan lifts up a bamboo stick, shows the assembly and says: "If you people call it a bamboo stick, you touch it. If you do not call it a bamboo stick, you turn your back on it. You all, tell me: what do you call it?" Wumen comments: "You must not have words; you must not have no words. Speak quickly, speak quickly."
E2: A monk asks Shoushan: "What is Buddha?" Shoushan says: "The bride rides the donkey, the mother-in-law leads it." 

=== SHUAI'AN FANZONG ===
E1: Evening talk. "Smash open empty space -- no seams! The robed monk takes his ease wherever he is. Yet because of the imperial edict he enters the mountains, and north of the clouds, south of the clouds, he makes a dream. Therefore all three-world Buddhas, all patriarchs, all old masters everywhere, mountains and rivers, sun moon and stars, grasses trees and insects -- each and every one is making a dream." Then: "Daytime thoughts become nighttime dream-realms; nighttime dreams generate daytime conditions. From the dust-kalpas until today, there has never been any difference. Tell me: are all dharmas dreams? Then what are dharmas? Are dharmas not dreams? Then why are we in a dream?"
E2: "Shuai'an has nothing to distribute for the year-end. Shake out the old stock -- the whisk wags its tail and nods its head, knowing how to play the lion's game. Casually it lets out a single roar that shakes heaven and earth. Old villager Wang burns paper money all night; the hearth-god dare not close his eyes." Then a verse: "At year's end, nothing to pass along to anyone. Four walls deeply wreathed in smoke. How many times I part the embers and question myself -- when the firewood is spent, that is the new year."

=== Shuijianhai ===
E1: Evening talk upon first arriving: "Yangqi's early days -- the walls were thin, and the whole bed was scattered with pearls of snow. He hunched his shoulders and sighed, recalling the ancients who lived under trees." Then: "Now I've just arrived at Jinsu. Not only are the walls crumbling and the fences collapsed, but there's no grain for tomorrow's meal and no firewood to warm water. The destitution is even worse than Yangqi's! Here's a verse: Arriving at Jinsu in the depths of winter, cold snow whirling and the larder empty. I stretch out my legs and sleep, taking heart -- tomorrow's provisions are heaven's concern."
E2: Ascending the hall: "Deshan met people and struck them -- a wartime rogue. Linji met people and shouted at them -- a peacetime bandit. All other minor techniques are not worth discussing. As for Jinsu's style -- what is it? Carrying a three-foot sword, cutting down the unjust."

=== SHUZHONG WUYUN ===
E1: Shuzhong ascended the hall and raised an old case: Chan Master Huanglong Xin was engaged in vigorous discussion with the scholar Xia Gongli about the Treatise on the Immutability of Things by Sengzhao, debating the thesis that "all things are the self" and that "sentient and insentient share one body." At that moment a dog happened to be lying beneath the incense stand. Huanglong picked up a ruler, struck the dog, then struck the incense stand, and said: "The dog has feelings and so it runs away. The incense stand has no feelings and so it stays put. If sentient and insentient share one body, how can that be?" Gongli could not reply. Huanglong said: "The moment you fall into thinking, it already becomes superfluous. How could you ever have understood 'all things are the self'?" Shuzhong commented: "Old Huanglong's compassion was not small, but Scholar Xia was like someone entering a treasure mountain and coming back empty-handed. Do you all want to understand 'all things are the self' and 'sentient and insentient share one body'? Kill the sentient dog, smash the insentient incense stand, gather everything up, tie it into a single bundle, and hurl it into the great Eastern Ocean. Naturally you'll be clean and free. Even so, you must still know there is an opening at the crown of the head." He struck the incense stand with his staff and said: "Ala la! Ala la! Climbing mountains makes the knees sore, sipping tea makes the tongue slippery. The stone guardian at the crossroads -- facing the moon in the breeze, playing the bamboo flute."
E2: Shuzhong raised an old case: Guishan, seeing Yangshan warming himself by the fire, asked: "Is it the weather that's cold, or is it the person who's cold?" Yangshan said, "Everyone is right here." Guishan said, "Why not speak directly?" Yangshan said, "What I just said wasn't crooked either. What about you, Master?" Guishan said, "One must simply go with the flow." Shuzhong commented: "When the pearl is bright, the river is beautiful. When jade is lustrous, the mountain is radiant. This describes the father-and-son relationship of Guishan and Yangshan. That is certainly so, but if at that time they had known there was still a path of turning the body around, their lineage would not have withered." He asked, "Do you understand? Humans and devas cannot fathom it -- take care, O red-bearded barbarian. If not yet clear, listen to another verse: A pair of lutes played beneath the moon, a cool breeze arises at the fingertips. They only know they are pouring out what is in their hearts -- who notices the bystander watching from the cold?"

=== Sixin Wuxin (Dead Heart) ===
E1: Sixin ascended the hall and said, "This matter is like a family that raises three sons. The first is intelligent and wise -- he honors his parents, receives guests, and manages the family estate. The second is wild and crafty -- he is greedy, lustful, and fond of drink, lying in streets and alleys, ruining the family fortune. The third is blind, deaf, and mute -- he cannot tell beans from wheat, is incapable of anything, and only knows how to eat rice. Among these three sons, Yunyan wants to select one to employ. Which will you choose? The intelligent and wise one? The wild and crafty one? The blind, deaf, and mute one? If you can make this selection, you enter the gate of Yunyan -- but you have not yet seen Yunyan himself. Do you want to see Yunyan? Spring rain falls equally everywhere; the branches of flowers are long and short of themselves."
E2: Sixin ascended the hall and raised an old case: Once there was a monk who sat in the sutra hall. He did not read the sutras, he did not practice dhyana, he did not study -- every day he just sat there in a heap. The librarian said, "Why don't you read the sutras?" The monk said, "I can't read." The librarian said, "Why don't you ask someone?" The monk stepped forward, bowed with palms together, and said, "What character is this?" The librarian had nothing to say. Sixin commented, "This monk was sitting at home with the door shut when disaster fell from the sky. If not for that librarian, he'd have nearly stormed the city of Caizhou."

=== Songyin Weianran ===
E1: The assembly gathered. Weianran looked left and right, said "Remember this clearly," and stepped down from the seat.
E2: A monk asks about the "one road upward that a thousand sages do not transmit." Weianran retorts: "Where did you get this news from?" The monk tries: "One who sells gold must meet a gold buyer." Weianran gives a great shout. When the monk pushes further -- "Gold dust, though precious, blinds the eye when it falls in" -- Weianran answers with verse: "Go look upon Embroidered Lake on a clear night; the bright moon scatters golden waves on the water every evening." The monk predicts: "In thirty years this teaching will spread widely." Weianran scoffs: "Fraudulent Zen monks are as thick as hemp and millet seeds."

=== Songyuan Chongyue ===
E1: From the preface by Meng You: "Songyuan said that he left home before even receiving full ordination, and had an initial breakthrough under Master Ying'an Tanhua. Later he trained under Mu'an Yong and Mi'an Jie. Though he had several awakenings after traveling widely among masters, he still harbored doubt about not being truly liberated. This went on for years -- he drove himself relentlessly, forgetting cold and heat. One day, while staying under Daochang Quan, he suddenly attained realization, and his web of doubt was entirely destroyed. Master Quan happened to be away. After several days when Quan returned, Songyuan rushed to enter the interview room, desperate for confirmation. But Quan's testing did not hit the mark. Songyuan cursed him and walked out. He immediately shouldered his pack and crossed to Fengkou to see Mi'an. Before Songyuan could even speak, Mi'an said: 'Congratulations -- the great matter is clear! But do not try to express it.' Songyuan then returned to the hall to rest." His departure verse read: "The essential point, right at the head -- no confusion, no error. Going and staying are like waves on water. When there is spirit, add more spirit. Let the level ground erupt in warfare."
E2: Songyuan ascended the hall: "The superior person hears the Way and practices it diligently -- a child playing with mud. The middling person hears the Way and half believes, half doubts -- cut in two with a single blade. The inferior person hears the Way and laughs loudly -- a motley household. Chengzhao announces it like this -- but where exactly is the fine print? A sharp knife cuts flesh and the wound still heals. Vicious words wound the heart -- and the scar never fades."

=== Su Shi ===
E1: "Su Dongpo wrote in a poem to Foyin: 'I have no leisure yet to study long life; for now I study long not-dying.'" 
E2: "They seek it from others, and others speak of it -- like Dongpo's explanation by metaphor: conjecturing back and forth, the farther one goes, the more one misses." The preface-writer invokes Dongpo as a cautionary example: the more brilliant the conceptual explanation, the further from the mark.

=== SURUHAN OF BOSHAN ===
E1: Ascending the hall at mid-autumn, the Master said: "When the water drops, the stones appear. When the mountain is high, the moon looks small. The great Way is straight as a bowstring -- take care not to wander." Then he continued: "The autumn wind blows off the leaves, the autumn dew dampens the robe. At this time of the silver moon, who pities the one who has not yet come home? The one not yet home -- to Chu and then to Qin -- both temples growing grey, and for what? Each time the grief wells up, each time the anger. Cloud-mountains stretch ten thousand distances apart, and the traveler on the road groans in pain with each passing day." He paused, then said: "One's own hidden treasury was originally secure and secret -- why must one search outward in bitter pursuit?" He struck a circle with his whisk and said: "One bright moon illuminates the heart of heaven. The four seas of living beings receive its light. Why wait for the west wind to shake the cassia tree? The blue sky will once more deliver the sound of the ninth autumn."
E2: ---

=== Sushan Kuangren ===
E1: In Xiangyan's assembly, a monk asks, "Not admiring the sages and not valuing one's own spirit -- what then?" Xiangyan says, "The ten thousand functions rest; the thousand sages do not carry it along." Shu (the future Sushan) makes a retching sound and says, "What kind of words are these?" Xiangyan asks who he is; told it is his Dharma uncle, he demands Shu try saying it himself. After the exchange, Xiangyan predicts: "If you live by water, there will be no water to drink. Remember this clearly." After twenty-seven years Sushan says to himself, "Xiangyan predicted thirty years of shitting backward for me; now I still owe three years." After every meal he induces vomiting to fulfill the prediction.
E2: After Dongshan passed away, Sushan completed the mourning rites and went to Tanzhou to see Great Weishan. Weishan was addressing the assembly, saying, "Traveling practitioners of high caliber must sleep within sound and color, sit and lie down within sound and color -- only then will they have attained it." Sushan came forward and asked, "What is the phrase that does not fall into sound and color?" Weishan held up his whisk. Sushan said, "This is a phrase that falls into sound and color." Weishan put down the whisk and returned to his quarters. Sushan was not satisfied and took his leave. He went to Xiangyan. Xiangyan said, "Why not stay awhile?" Sushan said, "I have no affinity with the Master." Xiangyan said, "What is the occasion? Try presenting it." Sushan brought up the previous exchange. Xiangyan said, "I have a saying." Sushan said, "What do you say?" Xiangyan said, "When speech issues forth, it is not sound; before color, it is not a thing." Sushan said, "So there is someone here after all."

=== Tan'an of Puguang ===
E1: The Honorable Bai Xian bowed. The Master said: "Today I will not answer questions." Xian straightened up and said: "What kind of talk is this?" the Master answered: "I already told you, today I will not answer questions." Xian paused to think. The Master gave a shout. Xian also shouted. the Master answered: "This sick monk's one shout has both host and guest in it. What about the Honorable's shout?" Xian said: "Two eyes facing two eyes." The Master shouted again. Xian said: "Today I'll let you off." the Master responded: "Don't assume the staff is not at hand."
E2: The storeroom keeper asked: "What is 'the ten thousand dharmas return to one'?" The Master said: "Firewood, rice, oil, salt, fruits, and vegetables." The keeper asked: "What is 'where does the one return to'?" The Master said: "You must guard it with a steadfast mind." The keeper bowed and said: "Thank you, Master, for answering." The Master said: "Be careful not to swallow the date whole."

=== Tanfang Shouzhong ===
E1: Evening talk at the winter solstice: "Shakyamuni's eyes have no sinews in them. Bodhidharma's skin has no blood beneath it. You all only know to count the nine cold periods from the solstice and hope for three snows before the new year -- but you don't know that last night the old plum tree's south-facing branch froze and snapped." He struck the bench. Then: "Before Shaolin Peak the golden phoenix dances; on the road to Caoxi the jade rooster crows. Qingshan tonight beats the evening drum and keeps idle monks standing a little while longer."
E2: Raising the old exchange between Shitou and Yaoshan -- Shitou said: "Words and actions have nothing to do with it." Yaoshan came forward: "Even what is not words and actions also has nothing to do with it." Shitou said: "Here, not even a needle can enter." Yaoshan said: "Here, it is like planting flowers on rock." Tanfang's comment: "The image-less one holds the pearl effortlessly in hand. Where Li Lou walks, waves reach the sky."

=== Tianhuang Daowu ===
E1: Daowu and his student Jianyuan go to a household to offer condolences. Jianyuan slaps the coffin and asks: "Alive, or dead?" Daowu says: "I will not speak of life; I will not speak of death." Jianyuan presses: "Why not speak?" Daowu: "Not speaking, not speaking." On the road home, Jianyuan demands an answer or threatens to beat him. Daowu says: "If you beat me, then beat me; if you want me to speak, then I will not speak." Jianyuan strikes him. Daowu sent him away for his safety. Only later, hearing a sutra recitation, does Jianyuan awaken and say: "At that time I wrongly blamed my former teacher."
E2: Yunyan asks Daowu: "The Great Compassion Bodhisattva uses so many hands and eyes -- for what?" Daowu: "Like a person in the middle of the night, reaching back with the hand to feel for a pillow." Yunyan: "I understand." Daowu: "How do you understand?" Yunyan: "The whole body is hands and eyes." Daowu: "You have said quite enough -- yet you only got eighty percent." Yunyan: "Then how do you say it, elder brother?" Daowu: "The entire body is hands and eyes."

=== Tianlong ===
E1: Master Juzhi was humiliated when a nun challenged him and he had no reply. He resolved to leave his hermitage. A local spirit said: "Do not go. Tomorrow a great teacher will come to teach the Dharma for you." Sure enough, Master Tianlong came to the hermitage. Juzhi bowed and related what had happened. Tianlong simply raised one finger. Juzhi suddenly had great awakening. From then on, whenever asked anything, Juzhi only raised one finger. At his death he said: "I obtained Tianlong's one-finger Chan. In a lifetime I have used it without exhausting it."
E2: A monk asked Tianlong, "How can one escape the three realms?" Tianlong said, "Where are you right now?"

=== Tianqi Benrui ===
E1: Benrui called on Baofeng Mingxuan. Baofeng asked: "Where have you come from?" "Beijing." "Have you been anywhere else?" "Wandering at ease wherever the road leads." "Have you been to Sichuan?" "I have." "How does the realm of Sichuan compare with here?" "The mountains and rivers differ, but the wind and moon are the same." Baofeng raised his fist: "Do they also have this?" "No." "Why not?" "It is not within my realm." "Then what IS your realm?" "Even the buddhas cannot recognize it -- who would dare force a name on it?" Baofeng approved him and gave the seal-verse of transmission.
E2: Tianqi Benrui once held a discussion with Puzhao Taichu. He raised the topic: "Setting aside the three principles of the highest vehicle, there remains a final matter to be resolved." Taichu asked, "What is this final matter?" Benrui said, "Wind blows the willows by the wall, sun falls on the elms by the stream." Puzhao said, "Where the green mountains are low, the sky appears broad; where the red lotus blooms, one smells the fragrance of water." Taichu made a retching sound and said, "That is just playing with words." Benrui said, "What about you?" Taichu said, "Like a man climbing a wall with no plan." Benrui made the same retching sound, rose from his seat, and returned to his place.

=== Tianran of Mount Lu ===
E1: The Master gave an evening talk: "I was just in the abbot's room when I heard the drum. Immediately someone stepped forward and asked, 'Today is the eighth of the twelfth month, and you happen to be giving a talk -- may this disciple pose a question?' I said, 'All four assemblies may ask -- how could I not allow it?' He then said, 'I am the tree spirit in front of the main hall. The other day the senior monk told me to move my dwelling, and I have already complied. But I have one doubt: if the entire great earth is a place of practice, why must you tear down my house?' I answered at once, 'Since you already know the entire great earth is a place of practice, where CAN'T you live? Why are you still clinging?' The spirit laughed and said, 'You Chan masters are always so clever with words! I merely said the entire earth is a place of practice, so why tear down my house -- and you turned it right around on me.' Seeing his quick wit, I called him forward and spoke to him plainly: 'Tree Spirit -- your house is also partly mine; my temple hall is also partly yours. Why keep dividing yours from mine?' The tree spirit fell silent, embarrassed, and withdrew." The Master struck the floor with his staff. "Do you all know who that tree spirit really was? He knew how to ask, but he didn't know how to seize the advantage."
E2: On the eighth day of the twelfth month, the Master gave an evening talk: "Our Buddha, the World-Honored One, on this night long ago saw the morning star and awakened. Awakened -- granted. But hasn't he already fallen into the second rank? What is the FIRST rank?" He then chased the entire assembly out with his staff. Then he said, "Regret! Regret!" -- and returned to the abbot's room.

=== Tianru Weize ===
E1: Tianru addressed the assembly: "Talking about the mysterious, talking about the marvelous. Discussing nature, discussing mind. Heaping up flowers and piling up brocade. Clever, subtle, sharp, and new. Thick as hemp, numerous as millet, from ancient times to the present -- all of them are nothing but men catching echoes in empty air, spirits clinging to grass and trees. Though I too am a weed from that same family garden, I absolutely refuse to hide my body in that thicket. Since that is so, what is the brand-new command for opening the hall today?" He gave a shout and said: "When the tally arrives, carry out the order."
E2: At a Huayan assembly, a monk asked Tianru Weize, "The boundless realm of lands -- self and other are not separated by so much as a hair's breadth. Since there is self and other, how are they not separated?" Tianru said, "The ox in Huaizhou eats the grain, and the horse's belly in Yizhou swells." The monk asked, "Ten ages past and present, beginning and end, do not depart from this present thought. Since there is beginning and end, how do they not depart?" Tianru said, "Seek a doctor throughout the world, and he cauterizes the pig's left shoulder." The monk said, "This assembly expounds the scriptures; there is no need for Chan talk. I only hope the Master will speak directly on the teaching texts." Tianru said, "This mountain monk does not have two tongues." The monk said, "The One True Dharma Realm, the Ten Mysterious Gates -- is there still self and other, beginning and end, or not?" Tianru shouted and said, "Where do you get so many old antiques?" The monk said, "Since there are no old antiques, what exactly does the Huayan teach?" Tianru said, "It teaches the Huayan." The monk said, "Apart from the Dharma Realm and the Mysterious Gates, where is the Huayan Sutra?" Tianru said, "It is in all of your hands." The monk said, "Then I shall receive it in faith and carry it out." Tianru said, "I'll give you three coins to buy straw sandals."

=== Tianshuzhi of Helin ===
E1: The Master said: "Since entering the monastery I have been dealing with affairs, dragging through mud and water, running through the city, and with the rain falling for days on end, the monastery short of firewood and rice. All day long we discuss the size of pot-eyes and the length of ladle-handles -- I have completely forgotten the Buddha-dharma. I recall the other day I happened to board a bottomless boat and pass beneath Jiao Mountain. In the rapids I fished out a holeless iron flute and blew a tune on it without thinking. 'The person in the tune is nowhere to be seen; over the river, several peaks stand blue.' Now I shall play one more tune for the assembly." He took up the whisk, mimed playing a flute, and sang out: "La-li la-li la-la-li!" Then he struck the incense table: "Stop! Stop! Everyone before my eyes is a true connoisseur -- a fine tune played needs no repetition."
E2: On Buddha's Enlightenment Day, the Master said: "The sun does not need fire to be hot. The moon does not need wind to be cool. The Buddha does not need awakening to be complete. The Way does not need cultivation to be realized. If that is so, then heaven is heaven, earth is earth, mountains are mountains, water is water, monks are monks, laypeople are laypeople. The tall have a tall Dharma-body, the short have a short Dharma-body -- not a single hair's breadth is displaced. Then why, three thousand five hundred years ago, did that blundering fellow Shakyamuni abandon the wheel-turning kingship, go straight to the snowy mountains, endure six years of austerity, and suddenly at midnight, glimpsing the morning star, burst out exclaiming: 'How marvelous! How marvelous!' -- as if a beggar had struck it rich, making a great fuss over nothing? Let me put it in verse for you all: Six years of bitter practice on the snowy peak, / Suddenly he glimpsed the morning star in the blue-green sky. / Just when he knocked out his own eyeball, / One blind man began leading the other blind ones along."

=== Tiantong Rujing ===
E1: When invited into the palace for a vegetarian feast, all the great monks and elders read sutras; only the master's group sat silent. The emperor asked, "Why do you not read sutras?" The master said: "When the Way is at peace, one does not transmit the Son of Heaven's command; when the age is clear, one need not sing songs of great peace." The emperor asked why the disciples also did not read. The master said: "In a lion's den there are no other beasts; where the elephant king walks, fox tracks are cut off." The emperor asked why all the other monks read. The master said: "The jellyfish originally has no eyes; to seek food it must depend on shrimp."
E2: Rujing was notorious for his sharp style. His most famous teaching moment came when he struck a sleeping monk and shouted: "The practice of zazen is the dropping away of body and mind! What is the use of single-minded sleeping?" This phrase -- "dropping away of body and mind" -- pierced Dogen to his core and became the seed of his life's teaching.

=== Tianyi Yihuai ===
E1: Tianyi versified the famous case of Vimalakirti's thundering silence when asked about nonduality. A monk once asked a certain master, "In the records they often say 'a long while' -- who is this 'Long While'?" The master answered: "'Long While' is Liang Ba's younger brother." Those who heard it took it as a joke. But Tianyi's verse cuts deeper: "In the case of the hair-blowing sword, cold light is born in the box; outsiders and heavenly demons are all beheaded."
E2: When Tianyi traveled to take up residence at Shanshan Monastery, he entered the hall and announced: "For twenty years I have delighted in and admired this mountain. Today I am glad to have come through the meeting of causes and conditions. Before this mountain monk arrived at this mountain, my body had already arrived at this mountain. When I finally came, Shanshan was instead within this mountain monk's body."

=== TIANYI YUE ===
E1: Ascending the hall: "Seeing form is not about form; hearing sound is not about sound. If it is neither form nor sound, then what is it?" He picked up the staff and said: "The Bodhisattva Avalokiteshvara took money to buy a sesame cake. When she put it down, it turned out to be a steamed bun. At this point, what is so hard to understand?" He tapped the staff: "A clever fellow sees smoke across the mountain and knows there is fire; sees horns above the wall and knows there is an ox."
E2: Ascending the hall: "Dogs guard the night, roosters herald the dawn, silkworms spin thread, bees gather honey. Shakyamuni for forty-nine years and over three hundred assemblies used every skill, flapping his two lips, expounding horizontally and vertically, ceaselessly -- yet never once did he reach this point. Bodhidharma sailed ten thousand leagues across the sea, traveled through Liang and Wei, intending to show off his elegance -- but Liu Zhisan knocked out his front teeth!" He gave a shout and descended.

=== Tianyin ===
E1: Pumen led a group to visit the Master. Over tea, Pumen said: "Why aren't you drinking tea?" said the Master: "I am drinking." Pumen said: "You don't have any." The Master held up his tea-cup to show him. Pumen said: "That one's mine." The Master hurled the tea in his face, saying: "Is it yours? Or mine?" Pumen had nothing to say. After the meal, Pumen remarked: "People in the world are like flying kites -- when the wind is too strong, you shouldn't fly them." the Master replied: "Not so." Pumen asked: "Why not?" The Master said: "What if you've already launched it and the wind picks up?" Pumen said: "Then it's finished." The Master said: "Also not so." Pumen asked: "Why not?" The Master said: "Why not just reel in the string?" Pumen again had nothing to say.
E2: A newly ordained nun came. The Master asked: "Why did you leave home?" She said: "For my own sake." He said: "For your own sake -- then why did you abandon your husband?" She replied: "A shadow in the clouds." The Master threw both hands behind his back and said: "Say more." She said: "Mind does not think, thought does not stir." He said: "If mind doesn't think and thought doesn't stir, who's making you talk?" She shouted. He said: "After a thousand shouts and ten thousand shouts, then what?" She was stuck. He drove her out with blows.

=== Tianyin Yuanxiu ===
E1: Pumen came with his assembly to visit the master. During tea, Pumen said: "Why aren't you drinking tea?" The master said: "Drink." Pumen said: "You don't have any." The master held up his tea bowl and showed it. Pumen said: "That's mine." The master splashed the tea right in his face and said: "Is it yours? Or is it mine?" Pumen had no words. After the meal, Pumen said: "People in the world are like someone flying a kite -- when the wind is too strong, you shouldn't let it out." The master said: "Not so." Pumen said: "Why not so?" The master said: "Suppose you have already let it up when the wind is strong -- what then?" Pumen said: "It's done for." The master said: "Also not so." Pumen said: "Why not?" The master said: "Why don't you say 'reel in the string'?" Pumen again had no words.
E2: A newly ordained nun came to the master. He asked: "Why did you leave home to become a nun?" She said: "For my own sake." The master said: "For your own sake -- then why did you abandon your husband?" She said: "A shadow in the clouds." The master threw both hands behind his back and said: "Say more." She said: "Mind does not think, thought does not stir." The master said: "If mind doesn't think and thought doesn't stir, who made you say that?" The nun gave a shout. The master said: "After a thousand shouts, ten thousand shouts -- what then?" The nun was at a loss. The master drove her out.

=== TIANYIXIANG ===
E1: Tianyixiang entered monastic life at age three. After traveling widely and impressing all he met, he arrived at Furong Mountain and presented himself to Master Gumei. He followed Gumei to Nanjing, where he sealed himself in solitary retreat for over seven hundred days. One day, he burst out laughing, smashed open the barrier, and shoved Master Gumei to the ground. Gumei rose up delighted and said: "My work is now nearly done -- truly, one such as you is enough."
E2: On New Year's Day, a monk came forward. The Master immediately struck him. The monk said: "Is this the new year's decree?" The Master said: "Yesterday you received a beating -- was that you?" The monk said: "Yes." The Master said: "Come back tomorrow for another round." The monk said: "All the world sings of the new year, but on this platform the old family style never changes." The Master threw down his staff and said: "New year, new decree -- one blow, one welt; one slap, one mark. But even so, you still need me to strip off your skull before you're done. Why? Lacquer cracks from its own hardness; oil burns from its own brightness."

=== Tianzeneng ===
E1: Addressing the assembly, the Master held up his staff: "The staff has swallowed the mountains, rivers, and the great earth. All of you -- right now, where do you plant your feet to sustain your lives?" No one answered. He struck the staff: "You may cry until blood flows, but it serves no purpose. Better to seal your lips and see out the last of spring."
E2: Ascending the hall. A monk stepped forward. The Master said: "Already a great mistake." He descended from the seat.

=== Tie Mei 'Three Slaps' ===
E1: Chan Master Poshan was passing through Jixiang Hermitage. The Master came out of the abbot's quarters and found Poshan drinking wine. Poshan said: "Do you dare come?" the Master responded: "In the ocean treasury of a thousand treasures, each takes what pleases them." Poshan said: "What do you call treasure?" The Master gave him a slap. Poshan said: "Try hitting me two more times." the Master answered: "I have slaps, but I don't waste them on dull flesh." Poshan held up a finger: "Is this finger the same or different from your slap?" The Master said: "A pear tree in bloom, leaning against a whitewashed wall."
E2: Scholar Yang said: "Disciple has emptied all matters and come specially to visit the Master." The Master said: "Will you go home?" Yang said: "Yes." said the Master: "What emptiness is there then?"

=== Tiebiji ===
E1: A monk came out and said: "Stomp through the plum-tip moon, no need to talk of fire refining cinnabar." The Master said: "Hit the wooden bell." The monk continued: "Stomped right through it!" The Master said: "Hit the wooden bell." The monk returned to the assembly. The Master said: "Hit the wooden bell." Then: "The new wooden bell of Juyun -- strike it and it rings clear. A thousand sages all cover their ears; snow and fire in one furnace, glowing red."
E2: A monk asked: "Zhaozhou said: 'The word "Buddha" -- I don't like hearing it.' What is the meaning of this?" The Master said: "The word 'Zhaozhou' -- I don't like hearing it."

=== Tizongning of Yunfeng ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the first meaning of the supreme truth?" The Master struck him. The monk burst out laughing. The Master struck him again.
E2: The Master entered the hall. He happened to find the monks warming themselves by the fire. The Master said: "Warming by the great fire, investigating the great Chan -- I wonder how many have grasped the great meaning?" None of the assembly spoke. The Master held up the fire poker and said: "All day long, bustling and noisy. All night long, bustling and noisy. A great brilliant light -- and you miss it right before your face."

=== Tongan Guanzhi ===
E1: A monk asks about hitting the mark (in the archery metaphor). Tong'an responds: "What kind of person is the lord within the passes?" The commentary notes: "Even so, Tong'an did not mean well."
E2: Tong'an Cha (likely Guanzhi) said: "The wondrous body originally has no place. Through the whole body there is no further trace or cause." Also: "Before the dead-tree cliff there are many branching roads."

=== Tongzhen of Wanfeng ===
E1: A monk asked: "Before the furnace opens, cold light is desolate and still. Once the hammer and tongs are set in motion, fierce flames blaze. Where is the error?" the Master replied: "Do you hear the sound of flowing water?" "What about the one who arrives without taking the secondary path -- how do you forge such a person?" "Half is autumn, half is wind." The monk said: "Then I will sever and hold the vital crossing -- no needle can penetrate!" The Master struck him. The monk shouted. The Master struck again.
E2: At a night discourse, the Master gave three shouts and said: "Long ago, Old Man Linji used four shouts to establish Huangbo's teaching. I am his distant grandson, and here I establish Linji's teaching with only three. If under these three shouts you can grasp it, you will know that in the original text not a single thing remains extra. If you cannot, I must wade through mud and tangle in vines, rehashing old cases."

=== Touzi Datong ===
E1: Zhaozhou meets Touzi on the road: "Could you be the hermitage master of Touzi?" Touzi says, "Tea overseer, give me one coin in alms." Zhaozhou goes up the mountain first. Touzi carries an oil bottle and comes after. Zhaozhou says, "I long heard of Touzi, but on arriving I see only an old oil seller." Touzi says, "You only see the oil seller, and do not yet know Touzi." Zhaozhou says, "What is Touzi?" Touzi lifts the oil bottle and says, "Oil, oil." Later, Zhaozhou asks the real question: "When a person greatly dead comes back to life, how is it?" Touzi says, "Night travel is not allowed; you must arrive at dawn."
E2: Touzi first visits Cuiwei and asks, "The hidden meaning of coming from the West -- Master, how is it shown to people?" Cuiwei pauses and looks at him. Touzi begs again. Cuiwei says, "Do you want a second ladle of foul water too?" Touzi suddenly awakens. Cuiwei says, "Do not fall away." Touzi says, "When the time comes, root and sprout of themselves grow."

=== Touzi Yiqing ===
E1: At the opening ceremony, a monk asked: "Whose song does the Master sing? Whose lineage does the wind carry?" The Master said, "One arrow from before the age of Awesome Sound -- it pierces two layers of mountains." The monk pressed: "What is the matter that was transmitted?" The Master said, "It is entirely due to the Huai region's moon that the spring of Ying-yang is illuminated." The monk said, "In that case, entering the water one sees the tall person." The Master said, "One only knows that the jade of Jing is extraordinary -- who can discern the heart of the King of Chu?" The attendant struck the seat once with the whisk. Another monk asked: "Yesterday I left Shuzhou's Taiping; today I've arrived at White Cloud Sea Assembly. What is the Immovable Honored One?" The Master said, "White clouds come and go beyond the green mountains; pines on the ridge stand tall, bearing the moon." The monk said, "Then without leaving this place, one arrives everywhere." The Master said, "Don't ask about the road before the mountain gate -- where the lone gibbon cries, it goes deep." The monk bowed. The Master breathed a single "hush."
E2: Touzi Yiqing arrived at Qixian Monastery under Yuantong Xiu. He made no effort to ask questions or practice, but only slept all day. The duty monk reported to Yuantong, saying, "There is a monk in the hall who sleeps all day. The rules should be applied." Yuantong said, "Who is it?" The monk said, "The senior student Qing." Yuantong said, "Not yet. Wait until I test him." Yuantong then dragged his staff into the hall and found Yiqing sleeping. He struck the bed and scolded, "I don't have idle rice here to feed you so you can eat your fill and sleep." Yiqing said, "What would the Master have me do?" Yuantong said, "Why don't you go practice Chan?" Yiqing said, "Fine food is not fit for a man who is already full." Yuantong said, "But plenty of people do not approve of you." Yiqing said, "Even if they approved, what good would it do?" Yuantong said, "Whom have you seen in your travels?" Yiqing said, "Fushan." Yuantong said, "No wonder you are so impossibly stubborn." They clasped hands, laughed together, and went back to the abbot's quarters. From then on, Yiqing's fame in the Way spread far and wide.

=== Tui'an ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is 'taking away the person but not the environment'?" The Master said: "The path is remote -- wanderers cease; the forest is deep -- moonlight lingers." The monk pressed: "What is 'taking away the environment but not the person'?" the Master answered: "Cut away the idle weeds and trees; underfoot, nothing is private." The monk pressed: "What is 'both person and environment taken away'?" the Master answered: "No trace of carriage or horse remains; how could host and guest be established?" The monk pressed: "What is 'neither person nor environment taken away'?" The Master said: "The guest arrives showing his old face; flowers fall, and new branches grow." The monk pressed: "Person and environment have been shown by the Master's kindness. What about the matter of the supreme vehicle?" The Master struck him.
E2: At a small gathering the Master said: "No need for 'how about this' or 'what about that' -- just enter straight with a single blade. Anyone? Anyone?" A monk stepped forward. The Master struck him across the back. The monk said: "I haven't even asked my question yet -- why do you strike me?" The Master said: "You lacquer bucket -- you can't even recognize the topic!" The monk shouted. The Master struck again. Another monk came forward; the Master also struck him: "Tell me -- is this stick a reward or a punishment?" The monk tried to speak; the Master struck again. Yet another monk came forward; the Master struck: "What bowl are you begging for?" The monk was silent; the Master struck again. Then the Master said: "If you were a sharp fellow, you'd know the head from the tail and stop right there. Why require the teacher to add salt and vinegar?"

=== Wanfeng Shiwei ===
E1: One day two monks came to visit. The master asked, "Where do you come from?" The first monk said, "From Longxi." The master said, "I've heard that in Longxi there are parrots. Is that so?" "Yes." "Can they compose poems and write verses?" "They can." "What poem do they recite? Try saying one." The monk had no reply. The master struck him with a blow and said, "Liar! You didn't come from Longxi at all." Then the master turned to the second monk: "Now you try." The second monk made a dancing gesture. The master said, "That's all very well -- but what about 'Big-man Qiu, Yi, Ji'?"
E2: The master raised the old case: "Zhaozhou went to visit a hermit and asked, 'Is anyone home? Is anyone home?' The hermit raised his fist. Zhaozhou said, 'The water is too shallow to moor a boat here,' and left. He went on to another hermit and asked the same: 'Is anyone home? Is anyone home?' This hermit also raised his fist. Zhaozhou said, 'Able to release, able to seize; able to kill, able to give life.' And he bowed." The master commented: "Zhaozhou split open an ancient mirror and made both sides perfectly clear. Students who can't tell good from bad are simply baffled. Both hermits raised a fist -- yet Zhaozhou bowed to one and dismissed the other. Wouldn't you say Zhaozhou lost one of his eyes? Even so -- why did he approve one and not the other?" Then the verse: "Zhaozhou digs deep pits right in the road, demanding that travelers measure for themselves. Break through the double barrier and there's no separate path -- every single thing, everywhere, is home."

=== Wanru ===
E1: Wanru had been stuck for years after his first interview with Miyun left him "drenched in cold sweat." One day walking in town, he heard someone beating a child and shouting: "Let's see where you hide!" Instantly enlightened, he composed on the spot: "Nowhere to hide, nowhere to hide -- the whole body stands exposed on the open street! How laughable, that Huating ferry-man -- all his entangling vines were just beating around the bush."
E2: Wanru explains his method: "I only have one staff. Those who haven't entered, I give them a beating to help them enter. Those who have entered, I give them a beating to drive them out of their nest. Those who have left their nest -- I also give them a beating." Then adds: "The first two beatings, everyone understands. The third beating -- even veteran practitioners of many years don't know where it lands." He strikes his staff on the ground and steps down.

=== Wansong Xingxiu ===
E1: Wansong raised the case: "A man hangs from a tree by his teeth. Hands can't grasp, feet can't touch. Below, someone asks the Patriarch's meaning. If he doesn't answer, he fails. If he answers, he dies. What does he do?" Tiger-Head Zhao said: "I don't ask about being up in the tree. Before climbing, please speak, Master." Xiangyan burst out laughing. Xuedou commented: "Speaking up in the tree is easy; speaking below is hard." Wansong added: "If I were Tiger-Head, the moment Xiangyan posed his question, I'd just burst out laughing myself. Let's see how thick his face is."
E2: Wansong raised the case: Wolun's verse: "Wolun has a technique: he can cut off all thoughts. Facing objects, mind doesn't arise. Bodhi grows daily." The Sixth Patriarch responded: "Huineng has no technique, doesn't cut off thoughts. Facing objects, mind arises repeatedly. How could bodhi grow?" Wansong then told an anecdote: a Quanzhen Daoist came saying he'd spent thirty years trying to subdue deluded thoughts. Wansong posed four questions: (1) How long have deluded thoughts existed? (2) Were there originally deluded thoughts? (3) How do you cut off deluded thoughts? (4) Is cutting them off right, or is not cutting them off right? The Daoist bowed and never came back.

=== WEILIN DAOPEI ===
E1: In his first dharma talk after receiving transmission, Daopei said: "This matter -- the three Buddhas of past, present, and future enter it through no gate. The entire Buddhist canon cannot express it. Even Yunmen, Caoshan, Linji, and Deshan arriving here can only clasp their hands in surrender and fall behind. Suppose there is a fellow who, hearing me speak thus, immediately halts his monkey-mind and reins in his horse-intent, releases his grip at the edge of a ten-thousand-foot cliff, lets his life-root snap clean through, lets not a trace of breath remain. Then, reviving, he leaps through empty space, takes a single blade of grass and uses it as the sixteen-foot golden body, takes the sixteen-foot golden body and uses it as a single blade of grass, stirs the Milky Way into butter, transforms the whole earth into gold -- freeing everyone under heaven from their bonds, relieving the hungry, aiding the destitute, all with ample energy to spare. Such a one does not betray the original purpose of leaving home. Is there such a person? If so, the Dharma has an heir. If not, I must splash a second ladle of foul water." He raised the whisk and called to the assembly: "Just this -- don't you see it?" He struck the desk once. "Don't you hear it? Since you both see and hear -- what ultimately is it? Bah! And what more is there to say?"
E2: In a tea gathering, Daopei said: "No need to practice Chan. No need to study the Dharma. Just recognize these two words -- birth and death -- and a lifetime of study is complete. My teacher Boshan used to instruct people to look into: 'Where does birth come from? Where does death go?' If you truly discern where birth comes from and where death goes, what else remains? Even so, there are three things that must be said plainly: When drinking tea, don't get your tongue wet. When biting fruit, don't let it touch your teeth. When returning to your room, don't bump into the pillar. If anyone can pass through these three, tomorrow I'll set a special tea to welcome them. If you cannot pass through -- the daylight is already fading. You'd better lace up your straw sandals tight."

=== Weishan Lingyou ===
E1: One day, Baizhang asked Lingyou, who was standing beside him, "Who is it?" Lingyou said, "It is me." Baizhang said, "Poke in the stove and see if there is any fire." Lingyou poked around and said, "There is no fire." Baizhang rose from his seat, reached deep into the ashes, and picked out a small ember. Holding it up, he said, "You said there was none -- what is this?" At that moment, Lingyou was awakened. He bowed and described his understanding. Baizhang said, "This is merely a fork in the road. The sutra says: 'To know buddha-nature, observe causes and conditions in their proper time.' When the time arrives, it is like suddenly waking from confusion, like suddenly remembering what was forgotten -- only then do you realize that what you possess was never obtained from another." The next day, when they went together into the mountains to work, Baizhang said, "Did you bring the fire?" Lingyou said, "I brought it." Baizhang said, "Where is it?" Lingyou picked up a branch, blew on it twice, and handed it to Baizhang. Baizhang said, "Like an insect boring into wood."
E2: Deshan came to call on Weishan. Carrying his travel bundle, he walked across the dharma hall from west to east and then from east to west, looked toward the abbot's room and said, "Is there anything? Is there anything?" Weishan was sitting and paid him no attention. Deshan said, "Nothing! Nothing!" and walked out. But at the gate he stopped and said, "Even so, I must not be careless." He put on his full ceremonial robes, re-entered, and as soon as he crossed the threshold, held up his sitting cloth and said, "Master!" Weishan reached for his whisk. Deshan gave a shout, flapped his sleeves, and walked out. That evening Weishan asked the head monk, "Is the newcomer still here?" The head monk said, "At that time he turned his back on the dharma hall, put on his straw sandals, and left." Weishan said, "That fellow will one day go to a solitary peak, build a grass hut, and rail against the buddhas and curse the patriarchs."

=== Wenmunian ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall and raised this: "Puhua would enter the marketplace shaking his bell and calling out: 'If you come in brightness, I strike in brightness. If you come in darkness, I strike in darkness. If you come from all four directions and eight faces, I strike like a whirlwind. If you come from empty space, I strike with a flailing blow.' One day Linji sent a monk to seize him. The monk said: 'What if none of these apply?' Puhua pushed him away and said: 'Tomorrow there is a feast at Dabei temple.' The monk returned and told Linji. Linji said: 'I have always had my doubts about that fellow.'" the Master responded: "Puhua's samadhi -- Linji did not know it. If Linji had known, he would not have resorted to an ambush arrow. Linji's samadhi -- Puhua did not know it. If Puhua had known, would he have hidden in Dabei temple? When Shuanglin renders judgment, neither elder's samadhi is understood. If Shuanglin understood, where would Puhua or Linji be? Furthermore: 'This fellow Puhua, madly dashing about, thought he had some great marvel. One light push and his donkey-legs were exposed.'"
E2: The Master ascended the hall and raised this: "Master Hai of Yuelu was asked by a monk: 'What about taking three steps forward?' Yuelu said: 'You bang your head and stub your toes.' 'What about retreating three steps?' 'You fall into pits and ditches.' 'What about neither advancing nor retreating?' 'A dead man standing.'" The Master said: "Toss him a wooden peach, get back a jade gem -- that is how it should be. But he was too ruthlessly cold. At Shuanglin it is different. 'What about three steps forward?' 'Cannot be mixed up.' 'Three steps back?' 'Cannot be lumped together.' 'Neither advancing nor retreating?' 'When the heirs are capable, those inside the room don't even know it.'"

=== Wenyi ===
E1: When Wenyi was traveling, he stopped at the monastery of Dizang (Luohan Guichen) because of snow. As they sat by the fire, Dizang asked where he was going. Wenyi said, "Just wandering on pilgrimage." Dizang said, "What is this business of pilgrimage?" Wenyi said, "I don't know." Dizang said, "Not-knowing is most intimate." Later, when Wenyi and his companions were about to leave, Dizang saw them off at the gate and asked, "You always say 'the three realms are mind-only' and 'the ten thousand dharmas are consciousness-only.'" He pointed to a stone in the courtyard and said, "Tell me -- is this stone inside your mind or outside your mind?" Wenyi said, "Inside my mind." Dizang said, "What kind of pilgrim puts a stone inside his head?" Wenyi was stumped and could not reply. He put down his pack and stayed, seeking resolution. For over a month, every day he presented his understanding and offered explanations. Each time Dizang said, "The Buddha-dharma is not like that." Finally Wenyi said, "I have exhausted all my words and reasoning." Dizang said, "If we are talking about the Buddha-dharma, everything is fully present right here." At these words, Wenyi was greatly awakened.
E2: A monk asked, "I won't ask about the finger -- what is the moon?" Wenyi said, "Which is the finger you are not asking about?" Another monk asked, "I won't ask about the moon -- what is the finger?" Wenyi said, "The moon." The monk said, "I asked about the finger -- why does the Master answer 'the moon'?" Wenyi said, "Because you asked about the finger."

=== Wu Yi of Boshan ===
E1: When Wu Yi was living in seclusion at Heshan, the Master was returning from Shigu. He passed through Jianzhou and met Yuanxian at the Guangxiao Temple. The Master said: "Have you swept Shouchang's memorial stupa yet?" Yuanxian said: "I never fail to sweep it, but I don't let anyone know." The Master said: "So you've been sweeping it on the sly!" Yuanxian said: "That's all I can manage. How about you, Master?" The Master said: "I never fail to sweep it, but I've never once moved." Yuanxian said: "Then it seems you haven't swept it at all." They both laughed and parted.
E2: Ascending the hall: "Winter isn't cold -- wait till after the twelfth month! The old man doesn't love snow, and the child weeps for a thin coat. But in the East Village there's this one utterly shameless fellow -- matted hair, filthy face, bare hands and empty fists. In the cold he doesn't fear cold; in the heat he doesn't fear heat. At the coldest moment he sings a little snow song; at the hungriest moment he plays the grain merchant. Without a single coin he wants to compete in wealth with all under heaven. Without a trace of beauty he wants to rival the whole earth in charm. Sometimes at the crossroads he rides an iron horse backwards; sometimes on the great Western sea he climbs Mount Sumeru in reverse; sometimes in roaring flames he chews ice and gnaws snow; sometimes amid red dust he plucks grass and trims lamp wicks; sometimes he points east and talks west; sometimes he calls south 'north.' He takes the three-vehicle dharma trenches as his garden walls, and points to the bodhisattvas of the ten stages as his household retainers. Brothers! Should you keep company with this man or not?" Then he laughed and said: "Too late -- Boshan has already taken him in!"

=== Wu'an Puning ===
E1: When an old friend arrived, Wu'an ascended the hall and said: "The stringless lute -- its meaning runs deep. A fresh and pointed melody requires a true listener." Then he laid the staff across his lap and mimed playing a lute, asking: "Do you understand? High mountain, flowing water -- limitless meaning. Sheer cliffs dropping away ten thousand fathoms."
E2: Ascending the hall, Wu'an said: "Cold Food, Qingming Festival -- every household goes to sweep the graves. The wooden man sighs in vain. The stone woman sheds twin streams of tears. Only the man of the Way beneath the forest, beyond all study and free of contrivance, knowing nothing upon nothing -- takes up the noseless flute of Shaolin and blows it first against the wind, then with the wind. What a fine fellow!"

=== WUCHU DAGUAN ===
E1: Ascending the hall, Wuchu cited: A monk asked Zhaozhou, "Two dragons contend for a pearl -- who gets it?" Zhaozhou said, "This old monk just watches." Wuchu commented: "Old Zhaozhou only knew how to steer against the wind -- he could not yet sail with it."
E2: A monk asked Baofu, "When a poor household is robbed, what then?" Baofu said, "They cannot take everything." "Why not?" "The thief is a family member." "If a family member, why turn thief?" "Inside there is no response, so outside nothing can be done." "What if the thief is caught?" "Inside and outside -- all messages cease." "After the catch, where does the merit go?" "Reward has never been heard of." "Then it was labor without merit?" "Merit is not absent, but once accomplished, one does not dwell in it." "If merit was accomplished, why not dwell?" "Haven't you heard: 'It is the general who brings about the peace, but the general is not permitted to see the peace'?" Wuchu commented: "If Baofu had not known the thief's condition intimately, how could he have investigated the case so clearly? Only at the very end, his hands and feet showed a bit too much."

=== Wufeng ===
E1: Baizhang asked Wufeng: "Seal up your throat and lips -- how will you speak?" Wufeng said, "The master must seal it up too." Baizhang said, "In a place with no one, I break my brow and look to you."
E2: Wufeng Changguan asked a monk, "Do you see the ox?" The monk said, "I see it." Wufeng said, "Do you see the left horn, or the right horn?" The monk had no reply. Wufeng answered on his behalf: "Seeing without left or right." Yangshan offered an alternative reply: "Can you even distinguish left from right?"

=== Wufengxue ===
E1: A monk came up with his hands behind his back, gazed intently at the Master, and announced: "Before I even stepped through the gate, I already had a question for you." The Master instantly grabbed him by the collar: "Speak! Quick!" The monk tried to formulate words. The Master shoved him aside: "Get to the kitchen, rice-slave."
E2: A monk asked: "What is Buddha?" the Master replied: "You are a donkey." The monk pressed: "What is the meaning of this?" The Master picked up a brush and said: "This one came from Huzhou."

=== Wuhuan ===
E1: Wuhuan asks the assembly: "The ancients who said 'rest and cease' only created a special kind of worry. Those who said 'one thought spans ten thousand years' -- just a dead skull with no living maggots. Is there anyone here who is a tiger in the crowded market?" A monk suddenly leaps forward. Wuhuan immediately walks out. The monk chases him: "Master, what did you say?" Wuhuan replies: "The crow just went into a cloth bag."
E2: A monk asks Wuhuan to demonstrate the four "taking away" positions of Linji. "Taking away the person but not the environment?" -- Wuhuan opens his hand in a beckoning gesture. "Taking away the environment but not the person?" -- he makes a grasping, gathering motion. "Both person and environment taken away?" -- he tucks his hands into his sleeves. "Neither taken away?" -- he throws open his arms and walks away.

=== Wujian Xiandu ===
E1: Addressing the assembly, Wujian said: "If we speak of this matter, the Buddhas of three ages and the entire canon cannot annotate it; all the old masters under heaven cannot raise it up. Even if you had eloquence that could drain a lake or momentum that could topple a mountain, not a single point of it could be applied." He continued: "Good people, when hungry you eat, when tired you sleep, when hot you seek shade, when cold you warm by the fire -- each of these is perfectly natural, each perfectly luminous. Why do you stride forward to discuss Zen and discuss the Way, mistaking fish-eyes for pearls?" Then he raised the old case of Layman Pang asking Mazu: "Who is the one not companion to the ten thousand things?" Mazu replied: "Wait until you can swallow the entire West River in one gulp, then I will tell you." The Layman had an awakening. Wujian's verse: "Swallow the West River in one gulp -- a partridge cries deep among the flowers. Even if you accept it right there on the spot, you are still a hundred thousand miles from the white clouds."
E2: In a dharma talk to a physician-layman, Wujian said: "The Buddha was the great physician king for all beings. The entire canon of over five thousand scrolls is nothing but prescriptions for the world. You would think that matching medicine to illness would work, but in fact too much medicine makes the illness worse. Later patriarchs, unable to remove the root of disease, piled moxa upon old scars. Some said 'point directly to the human mind, see your nature and become Buddha.' Some gave a shout the moment you hesitated, or struck you the moment you opened your mouth. If the medicine is digested it becomes sweet dew; if not, it becomes poison. When the illness departs but the medicine remains -- that too is illness."

=== Wumen Huikai ===
E1: Wumen addressed the assembly: "In my former master's assembly I simply looked at the single word 'Wu' for six years, unable to give a turning-word. I made a fierce vow: if I do not clarify this matter, may my body rot away. Whenever drowsiness came, I went to the corridor and knocked my head against a pillar. One day, standing beside the Dharma-seat, I suddenly heard the meal drum and understood. The next day in the interview room, my master took one look and said, 'You have been seeing gods and ghosts!' He gave a thundering shout. I shouted back. He shouted again. I shouted again. From then on, my thrust never yielded to his." Wumen's enlightenment verse: "A thunderclap under a clear blue sky -- all beings on the great earth open their eyes. Every thing in the ten thousand forms bows its head. Mount Sumeru leaps up and dances."
E2: Wumen took leave of the Chancellor and the court officials. The Chancellor asked, "What day will you go?" Wumen answered, "Before Buddha's birthday." On the first of the fourth month he ordered workers to build his tomb. On the sixth, at evening, he asked the mason, "Is the work finished?" The mason said, "It is done; tomorrow morning the Master may come and see the tomb." The next morning Wumen inspected the tomb, returned to the abbot's room, called for paper, and wrote his farewell verse: "Emptiness is not born, emptiness does not perish. If you realize emptiness, emptiness is no different from you." Having written the verse, he sat in full lotus and passed away.

=== Wuming Huijing ===
E1: In a small gathering, Huijing said: "Students of the Way whose Dharma-eye is not yet clear should simply watch their inquiry-word. Establish an iron will. Like a single man facing ten thousand enemies -- settle your intention and fight your way out. Be utterly intent, thought after thought. Never mind what color, never mind what sound. Enemies? Pay them no mind. Family? Pay them no mind. Buddha? Pay him no mind. The ordinary? Pay it no mind. This is not neglect -- it is that a deadly adversary stands before you. To protect life, you must kill. Kill completely, and only then can you dwell in peace. Though it sounds difficult, it is actually the most effortless thing. No need to chant sutras, no need to bow to Buddha, no need to sit in dhyana, no need to travel on pilgrimage, no need to study literature, no need to seek commentaries, no need to evaluate koans, no need to take precepts, no need for ascetic practice, no need to seek comfort. In every situation, only see the inquiry-word bright and clear. See nothing else. Then suddenly, in a flash -- like the sun rising into open sky, shining everywhere in all ten directions -- the whole great earth becomes the inquiry-word. This is what is called 'smashing open the great barrier gate and entering the gate of liberation.' At such a moment, you first have the power to speak. Only then may you meet others with the testing-pole in hand, attaining great freedom, beyond all snares."
E2: The master's verse on the classic case: "Nanquan was making trouble; Zhaozhou aided the evil. They dragged later people into it, bound with ropes and chains. Only the cat itself ascended to the highest paradise."

=== Wuming Huixing ===
E1: Wuming raised the verse of Hanshan: "My mind is like the autumn moon, the jade-green pool clear and bright. Nothing can compare with it -- how can I explain?" Wuming said: "Hanshan was sitting in the deep pit of liberation. In the school of Beishan, we'd smash your head open for that."
E2: Wuming said: "Before the fifteenth, 'one winter, two winters, hands folded before the chest.' After the fifteenth, 'draw the golden arrowhead behind your back, turn your body and pull the horn-bow.' Right on the fifteenth day, what then? Wind follows the tiger, clouds follow the dragon -- raise your eyes, and a falcon crosses over to Liaodong."

=== Wuming of Shouchang ===
E1: Wuming quotes Laozi: "The Great Way is formless, it gives birth to heaven and earth; nameless, it nourishes all things; I don't know its name, so I force-call it 'the Way.'" Then snaps his fingers and says: "Not so! THIS THING has form and gives birth to heaven and earth. THIS THING has feeling and drives the sun and moon. I DO know its name -- its name is THIS." Then warns: if even this collapses into wordplay, "have the Rector chase everyone out the gate with his staff -- spare us the thinking and discriminating."
E2: While the assembly prostrates, the lamp suddenly crashes to the ground. The Head Monk scrambles to frame it poetically: "The silver lamp tumbles to earth scattering heavenly flowers! We humbly beg you to relight the precious torch..." Wuming calmly replies: "The golden censer trails fragrant wisps, the jade candle radiates brilliance, the jeweled chime rings clear -- this is the assembly of humans and gods. All this has already finished preaching the Dharma for me. Why? The Dharma is inherently its own Dharma; beyond the Dharma, what Dharma is there? To try to preach more would insult the great Dharma."

=== Wuqu ===
E1: Wuqu distributes rice cakes and announces everyone must deliver a Zen saying incorporating the word "round" to earn one. The whole assembly tries and fails. His student Xingchong says: "If that's how it is, I'm definitely not getting a cake." Wuqu asks: "What do you mean?" Xingchong replies: "Just hand one over." Wuqu laughs: "Can't refuse that one!" -- and gives him the cake. The only person who stopped performing gets fed.
E2: Wuqu finds Feng Ziran in Hangzhou mending his robe and asks: "Are you patching that thing against cold, or against heat?" Feng just looks up silently. Wuqu bows. Feng says: "Bring tea." Wuqu dances out of the room. The whole exchange -- question, silent glance, bow, tea order, dance -- unfolds as a flawless meeting of equals without a single conceptual word.

=== WUSHAN JINGDUAN ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master said: "Maitreya, the true Maitreya, divides his body into a thousand hundred million. At all times he shows himself to the people of this time, yet the people of this time do not recognize him. Is there anyone in the assembly who recognizes him? Speak up and share the news." After a long silence: "Why doesn't the assembly recognize him? Only because he is too close to living beings, who have long been turning in birth and death. They use it daily without knowing, never having ascended to true awakening, always dwelling in the dream-land. An ancient said: 'Last night I had a dream -- I dreamed of a ball of emptiness. This morning I tried to tell the dream, but when I raised my head I saw emptiness again. Is the emptiness the dream? Or is the dream the emptiness? I reckon that within this floating life, we are still in the midst of this dream.' That was the ancient's dream. This mountain monk also had a dream last night, different from the ancient's. I dreamed the local earth god came and said to me: 'Tomorrow the Prefect and the officials will enter the mountain and invite the Master to preside over Shousheng Monastery. But since you have never gone on pilgrimage, how can you be an abbot?' I said to the earth god: 'Studying the teachings does not depend on wide learning; practicing Chan does not require traveling far. If it is a true lion cub, from the moment it is born it can give a great roar.' The earth god asked: 'What is a lion cub?' Have you not heard Yongjia say: 'The lion cub, with the pack following behind -- at three years old it already gives a great roar. If a jackal pursues the Dharma King, a hundred years of demon craft opens its mouth in vain.' How marvelous! How marvelous! Laughing at myself -- the lion cub of Wushan! For years lying in the deep forest. Today, slowly stepping out through the cliff gate. Baring claws, displaying its awesome power, both eyes blazing and shooting forth light. The blue-eyed barbarian monk from the West still wouldn't recognize it -- how could the earth god or the mountain monk know? In the dream, this mountain monk struck the earth god once with his staff, and the earth god suddenly vanished."
E2: One day the Master visited Chancellor Zhang's residence. The Chancellor invited him to stay for a meal and served him lamb-filled dumplings. After the Master ate them all, the Chancellor said he had been tricked. The Master said: "I always said they tasted good -- what beast bumped into me!" He then left a verse: "In drought years when prayers bring rain, high mountains make fine fields for planting. If eating vegetables could make you a Buddha, then donkeys and horses would be born in heaven too."

=== Wuwen Daocan ===
E1: Taking his seat in the abbot's quarters for the first time at Jianfu Monastery, Wuwen said: "Today I open the gates of hell. I invite all beings across the great earth to create hell-karma and realize hell-fruit. If a single person attains Buddhahood, I vow never to achieve perfect awakening."
E2: Wuwen said: "Autumn deepens, the nights grow long, the dew is cold, the moon bright. The bell sounds -- short ones short, long ones long. The insect voices -- large ones large, small ones small. Hearing all this, I tossed and turned, unable to sleep until dawn. Why? One fragment of the patriarchs' heart -- the wreckage, who knows how much?"

=== Wuwen Mingcong ===
E1: Mingcong was from Shaobu. He had his hair shaved at Hidden Hermitage. One day he heard a horse whinny and was thoroughly awakened. He went to call on Tianqi Benrui. Tianqi asked: "Being in the world yet forgetting the world -- how is this?" "To grasp things as non-things." "Being in thought yet forgetting thought -- how is this?" "Within mind, no mind." "When both mind and things are utterly forgotten -- then what?" "Mount Hua rises sheer, Taihang Mountain towers." Tianqi said: "Ruining every decent man and woman in the family -- only you could do it!" He then gave the transmission verse: "Smashing feelings till feelings shatter and shatter again into feeling; cutting tracks till nothing private remains, essence within essence..."
E2: Wuwen Mingcong went to see Tianqi Benrui. As he entered the gate, he encountered Tianqi coming out. Mingcong said, "One going out, one coming in -- are they the same or different?" Tianqi said, "Same and different aside, who is the one that sees coming and going?" Mingcong stood silent for a long while. Tianqi cursed him angrily and walked away. That night, Tianqi returned and asked the guest prefect, "Is the monk I scolded today still here?" The prefect said, "He is." Tianqi dragged his staff to the guest quarters. Mingcong bowed. Tianqi struck him. Mingcong said, "Just now I clumsily offended the Master." Tianqi said, "Today the old monk has been seen through by you." He then asked, "What is it to be in the world yet forget the world?" Mingcong said, "To comprehend things as non-things." Tianqi said, "What is it to be in thought yet forget thought?" Mingcong said, "In mind, there is no mind." Tianqi said, "When both mind and things are forgotten, what then?" Mingcong said, "Mount Hua towers loftily, the Taihang range soars high." Tianqi said, "The one who corrupts the sons and daughters of other families -- that is you alone."

=== Wuxie Lingmo ===
E1: Wuxie visits Shitou, agreeing beforehand: if one word matches, he will stay; otherwise he will leave. Shitou sits on his seat. Wuxie flicks his sleeves and goes out. Shitou, knowing he was a vessel of Dharma, calls out: "Venerable!" Wuxie turns his head. Shitou says: "From birth to death, it is just this. Turning the head, turning the brain -- what more do you seek?" Wuxie has a great awakening at these words.
E2: After his awakening under Shitou, Wuxie Lingmo settled first at the Baisha retreat, then at Mount Wuxie. A monk asked, "What thing is greater than heaven and earth?" Lingmo said, "No one can recognize it." The monk asked, "Can it still be carved and polished?" Lingmo said, "Try putting your hand to it yourself." Another monk asked, "In this school, what is the matter from beginning to end?" Lingmo said, "How long has this very thing before your eyes been in the making?" The monk said, "I don't understand." Lingmo said, "What I have here is not what you are asking about." The monk said, "Doesn't the Master have some way of receiving people?" Lingmo said, "When you seek to be received, I will receive you." The monk said, "Then please receive me right now." Lingmo said, "What is it that you lack?"

=== Wuyi Yuanlai ===
E1: A monk asked: "The whole of the ten directions is a single staff." The master laughed and said: "The whole of the ten directions is a single staff." He patted the chair and said: "Then my chair is also your staff." The monk said: "Yes." The master said: "When I am sitting on it, what do you do?" The monk was about to open his mouth when the master gave a great shout. The monk hesitated. The master said: "Heavens!"
E2: A layman named Wan asked: "My surname is Wan (Ten Thousand). What was my surname before my parents gave birth to me?" The master said: "I cannot say it here." The layman bowed. The master said: "Tell me -- have I answered you or not?" The layman said: "I don't understand." The master said: "Not understanding -- is your surname still Wan?"

=== Wuzhun Shifan ===
E1: Wuzhun pointed at the Dharma seat: "The Buddhas of the three times take this seat and fully reveal the True Seal. The Patriarchs of every generation take this seat and tell great lies. What should be done today? Many empty words are not as good as a few true ones." He ascended and, after the ceremonial mallet, said: "The meaning of the First Principle has been shattered by a single blow of the mallet. Is there anyone who won't accept this?" A monk asked about the founding of the hall. Wuzhun answered: "Heaven endures, earth persists." The monk pressed: "Take up the holeless flute of Shaolin and play the song of ten thousand years into the wind." Wuzhun said: "Xu You never had to wash his ears."
E2: After years of study, Wuzhun went to serve under Master Poan at Xihua Xiufeng. There were only about a dozen monks in the hall, all seasoned practitioners. One named Chun Dian ("Crazy Chun") was fiercely combative during private interviews, refusing to yield on any point. Poan beat him all the way to the Dharma Hall and was about to expel him. Wuzhun intervened: "When Chan practitioners compete in Chan, that is an ordinary affair. Why go so far?" Poan said: "Have you not heard the saying: 'My belly is hungry; hearing the meal board, I want to go eat' -- what about THAT?" Hearing these words, Wuzhun suddenly broke out in a cold sweat from head to toe. Later, he left to stay at Huazang Monastery, then returned to Poan at Lingyin as the head monk. After a meal one day, they strolled together to the Stone Bamboo Shoot Hermitage. A practitioner at the hermitage asked for instruction: "The monkey-mind -- I cannot catch it. I beg the Master for an expedient." Poan said: "Why try to catch it? It is like the wind blowing across water -- patterns form naturally of themselves." Standing at his master's side, hearing these words, the thing that had been obstructing Wuzhun's chest his entire life departed without so much as a farewell.

=== Wuzu Fayan ===
E1: During an evening talk, a monk asked, "What is Buddha?" The Master said, "Fatness enters through the mouth." He then raised a case: "Deshan once addressed the assembly, saying, 'Tonight I will not answer any questions. Anyone who asks will get thirty blows of the staff.' Many have raised this case and not a few claim to understand it. But tell me -- where do you actually see Deshan in this? If there is a fearless fellow here, come out and speak! If not, I will go meet old Deshan on behalf of all of you. When Deshan says, 'Tonight I will not answer questions; anyone who asks gets thirty blows,' simply say to him: 'I have no question to ask, and I will take no blows either.' Tell me -- does this accord with old Deshan or not? At this point you must be a real person to get it. I, Fayan, wandered on pilgrimage for more than ten years. I visited several venerable teachers across the seas and thought I had finished the matter. But when I reached Fushan Yuanjian's assembly, I simply could not open my mouth. Later, at Baiyun's gate, I bit through an iron dumpling and found it contained all one hundred flavors. But tell me -- what is the dumpling-filling verse? The cockscomb flower blooms, charming in early autumn -- who could dye a purple thread? Sometimes the wind stirs them into leaning together, as if fighting before the steps without rest."
E2: The Master ascended the hall and raised a case: "Yaoshan had not ascended the hall for a long time. The monastery director reported, 'The assembly has long been thinking of your teaching, Master.' Yaoshan said, 'Beat the drum.' When the assembly gathered, Yaoshan simply returned to his quarters. The director said, 'Master, you agreed to teach the assembly -- why did you not say a single word?' Yaoshan said, 'There are sutra teachers for sutras and treatise teachers for treatises. How can you blame this old monk?'" The Master commented: "Although he used himself to obstruct others, the thief's body was already exposed. Do you want to recognize Yaoshan? Idly holding a sutra scroll, leaning against a pine -- he smiles and asks the visitor, 'Where have you come from?'"

=== Xianglin Chengyuan ===
E1: A monk asks Xianglin: "What is the intent of the Patriarch's coming from the West?" Xianglin says: "Sitting long becomes toil." The commentary: "Words without flavor, phrases without flavor. Flavorless talk blocks mouths and shuts them off, leaving you nowhere to breathe out." He once said: "Only after forty years did I finally hammer it into one piece."
E2: A monk asks: "What is a lamp inside the room?" Xianglin says: "Three people confirm a turtle becomes a soft-shelled turtle." The monk asks: "What is the matter beneath the patched robe?" Xianglin says: "In the twelfth lunar month, fire burns the mountain." At Yunmen's side for eighteen years, Yunmen would call: "Attendant Yuan!" and when he responded, say: "What is it?" Xianglin toyed with cleverness for years until one day he suddenly said: "I understand!" Yunmen said: "Why not bring it forth in an upward way?" He stayed another three years.

=== Xiangtian Jinian ===
E1: A monk asked: "'If you grasp it at the first phrase, you can be teacher of Buddhas and Patriarchs.' What is the first phrase?" The Master said: "There is no place for your question." The monk continued: "'Grasping at the second phrase, you can be teacher of humans and gods.' What is the second phrase?" The Master said: "Your question cannot reach it." The monk continued: "'Grasping at the third phrase, you cannot even save yourself.' What is the third phrase?" The Master said: "Ask it and it is already worthless." The monk said: "Which phrase, then, did the Master himself grasp?" said the Master: "You don't understand my meaning." The monk said: "Then is spring without limit at the tip of the whisk?" the Master replied: "Idle chatter."
E2: A monk asked: "There is a thing prior to heaven and earth, formless and originally still -- may a student apprehend it?" the Master responded: "Across ten thousand miles of clear sky, a single scrap of cloud breaks through." The monk said: "The wooden maiden beats the stone drum again and again!" The Master said: "The moment it takes on pattern and color, it belongs to defilement." The monk bowed, then stood and said: "Right at this very moment -- what then?" The Master said: "A fine lacquer bucket you are."

=== Xiangya Ting ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master said: "The entire universe is a single ancient mirror. Hundreds of thousands of oceans of fragrant water, hundreds of thousands of Mount Sumerus, the great earth, mountains and rivers, grasses and forests, saints and ordinary beings, monastics and laity, men and women, noble and lowly, sentient and insentient -- all are inside it. Then why is it that Guishan's water-buffalo cannot even cast a shadow there?" After a long silence he said: "Sleeping upside-down with no one to recognize it -- across ten thousand miles of blue sky, a single hook of moon."
E2: At the opening ceremony, a monk asked: "What is the meaning of the ancestral transmission?" The Master said: "A staff with eyes strikes sun and moon; a scale without a star-pointer weighs mountains and rivers." The monk bowed. The Master then said: "On a needle-tip, Mount Sumeru stands upside-down; in the crack between eyebrows, the entire ocean pours forth."

=== Xiangyan ===
E1: A monk asked about each of the five houses of Chan. "What is the Linji school?" The Master said: "One blow of the staff -- a single crimson stripe." "What is the Yunmen school?" "Green mountains tower high within white clouds." "What is the Caodong school?" "Gold needle and jade thread, subtly stitched in secret." "What is the Guiyang school?" "A kind father and a filial son manifest the family style." "What is the Fayan school?" "Step by step, all traces of travel vanish." The monk continued: "The five house styles have been pointed out by the Master. What about today's opening of the forge?" The Master said: "I'm just looking for someone who doesn't need to be tempered."
E2: At the evening talk after his first dharma assembly, the Master said: "Sometimes seizing the person, not seizing the environment. Sometimes seizing the environment, not seizing the person. Sometimes both person and environment are seized. Sometimes neither person nor environment is seized." Then he continued: "Being so earnest for people's sake, I rip open my belly and gouge out my heart. At Puming today, though this is just the first opening of the dharma seat, the assessment and discernment passed down from the ancestors -- I dare not recklessly add or subtract from it. I only have a certain Tightening Spell. If I start chanting it, I guarantee every single skull will crack open, and no one will be able to move. If among you there is someone with a copper head and iron forehead, utterly transparent on all eight sides, let him step forward and say: 'Please, Master, chant it.' Then I will simply say: 'Today the assembly has provided a fine meal. The offerings in the hall are excellent.'" He descended from the seat.

=== Xiangyan Zhixian ===
E1: Xiangyan says: "It is like a person up in a tree, with his mouth biting a branch, his hands not grasping the branch, his feet not stepping on the tree. Someone below the tree asks about the meaning of the coming from the West. If he does not answer, he goes against what is asked; if he answers, he loses body and life. At just such a time, how should one answer?"
E2: A monk asks Xiangyan, "What is the Way?" Xiangyan says, "A dragon's cry in a withered tree." The monk asks, "What is a person in the Way?" Xiangyan says, "Eyes in a skull." Later, Caoshan is asked the same. "What is a dragon's cry in a withered tree?" Caoshan says, "The bloodline is unbroken." "Who can hear it?" Caoshan says, "Across the whole earth there is not a single person who does not hear it." "What lines is the dragon's cry?" Caoshan says, "I do not know what lines they are; those who hear it all perish."

=== Xiaoshan Zongshu ===
E1: Xiaoshan heard that Yuezhou Wenzai's dharma-eye was piercing and sharp, so he went to study with him. He practiced intimately for eight years. One day, while reading Wenzai's recorded sayings, he came across the enlightenment dialogue of Dingguo (Wufang Kecong) and had an insight. He thought to himself: "This is just a case of red-eyes bumping into a fire-poker." He entered the room and asked: "Leaving aside nine years of wall-gazing -- what about the matter of cutting off the arm to find peace of mind?" Wenzai said: "Just because a poison was left behind at the start, the children and grandchildren wash the earth but it never turns to mud." The master said: "Without your raising it, Reverend, how would anyone see the Shaolin man?" Wenzai hissed twice. The master said: "Can't do anything about the boat -- smash the bailing bucket!" And walked out.
E2: Another day entering the room, Wenzai said: "Coming through the gate, you must have a word -- do not use a question to ask a question." The master said: "Sun-face Buddha? Moon-face Buddha?" Wenzai said: "Seeing jowls behind the head!" The master said: "You too should be careful, Reverend." Wenzai drew back: "This mountain monk's fortune-year is in the water sign." The master bowed: "Your student is at fault." Wenzai then entrusted him with the great dharma.

=== Xiaotang ===
E1: Xiaotang picked up his staff and said: "You normally see the staff and call it a staff, see the whisk and call it a whisk. You want to walk, so you walk. You want to sit, so you sit. How wonderfully direct and refreshing! But the moment I ask you about it, the staff blocks you and the whisk obstructs you, and you turn into wooden puppets. Tell me -- where does the fault lie?" He struck the ground repeatedly: "Speak! Speak!" After a long silence he said: "Today I've profited! I'm happy to report that the staff has finally understood." He made the staff dance, and descended from the seat.
E2: Layman Qin asked: "Confucius said 'What Heaven confers is called the nature.' What is this nature conferred by Heaven?" Xiaotang said: "Don't chop it into two pieces." Qin continued: "'The Way cannot be departed from for a single instant.'" Before Qin finished speaking, the master said: "Strip away all the 'this-es' and 'that-s' and 'therefore-s' and try saying something!" Qin shouted. The master said: "And after the shout?" Qin hesitated. The master laughed: "Bow and withdraw." Qin bowed. The master said: "Clever layman!"

=== Xiaoyan Debao ===
E1: Xiaoyan asked Wuwen Mingcong about the phrase "the ten stages of sainthood and three stages of worthiness have already perfected holy wisdom -- yet why say they do not illumine this meaning?" Wuwen thundered: "You already know the ten stages and three stages of worthiness -- what IS this meaning? Speak! Speak!" The master gave several answers, none of which hit the mark. He grew desperate, forgot food and sleep. One day, carrying a basket to the stream to wash vegetables, a single leaf fell into the water and spun in the current -- he could not grab it. Suddenly he had an insight. He seized the basket, leaping with joy, and ran back. Wuwen was standing under the eaves. He asked: "What is it?" "A basket of vegetables." "Why not say something else?" "Please ask something else, Reverend!"
E2: A monk came to pay respects and said: "I have strung the seventeen hundred old frozen corpses of the patriarchs on a single thread and present them to you, Reverend. Please render judgment." At that moment, a dog outside the gate suddenly barked. The master quickly turned to his attendant: "Go see what guest is arriving!" The attendant went out. The monk stood there, dumbfounded. The master said: "What was it you just asked?" The monk tried to repeat his question. The master struck him with his staff repeatedly and drove him out.

=== Xiaoyin Daxin ===
E1: Xiaoyin commented on the classic case: Deshan arrived at Guishan's monastery carrying his bundle. He walked from east to west across the dharma hall, from west to east, looked around and said "Nothing! Nothing!" and left. At the gate he said, "Still, one must not be careless." He re-entered with full ceremony. Holding up his sitting cloth, he called out "Master!" Guishan reached for the whisk -- Deshan shouted, flicked his sleeve, and left. That evening Guishan asked the head monk where the newcomer had gone. The head monk said, "He turned his back on the dharma hall and walked away in his straw sandals." Guishan said, "Someday that fellow will go to a solitary peak and build a grass hut, cursing Buddhas and reviling patriarchs." Xiaoyin's verse: "Striding alone with great confidence, turning left and right -- the golden crow flaps its wings and ocean waves overturn, the iron net hangs upside-down from a coral tree. His hidden strategy silent, ten thousand appearances sink level. Complete killing and complete giving life, able to release and able to restrain. Don't despise the old man for lacking strength -- within his laughter and conversation, the brocade pit runs deep."
E2: Xiaoyin raised the case: A woman sat near the Buddha in deep samadhi. Manjushri asked the Buddha why she could sit so close when he could not. The Buddha told Manjushri to rouse her. Manjushri circled her three times, snapped his fingers, even lifted her to the Brahma heaven -- yet could not bring her out of samadhi. The Buddha said even a hundred thousand Manjushris could not do it. From below, past forty-two Ganges-sands of worlds, Wangming Bodhisattva emerged and snapped his fingers once before the woman -- and she arose from samadhi. Xiaoyin held up his staff and said: "Strung on a single thread."

=== Xieyunji ===
E1: Taking up his staff, the Master said: "Just this one thing -- before the two primal forces emerged, before father and mother were born, its branches and leaves spread luxuriantly, sheltering the myriad things. After father and mother gave birth to you, all skin and husk falls away, and only the one true reality remains. It props up the falling and steadies the tottering. Each of you is wholly sustained by its power."
E2: Mending a robe, he held up the torn cloth and said: "The business of ascending to heaven -- you should just throw this rag away. The fully accomplished thing -- throw that away too, right before the assembly. Cast it to the ground and it rings like gold. Don't look after it. This thing that is 'just like that' -- it still shows horn and hoof. Tomorrow, when the master's nostrils hang down and the three drum-rolls sound, who did you think would come to haggle over the price?"

=== Xinghua Cunjiang ===
E1: As Linji was about to die, he instructed Sansheng: "After I have passed away, do not extinguish my Treasury of the True Dharma Eye." Sansheng said, "How could I dare extinguish master's Treasury of the True Dharma Eye?" Linji said, "If suddenly someone asks you, what will you say?" Sansheng gave a shout. Linji said, "Who would have known? My true Dharma eye would be extinguished at the side of this blind donkey."
E2: After falling from a horse and breaking his arm, Xinghua versified: "Great Compassion Bodhisattva has a thousand hands; what real man does not have them?" Additionally, Xinghua came to Yunju at Sanfeng Hermitage and said, "I will borrow a question for the moment as a sketching line. What about it?" Yunju could not answer. Twenty years later Xinghua commented: "For twenty years Yunju only managed to say 'Why must it be so?' Xinghua is not like that. Better to say: There is no need."

=== Xingkong Zhen ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the place from which all Buddhas emerge?" The Master said: "The eyebrows painted in a mirror." "What is the pure Dharma body?" "The scraping-stick in the privy." "What is the perfect reward body?" "The patterned ball on the rack." "What is the hundred-billion transformation body?" "There is a moon in the water, and in the mirror there is no head."
E2: The Master recounted the awakening story of a disciple: The teacher asked, "You who write scriptures, bow, walk, sit, lie down, dress, and eat -- what person is this?" The student said: "There is no one else." The teacher shouted: "You say -- ultimately, who is it?" As the student was about to answer, the teacher covered his mouth with his hand and gave a forceful push. The student fell back, cold sweat drenching his whole body, and his mind suddenly opened wide.

=== XISHAN LIANG ===
E1: Ascending the hall, Xishan Liang cited: "The Master Sansheng said, 'When I meet someone I go out, but going out is not for the person's sake.' Xinghua said, 'When I meet someone I do not go out, but when I do go out, it is for the person's sake.' Sansheng and Xinghua each extended one hand, wanting to prop up the Linji school's tradition. Little did they know that the Linji tradition was swept clean by these two elders." Then: "Today, this fellow Liang comes forth to teach -- what is it ultimately about? Fortunately, it is a time of peace with nothing to do. When meeting, why bother with weapons? Even so, this is just what Xuefeng said."
E2: "Poverty runs to the bone, and I don't weary of poverty. Lying crosswise, sleeping upside-down, among white clouds. Hungry, I eat a bowl of plain rice. Beyond this, I have no ability to revive the ancestral tradition."

=== Xisou Shaotan ===
E1: Xisou raised the case in verse: "Master Nanquan heard of a hermit at the foot of his mountain. A monk had asked the hermit: 'Now that Nanquan has appeared in the world, why don't you go pay respects?' The hermit replied: 'Never mind Nanquan -- even if a thousand buddhas appeared, I would not go bow.' Nanquan sent Zhaozhou to test him. Zhaozhou arrived and bowed; the hermit paid no attention. Zhaozhou walked from west to east, from east to west; the hermit still paid no attention. Zhaozhou said: 'The grass-bandit is utterly defeated!' and pulled down the hermit's blind and left. Returning, he told Nanquan, who said: 'I have always had my suspicions about that fellow.'" Xisou versified: "Slavish faces and bended knees hurry through the human world, ashamed before the sheepskin cloak at Seven-Mile Rapids. Though Guang Wu became Son of Heaven, Ziling only treated him as an old friend."
E2: Xisou raised the case: "A non-Buddhist asked the Buddha: 'I do not ask about words; I do not ask about non-words.' The World-Honored One sat in silence for a long time. The non-Buddhist said: 'The World-Honored One's great compassion has parted my clouds of delusion and let me enter.' Ananda then asked: 'What principle did the non-Buddhist see that made him say he had entered?' The Buddha replied: 'Like a fine horse in the world that moves at the mere shadow of the whip.'" Xisou commented: "To erase a tattoo but leave a scar, to wipe away tracks but leave traces -- the yellow-faced old man cannot escape the critics' tongues. But to not move the blade's edge, to not apply medicine -- a patient who seems alive will die of a hidden ailment. Can anyone here discern this? If so, then even a fine horse glimpsing the whip is already eight beats too slow. If not, then the monks of the Eastern Land are no match for the non-Buddhists of India." He versified: "Ten thousand li of limpid river after the snow has cleared, a jade jar of one color shimmering cold light. The fisherman recognizes the way to the smoke-wreathed village, threads a fish on his willow line, and comes home under the moon."

=== Xitang Zhizang ===
E1: A monk asks Mazu about the meaning of Bodhidharma's coming from the West. Mazu says: "I am weary and cannot speak for you. Go ask Zhizang." The monk goes to Zhizang, who says: "Why not ask the master?" The monk says: "The master told me to ask." Zhizang says: "Today I have a headache; I cannot speak it for you. Go ask Brother Hai [Baizhang]." The monk goes to Baizhang, who says: "Arriving here, I too do not understand."
E2: Mazu Daoyi one day asked Xitang Zhizang, "Why don't you read the sutras?" Zhizang said, "Are the sutras any different?" Mazu said, "Even so, you will need them later when you teach others." Zhizang said, "Zhizang is sick and must tend to himself. He dare not speak of teaching others." Mazu said, "In your later years, you will surely flourish in the world." Zhizang bowed. After Mazu's death, in the seventh year of Zhenyuan, the assembly requested Zhizang to open the hall and teach. Academician Li Ao once asked a monk, "What teaching did Grand Master Ma have?" The monk said, "The Grand Master sometimes said 'mind itself is Buddha,' and sometimes said 'neither mind nor Buddha.'" Li said, "All that has passed beyond this point." Li then asked Zhizang the same question. Zhizang called out, "Academician Li!" Li responded. Zhizang said, "The drum and bugle are sounding."

=== Xiuyelin ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall and raised this: "An ancient worthy said: 'To be a true teacher, you must drive the farmer's ox and snatch the hungry man's food. Drive away his ox so that his seedlings and grain flourish; snatch his food so that hunger is forever ended.'" The Master said: "The ancient worthy obtained a little trick and his bearing was like a king's, seizing and releasing at will. Many teachers everywhere raise this saying, but listeners let it pass like wind through the ears. They do not know the ancient's expedient means were just to smash delusion and attachment. Having driven away the ox and snatched the food, why then do the seedlings flourish and hunger end?" He gave a shout and said: "Is this driving the ox? Snatching the food? Is there anyone who can tell black from white? Step forward and show your clumsiness. If not -- disaster never comes alone, but fortune never doubles."
E2: The next day, at the beginning of the retreat, the Master was asked to ascend the hall. "Xilai begins its retreat. The cloud-and-water monks have gathered. Seizing the throat -- where do you breathe? It is not that this mountain monk oppresses the good; it is only that you all have not yet realized it. Have you realized it? If so, each person's pure jeweled furnace needs neither a stick of firewood nor a lump of charcoal; day and night it blazes with no place to hide and no gap between." A monk asked: "You began this retreat gathering all the monks from the ten directions. Taking the assembly as your mind -- but mind cannot be grasped. What do you really have?" The Master said: "Slapping the grass is precisely to startle the snake." The monk said: "Don't fool people." the Master replied: "Why have you stuck your head into the glue pot?" And he struck him.

=== Xixinshui of Xiangyan ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the true Dharma eye?" the Master asked: "A worn-out straw sandal." The monk pressed: "What is the meaning of this?" The Master said: "You can't put it on."
E2: In an evening talk, the Master said: "Last night at the second watch of the third period, a comet rolled into my abbot's quarters and reported: 'The four seas are drained, the mountains are exhausted, countless fish and dragons are dying of thirst. Yet people just stay in their warm rooms on heated beds, eating when hungry, sleeping when tired -- how could they know of such events?' This mountain monk could not respond. On your part, what do you do?" He struck his staff on the ground: "Investigate!"

=== Xiyan Liaohui ===
E1: Evening talk at Donglin: "Each of you, beneath your traveling bundle, possesses a wordless calendar. Within it, the seventy-two seasonal markers, the twenty-four solar terms, the months long and short, the leap years -- all perfectly clear. Why have you never once glanced at it? You have scrambled your own sixty-year cycle, and now come to my mouth to hear me announce summer and winter. What an injustice! I certainly do not hold the authority of yin and yang, nor do I possess the hand that turns the seasons. But tonight I shall try to point this calendar out for you." He struck the left side of the seat: "Yang is the gentleman." He struck the right side: "Yin is the petty person." He drew a line through the middle: "The way of the gentleman grows; the way of the petty person wanes." Then: "Even so -- take the myriad folds of Mount Lu before your eyes. Since ancient times, the south slope is called 'yang,' the north slope 'yin.' Can you speak of waxing and waning here?" He barked: "At the gate of Sun Bin, beware of consulting the tortoise shell!"
E2: Xiyan ascended the hall and addressed the assembly: "Yesterday at the mountain gate I met two newly arrived monks. I asked the first: 'Where do you come from?' He said: 'From beyond Cart Ridge.' I asked: 'Where is the cart?' He made a pushing gesture. I asked the second: 'Where do you come from?' He said: 'From beyond Leqing.' I asked: 'Where is the joy?' He made a gesture of playing music. My question was exactly the same both times, and both men's responses looked alike. Yet one had a spark of genuine understanding, and the other had none whatsoever. Can any of you distinguish which is which? If you cannot, I will not spare my mouth-karma and will spell it out plainly: the one with the spark and the one without -- today is the first, tomorrow is the second."

=== Xuansha Shibei ===
E1: Xuansha instructs the assembly: "The old worthies in all quarters all speak of meeting beings and benefiting life. Suddenly, if three kinds of sick people come, how do you receive them? If one is blind, you lift the hammer and raise the whisk -- but he does not see. If one is deaf, you use the speech samadhi -- but he does not hear. If one is mute, you tell him to speak -- but he cannot speak. So how do you receive them? If you cannot receive such people, the Buddha-dharma has no efficacy."
E2: One day, Master Shibei set out to travel and visit teachers everywhere. He packed his bag and left the mountain pass. He stubbed his toe on a rock, and blood flowed with sharp pain. He sighed and said: "This body does not truly exist -- so where does the pain come from?" He immediately turned back to Xuefeng. Later, Xuefeng asked him one day: "Which one is Shibei the ascetic?" The Master replied: "I would never dare deceive anyone." On another day, Xuefeng called out: "Ascetic Bei! Why don't you go on pilgrimage everywhere?" the Master responded: "Bodhidharma did not come to the Eastern Land; the Second Patriarch did not go to the Western Heavens." Xuefeng approved of this.

=== Xuedou Chongxian ===
E1: "In our tradition there are Xuedou and Tiantong, just as in Confucius' school there were Ziyou and Zixia. Of these two masters' verse comments on old cases, they are like Li Bai and Du Fu in the poetry world. The world says Xuedou had the talent of a Hanlin scholar."
E2: After Fengxue's teaching, Xuedou lifts his staff and asks: "Is there any patched-robed monk who lives and dies together with this?" Also, on Zhaozhou's cypress tree: "He only knows how to push it down, not how to set it back up." These characteristic interventions pepper the entire Blue Cliff Record.

=== XUEFENG HUIKONG ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master cited: "Once, Master Zhenjue asked Xuansha Bei: 'Head Monk, why don't you go on pilgrimage everywhere?' Bei said: 'Bodhidharma did not come to the East; the Second Patriarch did not go to the West.' Zhenjue approved of this." The Master raised the case and laughed loudly: "Later, everyone in the monasteries said this exchange was extraordinary. But they don't realize that this old fellow is still sitting in a heap under his own stupa to this very day, all because of those words back then. If someone were to say now, 'Bodhidharma did not come to the East; the Second Patriarch did not go to the West' -- they would simply be beaten with a stick and driven out. Why? Back then it was approved; now it would earn an expulsion. Those with clear eyes, discern!"
E2: The Master spoke on the occasion of a patron distributing sutras: "If life and death are real, then from ancient times to now no one has been able to escape them. If life and death are unreal, then from ancient times to now no one has been able to escape them. Whether you say they are both real and unreal, or neither real nor unreal -- still no one is exempt. This being so, how can one be free? There is only the single word 'awakening.' Apart from this, there is no gate; apart from this, there is no path." "Suppose right now you were to awaken on the spot -- not only life and death but the entire ten directions of empty space would all be annihilated. But I fear your faculties are slow. So let me give you a simile: It is like a person sleeping. The body lies safely on the bed, perfectly at ease. But in a dream, without any reason, poisonous snakes and fierce tigers appear, competing to devour you. In your terror you run frantically. And right at that point of frantic running -- suddenly your eyes open. The dharma of life and death is exactly like this." Then a monk came forward and said: "The great Snow Peak abbot receives such generous offerings from the patron, yet on the dharma-seat he only tells a dream!" The Master laughed loudly and said: "Indeed -- one must not tell dreams to fools."

=== Xuefeng Yicun ===
E1: Xuefeng was traveling with Yantou. They were stranded by snow at Ao Mountain. Yantou spent each day sleeping. Xuefeng sat in dhyana without ceasing. One day he called out, "Elder brother! Elder brother! Please get up." Yantou said, "What is it?" Xuefeng said, "In this life I've had no luck -- traveling with this obtuse fellow, everywhere I go he drags me down. Now we're stuck here, and all you do is sleep." Yantou shouted, "Go to sleep yourself! Every day you sit on the bed like a clay idol in some village shrine. Later you'll bewitch the sons and daughters of good families." Xuefeng pointed to his own chest and said, "I'm not yet settled here inside. I don't dare deceive myself." Yantou said, "I always thought you'd end up on some solitary peak, thatching a hut and broadcasting the great teaching -- and you're still talking like this?" Xuefeng said, "I'm truly not yet settled." Yantou said, "If that's really so, then state your understanding point by point. Where it's correct, I'll confirm it. Where it's wrong, I'll cut it away." Xuefeng said, "When I first arrived at Yanguang's, I heard him expound on form and emptiness, and I gained an entry." Yantou said, "For the next thirty years, never bring that up again." Xuefeng then said, "I also saw Dongshan's verse on crossing the stream: 'Do not seek from others -- far, far away from me. Now he is exactly me; now I am not him.'" Yantou said, "If that's how you try to save yourself, you'll never make it." Xuefeng then said, "Later I asked Deshan, 'In the matter of the ancestral tradition, does this student have any share?' Deshan struck me with his staff and said, 'What are you saying?' At that moment I felt like the bottom fell out of the bucket." Yantou shouted, "Haven't you heard the saying: 'What enters through the gate is not the family treasure'?" Xuefeng said, "Then what should I do in the future?" Yantou said, "In the future, if you wish to broadcast the great teaching, let each and every thing flow forth from your own breast. Then come and cover heaven and earth for me." At these words Xuefeng was greatly awakened. He bowed and cried out repeatedly, "Elder brother! Elder brother! Today at last -- enlightenment at Ao Mountain!"
E2: Two monks came to visit Xuefeng at his hermitage. He pushed open the door, thrust himself out, and said, "What is this?" The monks also said, "What is this?" Xuefeng lowered his head and went back inside. Later the monks came to take their leave. Xuefeng asked, "Where are you going?" They said, "To Hunan." Xuefeng said, "I have a companion who lives at Yantou's place. Please deliver a letter for me." The letter read: "Since my enlightenment at Ao Mountain, I have been full and never hungry." When the monks arrived at Yantou's and delivered the letter, Yantou asked, "Did he say anything else?" The monk related the hermitage-door exchange. Yantou said, "What did he say?" The monk said, "He said nothing -- just lowered his head and went back inside." Yantou said, "Alas! I should have told him the last phrase back then. If I had told him, no one in the world could do anything about old Xuefeng." At the end of the summer retreat, the monk asked about the meaning of these words. Yantou said, "Why didn't you ask sooner?" The monk said, "I didn't dare take it lightly." Yantou said, "Xuefeng and I were born on the same branch, but we will not die on the same branch. If you want to know the last phrase -- just this is it."

=== Xueguan ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the meaning of the Patriarch coming from the West?" the Master asked: "Never mind that -- whose conscript are you?" The monk said: "At this point I'm your conscript." The Master said: "Then why do you owe public debts and private loans?" The monk said: "I owe no public debts, no private loans -- I just have no way in." He turned and walked out. said the Master: "The bandit is routed!" The monk looked back and said: "I have field-work to do, I'm busy." The Master said: "Even if you're busy to death, what use is it?" Several monks rushed out at once. The Master stopped them and said: "None of you know how to be a proper thief -- you all come forward offering the stolen goods."
E2: The Master said on Buddha's Birthday: "He came down pointing at heaven and earth, declaring himself alone honored. But a lame old teacher wanted to beat him to death with one blow and feed him to the dogs, just to bring peace to the world. Today I want to beat that lame old teacher to death -- just so the two of us can meet face to face. Is there anyone who will stand up for the cripple?" The assembly was silent. The Master laughed and said: "It's not that I enjoy making enemies -- it's just genuinely hard to find a complete man."

=== Xueqiao Yuanxin ===
E1: The master ascended the hall and said, "Today at Yihao Temple, I'm not going to do lion dances or turn somersaults. I'll just speak some plain, honest words to benefit beings. Tell me: what is the phrase that benefits all beings?" Then he said, "Practice must be real practice. Awakening must be real awakening." A monk came forward, bowed, and was about to ask a question. The master struck him. The monk said, "I haven't even asked my question yet!" The master said, "By the time you open your mouth, what good would it do?" And he stepped down from the seat.
E2: A monk asked, "What is the monk's fundamental matter?" The master hit him. The monk said, "Setting aside the stick, please say another word." The master hit him again. The monk bowed, then stood and gave a shout. The master hit him three times in succession. Another monk asked, "Yunmen's universal -- Zhaozhou's barrier -- those I'll set aside. Before heaven and earth were established, before the world took shape -- where did the master of the house plant his feet?" The master said, "You word-spouting wretch." The monk tried a verse: "The crane roosts in the shadowless tree; the flower opens on the branch that never sprouts." The master said, "It's sprouting now."

=== Xueyan Zuqin ===
E1: Xueyan entered the new monastery at Longxing and sat down: "The solitary tune of Shaolin was transmitted five times down to the Sixth Patriarch -- in deep mountains and cold waters, he struck up the ancient pure note. The tune was transposed at Nanyue, nine generations down to Ciming -- the singing was lofty, the harmony was steep, performing the rarest of sounds. Thus it was that the Buddha-dharma flourished in Jiangxi and Hunan -- vast, vast! boundless, boundless! -- beyond any name. But who could have predicted that three hundred years later the land would be broad and the people scarce, the Way following the times into decline? The great bells and pitch-pipes fell silent, and even the popular songs of Zheng and Wei were no longer heard. This fellow Qin has no special talent. But since a gust of karmic wind has blown me from the other side of the Zhejiang River into the city of Tanzhou, I have no choice but to change the key and reverse the melody, and retune this ancient song right in the middle of the crossroads. What is the rhythm? --" He struck the whisk. "Ten thousand years of joy."
E2: Xueyan raised a case: "Weishan asked Yangshan, 'You haven't come up all summer -- what have you been doing?' Yangshan said, 'I cleared a patch of hillside and planted a basket of millet.' Weishan said, 'Then you haven't wasted your time.' Yangshan asked, 'And you, Master?' Weishan said, 'One meal at midday, one sleep after nightfall.' Yangshan said, 'Then you haven't wasted your time either.' After saying this, he stuck out his tongue. Weishan said, 'Jizi, why do you wound your own life?'" Xueyan commented: "Weishan and Yangshan -- yes, the son carries on the father's enterprise, and it is fine to observe. But by the end they are contradicting each other. You could say: the father is no father, the son is no son. As for Longxing this summer -- I too have done nothing special, and I too have not wasted my time. Is this the same as the ancients, or different? The toad at the bottom of the well swallows the moon."

=== Xuezui of Zhaojue ===
E1: An envoy asked: "When the blade is not exposed, what then?" The Master said: "Blood flows across the wilderness."
E2: A monk asked: "When a single arrow is shot into empty space, what then?" The Master said: "Dot." The monk said: "Then ten thousand forms drip fresh blood." The Master said: "Bullseye." The monk bowed. The Master said: "Why don't you bite the arrowhead?"

=== Xutang Zhiyu ===
E1: At the New Year's Eve evening gathering, the Master said: "Cold ashes, dead fire -- every household sends off poverty with firecrackers. The old year ends and spring returns -- everywhere they burn paper money to summon ghosts. Three hundred sixty days, head meeting tail, now unfolding fresh livelihood. Two thousand years of unsold goods -- time to set new prices. Root-fire, village music. The bare-ground ox -- no need to bring it out. The Diamond Ring, the Chestnut-Thorn Thicket, the Iron Sour-Plum -- now is the perfect time to present them. Coming from the south, heading to the north -- swallow them whole and you pass through the Gateless Barrier. Hawk-eye, falcon-gaze -- how will you gulp them down in silence? If my telling you all this at Xingsheng is already pulling back the clouds and coming down to earth -- why? South of the river it is warm; north of the frontier it is cold." The Master spoke again: "Everywhere else they serve dragon liver and phoenix marrow. Here in this desolate place, we have nothing to offer. Deep in the mountains, in cliff-faces where no human foot has trod, I picked up a single object. I flung it into the 'Nothing Happening' chest and left it there for many years. Tonight I bring it out completely and share it with all of you for the New Year." He struck his staff once. "Be careful not to swallow it whole."
E2: The Master ascended the hall and raised a case: "A monk asked Zhaozhou, 'I have just entered the monastery. I beg the Master for instruction.' Zhaozhou said, 'Have you eaten your rice porridge yet?' The monk said, 'Yes, I have eaten.' Zhaozhou said, 'Then go wash your bowl.'" "At these words, the monk had an insight." The Master commented: "Zhaozhou had the skill of the master carpenter who shaves a layer of paint off the tip of a man's nose with an axe without the man flinching. But tell me -- at what point did he apply the blade?"

=== Xuzhou Pudu ===
E1: Raising the old case of Governor Li Ao asking Yaoshan: "What is the Way?" -- Yaoshan pointed at the sky, then at a water jug, and asked: "Do you understand?" Li said no. Yaoshan said: "Clouds in the blue sky, water in the bottle." Li had a great awakening and wrote a verse: "I trained this crane-like body under a thousand pines with two cases of scripture. I came to ask about the Way and received no extra words -- clouds in the blue sky, water in the bottle." Xuzhou commented: "The Governor held the sun and moon of Confucius in his hands and wore the true seal of Vairocana at his waist -- that much is undeniable. But as for Yaoshan's meaning? He has not yet understood."
E2: During a snowfall, ascending the hall: "One night the river wind churned a jade storm. The solitary peak, refusing to turn white, redoubled its spirit. Released from the sky and viewed from the sky -- how many people are chilled to the bone?"

=== Xuzhou Sheng ===
E1: On his first dharma hall address, the master recalled how Linji told Puhua and Kefu: "I wish to establish Huangbo's lineage here -- you two help me accomplish it." Both bowed and left. Three days later Puhua returned and asked: "What did the master say three days ago?" Linji struck him. Three days later Kefu came and asked: "Why did you strike Puhua three days ago?" Linji also struck him. The master said: "This is how Linji established Huangbo's lineage. I too have no other intention -- I only wish to establish my own teacher's lineage. But how? With just this one staff -- it cannot be negotiated, cannot be named, cannot be touched, cannot be turned away from. Sometimes putting down is entirely picking up: before you even enter the gate I've already given you a beating. Sometimes picking up is entirely putting down: though I strike you until the blood runs, I have never moved my hand."
E2: A monk asked: "What is the first principle?" The master said: "Zhao, Qian, Sun, Li." The monk said: "The dragon's sleeve opens and the buddha's whole body appears." The master said: "That doesn't apply here." The monk shouted. The master struck him.

=== YAN JUSHEN ===
E1: A monk asked: "This matter is not inside, not outside, not in between -- where exactly is it?" The Master said: "Exactly." The monk continued: "The dragon's sleeve sweeps open and the whole body appears; where the elephant king walks, all traces vanish." The Master said: "That is not your territory." Then he addressed the assembly: "The sun can grow cold, the moon can grow hot -- raise your eyebrows and observe the season! On this platform at Daxing, strike the donkey's waist -- in the fire god's temple, fresh blood flows. Lantern posts and pillars chatter noisily, the mountains and rivers of the whole world leak out the secret. This obvious matter has no place to hide -- how is it that all of you fail to glimpse it? Where exactly is your moment of sudden seeing?" After a long pause he said: "Bamboo shadows sweep the stairs but raise no dust; the moon pierces the waves but the water bears no scar."
E2: Ascending the hall, the Master said: "Flowers in the mirror, moon in the water -- clearly visible yet impossible to grasp. Since they are clearly visible, why can they not be grasped?" After a pause: "All along one wasted effort pushing and shoving -- today, in midstream, one sails freely."

=== Yangqi Fanghui ===
E1: When Yangqi first received his appointment at Jiufeng Mountain, he donned his dharma robe and held it up before the assembly, saying, "Do you understand? If not, today I have blundered right into a herd of water buffaloes." He then ascended the seat. A monk stepped forward. Yangqi said, "The fisherman hasn't even cast his line, and already a fish leaps through the waves." The monk shouted. Yangqi said, "I knew it." The monk clapped his hands and returned to the assembly. Yangqi said, "How much wind did it take the Dragon King to produce that?" A monk asked, "Whose tune does the Master sing? Whose lineage do you continue?" Yangqi said, "If there is a horse, ride the horse. If there is no horse, go on foot." The monk said, "A young abbot surely has plenty of stratagems." Yangqi said, "Out of respect for your old age, I spare you thirty blows."
E2: Ascending the hall, Yangqi said, "The one essential of Yangqi -- a thousand sages share its wonder." He slapped the platform once and said, "Sure enough, I have lost my bearings." Again he said: "One word of Yangqi -- it conforms to every shape, round or square. But if you stop to deliberate, you are eighty thousand leagues away." He descended from the seat. Again: "One phrase of Yangqi -- it reviles the buddhas and curses the patriarchs. Before a person with clear eyes, do not make a mistake in quoting it." He descended from the seat. Again: "One sentence of Yangqi -- open your eyes quick and look! On the long sitting platform: picking up the spoon, grasping the chopsticks." He descended from the seat.

=== Yangshan Huiji ===
E1: One night Yangshan dreamed that he entered Maitreya's inner court. All the seats in the assembly hall were filled; only the second seat was empty. Yangshan took that seat. A presiding elder struck the gavel and announced, "Today it falls to the one in the second seat to preach the dharma." Yangshan rose, struck the gavel, and said, "The dharma of the Great Vehicle is apart from the four propositions and beyond the hundred negations. Listen carefully! Listen carefully!" The entire assembly dispersed. When Yangshan awoke, he told Weishan about it. Weishan said, "You have entered the ranks of the sages." Yangshan bowed.
E2: Yangshan was sweeping the ground. Weishan asked, "Dust cannot be swept away, and emptiness does not arise of itself. What does it mean that dust cannot be swept away?" Yangshan made a sweeping motion. Weishan said, "What does it mean that emptiness does not arise of itself?" Yangshan pointed to himself, then pointed to Weishan. Weishan said, "Dust cannot be swept away, and emptiness does not arise of itself. Apart from these two approaches, how would you express it?" Yangshan made another sweeping motion, pointed to himself, and pointed to Weishan.

=== Yanguan Qi'an ===
E1: One day Yanguan called to an attendant: "Bring me the rhinoceros-horn fan." The attendant said: "The fan is broken." Yanguan said: "If the fan is broken, return my rhinoceros to me." The attendant had no reply. Touzi Datong later said: "I would not refuse to produce it, but I fear the horn and all its features would not be complete." Xuedou said: "I want the incomplete horn and all its features." Shishuang said: "If I return it to you, then you will have nothing."
E2: A monk asked Damei: "What is the meaning of the Patriarch coming from the West?" Damei said: "Coming from the West has no meaning." Yanguan heard and said: "One coffin, two dead fellows." Xuansha heard and said: "Yanguan is a genuine hand."

=== Yangzhuoming ===
E1: A monk asked: "The World-Honored One spoke for forty-nine years without ever uttering a single word. What dharma does the Master expound on this seat?" The Master struck him and said: "I only know how to hit people." The monk said: "Today I see the World-Honored One in person!" The Master said: "Don't let your eyes play tricks."
E2: The Master told the assembly: "Dawei is completely stripped bare -- not a grain to offer you for a meal. Yet there is one true offering. When I was at Jinsu under Miyun, the old master's grandfather in dharma, I was carrying water. During an interview session, the old man hit me with a single blow and smashed my water-bucket. In that instant, the accumulated family fortune of boundless kalpas was poured out all at once, and all I kept was this one thing I use in the original, basic way." He held up his fist: "Just this one thing -- sour, sweet, salty, bland, bitter, spicy, with all hundred flavors complete. Today I bring it out before the assembly. Is there anyone among you who can swallow it? Investigate!"

=== Yantou Quanhuo ===
E1: Yantou went to Deshan. Straddling the threshold, he immediately asked, "Is it ordinary or holy?" Deshan immediately shouted. Yantou bowed. Dongshan heard of it and said, "If not for Huogong, it would have been hard to bear." Yantou said, "That old fellow Dongshan does not know good from bad. At that time I raised with one hand and pressed with the other."
E2: Luoshan asked Yantou, "What about when arising and ceasing do not stop?" Yantou barked, "Who is it that arises and ceases?" At this Luoshan awakened.

=== Yanxi Guangwen ===
E1: Yanxi commented on the classic: Yaoshan said at a small gathering, "I have a single phrase -- I'll tell it to you when a bull gives birth to a calf." A monk stepped forward and said, "The bull has given birth! Please, Master, speak!" Yaoshan said, "Bring a lamp." The monk withdrew into the assembly. Yanxi said: "Yaoshan stuck his head out too far, as if no one else existed. That monk had sharp eyes and acted on the opportunity. But as for 'the single phrase' -- he still hadn't awakened to it."
E2: Yanxi raised: Baling asked a monk, "Have you come to roam the mountains, or for the Buddha-dharma?" The monk said, "In a peaceful world, why speak of Buddha-dharma?" Baling said, "A fine carefree Chan practitioner." The monk said, "That's already too many complications." Baling said, "Did you spend last summer here?" The monk said, "No." Baling said, "Then we haven't met before. You may go." Yanxi commented: "Baling was like Lord Mengchang's open gate. That monk was a practiced guest -- advancing and retreating with perfect ease, host and guest in harmony. But when Baling said 'We haven't met before -- you may go,' what was his real meaning? Three cups of wine give a lord's son his bearing; a single flower tucked in a beauty's hair."

=== Yaoshan Weiyan ===
E1: Yaoshan had long not ascended the seat. The prior said: "The assembly has longed for instruction for a long time. Please, master, teach the Dharma." Yaoshan ordered the bell struck. The assembly gathered. Yaoshan ascended the seat, sat silently for a long while, then descended and returned to his quarters. The prior followed and asked: "Master, you just now agreed to teach. Why did you not let fall a single word?" Yaoshan: "Sutras have sutra teachers, treatises have treatise teachers -- why do you blame this old monk?"
E2: A monk asks Yaoshan: "On flat fields with shallow grass, the deer and the musk-deer gather in herds -- how do you shoot the musk-deer among musk-deer?" Yaoshan: "Watch the arrow." The monk lets his body go and falls. Yaoshan: "Attendant, drag out this dead fellow." The monk then runs off. Yaoshan: "You mud-ball fellow, what limit does he have?"

=== Yelu Chucai ===
E1: Yelu describes being referred to Wansong by his first teacher Sheng'an, who told him: "In the past, you held an important post, and moreover Confucian scholars often did not truly trust Buddhist books, but only picked through sayings and cases to furnish topics for talk. Therefore I did not dare apply the hammer and drill too harshly. But now, judging your mind, you truly ask for the sake of the fundamental matter. There is an elder called Wansong, who in both Confucian and Buddhist learning is fully equipped." Yelu then describes: "After I had paid respects to Wansong, cut off all visitors and set aside household affairs. Though in bitter cold or great heat, there was not a day without practice. Burning the lamp to continue past daylight, neglecting sleep and forgetting meals, for nearly three years."
E2: On military campaign with the Mongol army far from his teacher, Yelu begged Wansong through nine letters over seven years to compose commentaries on Tiantong's verses. When the book finally arrived: "I in the western regions, lonely and adrift for several years, suddenly received this book, and it was like sobering from drunkenness, like reviving from death. Leaping with joy, I cried out in delight, bowed toward the east, read and reread it again and again, stroked the scroll and sighed: Wansong has come to the western regions."

=== Yezhu of Mount Song ===
E1: Wild Bamboo ascended the hall: "This mountain monk has been shoveling dung for days, until body and mind were utterly exhausted. Just as I settled onto my cushion for a nap, the night-watchman's clapper startled me awake. My attendant said: 'Swords and halberds clashing! Horses and chariots lined up! It must be royalty or the provincial governor!' But when I cracked open the brushwood gate, it was just the old lay patrons. So I had no choice but to sling my robe on sideways, grab the Buddha-ladle backwards, climb up here, and try to issue some decree. But now that I'm up here, there's nothing to say." He held up the invitation letter: "Fortunately there's this. Understand? This is the boundless etiquette of a person of immeasurable capacity. May you two laurel trees flourish forever."
E2: The master raised an old verse: "Mind is not a thing; wisdom is not the Way. Linji's little servant-boy takes three steps and does a jump." Then he said: "This mountain monk also has a view: Mind IS a thing; wisdom IS the Way. Linji's little servant-boy -- poke him and he jumps! Everyone -- those who haven't verified this, take a look!"

=== Yi'an ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the true original face?" Yi'an gave a rapid series of alternate answers: "One has always been familiar with it -- no need for further polishing." "Looking at it today, it is clearly something altogether different." "It is not only harmonizing with the light, but also blending with the dust." "If you say the outside is this and not that, everywhere the pure light is unobstructed." "Sitting here, it finally becomes one color." "Even when light and scene are both extinguished and not a speck of ground remains -- still, without opening the road of mind and thought, the moment you step on it, a path forms." Then he concluded: "Try to compare it to something and it is already unlike."
E2: Returning from Stone Bridge, Yi'an held a small gathering. A monk asked: "The wind moves, the banner moves -- the Sixth Patriarch said it was the listener's mind that moves. What do you say?" Yi'an leaned on his staff and said: "Wait -- let me think whether I remember anything about this." The monk said: "I would put it differently." Yi'an said: "How would you put it?" The monk spread both hands wide. Yi'an said: "So it was right here all along." Then he addressed the assembly: "Mountains and streams have no barriers. The light penetrates everywhere. The five hundred arhats ride backwards on great whales, entering through your eyes and coming out through your ears, coming in through your ears and going out through your eyes, performing the samadhi of miraculous play in all directions."

=== Yichu Yuan ===
E1: A monk asked: "When we meet on a narrow path, what then?" The Master said: "Dangerous!" The monk bowed. The Master said: "Fallen!"
E2: A nun asked: "What is my original face?" The Master said: "A total disgrace!" The nun bowed. The Master said: "Hard to fool any watching eyes."

=== Yigong of Fushi ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is 'seizing the person but not the environment'?" The Master said: "Crossing water and piercing clouds, one takes the path of Kan." "What is 'seizing the environment but not the person'?" "Throw open the city that never sleeps." "What is 'seizing both person and environment'?" "The Supreme Ultimate has always been right here." "What is 'neither person nor environment seized'?" "Rising up by itself, falling down by itself." The monk pressed: "You have shown me the four phrases. What is the matter beyond them?" said the Master: "Step back and look." She then struck her staff and said: "Look! The wooden fellow has split open the figure eight, releasing a great jeweled radiance that illuminates all of you."
E2: "Put down body and mind -- ten thousand affairs are finished. Simply raise the character 'nothing' and hold it in the center of your heart. When with a crash comes a clap of thunder, open your great mouth wide and verify the essential teaching." She struck a line with the bamboo whip and said: "Do you understand?" She hurled the whip down with a crack. "Apprehend it right here!"

=== Yikui of Cantong ===
E1: The Master said: "The ancients would slaughter the white ox of the open field and share it with the assembly for the year's end. I've thought about it -- no need, no need. The white ox of the open field -- every one of you already has your own. Why add a cup after you're already drunk? Since we've newly built the refectory this year at Cantong, I'll just take the word 'new' and say a few words about it. What is new? Every household has drums and gongs shaking heaven, pastes up a new couplet on the door, puts on a new set of clothes and hat, and calls it all brand-new on the outside -- yet inside, the same old ignorance and foul habits remain, and nobody pays attention to that. But our way is different: clear and luminous, everything ordinary, no new clothes or hat, no swapping old for new. Just take the three hundred sixty days of the year and review them from beginning to end. Is there a stinking jar you haven't washed clean? An old debt from years past you haven't repaid? A habit carried from your mother's womb you haven't shed? A root of karma from beginningless time you haven't pulled out? Clean it all to the bottom, then put on an entirely new suit of fierce wisdom, take up your original investigation, day after day make it new and again new. Only by pressing forward like this do you earn the one truly fresh phrase. How do you match this occasion? At Cantong temple, towers rise like planting a blue lotus on bare rock. In the sound of firecrackers the old year departs; on the fragrance of plum blossoms, spring arrives."
E2: The Master addressed the assembly: "Since you have come here to depend on this poor monk, seeking the cause of liberation from birth and death, you must risk your lives in one great effort. Whether you are old hands or newcomers, the problem is that the mind of birth-and-death is not urgent enough. When you pick up the huatou it is there; when you don't, it vanishes. That is why you cannot break through. I don't ask you to manage the temple's provisions or go out socializing. I only ask you to take 'Where does the One return to?' and investigate it day and night. Whether busy or idle, moving or still, whether in adversity or favor, anger or delight -- when rice comes, eat rice; when tea comes, drink tea. Diligently, earnestly, like an iron spike. The moment a stray thought arises, raise your original investigation like the King of Vajra's sword and look directly: where does this thought come from? Clench your teeth, straighten your spine -- the work will naturally become one piece. When you reach the point where it raises itself without your raising it, and your chest feels suffocated, pressing in -- at that moment you absolutely must not let go."

=== Yikui of Shending ===
E1: The Master asked the assembly, "It is not the wind moving, not the banner moving, not the mind moving -- what IS moving?" Qizhong said, "The Master's mouth is moving." the Master responded, "This old monk is at fault."
E2: While planting beans, the Master asked the assembly, "The ancients said, 'Plant beans and you won't get sesame.' But you may not call them beans. So what DO they produce?" None of the assembly's answers satisfied him. The Master answered for them: "When something different sprouts, I'll tell the Master about it."

=== YING'AN TANHUA ===
E1: Ascending the hall, Ying'an picked up the staff and said: "My late teacher, the elder of White Cloud, once said: 'The words and half-phrases left by the ancients, before you penetrate them, are like running into an iron wall. But when one day you suddenly see through, you realize that you yourself are the iron wall.' Tell me, how do you pass through right now?" Then he said, "Iron wall, iron wall!" He struck the staff once and said, "Iron wall, iron wall -- quick, quick, as if by imperial decree!" Then he descended from the seat.
E2: On the occasion of bathing the Buddha, Ying'an said: "Shakyamuni in his old age was merely peddling wares -- it was nothing but clinging to grass and wood, and both sides remained unresolved." He slapped the platform with his left hand and said, "Come over to this side. Do all of you see where Minguo stands?" Then: "Tears on the coral pillow, half longing for you, half resenting you."

=== Yingningjing of Luohan ===
E1: Yingningjing was studying under the master at Dongshan. One evening, the master challenged him about Yunmen's saying on "things among a different species." Yingningjing stood sweating, unable to answer, for over an hour. Then the master called the attendant to trim the glass lamp. The attendant fumbled and extinguished it. The master scolded: "Where is the fire?" The attendant hastily answered: "Here it is, right here." At that moment Yingningjing experienced great awakening and said: "Yunmen, ancient buddha! Guoqing, true teacher!" The master then came out and said: "Just now I raised the matter of 'things among a different species' -- try turning a phrase." Yingningjing said: "A thief sifting a gong at midnight." The master said: "Why not say 'a thief sifting a gong at daybreak'?" Yingningjing bowed in gratitude.
E2: The master was in his room. Three attendants -- Yinglin, Tiyuan, and Tianzhu -- stood before him. The master laid his staff across and said: "None of you may speak, none may stay silent. Turn a pivotal phrase, and only then may you leave." Yinglin immediately walked out of the room. The master pointed and said: "Look at this one -- a fish that slipped through the net." Tiyuan said: "The master opens the door and lets in the thief." The master said: "And what about you?" Tiyuan said: "I'll hold my tongue when the moment arrives." Tianzhu said: "The master is patrolling for curfew-breakers." The master then asked Tianzhu: "If the exposed pillar becomes pregnant, is the child a boy or a girl?" Tianzhu reached over and pinched the master's knee, then walked away.

=== Yinyuan ===
E1: A lay patron who practiced spirit-writing brought a planchette session to the mountain after a rain offering. The "immortal" spirit claimed to be able to compose poetry. Yinyuan proposed a poetry duel. He offered the opening line: "The immortal elder braves the rain to visit my mountain home." He told the spirit: "Your turn -- be quick!" The planchette stopped. The spirit-writer urged it forward. The planchette remained motionless. Yinyuan thundered a great shout and declared: "It hesitates and freezes -- white clouds stretch ten thousand miles. It's just carved from wood -- where does the spirit come from? Where does the holiness arise? Don't try to fool this mountain monk." He then composed the full poem himself and had it handed to the planchette. The spirit managed a weak reply only after lunch, hours later. Yinyuan remarked: "Nice last line -- but you were a bit slow."
E2: A monk asked: "Does a dog have buddha-nature or not?" The Master said: "Don't bark at random."

=== Yinyuan Longqi ===
E1: A monk asked: "Does a dog have Buddha-nature or not?" The master said: "Don't bark."
E2: County Magistrate Ling asked: "It is difficult being companion to the ten thousand dharmas. How can one be free of companionship with the ten thousand dharmas?" The master gave a thundering shout and said: "Do you understand?" The magistrate said: "Not yet clear." The master said: "Do you want another ladle of foul water?" The magistrate was speechless. A little later he asked again: "After all, how is one free of companionship with the ten thousand dharmas?" The master said: "Passing through a hundred flowers, not a single petal clings to the body." The next evening during tea, the magistrate said: "Yesterday's instruction -- I am ashamed." The master said: "Who is ashamed?" The magistrate asked: "Why did the old master fall back into a wild fox body?" The master said: "What body are you right now?" The magistrate had no words. The master said: "Tonight I too shall fall into the animal realm!" Then he made a tiger's roar, turned around, and went back to his quarters.

=== Yisou Gao of Tongtian ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is my original face?" The Master pointed to the cypress tree in the courtyard: "See how green that cypress is." Then: "Do you understand?" The monk said: "I don't understand." "Ask the one who doesn't understand." The monk bowed and started to leave. The Master called after him. The monk turned his head. the Master replied: "Ha!"
E2: A monk asked: "When birth and death arrive, how does one avoid them?" The Master said: "Right now -- are you alive or dead?" The monk stood there blankly. the Master answered: "You don't even know whether you are alive or dead."

=== YIZHEN OF JIANTANG ===
E1: Addressing the assembly, the Master said: "One who studies after me is called a younger brother; wisdom born from the teacher is called a son. Therefore the teaching has the virtue of shaping and completing, and learning has the capacity for drawing upon and receiving. As they say, study and inquiry are truly the student's vocation, while explanation and elucidation are truly the teacher's task. But today it is not so. Below, not a single word is raised in questioning; above, a hundred dharma-doors are upheld for guidance. Yet still square and circle do not match, long and short are at odds. Because of this, I wring my hands in deep regret and furrow my brow in long sighs. Is there anyone among you who can put this sighing to rest?" He looked left and right and said: "To awaken oneself and awaken others -- only I am awake. To know the music and know what follows -- who else truly knows?"
E2: At Changlesi, Yizhen of Jiantang (Jiantang Yi) addressed the assembly: "The learning lies in him who comes after me -- that makes him a younger brother. Wisdom born from the teacher -- that makes him a son. Thus teaching has the merit of craftsmanship, and learning has the capacity of inheriting and carrying forward. Yet nowadays it is not so: the junior says not a word of questioning and debate, while the senior abandons a hundred methods of guidance and instruction. Moreover, the forms do not match and the measures are at odds. I therefore wring my hands in deep regret and furrow my brow with a long sigh. Tell me, is there anyone here who can catch his breath?" He looked left and right and said, "Awakening self and awakening others -- only I awaken. Knowing the sound and knowing what comes after -- who else knows?"

=== Yongji Rong ===
E1: When Yongji opened the hall at Pucisi to "prove the orthodox against heretics," a man named "Lone Strider" led a mob of heterodox followers and rushed the dharma seat. The master pointed his staff at them: "Ignorant fools! The gavel already struck -- that was your chance to ask questions. Instead you barge in during the teaching? Fine, I'll let you try." Lone Strider asked about the World-Honored One's flower and Kashyapa's smile. The master struck the floor with his staff: "Understand?" Lone Strider was speechless. The master hit him. Lone Strider started to deliberate. The master hit him again: "Standing corpse!" Lone Strider protested: "Why hit me when I'm asking a proper question?" The master said: "Don't you know that in the Linji house, blows fall like rain and shouts crash like thunder? You come here and take it as mere hitting." He struck him several more times, then continued his teaching. When he finished, a violent wind rose howling -- the assembly was astonished.
E2: Yongji raised the old case: Nun Moshan was asked by Guanxi, "What is Mount Mo?" She said: "Its peak is not exposed." "What is the master of Mount Mo?" She said: "Not male, not female." Guanxi shouted: "Why don't you transform!" She said: "I'm not a spirit, not a ghost -- what would I transform into?" Yongji commented: "Big Guanxi tried to measure Sumeru with a foot-ruler! And Nun Moshan, though she answered well, still didn't fully receive Guanxi." Then he offered his own reply: When asked 'What is Mount Mo?' -- just say 'A rabbit drinking cow's milk.'

=== Yongjue Yuanxian ===
E1: The lay magistrate Huang Hai'an asked: "Master, you received the dharma at Shouchang -- what did you get?" The master spread open both his hands. The magistrate immediately bowed. A monk then asked: "Seizing the vital crossing -- I won't ask about that. What about when you release the line?" The master held up his whisk. The monk said: "When the dragon finds water, its spirit doubles; when the tiger meets the mountain, its ferocity intensifies." He flicked his sleeves and returned to the assembly. The master just smiled.
E2: The magistrate escorted the master upstairs after a dharma talk. He asked: "To exhaust the view for a thousand miles, one must ascend yet another storey. What is the 'one more storey'?" The master snapped his fingers once. The magistrate said: "Is there still a step beyond?" The master said: "Don't have delusions." The magistrate said: "I've seen through you!" The master did not look back. The magistrate said: "How fortunate for the Shouchang lineage!" The master still did not look back, and went straight into his quarters.

=== YU'AN ZHIJI ===
E1: One day the Master was washing his hands when a monk asked, "What is the meaning of the Patriarch's coming from the West?" The Master splashed water on him. The monk ran away. The Master called after him: "Come! Come! In the old days when they splashed water and chased with a stick, monks wouldn't leave. Why did you run?" The monk then made a gesture of splashing water back. The Master said, "Now you're making conceptual understanding out of it." The monk gave a shout. The Master also shouted. The monk shouted again. The Master hit him. The monk said, "Master, don't wrongly hit me." The Master said, "Just take the beating. I need this exchange to circulate."
E2: One day the Master entered the garden and saw the head cook cutting melons. The Master asked, "How many patriarchs' heads have you cut off?" The cook said, "Thirty." the Master asked, "Which one has blood under the skin?" The cook said, "Master, why do you keep playing games?" The Master said, "Good intentions don't get good rewards."

=== Yuan'an Feng ===
E1: While the Master was hauling roof tiles, a monk asked, "Hauling bricks and tiles aside -- who actually benefits from all this?" said the Master, "Come haul tiles." The monk said, "In that case, I'll just go my own way." the Master responded, "Come back! Carry a load for me." The monk stepped forward. The Master picked up the carrying pole and walked off.
E2: The Master told a monk, "Close off your throat and lips, then say a single phrase." The monk said, "I don't understand -- please, Master, you say it." The Master said, "Close off your throat and lips, then ask me." The monk hesitated. The Master struck him.

=== Yuanhu Yong ===
E1: The Master asked Yunfeng Jun about Linji's ancestor: "The Linji patriarch has a single phrase -- how do you express it?" Jun shouted. The Master struck him. Jun shouted again. The Master struck him again. Jun bowed. The Master said: "So you're just a blind donkey." Jun flung his sleeves and walked out.
E2: Two monks came to visit. The Master asked: "What are you doing here?" The first monk said: "I've come specially to pay respects to the Master." the Master responded: "Too bad -- this old monk is not in." The monk had nothing to say. The Master said: "Take your thirty blows and get out." To the second: "And what about you?" The second monk said: "Please, Master, give me instruction." Just then the Master happened to cough. He said: "Too bad -- this old monk is coughing." That monk also had nothing to say. The Master said: "Well then, sit down and have some tea."

=== Yuanjie Ying ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master drew a circle in the air with his whisk and said: "Even this cannot be escaped. Since heaven and earth cannot escape this circle, neither can the myriad phenomena, neither sentient nor insentient beings, neither sages nor ordinary people. Not only can the holy and profane not escape -- this circle itself cannot escape this circle. Why? Wait until it smashes open the eye of heaven and earth, then raise your eyebrows and look from the back of your head."
E2: A layman named Zhou, afflicted with foot disease, requested the Master ascend the hall to expound the teaching and dissolve his karmic obstructions. The Master cited the Second Patriarch's famous dialogue: "Bring me your sin and I will cleanse it for you." The man searched long and finally said: "I search for the nature of sin and cannot find it anywhere." The Patriarch said: "Then I have finished cleansing your sin." The Master added: "I too have an ancient prescription. Whatever the obstruction -- past karma, present karma, or future karma -- none can be found." He struck with his whisk and said: "Past karma has no fixed form and cannot be grasped. Present karma has no abiding form and cannot be grasped. Future karma has no arriving form and cannot be grasped. Since none can be obtained, what is the phrase for 'the naked body, utterly without support'?" He raised the whisk: "In the flower streets and willow lanes there are no acquaintances -- only then do you see the true person beyond learning."

=== YUANSOU XINGDUAN ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall and raised an old case: A monk asked Nanquan, "The mani pearl -- people don't recognize it, but it is intimately stored in the Tathagata's treasury. What is the treasury?" Nanquan said, "Old Teacher Wang going back and forth with you -- that is the treasury." The monk said, "What about when there is no going and no coming?" Nanquan said, "That too is the treasury." The monk asked, "What is the pearl?" Nanquan called out to the monk. The monk responded. Nanquan said, "Go! You don't understand my words." The Master commented: "Although Nanquan's giving and taking away was a fine sight, the mani pearl has already been shattered by this monk. I won't spare my eyebrows -- I'll reveal a bit of the message for everyone. But I also invite the worthies everywhere to examine it critically." He held up his staff: "Is there anyone right now who has a question?"
E2: The Master ascended the hall for the end of summer retreat: "On the fifteenth of the fourth month we closed the retreat" -- he struck the staff once on the left -- "and everywhere monks confined their feet and settled in. On the fifteenth of the seventh month we open the retreat" -- he struck the staff once on the right -- "and everywhere monks rest from the summer and examine themselves freely. Before the empty kalpa, there was no name for 'buddha' and no name for 'sentient being.' If there is nothing to close, what are you closing? If there is nothing to open, what are you opening?" He leaned on his staff and descended the seat.

=== Yuantong Faxiu ===
E1: Yuantong Faxiu saw two monks standing together talking. He took his staff, went over, struck several times, and said: "One patch of karma-ground, all the more with the assembly heads of two halls who, because of a cat, caused contention."
E2: Wansong cites Yuantong Xiu's "Iron Wall" verse on natural beauty vs. imitation: "Why toil to comb the hair three times a day? If tied up firmly at the root, then let it rest. In the end, what wins is natural flesh and bone; without applying rouge and powder there is still grace."

=== Yuanwu Keqin ===
E1: The Master ascended the hall and raised a case: "Wang the Commissioner once visited Linji. They went to the monks' hall together. The Commissioner asked, 'Does this whole hall of monks read sutras?' Linji said, 'They do not read sutras.' The Commissioner said, 'Do they study Chan?' Linji said, 'They do not study Chan.' The Commissioner said, 'If they neither read sutras nor study Chan, what on earth are they doing?' Linji said, 'I am making them all become buddhas and patriarchs.' The Commissioner said, 'Gold dust, though precious, becomes a disease when it falls in the eye. What about that?' Linji said, 'And I took you for a mere layman!'" The Master commented: "Old Linji wielded the Diamond King's precious sword, his spirit filling the cosmos, striding freely throughout the world. But this official, with one light squeeze, melted his ice and shattered his tiles. Tell me -- what was this official's special power? Listen to a verse: Between the worldly and the transcendent, a rare event -- to reveal it requires a person of extraordinary measure. With the very hands that mend the chancellor's cap and stir the sovereign's soup, he turns the Tathagata's wheel of true dharma."
E2: The Master ascended the seat and said: "Fire does not wait for the sun to be hot. Wind does not wait for the moon to be cool. The crane's legs are naturally long. The duck's legs are naturally short. Pine trees are straight, brambles are crooked. The crane is white, the crow is black. Every single thing reveals itself completely. If you truly understand this, then wherever you stand you are the master; whatever conditions you meet, that is the teaching. Carrying your staff with you, wherever you find a stage, you put on a play."

=== Yue'an Shanguo ===
E1: "Master Yue'an asked a monk: 'Xi Zhong made a cart with a hundred spokes. Remove both ends, take away the axle -- what is made clear?'" Wumen's comment: "If you can straightaway make it clear, your eyes are like shooting stars, your functioning like a flashing bolt of lightning." The verse: "Where the wheel of function turns, even the adept are still deluded -- the four quarters above and below, north south east west."
E2: "National Teacher Shanguo of Yuantong said: 'Magu is yes; Nanquan is not.'"

=== Yuechuang Liao ===
E1: The Master asked a monk: "If your throat is seized shut, how will you speak?" The monk said: "I will not speak." The Master struck him out.
E2: A monk asked: "What is the Guiyang school?" The Master said: "Shut your dog-mouth." "What is the Caodong school?" "Open the door, close your eyes, and look." "What is the Yunmen school?" "Water dripping from a high cliff." "What is the Fayan school?" "Just this." The monk pressed: "And that one school?" The Master struck, then said: "Last night this mountain monk grabbed the Dragon King of the ocean and gave him a slap -- blood flowed everywhere, scales flew in all directions, scattering into the five gates. This morning they are divided into lineage principles. But I wonder: beneath whose jaw has the luminous pearl fallen?" A monk made a gesture of presenting a pearl. The Master struck him.

=== Yuejian ===
E1: Ascending the hall: "Delusion does not delude itself -- delusion is established only in contrast to awakening. Awakening does not awaken itself -- awakening is spoken of only because of delusion. Awakening is the substance of delusion; delusion is the function of awakening." He gave a shout: "Broad daylight, blue sky -- do not speak of dreams!"
E2: Yuejian raised the case: "A monk asked Kaixian: 'When the year is exhausted and the age is finished, what then?' Kaixian answered: 'Still the first month of spring remains cold.'" Yuejian commented: "Kaixian took the priceless night-shining pearl and jewel of linked cities and tossed them away as ordinary rubble. If tonight someone asks me: 'When the year is exhausted and the age is finished, what then?' I will only say to him: 'Still the first month of spring remains cold.'"

=== Yuejiang Zhengyin ===
E1: Ascending the hall: "Generally speaking, in any exchange of question and answer, push and press, you must be a practitioner of the original color before you can hold your own. You bring me Yunmen's half a sesame cake, and I'll give you half of Mount Sumeru. You bring me Zhaozhou's one cup of tea, and I'll give you one drop of the great ocean. If your eyes cannot accommodate Mount Sumeru and your ears cannot accommodate the ocean, don't go blaming anyone else."
E2: Raising Fushi's teaching: "This mountain monk has opened a fortune-telling booth to determine people's poverty, wealth, life, and death." A monk asked: "Apart from poverty, wealth, life, and death, beyond the five elements, please point directly!" Fushi answered: "Metal, wood, water, fire, earth." Yuejiang commented: "From the beginning, every Buddha, every patriarch, every old master under heaven has been nothing but a fortune teller. Fushi gave this instruction, but true listeners are rare. That monk tried to break through the barrier and only knocked his head against the wall. When Fushi said 'metal, wood, water, fire, earth' -- how do you understand? Recognize the intent on the hook; do not fixate on the marks of the dial."

=== Yuelin Shiguan ===
E1: Yuelin ascended the hall and raised the case: A monk asked Zhaozhou, "Does a dog have Buddha-nature or not?" Zhaozhou said, "Wu" (No/Nothing). Yuelin commented: "It cuts off a person's life-root without need of a second blade. The four seas are one family; the wind is calm and the waves are still."
E2: Yuelin ascended the hall and raised the case: There was an old woman at Mount Wutai. Whenever a monk asked, "Which way to Mount Wutai?" she would say, "Straight ahead." When the monk had gone three or five steps, she would say, "There goes another fine monk, just like all the rest." Zhaozhou heard of this and said, "Wait -- I'll go investigate that old woman for you." He went and asked the same question; the old woman gave the same answer. Zhaozhou returned and told the assembly, "I have seen through that old woman of Mount Wutai." Yuelin commented: "'Straight ahead, straight ahead' -- broad daylight, clear sky. 'Seen through' -- not worth a penny."

=== Yuezhou Qianfeng ===
E1: Yunmen visits Qianfeng and asks, "Please, Master, answer a saying." Qianfeng replies, "Even this old monk has not yet arrived." Yunmen says, "Then I am late." Qianfeng says, "So then, so then." Yunmen retorts: "I had thought there was only Marquis White, but there is also a Marquis Black."
E2: A monk asks Qianfeng, "The Bhagavans of the ten directions have one road, the gate of nirvana. I do not know where the road is." Qianfeng made one stroke with his staff and said, "It is here."

=== Yuezhou Wenzai ===
E1: Wenzai called on Wufang Kecong and said: "You have taught that 'one's own fundamental matter needs no outside seeking -- one must directly let it burst forth from one's own breast, and only then arrive home.' But what about the person who has no self, whose very essence is empty -- how do you receive him?" Before he finished speaking, Kecong slapped him across the face: "Is THAT what you think?" The master was suddenly, greatly awakened. He presented a verse: "A slap across the face -- lightning, sparks from flint. To plant one's life where no shadow falls: in the twelfth month, lotuses bloom petal by petal."
E2: One day Kecong asked: "The Second Patriarch made three bows and returned to his place -- what was his meaning?" The master said: "A tattered shirt and a patched jacket." Kecong said: "Not yet. Say more." The master said: "Straw sandals on, leather boots." Kecong shouted: "How strange!" The master flung his sleeves and walked out. Kecong stroked his back and sealed him: "One day when you carry on the teaching, the lineage will spread greatly through the realm. Be careful! Do not neglect it."

=== Yumeiliang ===
E1: Entering the Buddha Hall, the Master said: "Buddha is something from your own house." He looked left and right and said: "Recognize it directly!" Then he prostrated. Entering the Abbot's Room, he said: "From ancient times, every old awl who occupied this room spoke of the Way, spoke of principle, discussed the wondrous, discussed the profound. Even if they piled up brocade and gathered flowers with the cleverest novelties, not a single word of theirs hit the mark. What is Tianning's brand-new phrase for today?" He gave a shout and said: "When the tally arrives, execute the order."
E2: The Master addressed the assembly: "To leave home and investigate Chan, there is no separate method. You must simply recognize it right under your own feet. If you seek outside, there is no Chan at all. Why? All sentient beings, from the beginningless past, within the dusty toil of worldly circumstances, have let the six sense-faculties run wild, craved the six sense-objects. Root and dust are stained with ignorance and mixed poisons; deluded thoughts fly in confusion; you chase each one as it arises, never once turning back. You have stirred up the originally pure nature-essence until it is a turbid mess. This is the being who turns away from awakening and joins with dust. But the practitioner, in all twenty-four hours, the moment a deluded thought arises, immediately illuminates it, gathers in the six faculties, separates from the six objects, smashes ignorance, cuts off confusion. In time, the dust settles and the light is born. Then you can verify the pure original essence, perfectly luminous and unobstructed. This is the buddha who turns away from dust and joins with awakening. Therefore it is said: 'When deluded, all buddhas are just sentient beings. When awakened, all sentient beings are just buddhas.'"

=== Yun'an Puyan ===
E1: Yun'an addressed the assembly: "Last night at the third watch, in a dream I was blown by a black wind and fell into the Land of Rakshasas. I nearly lost my life. Fortunately the dawn bell sounded and I startled awake. Eyes open, eyes shut -- a thousand threads and a hundred tangles. This implicates Bodhidharma, Shakyamuni, the lacquer tubs in the patriarchs' hall, and all of you senior monks in this hall. Not one can be spared. Why? Benevolence and righteousness are the first things cut when poverty strikes; worldly sentiment always favors the house with money."
E2: Yun'an raised: At Deshan's evening gathering, Deshan said he wouldn't answer questions, hooking them to a place beyond doubt. A monk stepped forward -- already caught. Deshan struck him. The monk said, "I haven't even asked my question yet -- why do you strike me?" -- a fellow who doesn't recognize pain. Deshan said, "Where are you from?" -- a second iron hammer descending. The monk said, "Silla." -- his voice carrying him out. Deshan said, "Before you even stepped onto the boat, you already deserved thirty blows." -- thunder roaring, but not a single drop of rain. Yun'an commented: "For all his mighty reputation, Deshan ended up a dragon-head with a snake-tail, leading this monk to thrash about in the weeds. At the moment the monk said 'I haven't even asked yet -- why do you strike me?', the blow should have landed at the soles of his feet and given thirty more. Why? When helping someone, help them all the way through."

=== Yune Xi ===
E1: One day the Master led a donkey up to the dharma hall and said: "Here is a ready-made case. If any of you can say one turning-word that matches my intention, I will hand over my staff and whisk with both hands." He lifted his foot and said: "How is my foot like a donkey's foot?" He raised his hand and said: "How is my hand like the Buddha's hand?" Then: "Everyone has a birth-connection -- where is yours?" No one in the assembly could answer to his satisfaction. For "my foot like a donkey's foot" the Master supplied: "Just bow." For "my hand like the Buddha's hand": "Just bow." For "where is your birth-connection": "Ride the donkey off to eat grass."
E2: The Master had just moved into the run-down Puji monastery. One night a violent wind tore the whole roof off. The next day he addressed the assembly with a verse: "I've only been here half a year, still patching the thatch and not yet settled, when a wild wind suddenly rolls everything away -- lying on my bench, I gaze up at blue sky. Relax your belly, go with what comes -- safety and danger are just the same."

=== Yunfu Zhi ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master said: "The entire ten-direction world is a great gate of liberation. You drag people by the hand and they will not enter. Yet you should know this gate of liberation encompasses the six realms and four types of birth, all sentient and insentient beings -- all are already fully inside it. Viewed with the correct eye, not a single thing is seen coming or going." He raised his staff and struck the ground once: "Do you understand? Coming and going, the whole body is revealed; there is simply no object that conceals the journey."
E2: Ascending the hall, the Master said: "Stop! Stop! There is no need to speak. My Dharma is subtle and hard to conceive. Those of overweening pride will surely not believe it if they hear. I dare not look down on any of you -- all of you shall become buddhas. I only wish that all of you, in the twelve hours of the day, eat when hungry, sleep when tired, and refrain from any further thinking or contriving. Would that not be splendid?" After a long silence: "Twenty years of taking medicine, never knowing this illness is incurable."

=== YUNGU ===
E1: In the evening, the Master held a small gathering and raised the case: "Treasure Minister Bao sent someone to relay a message to Master Si Da, saying: 'Why don't you come down from the mountain and teach living beings? Why do you just stare at the clouds?' Si Da said: 'The Buddhas of the three worlds have been swallowed in one gulp by me. What living beings are there to teach?' The Master commented: These two venerable elders -- one had a mouth sweet but a heart bitter; the other got drunk just from being propped up. Within the teaching tradition, that may be fine. But under the gate of the patchrobed monk, there must be blood dripping, drop by drop." He struck the ground once with his staff and said: "A cart does not push sideways; reason knows no crooked judgment."
E2: Ascending the hall, the Master raised the case: "Yaoshan was sitting when a monk asked: 'What are you thinking of, sitting there so still and solid?' Yaoshan said: 'I'm thinking of that which does not think.' The monk said: 'How do you think of that which does not think?' Yaoshan said: 'It is non-thinking.'" The Master offered a verse: "An ancient gnarled tree leans in the cold forest, snow pressing down, frost burying, the message of spring hidden deep. Suddenly a fine wind gently stirs it -- listen closely, and it is entirely the dragon's song."

=== Yungu Fahui ===
E1: Yungu had practiced in seclusion for years and attained a state he described as "the moon illuminating a cold pool." One day a wandering practitioner in rough hemp clothes visited him. The master presented his realization. The visitor scolded: "Strip away every last bit of 'seeing,' and everything is just ordinary. What you have attained, thinking it supremely profound and marvelous -- this is all just activity in a ghost-cave!" The master tried to say something. The visitor shouted fiercely: "What you call 'ordinary' -- what is it? What you call 'marvelous' -- what is it?" Without giving his name, the visitor shook out his sleeves and left. The master was vastly shaken. Twenty years of attainment dissolved completely.
E2: The layman Yuan Liaofan visited Yungu and they sat together in dhyana day and night. The master noticed Yuan did not produce a single stray thought. He asked: "How is it you have no idle thoughts?" Yuan said: "A fortune-teller determined my fate -- no success in the examinations, no children. So I have resigned myself to destiny. I have nothing left to fantasize about." The master said: "I took you for a man of outstanding caliber. You turn out to be merely ordinary! The sages say: fate is self-made, blessings are self-sought. How can the workings of creation bind a person?" He then showed Yuan the method of correcting faults and accumulating merit. Yuan followed the teaching faithfully and went on to pass the imperial examinations and have a son.

=== Yunhuanchen ===
E1: A monk asked: "If a single dharma exists, Vairochana falls into the rank of ordinary beings. If the myriad dharmas are empty, Samantabhadra loses his realm. Apart from these two paths, please speak at once." the Master responded: "Those in the east sit on the east side." The monk bowed. The Master said: "Those in the west sit on the west side."
E2: On the Master's birthday, he ascended the hall. A monk asked: "What is the unborn phrase?" The Master said: "Golden chrysanthemums are blooming, facing all directions." The monk asked: "What is the phrase after extinction?" the Master responded: "Winter plum draped in snow is even more exquisite." Then the Master said: "Everyone says today I was born. I say this day, this year, I die. This year is actually last year's occasion; next year will start again from the beginning. I fish up the bright moon to sell its elegance -- who can recognize the cosmic calendar of level heaven?"

=== Yunju Daoying ===
E1: Dongshan asks Yunju, "A great icchantika kills father and harms mother -- where is filial support then?" Yunju says, "Only then is filial support fulfilled."
E2: A monk asks Yunju, "When alone lodging on a solitary peak, how is it?" Yunju says, "If you do not sleep in the nine-bay monks' hall, who told you to go lodge on a solitary peak?"

=== Yunmen Wenyan ===
E1: Yunmen arrives at Muzhou's gate. Muzhou slams the door shut. Yunmen knocks. Muzhou asks "Who?" Yunmen gives his name. Muzhou asks "What do you want?" Yunmen says his own matter is not yet clear and asks for instruction. Muzhou opens the door, looks at him, then slams it shut again. This happens three days in a row. On the third day, when Muzhou opens the door, Yunmen pushes his way in. Muzhou grabs him and shouts "Speak! Speak!" Yunmen hesitates. Muzhou pushes him out saying "A cart-axle from the Qin dynasty!" and slams the door on Yunmen's foot, breaking it. Yunmen attains awakening from this.
E2: A monk asks Yunmen, "What is Buddha?" Yunmen says: "A dried dung stick." Wumen's comment: "Yunmen may be said to: The household is poor, so plain food must do; affairs are busy, so cursive script must serve. At a move he brings out a dung stick to brace the gate and prop the door."

=== Yunsou Zhu ===
E1: Addressing the assembly, the Master said: "Here at Dragon Fang, the shop is newly opened. We do not serve the surpassing-Buddha-and-Ancestors biscuit-Zen, nor the hundred-flavors sour-stuffing-Zen, nor the assorted five-flavor Zens of other places. We simply boil a single serving of no-rice porridge, waterless broth, and taking up old Ancestor Judun's cracked wooden ladle, without asking whether you are donkey or horse, saint or commoner -- whoever comes gets a ladleful or two." He raised the whisk and said: "Right now, please extend your bowls, each of you gets a serving. But tell me, what flavor is it?" He set down the whisk: "Only one who never comes is full from no-rice porridge."
E2: The Master addressed the assembly: "Spring has left the gate; green deepens in the courtyard." He raised his staff: "Before heaven and earth were divided, this spring had already bloomed. After the universe collapses, this spring remains brilliantly splendid. The four seasons and ten thousand things cannot cause this spring to flourish or wither -- yet this spring causes the four seasons and all things to flourish or wither." He held up the staff again: "Is this flourishing? Withering? The four seasons? The myriad things? This spring? The staff?" After a long silence he threw it down, laughed enormously, and said: "I thought spring had gone beyond finding -- who knew it had simply entered right here?"

=== YUNWAI YUNXIU ===
E1: Ascending the hall, Yunxiu said: "Thirty years ago, at the foot of Daochang Mountain in Huzhou, the ox belonging to Shen the Twelfth produced a heifer calf. I tell this to all of you, but none of you believe it. This mountain monk personally went to the house and asked to see it. Two horns pointed at heaven, four hooves pressed the earth. Its tail waved in the wind, its nostrils drew in air. Though its teeth had not yet grown in, it already understood the business of plowing fields and harrowing ground. Tell me -- is this remarkable or not?" He patted the platform and said: "No one under heaven understands this meaning."
E2: On the Lantern Festival, Yunxiu ascended the hall: "Last night this mountain monk had an extraordinary dream. I dreamt that at the bottom of the Great Eastern Ocean, someone lit a single bowl-lamp. Immediately the waters of all four seas blazed with brilliant light, and every fish, dragon, shrimp, and crab could be seen in perfect clarity. The Dragon King of the Ocean went with all the dragon kings to the palace of Lord Indra to report this matter. Indra assembled all the gods and dragon kings and descended together into this world of ours to investigate: 'What cause has produced this wonder?' At that point, this mountain monk woke from his dream. Today happens to be the Lantern Festival, and it would be wrong not to share this dream with all of you. If you can trust it completely, naturally there will be brilliant radiance. If you cannot trust it -- well, who could blame you?"

=== Yunwaize of Shending ===
E1: A monk asked: "When you seize, heaven and earth lose their color; when you release, broken tiles and pebbles shine with light. Right now the full command is raised -- who dares face its edge?" The master said: "Raise your eyes higher." The monk said: "Then I'll go straight home." The master said: "Three thousand miles away, face to face." The monk pressed: "Will you permit me to reveal some news of the supreme matter?" The master said: "You try saying something." The monk said: "The wild colors have no mountain to block them." The master said: "For birds to roost in the forest is easy; for a person to get free of right and wrong is hard."
E2: A monk asked: "When all activity ceases, what then?" The master said: "Do not betray this question of yours." The monk said: "Then I will shoulder it directly." The master said: "And now you betray me -- why?" The monk tried to open his mouth. The master struck him. The monk said: "My arrows are spent and my bow broken. I beg the master's compassion -- show me a gate of peace and ease." The master struck him again, saying: "You broken-down monk! If I don't hit you now, when should I?"

=== Yunyan Tansheng ===
E1: Yunyan asks Daowu: "The Great Compassion Bodhisattva uses so many hands and eyes -- for what?" Daowu: "Like a person in the middle of the night, reaching back to feel for the pillow." Yunyan: "I understand -- the whole body is hands and eyes." Daowu: "You said far too much; you only said eighty percent." Yunyan: "How do you say it?" Daowu: "The entire body is hands and eyes."
E2: Yunyan was sweeping the ground. Daowu said: "Too busy, too busy." Yunyan said: "You should know there is one who is not busy." Daowu: "In that case, there is a second moon." Yunyan held up the broom and said: "Which moon is this?" Daowu stopped and left.

=== Yushan Shangsi ===
E1: A monk came to the hall and said, "The drum of Heshan, the ball of Xuefeng -- never mind bringing those out. Please, Master, unfurl your own battle flags." The master struck him. The monk shouted. The master covered his ears. The monk stood silent. The master struck him again. Another monk stepped forward: "When light and darkness are both forgotten, what is reality?" The master said, "I get here and I don't recognize it." The monk pressed: "Can you fool the whole assembly?" The master replied, "Let me start by fooling just you." The monk persisted: "If I hadn't come up, how would I know the truth?" The master said, "A hundred thousand miles is not yet far."
E2: A monk asked, "What is the place where all Buddhas emerge?" The master said, "One drop of water, one drop of ice." Another monk asked, "Mind is not Buddha, wisdom is not the Way -- please point directly." The master said, "All you have is a mouth fit to hang on the wall." The monk pressed: "Then the student has freedom at last." The master said, "What principle do you see?" The monk tried a verse: "They told me not to walk the mountain road below -- and sure enough, I heard the heartbreaking cry of monkeys." The master said, "Idle talk." And the discourse continued: "Today is the eighth of the twelfth month. The yellow-faced old man Gautama had no special talent. He babbled about enlightenment under the morning star -- middle of the night, just blathering nonsense."

=== Yuzhaoyunfen of Hongshan ===
E1: A monk asked, "The weather freezes, the water congeals to ice -- what is the Master's household style?" The Master said, "Piercing to the bone and marrow." The monk asked, "When a guest arrives, how will you entertain him?" The Master said, "Two people sharing one bowl." The monk bowed. The Master said, "Tomorrow I'll give you another beating."
E2: A monk asked, "In the remote mountains the Dharma is seldom encountered; on New Year's Day the household style is spread wide -- what is the Master's very first phrase?" The Master said, "Today is the first day of the first month." The monk said, "Fresh new orders -- please carry them out!" The Master said, "Respectfully -- may the officials and elder monks enjoy ten thousand blessings."

=== Yuzhe Zhi ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the born prince?" The Master said: "It did not begin today." "What is the court-attending prince?" "He faces north and bows to the golden subtlety." "What is the last-born prince?" "He walks alone and never turns his back." "What is the transformed prince?" "His great function turns the red wheel." "What is the inner-born prince?" "Watch out -- the five-colored clouds of nobility are about to fall." "Before the prince ascends the throne?" "There is nowhere to look up to." "After he has ascended?" "He sits with folded hands -- no one dares peer in." "After that?" "The wind blows and the grass bends."
E2: A monk asked: "Binding is thus, releasing is thus -- why not be free of both binding and releasing?" The Master waved his whisk and said: "How can one help being vexed by this spring wind year after year?" The monk pressed: "Not binding is thus, not releasing is thus -- so why are Indra's net and interlocking reeds and hooks and awls spread everywhere?" the Master asked: "How can one help being unable to leave the dust of advancing and retreating?" The monk pressed: "Cut off both ends -- what then is liberation?" The Master struck him on the head with the whisk. The monk said: "Then the whole body is revealed!" The Master turned the whisk and said: "Sitting and dwelling only become toil." Then he said: "I have one long whistle -- to whom shall I entrust it? Since direct telling is not believed, all this chatter is in vain. Enough! Enough! Enough! Each of you, go your way. Those who go -- your straw sandals have thorns that catch in the mud. Those who stay -- don't miss the cloud-board's call to the dining hall. Let one person wander at ease with nothing to do, carrying a lantern into the green mountains to chant poems." He struck the whisk and said: "Know your error." He held up the whisk and said: "What is it that is free of both binding and releasing?" He put down the whisk and said: "I don't know."

=== Zhangjing Huaihui ===
E1: Magu carries his staff to Zhangjing, circles the seat three times, shakes his staff once, and stands upright. Zhangjing says: "Yes, yes." Magu then takes that "yes" to Nanquan and performs the same ritual. Nanquan says: "No, no." Magu: "Zhangjing said yes; why does master say no?" Nanquan: "Zhangjing is yes; it is you who are no."
E2: A monk came and circled Zhangjing Huaihui three times, then planted his staff and stood there. Zhangjing said, "Yes! Yes!" The same monk then went to Nanquan, circled Nanquan three times, planted his staff, and stood there. Nanquan said, "No! No! This is merely turned by the force of the wind, and will ultimately decay." The monk said, "Zhangjing said 'yes.' Why does the Master say 'no'?" Nanquan said, "Zhangjing's 'yes' is correct. It is you who are wrong."

=== ZHANRAN YUANCHENG ===
E1: On the Dragon Boat Festival, Zhanran said: "Barely past the eighth of April and already the Dragon Boat arrives. Listen well, Chan practitioners -- time flashes like lightning. Worldly things appear and disappear. Human feelings swing between elation and disgust. King Prasenajit said: 'Change steals forward in secret. I truly do not notice it. Through the drift of cold and heat, I have gradually come to this.' All of you -- do you know of something that does not drift?" He suddenly seized his staff. "Only this staff stands free and clear. Neither heat nor cold can shorten its life. Neither gods nor ghosts can envy its good fortune." He paused. "Even so, from the standpoint of a true monk, this is still dust in the eye." He struck the ground once with the staff. Then he raised the case: "Ruiyan asked Yantou: 'What is the principle of the Eternal?' Yantou said: 'Movement.' Ruiyan asked: 'When it moves, what then?' Yantou said: 'Then you don't see the principle of the Eternal.' After a long silence, Yantou said: 'If you affirm it, you haven't escaped the dust of the senses. If you don't affirm it, you sink forever in birth and death.' At those words, Ruiyan was greatly awakened." The Master added: "That was simply pressing the ox's head down to the water."
E2: Ascending the hall, Zhanran said: "Deshan, the old man, once declared: 'Whether prajna has form or is formless -- only I know.' He spent a thousand kalpas studying the Buddha's subtle conduct and ten thousand kalpas studying the Buddha's awesome bearing, and still hadn't become a Buddha. He said: 'Those demon-children in the south dare claim they point directly at the human mind and see its nature to become Buddha! I'll tear apart their den and wipe out their fox-breed to repay the Buddha's deep kindness.' So he shouldered his commentaries and left Sichuan. On the road he met an old woman selling snacks. She asked: 'What texts are you carrying?' He said: 'The Qinglong Commentary.' She asked: 'On what sutra?' He said: 'The Diamond Sutra.' The woman said: 'I have one question. If you answer it, I'll give you a snack. If you can't answer, find your refreshment elsewhere.' He said: 'Ask.' She said: 'The Diamond Sutra says: Past mind cannot be grasped, future mind cannot be grasped, present mind cannot be grasped. Which mind does the Venerable wish to refresh?' Deshan was speechless. That fellow had been an ocean of learning in Sichuan -- and one old woman's question killed him stone dead. Later, at Longtan's place, when the paper candle was blown out, he suddenly awakened. The next day he burned all his commentaries on the Dharma platform and said: 'Exhausting all abstruse arguments is like placing a single hair in the vastness of space. Depleting all the world's pivotal strategies is like casting a single drop into the great ocean.' After that he built a grass hut, reviled Buddhas, cursed patriarchs. Brothers, seeing how simple this seems, you refuse to do the work. You just peer east and west through the gates the ancients set up, memorize a phrase or two of living language, and declare you're done. You don't realize: Deshan in Sichuan already claimed that only he understood prajna. The work he put in was immense. Only upon awakening at Longtan did he realize that all his former learning was a single hair, a single drop -- and today's awakening was the vast sky, the boundless ocean."

=== Zhaozhou Congshen ===
E1: A monk said to Zhaozhou, "I have just entered the monastery. Please teach me." Zhaozhou said, "Have you eaten your rice porridge?" The monk said, "Yes, I have." Zhaozhou said, "Then go wash your bowl." The monk had an insight.
E2: The monks of the east and west halls are disputing over a cat. Nanquan picks up the cat and says "If you can speak, I will not cut it." No one can answer, so Nanquan cuts the cat in two. That evening Zhaozhou returns from outside. Nanquan tells him the story and asks "How would you have saved the cat?" Zhaozhou puts one sandal on his head and walks out. Nanquan says: "If you had been there, the cat would have been saved."

=== Zhe'an Fan ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is it like when the precious sword has not left its sheath?" The master said: "Its radiance pierces the stars." The monk asked: "And after it leaves the sheath?" The master said: "Still too dull to cut vegetables."
E2: A monk said: "I have been investigating 'Who is it?' but can find no ground at all. Please, master, give me instruction." The master said: "The wind is strong today. Do you feel cold?" The monk said: "Cold." The master called out loudly: "Who?!" The monk hesitated. The master immediately pushed him out.

=== Zhenjing Kewen ===
E1: Yuanwu quotes Zhenjing's verse: "Beating drums, playing the pipa -- two who understand meet." Used in Yuanwu's discussion of how genuine Chan communication works between adepts, like two musicians in perfect accord.
E2: Zhenjing Kewen was spending the summer retreat at Dawei. He heard a monk raise the case: "A monk asked Yunmen, 'Is the Buddhadharma like the moon reflected in water?' Yunmen said, 'Clear waves offer no path through.'" Kewen thereupon had an understanding. He went to see Huanglong Huinan, but they did not connect. Kewen said to himself, "I have something fine; this old fellow simply doesn't recognize me." He then went to Xiangcheng and called on Master Shun. Shun asked, "Where do you come from?" Kewen said, "From Huanglong." Shun said, "What has Huanglong been saying lately?" Kewen reported the episode of how Huanglong had asked the assembly to supply a turning word about "chanting the litany in the bell tower and planting vegetables under the bed," and how Senior Student Sheng answered "A fierce tiger sits athwart the road," and was appointed to preside at Huangbo. Shun said involuntarily, "Senior Sheng merely produced one turning word and got Huangbo to preside over! He hasn't even dreamed of the Buddhadharma." At these words, Kewen was greatly awakened and finally understood Huanglong's way of working. He returned to see Huanglong. Huanglong asked, "Where have you come from?" Kewen said, "I have come especially to pay my respects to the Master." Huanglong said, "It happens that the old monk is not here." Kewen said, "Where has he gone?" Huanglong said, "Tiantai has gone for a communal work session; Nanyue has gone sightseeing in the mountains." Kewen said, "In that case, this student may take his freedom." Huanglong said, "Where did you get those shoes on your feet?" Kewen said, "I bought them in Lushan for seven hundred and fifty cash." Huanglong said, "How is that freedom?" Kewen pointed to his shoes and said, "How is it not freedom?" Huanglong was struck with admiration.

=== ZHENXIE QINGLIAO ===
E1: When Qingliao first met Master Danxia, Danxia asked: "What is your original self before the empty kalpa?" Qingliao was about to answer. Danxia cut him off: "You're too noisy -- get out." One day, climbing Bowl Peak, Qingliao suddenly experienced a great opening. He went straight back to see Danxia. He had just taken his place to stand beside the master when Danxia slapped him across the ear and said: "I thought you actually knew something." Qingliao bowed joyfully. The next day, Danxia ascended the hall and said: "Sunlight on a lone peak, green. Moonlight on the valley stream, cold. The ancestral patriarch's wondrous secret -- do not try to settle it in the inch of your mind." Then he descended. Qingliao said: "Today when you ascended the hall, you could no longer deceive me." Danxia said: "Try to present my teaching for me." Qingliao stood silent for a long time. Danxia said: "I thought you weren't taken in." Qingliao turned and walked out.
E2: Qingliao visited Master Yungai. Yungai asked: "How do you understand the story of the girl coming out of samadhi?" Qingliao said: "Close up the skin bag." Yungai said: "Not so. I'll enter samadhi myself -- you try to bring me out." He drew up his feet and sat in formal posture. Qingliao shoved him bodily to the floor and walked out.

=== Zhenzai of Shanduo ===
E1: During a snowfall, the Master cited: "Yangqi addressed the assembly: 'When Yangqi first arrived, the walls were full of gaps and the bed was covered with snow-pearls. I drew in my neck, sighing silently, and recalled the ancients who lived beneath trees.'" His own teacher, Jinming, had said: "For ten years at Jinming in a broken-down hut, I let the wind and rain come and stopped sighing about it. Sleeping soundly on a high pillow, better than a mountain hermitage -- at ease I sing a little song of contentment." The Master added his own verse: "Already at Donglin in the tenth-month cold, / every morning I pick up fallen rafters. / Don't be lazy, don't idle away, / I too must earn my porridge-and-rice money."
E2: The Master cited Fu Dashi's verse: "Empty-handed, grasping the hoe-handle; walking on foot, riding the water-buffalo. A man crosses over the bridge -- the bridge flows, the water does not." He then cited three different commentaries on it, adding his own: "Fu Dashi should not have used public goods to curry private favors, and Patriarch Lun claimed the verse for his own -- by the law, both deserve three thousand strokes at dawn and eight hundred at dusk. Old Hao shouldered the burden with all his might, but 'as before, how pitiable.' Donglin also has a verse: In spring sleep one does not notice the dawn; / everywhere one hears the birds singing. / In the night came the sound of wind and rain -- / who knows how many flowers have fallen?"

=== Zhikongyun ===
E1: At the opening hall, a monk's voice had barely begun his question when the Master gave a great shout. The monk bowed and said: "The troops follow the seal, the generals follow the tally. Now that you lead the assembly and ascend the hall, where is the seal?" The Master struck him and said: "One blow, one welt." The monk pressed: "What did Nanyun, the Old Man of the Southern Cloud, bestow upon you?" The Master struck again: "You fellow who cannot tell pain from itch." The monk continued: "That belongs to the Old Man of the Southern Cloud. What about on your own account?" The Master hit him with two consecutive blows.
E2: the Master responded: "Jiashan said: 'There is no dharma before the eyes; the intention is before the eyes. It is not a dharma before the eyes -- it is not what ears and eyes can reach.' Yanzi said: 'Looking up, it is ever higher; boring in, it is ever harder. Gazing, it is before me; suddenly it is behind.' Look at these two great elders -- though their starting points differ, their destinations are the same. It confirms that principle admits no discrepancy, and ancient and modern are one. Even so, you must examine finely and discern precisely before you can stand securely."

=== Zhimen Guangzuo ===
E1: A monk asks Zhimen: "What about when the lotus has not yet emerged from the water?" Zhimen says: "Lotus." The monk asks: "After it emerges from the water, what then?" Zhimen says: "Lotus leaf." The commentary notes this answer "severs the tongues of everyone under heaven."
E2: A monk asks Zhimen: "What is the substance of prajna?" Zhimen says: "A clam holds the bright moon." The monk asks: "What is the function of prajna?" Zhimen says: "A rabbit carries a fetus." Both images refer to mid-autumn moon folklore -- the clam opens its mouth and takes in moonlight, producing a pearl; the rabbit swallows moonlight and becomes pregnant.

=== Zhitan Zheng ===
E1: A monk asked: "Within heaven and earth, within the cosmos, there is a single treasure. Where is this treasure?" The master said: "Form." The monk continued: "The treasure has been pointed out. What about the matter of ending the retreat?" The master said: "Emptiness." The monk pressed: "Without trace or track, what is there to make use of?" The master said: "Function." The monk hesitated. The master struck him. The monk bowed and returned to his place.
E2: Citing an old case: A monk asked Jiufeng Qian: "I have heard the master say 'All the sages who have appeared were merely messengers.' Is this so?" The master said: "Yes." The monk said: "The World-Honored One pointed one hand to heaven and one to earth, saying 'Above the heavens and below, I alone am the honored one.' Why do you call him a mere messenger?" Jiufeng said: "Precisely because he pointed one hand to heaven and one to earth -- that is why I call him a messenger." Zhitan's comment: "A pair of holeless iron hammers."

=== Zhiyan Xiu ===
E1: A monk asked for the five schools of Chan. "What is the Linji school?" -- "One blow, one welt." "The Caodong school?" -- "No night travel; arrive by dawn." "The Yunmen school?" -- "The sun behind your skull glows red." "The Fayan school?" -- "Arrow-points meeting." "The Weiyang school?" -- The master struck a circle with his staff: "All of empty space bundled into one ball." The monk pressed: "Five schools pointed out -- but what about seeing one's nature and becoming Buddha?" The master raised his whisk: "Do you recognize this?" The monk said: "I do." The master said: "Then you'd better treasure it."
E2: Someone asked: "What is the past Buddha?" -- "The one in the hall." "What is the present Buddha?" -- "A golden body cast in purple-gold." "What is the future Buddha?" -- "Make your bow." The monk pressed: "The three Buddhas of past, present, and future -- you've pointed them out. But where exactly are their nostrils?" The master struck him: "Strung on a single thread."

=== Zhuanyuheng ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the eternally abiding true mind?" the Master answered: "Mouse droppings are pointed; sheep droppings are round." The monk continued: "What then is delusion?" The Master said: "Peach blossoms are red; plum blossoms are white."
E2: A monk asked: "What kind of person can use the eternally abiding true mind?" The Master said: "Black donkeys and white oxen." The monk continued: "What kind of person uses delusion?" The Master said: "All Buddhas and bodhisattvas." The monk pressed: "Why are all Buddhas and bodhisattvas inferior to black donkeys and white oxen?" The Master said: "How can you blame them?"

=== ZHUFENG MIN ===
E1: Master Chuiwan, in his youth, encountered the record of Dahui Gao and sighed: "This is the precious raft across the bitter sea, the bright torch illuminating the dark night. I only regret I was not born in his time, that I might have wandered with this old fellow." He went to Chaoyang and called on Master Lianchi to ask about the dharma beyond the world. For a long time he investigated beyond words and sounds, but could not pierce through. He built a hut on Fozi Mountain and spent three cycles of cold and heat in solitary practice. Then he returned to Chaoyang, bowed before Lianchi, and asked: "Ultimately, how does one make it manifest?" Lianchi placed his hand over Chuiwan's mouth. Chuiwan was instantly and vastly awakened.
E2: Master Zhufeng Min (Zhufeng of Zhiping, Sichuan) once addressed the assembly: "The red banner raised, the Caoxi source waters flow -- forever moistening the stream of the Linji line. The dharma seat opens, solemn as Vulture Peak, forever enduring. The lion's roar has resounded for years, the six supernatural powers perfectly penetrating. Driving the ox-cart without end, the four assemblies all rely upon it." A monk asked, "What is the meaning of the Patriarch coming from the West?" Min said, "Where there is water, all contains the moon; no mountain fails to bear the clouds." The monk said, "Is there nothing more remarkable?" Min said, "Don't mistake a tortoise for a turtle."

=== Zhufeng of Santa ===
E1: The well had run dry. The Master prayed to the well-spirit: "Dragon-spirit, dragon-spirit, awesome and numinous -- if there is water, I stay; if there is no water, I leave." The next morning the well was half-full of sweet spring, enough to supply the whole community.
E2: One day the Master's teacher visited the abbot's quarters and saw the image of the Send-child Guanyin. He asked: "What image is this?" The Master answered: "The Child-giving Guanyin -- prayers are always answered." The teacher said: "She spends all day granting children to others. Why doesn't she seek one for herself?" The Master replied: "What she seeks is not a child." The teacher said: "Even so, she must still exert herself." The Master immediately struck the drum and addressed the assembly, speaking of the need for collective effort in maintaining the monastery.

=== ZHUFENGXU OF ZHAOJUE ===
E1: Ascending the hall, the Master said: "When the primal vitality first divided, beginning and end never departed from this present thought. When forms separated in creation, self and other were never farther apart than a hair's breadth. Boundless lands of the universe are fully displayed on the tip of a single hair. All ages past and present return to the palace of the Dharma King. Sitting in judgment, blocking the pass so tightly that not a drop of water leaks through; throwing the gates wide open, letting dust fly and earth scatter. Overturn the great ocean, smash empty space -- everywhere is Maitreya's tower, everyone possesses Sudhana's adornment. When you press through to where there is no way out, you still must borrow a road along the side." Holding his staff crosswise, he looked at the assembly and said: "The sword leaves its jeweled scabbard because of injustice in the world; medicine leaves the golden bottle because of illness."
E2: At Zhaojue Monastery, Zhufengxu (True Continuation) was once asked by a visiting official, who said, "The sutras teach that all sentient beings possess Buddha-nature. If so, why is practice necessary?" Zhufengxu replied, "Though gold lies in the ore, without smelting it does not shine." Later, during a dharma assembly, he addressed the monks: "Clear tranquility serves as governance; compassion suffices as love for the people." He then held up his staff and said, "This mountain monk has lived in the empty gate for over fifty years, taking stillness as his heart and compassion as his teaching. The officials and scholars of Yizhou have all received guidance in dispelling confusion. Even the civil and military officers of the provincial capital pay reverence. But tell me, what is the meaning of the Patriarch coming from the West?" He struck his staff once and said, "The pine before the gate is green for a thousand years; the crane on the peak cries once and the sky is clear."

=== Zhulangsheng ===
E1: When visitors asked for instruction, the Master would suddenly stick out his foot and say: "This is the freshest Buddhadharma. This is the place where you plant your life. If you understand, you are no different from the old fellow before Vulture Peak. If you have not yet understood..." Then he would pull his foot back and say: "Return my topic of inquiry."
E2: From the preface by his dharma-brother Chegang: "The Master never peddled warmed-over Zen. In the cracks between his labors -- between hoe-strokes and resting in the shade -- he would bring up pivotal matters, releasing and gathering at will. An eyeless flute, a stringless lute -- they awoke the deaf and the blind."

=== Zhuofeng Jue ===
E1: "There is no special method for investigating Chan. Just take a saying from a clear-eyed master and raise fierce doubt where you cannot understand. Doubt while walking, doubt while standing, doubt while sitting, doubt while lying down. When stray thoughts arise, be aware they are stray thoughts -- do not try to cut them off. Just take up your original saying clearly and keenly; the stray thoughts will naturally dissolve, and the stray thoughts themselves become the saying. Push on until you cannot drink though thirsty, cannot eat though hungry, cannot walk, cannot sit, cannot sleep -- dull and stupid, like a breathing corpse. At such a time, meet a master-thief who strips you of everything, who beats you morning and night demanding your original face. When you reach the place where you can neither live nor die, then suddenly while dressing you touch your belt, while washing your face you touch your nose -- only then do you realize your own eyebrows were never on someone else's face."
E2: Ascending the hall: "Heaven is not high, earth is not thick, water is not cold, fire is not dry. The wood person deliberately walks to Chang'an; the stone woman watches from the side, clapping and laughing. What is she laughing at? Those who arrive, I do not point out; those I point out have not arrived."

=== Zhuyan Yan ===
E1: The Master addressed the assembly. He raised this: "Great Master Yunmen said: 'All day long you eat rice, yet you have never bitten a single grain.' The King of Zhenzhou asked Zhaozhou: 'Venerable one, you are old -- how many teeth do you have?' Zhaozhou said: 'Only one.' The King said: 'How can you chew anything?' Zhaozhou said: 'Though it is only one, every bite hits the mark.'" The Master said: "Zhaozhou hits the mark with every bite; Yunmen never bites at all. Tell me -- is the one who never bites correct? Or the one who hits with every bite? Only with the single eye can you see into this." He suddenly took up his staff and said: "Hard to escape the lion's mouth." When the assembly tried to respond, he drove them all out at once.
E2: The Master addressed the assembly. He raised this: "A monk asked an ancient worthy: 'At the winter solstice, when one ray of yang returns and the day grows longer by a thread -- how much does the Buddha-dharma grow?' The answer was: 'One thread.' Another ancient worthy said: 'A thread's length.' Someone asked Master Gaofeng Miao: 'How much does the Buddha-dharma grow?' Miao said: 'Ten thousand miles east to west, eight thousand north to south.'" The Master said: "When these three venerable elders spoke like this, none of them hit the level ground. Today if someone asks this old Lotus Root: 'How much does the Buddha-dharma grow?' I simply say: 'Just right.' Tell me -- is this the same as the ancients or different? Those with eyes, try to analyze it."

=== Zihu Lizong ===
E1: Zihu set up a sign at his gate. On the sign it read: "Zihu has a dog. Above, it takes your head; in the middle, your waist; below, your feet. If you deliberate, you lose body and life." When a newcomer had just arrived, the master would shout, "Watch the dog!" As soon as the monk turned his head, the master would return to the abbot's quarters.
E2: Zihu went to visit Liu the Iron Grinder and said, "Are you Liu the Iron Grinder or not?" The Grinder said, "I would not dare." Zihu said, "Turn left, turn right." The Grinder said, "Venerable, do not turn things upside down." Zihu immediately struck her.

=== Zishui of Wolong ===
E1: A lay disciple, Zhang Maode, was asked to write a preface to the master's record. He fell asleep and dreamed he entered the master's garden, presented a blank sheet of paper, and drew a circle on it. The master said: "You just won't say anything, will you?" Zhang replied: "Don't tell dreams to fools -- who'd filter the dregs after someone farts? The turtle carrying the stele has lost its life at the red inscription; the wild goose has already flown -- why still grope for the pointing finger in the yellow reeds?" He then felt the master's forehead and said: "Let me measure how thick your face-skin is." The master instantly smacked him on the head with his staff: "Thief!" Zhang woke with a start, grabbed a brush, and wrote out his dream as the preface.
E2: The master raised the old case of Xiu: "This one, that one, yet another one -- if you have clear eyes, why repeat it?" And Gaofeng's rejoinder about silent-illumination sitters crouching forever in their ghost-caves. "At Qiling, it's not like that!" Long pause. "I forgot." He descended from the seat.

=== Zisu of Panlong ===
E1: A monk asked: "The way pointing upward was not transmitted by the thousand sages. Does the Master transmit it?" Zisu said: "I transmit it." The monk pressed: "The thousand sages did not transmit it -- why do you?" Zisu replied: "I am not one of the thousand sages." Then he said: "Sometimes I shut the critical pass, and the mouths of the three-world Buddhas hang on the wall. Sometimes I open a single thread, and stray cats and white oxen roam freely in every direction. As for the phrase in which neither grasping nor releasing applies -- no one in the whole great earth can lay a finger on it. I, Panlong, do not begrudge my eyebrows: let me share the news with all of you." He gave a shout and descended from the seat.
E2: A monk asked: "What about the cold spring in the ancient ravine?" Zisu said: "Cold." The monk asked: "What about the one who drinks it?" Zisu said: "It will choke you to death."

=== Zixianjue ===
E1: On the Lantern Festival the Master ascended the hall. A monk was about to step forward, but the Master held him back: "Stop, stop! Today I have no leisure for questions. There is an urgent matter -- though it shames our household, it must be aired publicly." He suddenly held up his staff: "This Wooden Worthy has followed me for years, upholding the rules and keeping himself correct, without the slightest lapse. But last night during the lantern celebrations, he went out arm-in-arm with the two Guardian Kings, watching the lanterns from the south bank all the way to the north bank, and did not return until the third watch. In the past, Manjusri was banished to Iron Ring Mountain merely for giving rise to views of Buddha and Dharma. This Wooden Worthy has violated the precept against attending spectacles with the two Guardian Kings -- to where should he be banished?" He threw down the staff and called to the work supervisor: "Drive them all out through the triple gate at once!" Then he descended from the seat.
E2: Ascending the hall: "One person sits quietly in the abbot's room, his whole body sunk in wild grass. Another person walks the crossroads, each step treading the crown of Vairocana. Which of them deserves the offerings of gods and humans?" After a long pause: "Today a great many people did not show up for communal work."

=== ZIYONGRU ===
E1: A scholar from the south came to the hall and said: "All day I sought the Boat of Compassion, only to find that the Boat of Compassion has the face of an old woman." The Master gave a thunderous shout: "What kind of place is this for talk of male and female?" The scholar was speechless. The Master said: "Step forward -- I will tell you something." When the scholar stepped forward, she seized him and said: "Since parting from Vulture Peak there has been nowhere to find it. Today mother and child meet again." The scholar said: "I am deeply convinced." He immediately took refuge and asked to be ordained.
E2: At West Mountain Yong'an Temple, a traveling monk walked straight into the abbot's quarters and sat down on the platform. The Master said: "A jackal has blundered into the lion's den." The monk said: "Manjushri is here." The Master said: "Just right -- he can wash my feet." The monk said: "The lion makes a great turn of the body!" The Master struck him. The monk had no reply, so she drove him out with repeated blows of the stick.

=== Zizhouchuan of Tanxi ===
E1: A monk asked: "What is the matter before father and mother were born?" The master planted his staff on the left. The monk pressed: "What is the matter after birth?" The master planted his staff on the right. "What is the matter of neither birth nor death?" The master planted his staff again. The monk bowed. The master struck him and said: "Seeking the mind, it cannot be found -- only then can the mind be at peace. When defilement cannot touch it, the fist returns beneath the ribs. Neither this side nor that side admits saints or ordinary beings -- only then can one play freely in samadhi."
E2: A monk said: "Capture and release, kill and revive -- I won't ask about those. What is the single hall of cold wind?" The master said: "You yourself are the witness." The monk pressed: "Witness to what?" The master said: "Ten-thousand peaks, hands released." The monk bowed. Another asked: "What is seven within seven?" The master held up his staff. The monk said: "Ten-thousand peaks, hands released at once!" The master struck him. The monk tried to push half a word. The master said: "Look -- you've fallen right into the mortar." Then: "And where exactly is your mortar?" The monk hesitated. The master struck again.

=== ZONGBAO DAODU ===
E1: Ascending the hall, Daodu raised the case: "Seven wise women were walking through a charnel ground. One said: 'The corpse is here -- where is the person?' Another said: 'What? What?' All seven women simultaneously realized the patience of no-birth." Then Daodu continued: "Today the vice-abbot carries the bones of his father, the lay-practitioner Jingzong, to build a memorial stupa on Mount Luofu. He requests that this mountain monk ascend the hall to forge a karmic connection with the assembly and dedicate merit to the departed. Suppose someone asks the late practitioner: 'The bones are here -- where is the person?' What would this mountain monk say?" After a long silence: "Tomorrow is the Qingming Festival."
E2: On his birthday, Daodu said: "You've all heard the story. The Sixth Patriarch arrived at Faxing Temple and heard two monks arguing. One said: 'The wind is moving.' The other said: 'The banner is moving.' The Patriarch, unable to hold back, stepped forward and said: 'It is not the wind moving. It is not the banner moving. It is your minds that move.' All of you -- if you understand this, you directly see where the Sixth Patriarch makes his home. You directly see where Shakyamuni makes his home. You directly see where you yourself make your home. Top to bottom, through and through, with nothing left over." He then quoted an old verse: "Beautiful as Xi Shi leaving the golden palace, graceful as Yang Guifei descending the jade tower. Day after day, drunk with you beneath the flowers -- where is there a place that is not elegant?" "This mountain monk borrows these lines to annotate for you: 'Not the wind moving, not the banner moving' -- that is 'beautiful as Xi Shi, graceful as Yang Guifei.' 'It is your minds that move' -- that is 'day after day, drunk with you beneath the flowers, where is there a place that is not elegant?'" He struck the desk with his whisk and descended.

=== Zongchi ===
E1: Chan Master Shen of Fengsheng in the Western Capital had a nun, Zongchi, of notable capacity. When illness came she composed a verse, saying: "Breath cut off, all feelings spent; raise an intention and there is no road for intention. Even blinking lacks strength; all year I do not leave the door." Wansong comments: "Though this is Patriarchs' Zen, it is much like an old crow in a cloth sack." But the master Furong Kai said: "This single verse naturally inherits our school."
E2: Bodhidharma, nearing the end of his life, said to his disciples, "The time has come. Each of you, speak your understanding." Dafu said, "As I see it, we should neither cling to words nor abandon words, but use them as instruments of the Way." Bodhidharma said, "You have attained my skin." The nun Zongchi said, "As I understand it, it is like Ananda's vision of the land of Akshobhya Buddha -- seen once, and never to be seen again." Bodhidharma said, "You have attained my flesh." Daoyu said, "The four elements are originally empty, the five aggregates do not truly exist. As I see it, there is not a single dharma to be grasped." Bodhidharma said, "You have attained my bones." Last, Huike came forward, bowed, and stood in his place without saying a word. Bodhidharma said, "You have attained my marrow."

=== Zuliangqi ===
E1: At the evening small talk after entering the monastery, the Master said: "My late teacher used to say: 'The conduct of a patchrobed monk, attending a teacher and befriending fellow practitioners, requires nothing but a single true and real heart. Shakyamuni, the old man, went forth into the world and held up a flower with this true and real heart. The golden-headed elder smiled with this true and real heart. Even Bodhidharma sat facing the wall for nine years at Shaoshi Peak with this true and real heart. Shenguang cut off his arm to seek the dharma with this true and real heart. Generation after generation transmitted it, down to the Sixth Patriarch, Nanyue, Mazu, Baizhang, Huangbo, Linji -- every great teacher under heaven, without exception, used this true and real heart to ferry the four kinds of beings and to bridge the nine realms of existence.'" Then the Master held up his staff and said: "Now I hang this one true and real heart on the tip of the staff. All of you, raise your eyebrows and look! Each of you, verify this true and real heart. Let this true and real heart be your ridgepole and beam. In every moment of daily use, do not act in any way that does not rely on this one true and real heart. But tell me: where does this heap of true and real hearts ultimately come to rest? Phoenix Mountain stands precipitous through past and present; the true dharma continues in an unbroken thread for ten thousand years."
E2: At the evening talk, the Master said: "Today on the fifth day, people say they fear the monthly taboo day. But when this old monk went out, everything was supremely auspicious. Walking to the front of the Shengyuan Daoist Temple, I ran into Laozi and Immortal Ge Zhenzhen. They dragged me off to tour the Elixir-Refining Terrace and climb the Cloud-Mounting Rock. There on the rock we lingered awhile. I asked Laozi: 'How is your practice going?' He answered: 'My scripture says: Dim and dark, within it there is essence. Faint and obscure, within it there is substance.' I gave a thunderous shout: 'You spirit-juggling charlatan!' Laozi said: 'How about you monks?' I said: 'One kick overturns the Elixir Terrace! One punch topples the Cloud Rock! A patchrobed monk's heroic spirit should be just like this -- such mettle is not given by heaven and earth.' At that moment, all three of us clapped our hands, roared with laughter, and parted ways."

TOTAL: 448 masters, 887 encounters EN, 887 encounters DE